<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7847 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-COLTS-HNS &LR;      01-17 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-COLTS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ For the first time since the Luv Ya Blue era, when
they were known as the Houston Oilers, the Tennessee Titans are
playing in the AFC Championship Game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rather than Bum Phillips and Earl Campbell knocking on the Super
Bowl door in Pittsburgh, it will be Jeff Fisher and Eddie George
trying to kick the SOB in at Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the best and most satisfying playoff games in the
franchise's 40-year history, the Titans stunned the Indianapolis
Colts 19-16 in an AFC divisional game Sunday, setting up the AFC
Championship Game at Jacksonville on Jan. 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars, who annihilated Miami 62-7 on Saturday, have a 15-2
record, with the only blemishes 20-19 and 41-14 losses to
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this game was a nuclear holocaust, that one's going to be
World War III,'' offensive tackle Brad Hopkins said after helping
the Titans rush for 197 yards.
</P>
<P>
   If the Titans can record a hat trick against the Jaguars, they
will be headed for Super Bowl XXXIV at the Georgia Dome against the
winner of the Tampa Bay-St. Louis NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope everything keeps going our way until Jan. 30 when we're
holding up the Vince Lombardi Trophy,'' Titans receiver Kevin Dyson
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Titans were the Oilers, guard Bruce Matthews made the
playoffs seven consecutive years but never advanced beyond the
second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, I've watched a lot of second-round games like
this, and I've told myself it wasn't that big a deal to win them.
But I was wrong,'' Matthews said. ``This is a big deal, and I feel
blessed to finally be part of something like this.''
</P>
<P>
   The underdog Titans upset the Colts with a throwback game plan
right out of the Phillips playbook.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, it was Eddie George right, Eddie George left and
Eddie George up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   George carried 26 times for 162 yards and scored Tennessee's
only touchdown on a team playoff-record 68-yard run on the first
series of the third quarter that gave the Titans a 13-9 lead they
never surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the game, I pulled Eddie aside and told him that in
April of 1996 we drafted him in the first round to win games like
this,'' Fisher said. ``It's taken us awhile to get here, but this
is exactly the way we wanted to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   George broke Campbell's single-game franchise playoff record of
118 yards with his prodigious performance. And he did something
else Campbell was never able to do when he became the franchise's
first player to post back-to-back 100-yard rushing games in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie ran hard all day,'' Titans quarterback Steve McNair
said. ``In a playoff game like this, there ae going to be one or
two big plays that make a difference. His run was the only big play
we had on offense, but it was good enough to stand up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indianapolis defense wasn't exactly the Steel Curtain.
Entering Sunday's game, the Colts had allowed an average of 141
yards rushing and 4.8 per carry over the previous three games, and
the interior defense had been marshmallow soft.
</P>
<P>
   Titans offensive coordinator Les Steckel called plays that
attacked the Colts' weakness. McNair crossed up the Colts with his
running ability, carrying seven times for 35 yards.
</P>
<P>
   After a slow start passing, McNair finished 13-of-24 for 112
yards. He didn't throw a touchdown pass, but he also wasn't sacked
and didn't throw an interception.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans played smart but relentless defense designed to
attack and contain the Colts' magnificent threesome of quarterback
Peyton Manning, running back Edgerrin James and receiver Marvin
Harrison. Defensive coordinator Gregg Williams devised an
aggressive plan that put eight players in the box and called for 95
percent man coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Manning completed 19 of 43 passes for 227 yards. Like McNair, he
didn't throw a touchdown pass and wasn't sacked or intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   James, the outstanding two-way threat who became the first
rookie to lead the NFL in rushing since Eric Dickerson in 1983,
carried 20 times for 56 yards, a 2.8-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   Titans cornerback Samari Rolle covered Harrison like a bad case
of poison ivy, limiting the Pro Bowl receiver to five catches for
65 yards and harassing him into three dropped passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second half, we made some adjustments and put Samari
exclusively on Harrison,'' Williams said. ``Samari did a fantastic
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We brought (rookie cornerback) Donald Mitchell off the bench
to cover the other receiver. Because Donald played so well, it
allowed Samari to shadow Harrison everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts finished with 305 yards to the Titans' 309. Because it
was an old-fashioned defensive struggle, the game featured an
exchange of field goals between Tennessee's Al Del Greco and
Indianapolis' Mike Vanderjagt.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderjagt gave the Colts leads of 3-0, 6-3 and 9-6 with field
goals of 40, 40 and 34 yards. Del Greco countered with 49- and
37-yarders that left the Titans behind 9-6 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   George began the second half with his 68-yard run up the middle
on which he received awesome blocks, made two cuts and outran the
Colts' secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just don't realize how powerful Eddie is,'' Titans
linebacker Barron Wortham said. ``And they misjudged his speed.
Because he's so strong, they underestimate his breakaway speed. If
they think a safety's going to chase him down, they're wrong. You
saw a good example of that today.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth quarter, good fortune smiled on the Titans. With
Tennessee leading 16-9, Colts rookie Gerald Wilkins had what
appeared to be an 87-yard punt return to the Tennessee three-yard
line. It was challenged by Fisher, reviewed and overturned by
referee John Grier, who ruled Wilkins had stepped out of bounds at
his 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge swing,'' said Indianapolis coach Jim Mora,
whose playoff record with the Colts and Saints dropped to 0-5,
including 0-4 at home. ``To have the ball at the three-yard line
and have to move back to the 34 hurt our momentum. Our coaches felt
the call was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Del Greco kicked a 43-yard field goal to give the Titans a 19-9
edge with 4:19 remaining. It wasn't a commanding lead, but it
should have been comfortable. The Titans, however, just had to make
it interesting.
</P>
<P>
   George committed the game's only turnover when he lost a fumble
at the Indianapolis 39 with 3:11 remaining. The Colts took
advantage when Manning scored their only touchdown on a 15-yard run
with 1:51 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Once receiver Yancey Thigpen recovered the onside kick and
survived a vicious hit to keep possession of the ball, the Titans
eliminated the suspense by running out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 0027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
