<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-COLTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS JUST PLAIN BETTER THAN COLTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Tricky devils, these Tennessee Titans. Last week
they pulled a playoff victory out of their helmets _ and out of the
Buffalo Bills' hearts. Sunday _ presto! _ they made the most
dynamic offense in the AFC disappear, vaporizing the far more
celebrated Indianapolis Colts, 19-16, in the process.
</P>
<P>
   In the den of din known as the RCA Dome _ shaking with 57,097
fans savoring the first postseason football game ever in Indiana _
the Titans' defense blunted Peyton Manning, Edgerrin James, and
Marvin Harrison, who had pulled off the statistical trifecta of
being the first teammates ever to lead the AFC in yards passing,
running, and receiving, respectively, since the AFL-NFL merger of
1970.
</P>
<P>
   And they made one thunderbolt _ Eddie George's 68-yard touchdown
blast up the middle on the third play of the second half, which
produced a 13-9 Titans lead and silence in the building _ stand up.
It rendered Manning's 15-yard scoring scramble with 1:51 left in
the game moot _ especially after Tennessee recovered the ensuing
onside kick _ and set up a visit to Jacksonville next Sunday for
the AFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   Win that and the Titans (nee Houston Oilers) will become the
last of the AFL originals from 1960 to qualify for the Super Bowl.
And the omens are good. While the Jaguars own the best record in
the NFL _ 14-2, not counting Saturday's 62-7 Jimmy Johnson
retirement party against Miami _ the Titans have dealt their
Central Division superiors their only two losses, 20-19 Sept. 26
and 41-14 Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means absolutely nothing,'' cautioned Titans coach Jeff
Fisher, who isn't interested in portents and spells even though
there seems to be something mystical about this team that compiled
a gaudy, if hardly overwhelming, 13-3 record during the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   Even after last week's improbable climax, the kickoff touchdown
lateral that stole survival from the Bills, 22-16, Fisher is not
acknowledging any celestial forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not destiny,'' he said. ``It's called winning games.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning them a certain way, to be precise. A way that would make
connoisseurs of the sport cover their eyes, truth be told.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday was vintage Titans football.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won it our way,'' said Fisher. ``It wasn't pretty, but you
look up at the end and we're up by 3. That's our way.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about as much as can be expected from an offense that
springs from the fertile imagination of coordinator Les Steckel,
the former Patriots assistant who surely wore a pocket protector
every day in class before he became a Marine. Steckel's idea of an
attack is George, George, and more George, with a little Steve
McNair play action thrown in when he wants to get funky. And son of
a gun if it didn't work against the Colts _ who became the third
and last member of the vaunted AFC East in two weeks to fall to the
supposedly weak sisters of the Central.
</P>
<P>
   George, the 6-foot-3-inch, 240-pound ramrod who may be the most
anonymous Heisman Trophy standout in history _ he's gained at least
1,000 yards in each of his four NFL seasons, with hardly a notice _
gouged out 162 yards on 26 carries, setting a franchise playoff
record and becoming the first Oiler/Titan to run for at least 100
yards in consecutive postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   His third-quarter romp put an end to what had been a glorified
tabletop football game, complete with triangular paper and
outstretched arms and forefingers for goalposts. The first half
consisted entirely of field goals _ three by NFL scoring champion
Mike Vanderjagt (40, 40, and 34 yards) and two by the Titans'
venerable Al Del Greco (49, 37).
</P>
<P>
   But in the locker room at halftime, the Titans prepared to
spring George.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a counter,'' he said. ``We hadn't run one all game. We
decided to run it at the half. It was the first chance we had to
run one with (fullback) Lorenzo Neal in there. I saw the middle
open and I just took off.''
</P>
<P>
   With an array of Colts in futile pursuit. So unaccustomed is
George to such freedom _ such blissful lack of pounding and
thrashing _ that he took a look up at the scoreboard above the end
zone just to see if he really was that clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never done that before,'' he said sheepishly. ``I've
never had the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   He finally was caught by defensive back Tyrone Poole, but only
for a brief ride in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Del Greco added fourth-quarter field goals of 25 and 43 yards to
make it 19-9, but the Colts were as good as cooked after George's
gallop, yet another franchise playoff record.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the Titan defense put the clamps on
Indianapolis's prolific troika. James, the first rookie to lead the
NFL in rushing since Eric Dickerson in 1983, was stuffed for 56
yards on 20 carries. Harrison was limited to five inconsequential
catches for 65 yards. And Manning was a mere 19 of 43 for 227
yards.
</P>
<P>
   The key ingredient was putting the shackles on James, which the
Titans did by using a defensive back _ Donald Mitchell _ rather
than a linebacker to shadow him on third down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gave us the matchup we wanted,'' said Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt the play pass wouldn't be a problem if we stopped the
run,'' said safety Blaine Bishop. ``We stopped Edgerrin and they
had to get away from that.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Colts were left with nothing but grudging admiration.
``We never put the ball and drive together,'' said Manning. ``We
got stopped on third and 1. It was just that kind of day until very
late in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Titans weren't averse to a little intervention.
</P>
<P>
   With 9:25 left in the game and the Titans ahead, 16-9, Indy's
Terrence Wilkins fielded a Craig Hentrich punt at his 11 and
zigzagged along the right side for 87 yards to the Tennessee 3,
electrifying the crowd and setting up the Colts for the tying
score.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   Titans strength and conditioning coach Steve Watterson spotted
Wilkins stepping ever so slightly out of bounds at the Colt 33. The
assistants in the press box confirmed this, but the Colts were
about to run a play, which would have precluded any challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``My pager wasn't working,'' said Fisher, ``so I had to burn a
timeout to get the replay.'' Which upheld the Titans and set the
Colts back on their heels for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a huge swing,'' sighed Indianapolis coach Jim Mora.
``What else can you say? Our coaches felt the call was right that
he stepped out of bounds. There is nothing we could do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Or anything else these Kismet Titans tried.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
