A7857 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     01-17 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ They come at you with all the subtlety of a road
grader and have about as many clever, unexpected moves.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the Titans got here with the niftiest bit of
great-escape chicanery this side of Houdini. Because the truth is
there is nothing tricky about them.
</P>
<P>
   In a bakery, they'd be white bread. In an ice cream parlor,
they'd be vanilla. In a presidential race, they'd even make fellow
Tennessean Al Gore look like the lampshade-wearing life of the
party.
</P>
<P>
   They are so much less than Elvis with swiveling hips and so much
more than the Queen Mother in support hose and a pillbox hat.
</P>
<P>
   Boring. As in reading the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   Boring. As in a giant drill bit that ground out a huge hole
straight through the middle of the Indianapolis Colts for Sunday's
19-16 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game,'' said head coach/art critic Jeff Fisher, ``is not
pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   In dating parlance, the Titans are coyote ugly, if you'll pardon
an old expression. A real two-bagger, for sure.
</P>
<P>
   In strictly football terms, they might now be the team to beat
on the road to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind those fancy-boy St. Louis Rams and their laser-guided
missiles, the Tampa Bay Bucs and their rookie quarterback or even
the Jacksonville Jaguars and their league-best-but-marshmallow-soft
15-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a team left standing in the NFL playoffs that is
truly worthy of wrapping its mitts around the Lombardi Trophy and
the no-nonsense man for whom it is named, it is these smash-mouth
Titans.
</P>
<P>
   They run the ball down your throat on offense and then squeeze
your windpipe on defense until you can no longer breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, the Colts were billed as the next great thing. But on
Sunday, they were only the next-best team on the field at the RCA
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive combination of Peyton Manning, Edgerrin James and
Marvin Harrison was supposed to usher the AFC side of the playoff
draw into the 21st century with their Star Wars attack. Instead, we
watched the Titans roll across the screen like an old Wagon Train
rerun, moving relentlessly, unstoppably along.
</P>
<P>
   The only bit of real drama came when the Colts' Terrence Wilkins
raced 87 yards with a punt return to the Titans' three-yard line
with just over nine minutes left. Call it payback for Mike Renfro,
but suddenly instant replay is this snakebitten franchise's best
friend. The previous weekend, ``Home run throwback'' was upheld,
and this time the replay showed Wilkins stepping out of bounds at
his 34.
</P>
<P>
   The throttling of the Colts' offense was accomplished by the
daring and simple notion of usually putting eight men on the line
of scrimmage to stop James on the run, while counting on the
cornerbacks to keep Indy's wide receivers from getting to the
outside for catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not afraid to play on the edge,'' said Titans defensive
coordinator Gregg Williams. ``All year long, they've been eating up
the zone defenses that most teams use against them. Other teams are
afraid to play eight-man fronts against them. But we knew if we
could play man, we could take them out of their play-action passing
game. We were ready to line up.''
</P>
<P>
   They lined Manning up against the wall and shut him down to a
season-worst 19-for-43 passing for 227 yards. They limited Harrison
to five catches for 65 yards and, most important, kept the cork in
James' bottle, giving up just 56 yards on 20 carries.
</P>
<P>
   One wouldn't describe the Titans' offense as explosive so much
as exhaustive. And exhausting. From Eddie George's franchise
playoff-record 162 yards rushing on 26 carries _ including a
third-quarter burst up the middle for a 68-yard touchdown _ to key
catches by Yancey Thigpen, Frank Wycheck and Chris Sanders,
Tennessee's offense is about as exciting and yet as full of answers
as an encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there is quarterback Steve McNair, whose
pedestrian 13-for-24, 112-yard passing numbers belie his ability to
keep opposing defenses holding their breath as if walking a
tightrope. He is the dash of hot sauce that keeps you guessing
while George pours oatmeal down your throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 10 minutes before we went out for warm-ups, Jeff pulled
me aside and asked me to relive draft day back in 1996,'' George
said. ``He told me to remember why he drafted me, and that was
because he thought I could lead this team to the brink of where we
are now. He challenged me to live up to those expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Now they are all living up. Doing it their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never pretty,'' said Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   Just pretty damn good.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
