<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-VIKINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER, ST. LOUIS PROVE THEY'RE FOR REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ They are confident, cocky, and brash, quarterback
Kurt Warner defining the attitude of all these Rams when asked
about Minnesota tough guy John Randle. ``He never showed up the
whole game,'' said Warner of the Vikings defensive lineman. ``He
was shouting out all these things to me, but I wasn't listening.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis was unveiled to all of football America for the first
time Sunday and the 49 points the Rams piled up on the Vikings in
an NFC playoff game, won by St. Louis, 49-37, came so easily. The
Rams will meet Tampa Bay for the NFC title Sunday here in the
raucous TWA Dome and, for those fans of deja vu all over again, the
Rams made their only Super Bowl appearance in 1980 after defeating
Tampa Bay, 9-0, in the NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   The 49 points were huge but only counted for so much. It was the
Rams' attitude that was as impressive as their offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we ought to win and we thought we were going to
win,'' said Rams coach Dick Vermeil, ``and I think we painted a
glaring picture that we don't have any glaring weaknesses on
offense, on defense, and special teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, added Vermeil: ``I don't think we've played our best game
yet.'' Or, as St. Louis wide receiver Isaac Bruce put it: ``I think
we finally smashed that question of us not playing anybody.''
Quickly, too.
</P>
<P>
   On St. Louis's first play, the Rams called for a slant to Bruce
that offensive coordinator Mike Martz had noticed Dallas had used
successfully against the Vikings. Martz and Vermeil talked it over
and then gave the word to Warner, the Rams QB making his most
important start since his Iowa Barnstormers lost to the Tampa Bay
Storm in Arena Bowl X 3 1/2 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Warner thought about the play much of Saturday night, ``going
over every scenario in my head of everything we could do on the
play,'' he said. ``And we couldn't wait to get out there and run
it.'' Warner dropped back from his 23 and hit Bruce on the run for
what would turn into a 77-yard scoring pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed,'' said Vikings cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock on what makes
this St. Louis offense so lethal. ``All their receivers are quick.
Isaac made the big reception on the game's first play and then we
couldn't tackle Marshall (Faulk, on a 41-yard screen pass for a TD)
on the second series of the first quarter. After that, it was a
circus act.''
</P>
<P>
   And Warner (27 for 33 for 391 yards, 5 TDs, and 1 INT) was the
ringmaster. The five TDs? ``Just an average Arena League game,'' he
sniffed, ``but I'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   A Warner interception and a Faulk fumble in the second quarter
enabled the Vikings to take the 17-14 lead at the half. But when
Vermeil gathered his troops at halftime, he told them not to worry,
``that we had taken the Vikings' best shots and we were down only
by 3.'' Faulk remembered Vermeil saying, `` `Hey, we're stopping
ourselves. Point blank. That's it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And then, the Rams' Tony Horne immediately turned the game on
its head by returning the second-half kickoff 95 yards for a TD.
``We had things going our way until the second-half kickoff,'' said
Minnesota linebacker Dwayne Rudd. ``That was a championship play
that helped them get to a championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   The 37 points the Vikings scored might suggest St. Louis had
little or no success stopping Jeff George, Randy Moss, Cris Carter,
and Jake Reed. In truth, though, St. Louis was superlative on
defense in the third quarter, holding the Vikings to no first downs
and minus-2 yards of offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you're not going to stop Randy Moss and Jeff George
all that time . . . you just can't do it,'' said St. Louis
cornerback Todd Lyght. ``But in that third quarter we really
stepped it up and held them; that was some of the best football
we've played all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in this matchup of two explosive offenses, the offense
that could not score when it had the ball would cost its team
dearly. And when the Vikings could not get even a first down on its
four possessions of the third quarter, the price Minnesota paid was
huge.
</P>
<P>
   After Horne's TD return, Faulk capped off a 51-yard drive with a
1-yard run and Warner hit tight end Jeff Robinson on a 13-yard TD
pass. Finally, after the Rams recovered a George fumble on the
next-to-last play of the third quarter, Warner needed only four
plays to move 23 yards, the last play a 1-yard flip to center Ryan
Tucker, who had lined up at tight end for the play, totally fooling
the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis was ahead, 42-17, and the game was over. What followed
was protracted garbage time that did little but make the final
score respectable ``and delay cocktail hour'' as Vermeil put it.
</P>
<P>
   But no score of 49-37 should hide the clear facts that the Rams
are a team built for Astroturf, faster and quicker than virtually
all the teams in the league, with one of the NFL's most accurate
passers at QB and an offensive coordinator who might try anything.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, the attitude, too. That nobody can beat the Rams.
</P>
</TEXT>
