<SLUG> BC-SOC-US-IRAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US BATTLES IRAN TO DRAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Score one for soccer diplomacy. The US
national team was hoping for revenge, or at least to regain some
self-respect against the Islamic Republic of Iran. Instead the US
settled for a 1-1 tie Sunday, an improvement on its poor
performance at the France '98 World Cup but much less impressive
than some of its 1999 results.
</P>
<P>
   Though this was a home match for the US, the game was conducted
in a surreal atmosphere of 50,181 spectators, nearly all of them
Iranian supporters who turned the day into a celebration. There was
little of the politically fueled tension that had marked Iran's 2-1
win over the US in Lyons, France, June 21, 1998, as much of the
tension had been dissipated by distance, time, and the openness of
the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   And the US presented a much different group of players. The team
performed as the home team should _ attacking and probing against
Iran's packed defense. The US maintained its composure after
falling behind to a ninth-minute goal by Mehdi Mahdavikia, then
adjusted its scheme to stifle strikers Khodadad Azizi and Ali Daei
and rallied to control the action in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Armas scored in the third minute of the second and nearly
broke the tie midway through the half, both times off feeds from
Cobi Jones. Armas proved to be vital in keeping the US organized in
support of Claudio Reyna in midfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not as fit as we need to be, and we had problems early
because we did not do a good job with Azizi,'' US coach Bruce Arena
said. ``Azizi was able to get his fair share of balls and run at us
and split the defense. But we played quite well the last 65
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't concern myself with the politics involved in the
matchup. We were excited to play a good football-playing country
and excited to start the year. The stadium was close to full, the
game was on TV, and we played good soccer. So it was a good day for
soccer.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran used the same counter-attacking tactics that functioned so
well in Lyons. The Iranians absorbed early US thrusts, including an
impressive looping shot off the far post by Jones in the second
minute. And they took command with their quickness and opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   Azizi set up the goal by winning a throw-in after breaking free
on the right. Azizi then took the throw-in and dribbled through the
defense into the penalty area. He left the ball for Mahdavikia, who
had scored Iran's second goal in Lyons, and Mahdavikia slotted a
shot past goalkeeper Brad Friedel.
</P>
<P>
   Azizi, 30, who plays for FC Cologne in Germany, had a breakaway
off a pass from Esmaeil Halili but sent a low shot off the right
post in the 21st minute.
</P>
<P>
   But Iran showed vulnerabilities. Goalkeeper Hadi Tabatabei, 24,
displayed excellent athleticism but struggled with positioning. And
this was nearly a fatal flaw as the Iranians retreated into a
well-organized defensive posture.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the US players from France '98 remained for this match.
And though the US seemed rejuvenated with a youthful team, it was
lacking the unpredictability of some veterans and the long-distance
threat of Preki.
</P>
<P>
   Central defenders Marcelo Balboa and Carlos Llamosa struggled
early, but their aggressive and poised play against Azizi and Daei
made the difference in the second half. This was an encouraging
sign, since both are likely to remain backups when Robin Fraser
(broken collarbone) and Eddie Pope (wedding) return.
</P>
<P>
   The US has an 8-4-3 record since Arena replaced Steve Sampson,
and it has a chance to capture imaginations during World Cup
qualifying, beginning later this year. The lack of US support was a
commentary both on the team's history of failures and on the
extraordinary number of Iranian immigrants in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do anything about what happened in France,'' US
striker Brian McBride said. ``We are concentrating on what this
team is able to do. We have to show progress, and after the first
minutes I'm happy with the way we came back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
