</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OPEN QUESTION FOR PATRIOTS BRASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ What was learned Sunday in the Trans World Dome is
that there is Patriot football and then there is pro football.
</P>
<P>
   During the St. Louis Rams' 49-37 victory over the Minnesota
Vikings in the NFC playoffs, more receivers were open in 30 minutes
than had been open in New England in 30 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A reserve center, Ryan Tucker, was more open in the end zone for
the Rams on one play than Terry Glenn was for the Patriots all
season. Plus he caught the ball when it was thrown to him there.
</P>
<P>
   What was apparent was that in St. Louis they play offense. In
New England, they play offense and then they punt.
</P>
<P>
   There could be no more stark contrast to the way it is among the
NFL's elite teams and the way it is in Foxborough than to have
watched the Rams offense dismantle the Vikings, a team that had won
nine of its last 11 by scoring points themselves.
</P>
<P>
   For a time the Vikings continued to do that, even taking a 17-14
halftime lead and piling up 476 total yards on the day, but the
Rams were relentless. Relentless with their speed, relentless with
their attack mentality, relentless with a slant pattern that has
been extinct in New England for years. Relentless with formations
and schemes that baffled the Vikings, relentless with talent
imported to St. Louis by a man the Patriots braintrust drove out of
town, personnel director Charley Armey.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, Kurt Warner, the Rams' Cinderella quarterback, had
thrown for 391 yards and five touchdowns while being sacked only
twice and touched not much more than that despite passing 33 times.
Drew Bledsoe is hit more often than that lining up for the national
anthem.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, Rams wide receiver Isaac Bruce was averaging 33.3
yards a catch and seven receivers were averaging 10 yards per
reception or better because they were running routes that got them
open rather than merely getting them 25 yards downfield.
</P>
<P>
   In one afternoon, two veteran Patriot watchers had seen more
open receivers in St. Louis than they'd seen in one season in
Foxborough. After watching New England's offense slog along as if
its feet were in cement, you watched the Rams and it reaffirmed
what you already knew.
</P>
<P>
   They are special.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are not.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams have speed on offense and speed on defense. They have a
blend of youth and experience. They have reliable if unheralded
veterans like linebacker Todd Collins and defensive tackle Ray
Agnew. (Why can't the Patriots get guys like that?) They have real
talent, not occasional talent. All-day talent, not off-and-on
talent.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, they have an offensive line that protects its
quarterback and an offensive plan that protects him, too. Only once
all day did a Rams receiver have to slow down or break stride or
reach back to grab a ball. Only once were Warner's throws not on
the money, which is why the Rams are on their way to the NFC
Championship Game Sunday against a Tampa Bay team that is going to
get pulverized regardless of how good its defense is because it
won't score 10 points on St. Louis's speed defense and eventually
the Rams' speed offense will score many more than that.
</P>
<P>
   The architect of much of this is Mike Martz, the Rams'
first-year offensive coordinator who is on every team's short list
as a head coaching candidate, including New England's. Teams win,
coordinators get the credit, and soon they become head coaches
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A few are successful. Others are not. The rest are like Pete
Carroll. Mediocre not because of a lack of football knowledge but
because they couldn't handle the other demands of the job.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows where Martz fits into this, but he knows where his
offensive scheme fits into it and why it's working here when it
didn't work half as well in Washington and even less so in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talent,'' Martz said. ``It's easy when you have people like we
have to put this together. This whole system is like Norv's
(Turner) in Washington and Ernie's (Zampese) in New England. But
this whole system takes a different look with the people we have.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept and approach are similar to Washington but we're
just a little more liberal with what we do. It's really the same
system in New England.'' It is?
</P>
<P>
   Then why were so many receivers standing wide open in St. Louis
after being so tightly bound in New England? And why was Warner
able to so often rifle them the ball with perfect accuracy, while
Bledsoe's passes were so often going in the wrong direction?
</P>
<P>
   This could not be the same system because when they ran it in
New England nobody ran into the end zone. They ran into the
showers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The approach we take and the routes we run and the positioning
of our receivers are all similar to Don Coryell's offense (which is
the father of the Zampese-Turner-Martz system),'' Martz explained
Sunday to an incredulous questioner from the East. ``We run our
routes and we expect to complete them with this kind of talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the situation in New England, but I'd guess the
problem is probably the offensive line. It's hard for me to think
of a better line than ours. Our perimeter people get a lot of
credit but our quarterback is well-protected. I imagine that has a
lot to do with the problems back there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole approach is to go as fast as we can and pressure
them. At times you can't do that, but the last thing we want to be
is afraid. We have so much speed here. People talk about our game
plans, and we work hard at them, but it's the players first and
foremost.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get in position to make plays. If you don't have good
players, you can get them in position but they still don't make the
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   They made plays Sunday in St. Louis running Ernie Zampese's
system. They didn't make them the last two months in New England
running Mike Martz's. You figure out why.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone watched the Rams' offense destroy the Vikings and
didn't believe they were watching a different brand of football
than they saw in New England all year they were watching with eyes
wide shut.
</P>
<P>
   And if anyone, including Patriots owner Bob Kraft or personnel
director Bobby Grier, watched the Rams play offense and defense and
concluded the players they have are their equal, they are saying it
with their fingers crossed.
</P>
<P>
   If anything was clear at the Trans World Dome it's this. They
play a different kind of football here with a different kind of
player.
</P>
<P>
   Better ones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
