<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE OFFENSE BREWING FOR BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Sergei Samsonov . . . definitely. Dave Andreychuk . . .
maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins, with ties in their last two games but 1-8-4 over
their last 13 and 0-3-2 over their last five, take on the Atlanta
Thrashers Monday at the FleetCenter with one (Samsonov) and
possibly two (Andreychuk?) of their top scorers back in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Both practiced Sunday at the FleetCenter, where Samsonov, out
the last 10 days with a knee sprain, pronounced himself ready for
action. Andreychuk, who limped off the ice Tuesday in the final
seconds of the Toronto game with a sore knee, is hoping for a
return Monday, but wants to see how he feels this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't expecting to be out that long, but you can't really
predict those kinds of things. I was hoping it would be
day-to-day,'' said Samsonov. ``I'm feeling more comfortable now, so
I'm ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk said he felt better after practice than before.
``It's day-to-day,'' he said. ``I've still got a little bit of
swelling, so we'll see how it goes. I'm hoping I can play. I'll see
the doctor early in the morning and we'll find out then.''
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say both were feeling a lot better physically than
their coach, Pat Burns, who left practice early because of the flu
that has hit a few members of the team recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible. I stayed up all night coughing. I couldn't go
out to dinner (Saturday) night in Montreal and I got up (Sunday)
with a terrible headache,'' said Burns, who at least feels a bit
better about his team's recent play, a 3-2 loss to Toronto in which
the Bruins outshot the Leafs by a wide margin and ties against
Buffalo (0-0) and the Canadiens (2-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've battled every single game lately,'' said Burns, who was
not satisfied, nevertheless, with the Bruins' tendency to cough up
the puck, particularly with the man advantage. ``We were losing the
puck like we were school kids,'' he said. ``That's not the system.
That's personal. We touched on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said goalie Byron Dafoe's play has been a key of late.
``He's been a lot better. He's coming out a little bit more,'' said
Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still building, confidence-wise,'' said defenseman Kyle
McLaren. ``The last week and a half, two weeks, we've been really
playing hard. We haven't gotten a win, but the work is there, the
passion is there, and guys want to win. It's just a matter of going
out there and finishing off our plays. Our power play's been
struggling and those are the things that we'll have to pick up in
order for us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   McLaren said the power play _ a dismal 0 for 16 over the last
three games _ probably could use an injection of intensity,
especially with Jason Allison out for the season. ``Things don't
happen just by being out there on the ice. You have to work at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The low-scoring games of late have been to McLaren's liking.
</P>
<P>
   ``They build your confidence,'' he said. ``We have a job to do,
which is play defense and keep the goals-against down and help get
our forwards into the offense a little bit. The intensity is there
and the work ethic is there and most of the time, when you have
that, you have a good chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Thornton said the long-term loss of Allison and the recent
spate of injuries that have sidelined Samsonov and Andreychuk, as
well as Joe Hulbig and Shawn Bates, have made the Bruins dig down
for something extra.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the guys in here care,'' said Thornton. ``We're
missing a lot of players, but over the last two games, everyone's
shown up to play and given us a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk put it even more bluntly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, our backs are against the wall,'' he said. ``We
just have to look at the standings and realize these games are
important to us. I think we've played pretty well in our last three
games. We haven't got a victory, but we're close. It was the same
thing at the start of the year. We were playing well and got close,
but we were in a dry spell there, too. It just takes a couple of
efforts to get over the hump.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go through the bad spells to realize what it takes
to get out of them, especially for the younger guys.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hulbig (groin strain) and Bates (wrist sprain) skated Sunday,
with Hulbig's return more imminent. ``I've made great strides over
the last three days,'' said Hulbig. ``I can go out there at about
80 percent, but the only problem I have right now is off the jump,
off the stop and start. I'm aiming for the road trip (three games,
starting in Atlanta Wednesday) right now.'' . . . Wing Rob DiMaio
didn't practice after experiencing a slight groin strain, but
expects to play Monday. ``He could have practiced,'' said Burns,
``but I'd rather have him at 50 or 60 percent than not have him at
all.'' . . . Next stop for the Bruins' Alumni team: Tuesday, Jan.
25 at 7 p.m. at the Somerville MDC Rink on Somerville Ave. The
opponent is KISS/108 and the beneficiary is Somerville Youth
Hockey. Admission is $10 for adults, $5 for children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
