<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S RETURN ADDRESS FOR CHEANEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He exchanged hugs with one of the MCI Center
workers on his way out of practice. Earlier, he chatted with former
teammate Juwan Howard. Monday, he'll have more than a few ticket
requests.
</P>
<P>
   This used to be home for Calbert Cheaney. Until this past
August, when he signed with the Celtics as a free agent, it had
been his only home. For six steady if unspectacular years, he
played for the Bullets/Wizards, starting out with the likes of Tom
Gugliotta, Rex Chapman, and Michael Adams in 1993 and finishing
last season with Howard, Rod Strickland, and Mitch Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Cheaney played for six coaches in six years here, and the
constant theme was disappointment and underachievement. He has
left, and things have not changed. The Wizards are in last place in
the division with a humongous payroll and no clue, hoping that
general manager/owner-in-waiting Michael Jordan can do in the front
office what he did on the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Cheaney made his first visit here since leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be back,'' he said following a short workout in
preparation for Monday's game with the Wizards. ``When you stay in
a place for so long, you're going to have friends and relationships
with people. It was nice to see everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheaney and the Wizards basically made a mutual decision to part
ways. As he put it, ``I knew it was time for me to move on.'' But
he said he still considers this a special part of the NBA
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still love the organization and all the people associated
with it,'' he said. ``It's a great organization and a great city.
But I know now that I'm with the right team.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheaney made his first start of the season Saturday in the
Celtics' win over the Nets. He played a season-high 42 minutes.
Monday, he'll be back on the bench, as Rick Pitino indicated he'd
go with Walter McCarty against the taller Howard. That's fine with
Cheaney.
</P>
<P>
   He said he doesn't know what kind of reaction he'll get. ``I
hope it's nice,'' he said. ``But really, it's over. I just want to
get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Antoine Walker, fresh off his 39-point performance in New
Jersey, did not practice because of a sore left knee. But he said
he was fine, and Pitino indicated there was no problem. Eric
Williams, who sat out the New Jersey game resting a sore right
knee, practiced and will be available . . . The Wizards may be
without Richmond, who bruised his ribs in Saturday's loss to the
Pistons . . . Two Chicago television stations sent crews to
Saturday's game, hoping to get a glimpse of Jordan. He wasn't there
. . . The victory over the Nets showcased a Celtics team that
Pitino has been looking for all season. The Nets and the Celtics
are, in some ways, a lot alike, two young teams with potential
stars to lead them. ``We've got a good nucleus,'' Pitino said. He
said there were two ways the team could go: ``Stay together, grow
together, get better, and add to it, or say it's not that good,
break it all up, or blow it apart. That's a decision you make.
We're not at that (blow it up) stage. Paul Pierce is basically a
rookie. Adrian Griffin is a rookie. Vitaly Potapenko is young. Tony
Battie is young. Let these guys grow together. That's how I feel.''
. . . Griffin will finish up his five-game minimum stay on the
injured list Monday. The Celtics return home for games Wednesday
(Toronto) and Friday (Seattle) . . . Pitino said he really enjoyed
the 2 1/2-hour train ride to Washington after the New Jersey game.
``It was fun. You guys (in the media) should have come,'' he said,
forgetting that the media is not invited to travel with the team.
``There were big tables, very good bonding.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
