<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7869 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-JONES-TELESCO-BOS     01-17 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JONES-TELESCO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES KEEPS TITLE _ SINGLE-HANDEDLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What do Pedro Martinez and Roy Jones Jr. have in
common?
</P>
<P>
   They both can pitch a shutout with one hand.
</P>
<P>
   That is the norm for the Red Sox ace, but usually the undisputed
light heavyweight champion needs both hands to complete his work.
Saturday night he would have liked to have had that luxury, but he
did not, so he accomplished the same goal with half his weaponry
instead, and made it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   That would be considered remarkable for most professional
fighters, but with Jones it might have gone unnoticed had he not
mentioned it after the decision was announced. The bout could not
have been more one-sided if the champion had had three healthy
hands.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading up to Saturday's first-ever fight at Radio
City Music Hall, challenger David Telesco kept saying he'd had a
dream about what would happen there and would share it after the
fight. When the dream turned into a nightmare of Jones's right
hands to the face, however, he not only kept mum about his dream,
he kept well-hidden.
</P>
<P>
   Too embarrassed by his performance to come to the post-fight
news conference, Telesco sent his apologies via his promoter after
losing every round to a fighter who had fractured his left wrist 3
1/2 weeks earlier in a motorcycle accident back home in Pensacola,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   There's no telling how much damage Jones might have done if he
had been healthy, but he did enough to restructure Telesco's face
in a way that forced the Port Chester, N.Y., native to use
sunglasses after the fight ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it took a while, but sometimes you have to do it that
way,'' Jones (41-1) said after throwing 494 punches, according to
CompuBox statistics, with about 85 percent coming from the same
direction.
</P>
<P>
   That knowledge didn't help poor Telesco, who was so much slower
that only one round _ the seventh _ was even remotely competitive.
Yet after the judges' cards of Melvina Latham, Luis Rivera, and Sid
Rubenstein were read and not one gave Telesco a round, the
challenger muttered ``I thought I did enough to win.''
</P>
<P>
   One assumes he was speaking of Round 7 or speaking with a
concussion, because under no other circumstances would those words
have made the remotest sense.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening bell, it was clear that the 12-1 underdog's
hand speed was no match for Jones, who proves time and again he is
without peer in his weight class and, perhaps, in any class,
pound-for-pound.
</P>
<P>
   No one is more aware of that than Jones, whose disdain for his
opponents is clear each time he fights. Saturday it was obvious
when the curtain rose on the Music Hall's stage, and Jones was
standing smack in the middle of a lineup of Radio City Rockettes,
high kicking with the best of them barely an hour before the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Jones's lack of concern for Telesco's challenge or his own
health was apparent then, but had anyone known of his injury, his
nonchalance would have been even more evident. What was obvious
immediately was that Telesco would not stop Jones's rapier right
hand with anything but his face most of the night. After just three
minutes, both of Telesco's cheekbones were red, and they only would
become more so as the fight wore on. But they were not as red as
they would become after the scorecards were read and he had not won
a round.
</P>
<P>
   Telesco was ready to dispute that, if nothing else, but arguably
he didn't win a single moment of a single round, although in the
seventh he at least landed several short hooks, and in the fifth he
drilled Jones in the body on several occasions when the champion
chose to stand deep in a neutral corner and wave Telesco in to
attack.
</P>
<P>
   At first, a wary Telesco (23-3) refused to budge, but finally
the target was too inviting, so he attacked. It didn't make a bit
of difference, just as Jones's broken wrist made no difference
except that it probably was the only reason Telesco finished the
night on his feet. In the fight game, you thank your lucky stars
for such tender mercies.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps emboldened or maybe just embarrassed, Telesco began to
taunt the champion midway through the fight, trying to turn a
boxing match into a street brawl that might have been more to his
advantage. He got nothing out of those efforts but a few more right
hands to the face and a brief conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You ever been in prison?' '' Jones explained when
asked what the former convict had to say to him. ``I said, `No, and
I don't plan on going.' I have to give him credit. The guy is
tough. But that's a hell of a thing to ask me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not when you're being mugged by a one-armed man, it isn't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 0103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
