<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BREAKUP?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY DID BILL GATES HIT THE ALT.CONTROL BUTTONS?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This insightful 650-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``f'' financial news and ``a'' domestic/general
news files.)  
  
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Computer industry analysts and stock traders dithered
Friday. Does Bill Gates's move to the newly-created job of ``chief
software officer'' mean Microsoft is set for breakup, a merger with
some new media company, or simply tackling the challenge of
competing in the Internet-driven marketplace?
</P>
<P>
   For computer users, the more important question is: is this the
beginning of the end for Microsoft, or a rebirth of the 25-year-old
company?
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives insisted there were no Machiavellian plans,
that they expected neither a breakup or a merger, and their true
intent was to get Microsoft in shape for the challenges of
competing operating systems such as Linux, of wireless and handheld
devices and of emerging Internet-centered software systems.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft does need to catch up fast there. Linux is used by a
growing number of companies.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's operating system for handheld devices, WindowsCE, is
a poor third and losing touch in a fast-growing market. It has
struggled to make itself known in the wireless trade, forecast to
be huge in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Allen, Microsoft's co-founder, who has long since left the
company, said categorically: ``Anyone who thinks this is a reaction
to the lawsuit...is getting it completely wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's share price did nothing but rise following
Thursday's announcement, floating gently up in after-hours trading
then gaining a further two points in Friday morning's session to
around $110.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts saw Gates's decision to abandon the top slot in
favor of his deputy Steve Ballmer as a positive development. But
others wondered if the share price movement did not have more to do
with the anticipation of a corporate carve-up: if it followed the
telephone company AT&AMP;T, which was broken up in the 1980s, Microsoft
stockholders would end up even richer.
</P>
<P>
   It came at the end of a week of wild news development and even
wilder rumors.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday came the announcement of America Online's megamerger
with Time Warner; Wednesday brought whispers from the Justice
Department that it might split Microsoft into two or more pieces to
end its operating system monopoly, and late on Thursday came
Gates's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Cause and effect? Or an admission that Ballmer was a better
manager?
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft insists Gates will have plenty on his hands, trying to
control the work on Windows2000, a new version of the
``industrial-strength'' operating system due for release in
February. It will run the back offices of the world's banks and
businesses, but is horrendously late and bug-ridden.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department also put in a touch on the tiller, saying
the whispers had been misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Gates intended to oversee the development of new technology
personally, in his twin new roles as chairman and chief software
architect, while Ballmer would conduct day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts broadly accepted this version of events. ``For
Gates, I believe that this is about making the Internet work for
Microsoft,'' said Rick Sherlund of Goldman Sachs. ``That's where
his heart is.''
</P>
<P>
   But one source close to the company quoted in the San Jose
Mercury News, the Silicon Valley daily, said the reshuffle at the
top might have been an attempt to reassure nervous executives as
they make contingency plans for a possible breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the team managers have plans ready...'' the source
said. ``But what they're concerned about is how Gates will react if
he's forced to do it. If he's backed into a corner, he might
explode.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts reacted with alarm at Gates' statement that ``in
the revolution ahead of us, software will be at the center,''
saying the opposite was true.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' replacement with a man of similar temperament and ideas
was thus a sign of weakness and inflexibility, they said. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 650-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
