<SLUG> BC-SOC-SOCNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOULD CONSIDER PLAYING IN IRAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHARD GONZALEZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PASADENA, Calif. _ Following the 1-1 draw with Iran on Sunday
at the Rose Bowl, U.S. coach Bruce Arena was asked if the U.S.
would consider playing a friendly in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   In their only other meeting, Iran beat the U.S. 2-1 during the
1998 World Cup in France. A group of U.S. wrestlers visited Iran in
1998, but no other sports team has visited Iran since the 1979
hostage crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were invited, I'm sure it is an invitation we would
strongly consider,'' Arena said. ``There's lot of issues involved,
whether we could fit it in, but I would not be opposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get involved in the politics. I don't know the reality
of the situation. But having played today, we would love to play
Iran again.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Unfriendly confines: So just how many Americans were among
the Rose Bowl crowd of 50,181, you ask?
</P>
<P>
   Other than a collection from ``Sam's Army'' deposited over the
tunnel entrance to the U.S. locker room, not many.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources within the USSF, only about 3,000 tickets
were purchased by Americans during the initial wave of selling
early last month. Shortly thereafter, the Iranian federation was
allowed to purchase the tickets, with supporters doing so en masse
as the sales figure immediately ballooned to 34,000.
</P>
<P>
   By the look of Sunday's overwhelming throng donning the red,
white and green, the ratio obviously never eased during the final
month of sales.
</P>
<P>
   __ Wasted fuel: The one blown investment on game day went to the
poor soul who paid for a plane to fly overhead with a banner that
read, ``Go Eric the Cannon Wynalda.''
</P>
<P>
   Wynalda, at age 30 and in the twilight of his career, was not
among the players on the 18-man roster declared by Arena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
