<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACING-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GREAT DAY FOR DIXIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif._ Even before Pat Valenzuela rode Dixie Dot Com
for the first time in the San Pasqual Handicap, the rider and the
horse had something in common. Each was working on a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Each took a big step in a return to the top Sunday as Valenzuela
put Dixie Dot Com in perfect position behind a swift front-runner
and the 5-year-old responded with a 1-length victory over Budroyale
in the San Pasqual.
</P>
<P>
   For Dixie Dot Com, the victory came a year to the day after his
latest win, in the San Fernando Stakes, in which he went to the top
of his class locally but suffered a leg fracture that forced a
nearly eight-month layoff.
</P>
<P>
   For Valenzuela, the Grade II San Pasqual marked his first
graded-stakes victory since the 1996 Del Mar Handicap aboard
Dernier Empereur, before the Kentucky Derby-winning jockey's
two-year suspension for drug-related absences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of seconds and thirds lately,'' Valenzuela
said, listing stakes near-misses Straight Man, Stormy Jack, Classy
Lady and Mr. Broad Blade. ``Today the good Lord blessed us with a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela, who finished second to Laffit Pincay in the jockey
standings at Hollywood Park, the second meet since his license was
restored, is tied for fourth in the Santa Anita standings with 13
wins. But victories in big races like the $200,000 San Pasqual have
eluded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it's like you guys wrote when I started back `We'll
see what happens,' '' Valenzuela said. He thinks major trainers and
owners have taken a wait-and-see approach with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame them at all,'' he said. ``But now they're
putting me on good horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixie Dot Com ($11.20) lived up to that description again in
Sunday's 1 1/16-mile race after finishing out of the money in the
first three starts of his comeback, two on the Hollywood Park turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, when this horse ran so well in the San Fernando, we
were talking about all the big things we had planned for him,''
trainer Bill Morey said, apparently wanting not to tempt fate.
``I'm going to be a little more conservative now until we see how
he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, Dixie Dot Com, a winner of 6 of 13 starts, will aim
for the Feb. 6 San Antonio and March 4 Santa Anita Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Budroyale, racing for the first time since he was runner-up to
Cat Thief in the Breeders' Cup Classic, was left with too much
ground to make up in the San Pasqual. The favorite finished 1
lengths in front of pacesetter Six Below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe as he's getting older, he doesn't have the (early) speed
he used to have,'' trainer Ted H. West said. ``Maybe he's more of a
mile-and-a-quarter horse now.''
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero, a top handicap horse a year ago, finished last in
the six-horse race, disappointing trainer Richard Mandella, who
thought the 6-year-old's recovery from ulcers would signal a return
to form.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: The 1999 Eclipse Award winners will be announced
tonight at a dinner in Beverly Hills. Horse of the Year is down to
sprinter Artax, Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner Charismatic and
Breeders' Cup Turf winner Daylami. . . . Olympic Charmer ($4.40)
ran her record to 6 for 12 by inching past Her She Kisses in the El
Encino Stakes for 4-year-old fillies Sunday, extending her winning
range to 1 1/16 miles. . . . Three-year-old War Chant is an
impressive 2 for 2 after a 1 1/16-mile allowance win. . . . Jockey
Brice Blanc wasn't seriously hurt in a fall after Biker Dude broke
down at the top of the stretch in a turf sprint. The horse had to
be destroyed. . . . Bobby Frankel has favorites Spanish Fern and
Keeper Hill as the trainer tries for his fourth San Gorgonio
Handicap in five years on the 12:30 p.m. Martin Luther King Day
program. . . . Kelly Kip finished fourth behind winner Mountain Top
in Gulfstream Park's Hallandale Beach Handicap in the sprint star's
return from a hock infection.
</P>
</TEXT>
