<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 03:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7893 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-ONPOLITICS-RUNNING-MA     01-17 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONPOLITICS-RUNNING-MATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INSIDERS SPECULATE ON POSSIBLE BUSH TICKET  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;       c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The best buzz from the Republican National Committee meeting this
week in San Jose, Calif. _ heavy-duty George W. Bush country _ was
about who the GOP front-runner might pick as a running mate if it
goes the way they hope.
<P>
   Bush doesn't have it locked up, but that isn't stopping anyone
from speculating.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, who's putting up a good fight in New
Hampshire, has said he isn't interested. Some Republicans here said
no matter: McCain's too much of a maverick to be controlled as a
vice presidential candidate. Besides, how can he suddenly start
toning down his campaign finance stance when he's on stage with
Bush?
</P>
<P>
   And there's Gen. Colin Powell, who also pooh-poohs the idea. So?
``He's definitely in play,'' said one knowing RNC official. ``And a
Bush-Powell ticket would blow the Democrats away.''
</P>
<P>
   That didn't go over well with a top conservative GOP voice. He
said Powell's ``Rockefeller Republican'' outlook and pro-choice
style would ``send conservatives walking, absolutely.'' Same for
New Jersey Gov. Christine Whitman, also pro-choice.
</P>
<P>
   So the conventional wisdom among Republican activists here goes
like this: Bush may go with the gut and make a surprise pick _ a la
Dan Quayle _ or he can get strategic.
</P>
<P>
   So there are plenty of Republicans who are furiously
strategizing for him. Their views of who's hot (and who's not):
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of ONPOLITI () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &UR; _ California Rep. Christopher Cox: &LR;  No kidding. The argument is
that Bush has Texas in the bag. He's got a good shot at Florida,
thanks to brother Jeb. ``If someone can deliver California, you can
put a fork in it _ they're (Democrats) done,'' said one RNC biggie.
Newport Beach, Calif.'s Cox is one of the brainiest folks on
Capitol Hill, an anti-Quayle, if you will. He's often been
discussed for a statewide run. He's well known to the Republican
base. He's strong on China _ witness the Cox Report _ with strong
foreign affairs credentials. He's anti-abortion, and he's Catholic,
a strong voting bloc that can deliver big-time. The downside: even
a sharp congressman like Cox is not well known in Northern
California, never mind outside the state. A long shot, but an
interesting one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ California Rep. David Dreier:  &LR; Like Cox, Southern
California's Dreier is one of two California congressmen often
mentioned for higher office. He's attractive (word is that he
recently dated Bo Derek). He's got solid support from state
Republicans. But could he deliver California? See ``downside'' of
Cox argument.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Sen. Richard Lugar, Illinois: &LR;  Midwest powerhouse, foreign
affairs heavy, smart guy, big credentials. GOPers are talking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Gov. Tom Ridge, Pennsylvania: &LR;  Big governor from a Northeast
state, a plus. High-tech savvy; has hit big in Silicon Valley,
another plus. Catholic, another plus. Pro-choice. ``A pro-choice
Catholic? That would be an insult to Catholics,'' said one top
GOPer, who says that puts Ridge out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Gov. George Pataki, New York: &LR;  The top insider of a rival
campaign insists that this will be the ticket. Pro-choice also, but
if he can deliver New York ...
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Elizabeth Dole: &LR;  It's over. High profile, good name, good
campaigner, sure. But GOPers here rule her out for one reason:
``The bumper sticker.'' Besides, she hasn't proved she can deliver
women voters, and Bush doesn't seem to have a gender gap problem
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Governors John Engler of Michigan and Tommy Thompson of &LR; 
 &UR; Wisconsin:  &LR; Loyal and big names, considered on the short list last
time around. This time, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Senator John Ashcroft: &LR;  ``The Christian Coalition loves him,
just loves him,'' said one leading RNC conservative. Plus, Ashcroft
has ex-staffers and supporters in place high inside the Bush team,
so he's got a cheering section making his case. ``There've been
discussions already on this one,'' the conservative said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
