<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 03:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7900 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     01-17 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FASTER THAN A SPEEDING JUDGE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Bad, bad boy Jack Bokin bolted out of the Hall of Justice in San
Francisco on Friday, chased by deputies and the judge who was about
to hand down sentence. I give it three weeks before that scene
winds up on a TV cop show.
<P>
   In the office pool, I'll take ``Nash Bridges.'' And in the
Hollywood version, guaranteed, the judge makes the tackle, robes
flowing, and Nash growls at the bad guy, ``Justice is swift,
Bubba.''
</P>
<P>
   In real life it was a deputy who made the flying tackle, and
maybe the 49ers' search for a tough and speedy cornerback is over.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad for Bad Jack that he didn't make it as far as the
McDonald's on the corner next to the Hall of Justice, where they
might have affirmed his efforts by saying, ``You deserve a break
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bokin, convicted of rape and attempted murder, was about to be
sent up the lazy river for 246 lazy years when he split, and as
Matt Regan says, ``Talk about your run-on sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming soon: Judges' shoes by Nike-Air Jailbreak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE OPPOSITE &LR;  of a jailbreak looms for P.J. Carlesimo, recently
fired as coach of the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   After years of firing girlfriends under his ``Three Dates and
You're Out'' policy/philosophy, P.J. has got himself engaged.
</P>
<P>
   They met at Moose's Restaurant in North Beach a year ago, but
probably won't hold the reception there. Not long after meeting the
love of his life, Carlesimo spirited away Moose's general manager,
Bob Mulhern, and they partnered up to open the lively P.J.
Mulhern's just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNCLEAR ON THE CONCEPT:  &LR; Women.com released on Monday its list
of the 10 most eligible bachelors in Silicon Valley. Basically,
they're computer dweebs who work 20-hour days, which makes them
most eligible for what? Heart attacks? Hemorrhoids?
</P>
<P>
   Technically, they are available because nine of the 10 guys are
not romantically involved with anything but a keyboard. But who
knows? If the right woman comes along and the chemistry clicks, any
one of these cyberstuds might be willing to squeeze a torrid
romance into his midday vending-machine break.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT'S THE DEAL?  &LR; I turned on the TV on Sunday, and they're
still playing NFL football. Isn't the season over?
</P>
<P>
   The heartwarming story of the playoffs, and possibly the
SuperBowl, is the woebegone St. Louis Rams and their castoff
quarterback, Kurt Warner.
</P>
<P>
   However, we're also going to have to hear songs of praise for
Rams' team owner Georgia Frontiere. She inherited the Rams after
the mysterious death of her husband Dominic, and her crowning
achievements as an owner so far have been to exaggerate her golf
handicap in her media-guide bio, to kiss players on the sidelines
and to be the first sports owner to have a luxury box with a hot
tub.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Georgia fits right into the cartoonish club of
pro sports team owners.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WITH ALL &LR;  the new quiz shows _ ``Greed,'' ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire?'' and ``Who Wants to Be a Greedy Millionaire?'' _ what
if they run out of questions?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THERE'S GLOOM &LR;  at the Boom Boom Room, John Lee Hooker's blues
club.
</P>
<P>
   They've pulled the plug on a big mural project, which had Willie
Brown's enthusiastic support and was to grace the side of the club
facing Geary Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   It boils down to some neighborhood backroom bickering, and the
result is the area and the city being deprived of a colorful
tribute to the rich musical and cultural heritage of the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NAME CHANGE:  &LR; After Friday night's festivities, shouldn't they
change the name of the Oakland Alameda County Arena to the OK
Corral?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, even though it's the home of the Warriors, who can't shoot
straight.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEY CAME, &LR;  they saw, they flopped onto the dock and called it
home.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, the sea lions hauled themselves onto the dock
outside Pier 39, so the pier will hold an anniversary celebration
next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   As my travel agent Seymour Seitz says, their arrival was a hell
of a lot easier and cheaper than bringing in a pro sports
franchise. Besides, the seals are more entertaining than the
well-paid Warriors, and so far they haven't threatened to leave
town if the city doesn't build them a new, splinter-free dock.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's too touristy to check out the sea lions, but I
watched 'em for a half hour recently, and it's a great show. Two
males battled for possession of one dock and its load of females.
Honk if you're horny.
</P>
<P>
   It's what you won't see in Silicon Valley _ eligible bachelors
with time to spend on women.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEWARE,  &LR; says Berkeley Bob, of creeping Los Angelesism.
</P>
<P>
   Bob heard a radio ad for a new Home Depot in Livermore, ``near
the 580.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoa! Who wrote that ad? As every L.A.-to-the-Bay transplant
quickly learns, up here you don't put a ``the'' in front of the
freeway number. In L.A., you take the 605 to the 405. Here you take
101 to 280.
</P>
<P>
   Says Berkeley Bob, ``Before Home Depot decides that we have to
call 880 `the 880,' we should link arms and shut the puppy down.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALSO CREEPING &LR;  into town from Lozzzangeles: the Cheesecake
Factory, a SoCal franchise coming soon to Macy's at Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   On the menu: Herb roasted chicken. If they make a subtle change,
to Herb roasted squab, they'll be paying a nice tribute to the
lategreat Mr. Caen, who never met a pigeon he wouldn't rather see
roasted or toasted than roosted.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AND SPEAKING &LR;  of lategreats, happy holiday to you, Dr. King.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ostler's column appears Monday through Friday. You can
reach him at (415) 777-7031, fax him at (415) 896-1107 or send him
an e-mail at ostler &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
