<HEADER>
A7960 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-DENZEL-WASHINGTON-IN-     01-17 1442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENZEL-WASHINGTON-IN-THE-HURRICANE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENZEL WASHINGTON FIGHTS THE GOOD FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Denzel
Washington in a scene from ``The Hurricane.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Denzel Washington knows about the urge to fight the whole world
until you get what you want, but he also knows what it is to need
help, even if you aren't willing to admit you do.
 &HT;    Those twin impulses have informed many of the characters he's
created on film, most notably his interpretation of boxer Rubin
``Hurricane'' Carter in the new film, ``The Hurricane.'' But
they've also figured prominently in his own story.
 &HT;    ``My mother saved my life,'' he says bluntly, looking back on
his early teens in Mount Vernon, N.Y., when he began hanging out
with a bad crowd. ``My mother got tough and said, `You're going to
boarding school.' And she sent me away.
 &HT;    ``The rest of the guys in the bunch I was pals with ended up in
prison.''
 &HT;    Now 45, Washington knows prison only secondhand, as an actor
playing prisoners such as Carter. Offscreen, he has become not only
a solid citizen, happily married and the father of four, but also
the biggest African-American star since Sidney Poitier, taking home
$12 million per movie.
 &HT;    Playing heroes is Washington's forte _ he's provided the moral
center for films such as ``Cry Freedom'' (l987), ``Malcolm X''
(l992) and ``Courage Under Fire'' (l996), and earned a Best
Supporting Actor Oscar for his performance as an embittered runaway
slave who finds new self-respect in ``Glory'' (l989).
 &HT;    But Washington doesn't look for squeaky-clean, comic-book leads.
His characters are troubled loners whose heroism is mingled with a
deep distrust of those around them and even of their own
self-worth.
 &HT;    His most recent film roles are both heroes, but could hardly be
more different from each other. In ``The Bone Collector'' (1999) he
plays a quadriplegic detective who substitutes brain for brawn, an
intense but dispassionate thinking machine who teams up with a
female cop (Angelina Jolie) to pursue a serial killer.
 &HT;    In ``The Hurricane,'' on the other hand, Washington plays the
real-life middleweight fighter Rubin Carter, a passionate dynamo
whose fury in the ring _ which he himself says was driven by his
hatred of the world around him _ earned him the nickname
``Hurricane.''
 &HT;    Carter's dreams of a world championship were shattered in l967,
when he was framed and wrongfully convicted of gunning down three
people in a New Jersey bar. But that was only the beginning of his
story, says Washington, who is being touted for a Best Actor Ocar
for his gripping performance.
 &HT;    When his story first became public, Carter's case became the
fashionable cause du jour for a number of celebrities. Fellow boxer
Muhammad Ali rallied to his defense, and Bob Dylan wrote a hit song
about the case, ``Hurricane.'' Carter won a second trial _ only to
be convicted again.
 &HT;    And then, as suddenly as it had begun, everything stopped.
 &HT;    ``I learned that Rubin went through an incredible spiritual
journey after his second trial also ended in conviction,''
Washington says. ``All the celebrities who had jumped on his
bandwagon abandoned him _ even Muhammad Ali dropped out. So he went
inside himself.''
 &HT;    Washington understood that kind of retreat.
 &HT;    ``I come from a very religious family,'' the actor says. ``My
father was a Pentecostal minister who worked two churches and was
this spirit-filled man until the day he died. My mother owned a
beauty parlor, and she was even more religious than he was.
 &HT;    ``But it was an oil-and-water marriage,'' he adds. ``My mother
was an urban woman raised in Harlem, my father a very rural man.''
 &HT;    The two eventually divorced in l969 _ his father died in 1991 _
and it was a bitter blow to the insecure young man. That's when his
mother sent him to a private school, the Oakland Academy in New
Windsor, N.Y., to get him away from his neighborhood pals.
 &HT;    At his new school Washington became an athlete, played in the
band and showed some interest in the arts. But only while studying
at New York's Fordham University in the mid-1970s was he bitten by
the acting bug.
 &HT;    ``That was my niche,'' he says. ``Until then I was
floundering.''
 &HT;    After achieving success in the theater, he was cast as Dr.
Phillip Chandler on the hit medical show ``St. Elsewhere''
(l982-1988). It wasn't long before he broke onto the big screen
with a series of eye-catching parts, including the escaped slave in
``Glory,'' South African activist Stephen Biko in ``Cry Freedom,''
the title role in ``Malcolm X'' and the homophobic lawyer in the
AIDS drama ``Philadelphia'' (1993).
 &HT;    Today he lives in a new, suitably grand Beverly Hills home with
his wife, Pauletta, and their four children _ 15-year-old John
David, 12-year-old Katia and 8-year-old twins, Malcolm and Olivia.
 &HT;    ``Pauletta is the rock that holds our marriage together,''
Washington says. ``Like my mother she's a deeply religious woman,
and I feel that is extremely important for our children. I know how
it helped shape my own life.
 &HT;    ``We go to church regularly, and we pray together several times
each day at home.''
 &HT;    And it isn't only prayer: The actor recently donated $5 million
to the Los Angeles church he and his family attend, the Church of
God in Christ.
 &HT;    Washington says he has been intrigued by Carter's story ever
since reading the fighter's autobiography, ``The Sixteenth Round''
(Viking, 1974). When he finally got the chance to play the role, it
came with a big bonus: At the helm was director Norman Jewison, who
had given him his breakthrough role in ``A Soldier's Story''
(1984).
 &HT;    To prepare for the role, Washington hired a boxing trainer and
began working out a year ahead of time.
 &HT;    ``I was filming `The Bone Collector,''' he recalls, ``and that
meant as the paralyzed cop I had to spend the entire day in bed. So
at the end of every day's shooting I rushed to the gym and worked
out for four hours every night. I knew that the only way I could do
justice to playing Rubin was to look the part when I stepped into
the ring.
 &HT;    ``Norman Jewison told me, `No special effect in the world is
going to make you look like a trim fighting machine. You've got to
do that,''' he adds. ``I had 18 months to lose 44 pounds and
reshape the body I had let go to pot.''
 &HT;    ``The Hurricane'' isn't only Carter's story, however. It also
traces the evolution of a young, troubled African-American boy who,
after reading ``The Sixteenth Round,'' began writing to the
imprisoned boxer. The young Lesra Martin, played in the film by
Vicellous Reon Shannon, interested his Canadian guardians in the
case, and it was their efforts which ultimately led to Carter's
freedom.
 &HT;    ``My main goal with this movie is to make sure we get it into
the schools,'' Washington says. ``I think it's very important for
African-American youths to see that anything is possible. This is
Lesra's story as much as Rubin's _ his parents were alcoholics, he
came from a ghetto and he rose above it all to become a lawyer.
 &HT;    ```Hurricane' shows that sometimes it takes great suffering for
people to realize that, to overcome the hate _ whether it's hate of
other people or hate of being unfairly locked up _ only love can
break you free.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The Hurricane,'' consult the
official Website at www.the-hurricane.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
