 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY - No. 2610 - January 17, 2000 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. FIDEL CASTRO'S CUSTODY BATTLE OVER HIS SON
</P>
<P>
   Interview by Jacki Lyden - National Public Radio Long before the
world knew of Elian Gonzalez, there was another 6-year-old Cuban
boy who also found himself in the middle of two battling forces. He
was known as ``Fidelito'' - actually Felix Fidel Castro Diaz - and
he was the young son of a rebel fighter named Fidel Castro. (This
commentary is adapted from an interview with Ann Louise Bardach,
visiting professor of international journalism at the University of
California in Santa Barbara. It was conducted on January 15 by
Jacki Lyden, senior correspondent for National Public Radio and
weekend host of ``All Things Considered.'') 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   2. WHAT NO SCHOOL CAN DO
</P>
<P>
   By James Traub - The New York Times Magazine A child living in
an inner city is in school for only so many hours. It's the rest of
the day - as well as the rest of the neighbourhood - that is the
big influence and the problem. Full-length (7,300 words) + edited
article available.
</P>
<P>
   3. THE GLOBAL WILLOWBROOK
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Winerip - The New York Times Magazine Humane
treatment for the mentally ill is the newest goal of human rights
activists, whose current target is Mexico's decrepit institutions.
Yet practically everywhere they go - Uruguay, Argentina,
Azerbaijan, Rumania, Russia - they see disabled men and women who
could live in the real-life community left to rot in remote asylums
that are worse than most prisons. Full-length (5,000 words) +
edited article available.
</P>
<P>
   4. HONOR DR. KING WITH PROGRESS, NOT SAINTHOOD
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Eric Dyson - The New York Times Magazine The official
story of a saintly Dr. Martin King Jr. has whitewashed the truth
that America harshly resisted his call to do the right thing. It
silenced the more radical aspects of King's challenge - his
advocacy of racial compensation, his attempt to destroy poverty,
his democratic socialist beliefs, his opposition to the Vietnam
War. Most of all, it placed him far beyond the reach of mere
mortals. His flesh-and-blood struggles - and failures - became
easily dismissed as mere preamble to his inevitable ascension.
1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   5. FUTURE TECH : CHIPS IN CHARGE
</P>
<P>
   By Ivan Amato - Discover Magazine These days, you never really
drive a car alone. Hidden beneath the glass-and-steel skin of a car
may be hidden computers that offer navigational tips, improved
control and the ability to call for assistance when something goes
wrong. This is only the beginning of the end of your automotive
autonomy. Before long, silicon chips will decide how you should
behave on the road, or whether you should be on the road at all.
Auto electronics mean that you will be behind the wheel, but won't
really be in the driver's seat. 1,300 words + photo.
</P>
<P>
   6. FROM MEDICAL PRESSCORPS NEWS SERVICE :
</P>
<P>
   (a) Scientists Develop Mice That May Aid Study of Diabetes In a
development that could lead to improved treatments for diabetes,
researchers have genetically engineered a mouse strain that
produces increased amounts of insulin. These mice were more
resistant to an experimental form of diabetes. 500 words. (b)
Protein Indicates Whether Breast Cancer Will Spread Scientists have
discovered a biomarker in women with breast cancer. Biomarkers are
proteins found in varying levels in early breast cancers that can
indicate whether the cancer is likely to spread. 500 words. (c)
Longer Antibiotic Treatment Far Better For Sore Throat For the
treatment of a sore throat, a penicillin regimen lasting seven days
is better than one lasting three. 500 words. (d) Sunscreen Numbers
Said To Confuse Consumers A doctor argues that sun-protection
factors on sunscreen packaging are misleading and should be changed
in favour of terms such as ``low,'' ``medium,'' ``high'' and
``ultrahigh,'' which would be more readily understood. 500 words.
(e) High Degree of Detail Possible with 3-D Ultrasound The advent
of three-dimensional ultrasound is helping doctors gain
unparalleled insight into the human body by allowing a view of
internal structures and functions with amazing clarity. This new
technology enables doctors to observe fetal development and
diagnose abnormalities with improved rates of accuracy. 500 words.
</P>
