<SLUG> BC-TREK-THE-OTHERS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTRODUCING THE OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of the cast of
``The Others.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    The Others are getting ready to take off.
 &HT;    It's 9:45 a.m. on Stage 24 at Paramount Pictures' Hollywood lot,
and director Tobe Hooper watches intently as a group of actors
rehearse a scene in a cramped airplane set. Gabriel Macht, John
Billingsley, Melissa Crider, Bill Cobbs, Kevin J. O'Connor and John
Aylward are all seated as Julianne Nicholson steps into the aisle.
 &HT;    ``Ah, the prodigal daughter,'' Aylward says, his voice dripping
with sarcasm.
 &HT;    Nicholson acknowledges the comment with a slight smirk.
 &HT;    ``Hi, everybody,'' she says softly, plopping down next to Cobbs.
 &HT;    For the next 20 minutes, Hooper choreographs this exchange, a
quiet moment before all hell breaks loose. And on ``The Others,'' a
supernatural creepfest debuting Feb. 5 on NBC, hell hath a distinct
habit of breaking loose.
 &HT;    ``The Others'' centers on several people blessed _ or cursed _
with otherworldly powers, who band together in an effort to
understand and harness their abilities. In the process, they
unshackle the restless spirits of the dead and ease the pain of
loved ones left behind.
 &HT;    Hooper, who directed 1982's chilling ``Poltergeist,'' is only
one of the nifty genre names attached to ``The Others.'' The series
comes from Dreamworks Television, and Dreamworks co-founder Steven
Spielberg reportedly works closely with executive producers Glen
Morgan and James Wong, veterans of ``The X-Files'' and
``Millennium.''
 &HT;    Back on the set, Hooper seems satisfied. He lets the actors take
a break so that crewmen can position lights and the camera in
preparation for filming.
 &HT;    ``This episode is called `Souls on Board,''' says Billingsley,
who plays Miles Ballard, a college professor who supervises the
Others' gatherings and believes in paranormal phenomena, but has no
gifts of his own. ``This plane is flying the same route as another
one which crashed.
 &HT;    ``The plane is the same airline, same make and model number as
the one that crashed,'' he says. ``The route has been renumbered,
but people flying it are experiencing strange manifestations.
They're seeing ghosts of the passengers and crew who died in
previous flights.
 &HT;    ``I finagle our way on board without telling anyone what I'm up
to,'' Billingsley adds. ``I'm caught and have to reveal my
purposes.''
 &HT;    The actor smiles.
 &HT;    ``Sure enough,'' he says ominously, ``strange things start to
happen.''
 &HT;    Over in his trailer, Bill Cobbs takes a few minutes to relax. He
plays Elmer Greentree, the Others' 83-year-old spiritual guide and
mentor to Marian (Nicholson), the group's newest and potentially
most powerful member.
 &HT;    Cobbs is pleased that the producers of ``The Others'' cast an
African-American actor in so pivotal a role as Elmer. But the
former star of ``I'll Fly Away'' wants more.
 &HT;    ``We know we've had this problem for a while, but in 1999 we had
even fewer African-Americans, Native Americans, Asian-Americans
and, really, any minorities working in Hollywood at any level,'' he
says forcefully. ``There also doesn't seem to be much concern about
changing that.
 &HT;    ``The problem still exists,'' Cobbs says, ``and I just have to
be mindful of that and realize I'm very fortunate to be working.
But the fact that I have a job doesn't make the situation all
better.
 &HT;    ``A lot more minorities need to be working and stay working
before things start to get better,'' he adds. ``It's nice for me to
be employed, but it's not a fantastic accomplishment to be the only
black face on the show.''
 &HT;    Nearby, Melissa Crider sits on the bed in her trailer. The
actress co-stars as Satori, a New Age-ish psychic who will soon
enter into a love triangle with Marian and Mark Gabriel (Macht), an
empathic medical intern.
 &HT;    Crider's genre credits include ``Millennium'' and ``Strange
World.''
 &HT;    ``I wasn't sure I wanted to do a series,'' says Crider, a
striking combination of big blue eyes, spiky blonde hair and
contagious energy. ``I love going into a job, letting a character
live in me and then telling her `Goodbye.'
 &HT;    ``My characters would have to start paying rent if they stayed
more than a couple of months,'' she says. ``But I love Satori. I
love all the characters and this whole group of actors.
 &HT;    ``As a viewer, just based on the pilot, I feel I've known some
of the characters, or people like them, throughout my life,''
Crider says. ``I think that's all a part of my excitement.''
 &HT;    The possibility of a long run for ``The Others'' no longer
horrifies Crider.
 &HT;    ``We're dealing with a show where the sky is not the limit,''
she says. ``We're beyond the beyond.
 &HT;    ``That makes me feel we'll have enough oxygen to breathe.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
