   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GOLAN-SKI (Golan Heights, Israel) _ In an Israeli village that
owns and operates a popular ski resort, residents adamantly oppose
the return of the Golan Heights to Syria. The region is one of the
more contentious issue in the budding peace talks between the two
longtime adversaries. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   RIO-FERTILITY (Rio De Janeiro, Brazil) _ Even by Brazilian
standards, Musa Cipriano comes from a big family. In her home state
of Minas Gerais, her farmer father and mother, a part-time cook,
struggled to support Cipriano and her 10 brothers and sisters.
Cipriano's grandmother bore even more children. We look at the
hardships of rural families. By JENALIA MORENO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PLUG-POWER (Colonie, N.Y.) _ Plug Power, a two-year-old startup
with no marketable product and mounting losses, has made millions
for investors and generated real buzz on Wall Street. And it's not
even a dotcom. The company is poised to produce the first compact,
affordable fuel cell to power homes. By CLAIRE HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   FEATURES/LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Two weeks before a hearing
that could put them on trial, a group of United Methodist ministers
has publicly reaffirmed their blessing of a lesbian couple a year
ago. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SCANDAL (Pasadena, Calif.) _ ``Kick the habit of ludicrously
bad television. Just say no! This message brought to you by the
U.S. government.'' If only the office of the drug czar were this
straightforward about its involvement in prime-time television _
instead of script-doctoring over drug issues _ then it's something
we could get behind. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-TYRELL (Houston) _ Steve Tyrell can't help it. Boosting
the careers of other singers is his nature _ even at the expense of
his own vocal career. After three decades of producing songs for
Elvis Presley, B.J. Thomas, Linda Ronstadt, Rickie Lee Jones and
many others, Tyrell has finally come full-circle on a singing
career that began in his native Houston in the late 1960s. His
rebirth _ the result of a happy accident that found him singing
``The Way You Look Tonight'' for the ``Father of the Bride''
soundtrack _ has earned him a record deal, a just-released album
titled ``A New Standard.'' By MICHAEL D. CLARK.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-CAMELS (Big Bend Ranch State Park, Texas) _ There is no
wind, no birdsong, and no highway noise in this stretch of West
Texas. Just the sound of a very annoyed camel getting saddled. And
the absurdity of the situation _ riding a camel _ hasn't warn off.
But when I got off that camel, the swagger in my walk was more than
just crippling pain and swelling. For I'm a real cowgirl. I am
tough. Man, I rode that camel. By EMILY SPICER. (Photos available
on Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AUSTRALIA (Anglesea, Australia) _ Travelers in the United
States are familiar with scenic roadways that hug the Pacific Coast
in California and Oregon and the Atlantic from Maine to Florida.
But only along the Great Ocean Road in far south Australia can you
play golf with the kangaroos and pray with the Twelve Apostles, the
most celebrated among numerous spectacular rock formations along
the ``Shipwreck Coast.'' By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   With: TRAVEL-GO-AUSTRALIA
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ It's a familiar dilemma to many
travelers: Too much to see. Too little time. And so it was in
Melbourne, with one short day to tour one of Australia's
fascinating cities. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
