<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8067 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-GOLAN-SKI-HNS &LR;      01-17 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLAN-SKI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKI VILLAGERS SAY THEY WON'T LEAVE GOLAN HEIGHTS IF DEAL IS MADE
WITH SYRIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEVE ATIV, Golan Heights _ It's not yet 9 a.m., but Yitzhak
Tsuela's telephone already is ringing.
</P>
<P>
   The callers are Israelis trying to rent rooms near the ski runs
of Mount Hermon on the Golan Heights. Tsuela, the owner of a small
bed-and-breakfast inn just five minutes from the slopes, politely
turns each one away.
</P>
<P>
   Like other owners of small hotels and inns in this remote
mountain village, his inn is booked solid with vacationers from all
over Israel who want to ski, or simply to see, the glistening white
peaks before they may be returned to Syrian control as part of a
peace deal. Israel captured the strategic plateau from Syria in the
1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   Tsuela, a towering, Paul Bunyan-like man with a thick, graying
beard and muddied hiking boots, refuses even to consider the
prospect of returning the land that Israel captured from Syria in
1967. As he sees it, he will hang a `no-vacancy' sign during the
peak winter seasons for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't leave,'' he says in between taking phone calls. ``I
don't know what I'll do. Maybe, there will be war here between the
Jews. No one can know. But I won't leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk is not unusual for the residents of Neve Ativ. Of the
18,000 Jewish settlers who have moved to the Golan Heights, the
ski-mountain villagers are well known for their rugged
independence.
</P>
<P>
   They developed the lucrative ski slopes, which attract nearly
250,000 visitors each season and are owned collectively by the
families of the village. Some opened restaurants, inns and other
tourist businesses that also bring in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other enterprises on the Golan Heights _ the dairy
farms, cattle ranches and apple orchards _ the ski slopes can't be
moved or replaced.
</P>
<P>
   If the Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak makes a deal with
Syrian President Hafez Assad that includes giving up the heights,
the residents of Neve Ativ may have the most to lose and likely
would refuse to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Established by a small group of men who served in an army
commando unit, the village has attracted the type of settlers who
might just as easily feel at home in the Big Sky Country of
Montana. Many are independent-thinking, well-armed outsdoorsmen who
tend to view the government with suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see the government here,'' Tsuela says. ``I
know Barak did some heroic things in the army, but we don't need
him here.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the peace talks resumed in December, Tsuela's sentiments
have been echoed by about half the Israeli public. The other half
are willing to trade land for peace. But their numbers have been
slipping, according to recent opinion polls, from 45 percent of the
public to about 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, before Barak returned from talks with the Syrians in
Shepherdstown, W.Va., more than 100,000 people gathered in Tel
Aviv's Rabin Square to protest a Golan Heights withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts attribute the decline in support of giving up the Golan
Heights to a perception that Syria is more interested in acquiring
lost territory than in making peace.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, whose opening gambit in the talks reportedly included a
demand for the settlers to remain on the Golan, keeps reminding
Israelis that the talks are about substance, not style. So far,
many Israelis have been disappointed by what they see as a Syrian
cold shoulder. Israeli columnists have repeatedly noted Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa's refusal to even shake Barak's
hand.
</P>
<P>
   From his office on the ski slopes, Menachem Baruch, a resort
manager who also lives in Neve Ativ, notes with satisfaction the
absence of the handshake.
</P>
<P>
   He says it will help to persuade Israelis to vote ``no'' in a
referendum on any deal that would include a hand-over of the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israeli people are stupid and innocent,'' he says, glancing
out of his office window to watch lifts full of skiers go by. ``If
al-Sharaa would have shook Barak's hand, everything would have been
different. We would have been finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, the referendum won't pass,'' he says. ``They can pass
it politically (in the Parliament), but when it comes to a
referendum, the people won't accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baruch says he is encouraged because many Israelis dislike the
notion of relinquishing a plateau full of hiking trails, waterfalls
and the country's only ski resort. But outside in the ski lounge,
some of the visitors sipping hot chocolate on cold wooden benches
say they still believe peace with Syria would mean giving the land
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad but we're happy there will be peace,'' says Ronni
Vardi, a marketing analyst from a town north of Tel Aviv who came
to show his two children the snow.
</P>
<P>
   Gesturing to his children, he says, ``Their not being soldiers
is the most important thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's government has promised that soldiers serving in Lebanon
would be brought home once peace is made with Syria. ``I'm worried
(about giving up land),'' says Vardi, ``but I'm more worried about
the soldiers. It's houses or life, and life is more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many residents of Neve Ativ, Tsuela, the innkeeper, scoffs
at such talk. He sees no connection between Israel giving up the
Golan Heights and withdrawing from southern Lebanon. He says any
link between the Golan and southern Lebanon, where Israeli troops
are fighting a war of attrition against Lebanese guerrillas, was
fabricated by the government as part of a ``psychological war''
against the Golan settlers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had eight years of psychological battle,'' he says,
referring to the time since late Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin took
office in 1992. ``From Rabin until now, we have been told we will
leave here. It's like brainwashing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tsuela moved to Neve Ativ in 1971, he had just left an
Israeli army commando unit responsible for ambushing Arab
guerrillas, sometimes behind enemy lines. Four of the men from his
unit were killed in combat. ``Ativ'' is an acronym derived from
their first names.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Tsuela lived in a tiny bunkerlike house built with
reinforced concrete and steel. After spending years of working on
the ski slopes and in his inn as well as designing cable cars, he
has expanded his small home into a sprawling residence with the inn
out front and a wine cellar in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Life in Neve Ativ, he says, was never meant for the
faint-hearted, the ``vegetarians,'' he calls them. Those who made
it this far, he says, are here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the people here were weak, they wouldn't have been here for
so long,'' he says, slapping the concrete walls to emphasize his
words. ``We're still here. We're not going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
