<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8068 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRALIA-2NDA     01-17 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRALIA-2NDAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
ANGLESEA, Australia: ready for exercise.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 55,000-acre Angahook-Lorne State Park dominates this area,
and more than 30 miles of well-maintained trails encourage hiking _
bushwalking, in Aussie lingo _ through forested valleys teeming
with wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Waterfalls are especially riveting; the most popular is Erskine
Falls, which cascades almost 100 feet into a lovely tree-lined
gully. It's a short drive from Lorne, and an overlook is a
five-minute walk from the car park. Ambitious visitors take steps
to the base of the falls for a closer view.
</P>
<P>
   More bushwalks and waterfalls prove inviting as the route
continues westward toward the communities of Wye River, Kennett
River, Skenes Creek and Apollo Bay. Even from your car, this is one
of the most tantalizing segments of the road, at times rising high
above the sea.
</P>
<P>
   A good perspective is available from Mariner's Lookout above
Apollo Bay. The drive from town takes only a minute or two, but a
steep walk from the car park is required to enjoy the most sweeping
views.
</P>
<P>
   Back at sea level, Apollo Bay offers a welcome midday respite
before you tackle even higher adventure. With a population of
1,000, it's sleepier than Lorne but has a down-home charm and an
idyllic setting.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea-Grape, along the highway, serves the freshest of seafood
caught just off shore. Crayfish (resembling lobster more than our
crawfish) and whiting are among specialties, and
shrimp-and-asparagus risotto is a delectable bargain at $7 U.S.
Dining outside here on a sunny, breezy day seems almost sinful.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need ample sustenance, and good walking shoes, as the
afternoon progresses because the fun is only beginning.
</P>
<P>
   For practical purposes, the Great Ocean Road becomes the Great
Inland Road after Apollo Bay, weaving through the heart of
32,500-acre Otway National Park.
</P>
<P>
   Pause at the Maits Rest Rainforest Walk (named for forestry
officer Maitland Bryant, who rested his horse here during patrols).
A 45-minute self-guided trek on boards and footbridges winds
beneath a deep-green canopy of myrtle and beech trees, some 300
years old, surrounded by sheltering ferns. More than 250 bird
species have been spotted here.
</P>
<P>
   Next, drive two miles west, turn left on Otway Lighthouse Road
and detour for about 15 minutes to Cape Otway. It's not uncommon to
spot wallabies en route.
</P>
<P>
   The Cape Otway Lighthouse, oldest on the mainland, dates to
1848. For a small fee _ and a 10-minute walk _ visitors can tour
the lighthouse, climb a narrow staircase to its summit and step
onto a balcony from which the Shipwreck Coast is on grand display.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the Great Ocean Road, the route continues northwest.
Before you reach Lavers Hill, once the center of a thriving timber
industry, you'll see the turnoff to beautiful Johanna Beach. Just
after Lavers Hill comes Melba Gully State Park, which rivals Maits
Rest.
</P>
<P>
   By now, however, the sun likely is dipping fast. So take
advantage of the mostly straight route back to the sea, where
arguably the most remarkable scenery remains to be witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   Port Campbell National Park extends for 17 miles along a
shoreline guarded by scores of dazzling rock formations. You'll
pass the Twelve Apostles just before reaching the small township of
Port Campbell. If sunset is approaching, pull off the road, park,
walk onto a wide viewing platform and prepare to be enthralled.
</P>
<P>
   But for a better understanding of the history behind these
monuments, plan to return the next morning. Port Campbell, a good
choice for lodging, goes to sleep early. Don't miss out on tiger
prawns in sweet chili sauce at the Southern Ocean Motor Inn's
Napiers Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DAY 3: TO PORT FAIRY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Shipwreck Coast is so named because almost 200 vessels and
hundreds of lives have been lost as treacherous windblown seas
pounded vessels into the craggy shore.
</P>
<P>
   The same elements have created the landscape. Sheer limestone
cliffs, some millions of years old and towering 225 feet above the
ocean, are subjected to a fierce attack by waves and tides. Erosion
has shaped the rock into a series of stacks, gorges, arches and
blowholes.
</P>
<P>
   Best-known are the Twelves Apostles, whose tallest rock stack
soars to 165 feet. They are mesmerizing at sunset and in early
morning as you face the west from the viewing platform with the sun
rising behind your shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   But what's this? Only seven rocks. Seven Apostles?
</P>
<P>
   One theory holds that erosion has washed away the other
boulders. Another suggests that the person responsible for the name
was a tad tipsy at the time.
</P>
<P>
   About a mile to the west, back toward Port Campbell, the Loch
Ard Gorge provides more insight and a bit of lore.
</P>
<P>
   Here, on a misty, windy May evening in 1878, 52 lives were lost
when the Loch Ard, a vessel nearing the end of a 90-day voyage from
London, was swept into the cliffs. Only two 18-year-olds survived:
midshipman Tom Pearce and Eva Carmichael, who was traveling with
her parents and six siblings. According to legend, Tom swam to
safety, then heard nonswimmer Eva's screams as she clung to rocks
at the edge of the gorge. He returned to rescue her, and the two
became folk heroes throughout Australia (though not the romantic
couple many had hoped for).
</P>
<P>
   Only four bodies were found, including that of Eva's mother;
they are buried in a small cemetery overlooking the gorge.
</P>
<P>
   Three walking trails have been developed, with exhibits and
signposts focusing on the Loch Ard tragedy, geology and wildlife.
Birders delight in spotting the rare rufous bristlebird, and nearby
Muttonbird Island is a nesting site for the short-tailed shearwater
in summer (our winter) and the black-faced cormorant in winter.
</P>
<P>
   West of Port Campbell, dozens more rock formations are
distinctive in appearance. One, known as London Bridge, gained
notoriety 10 years ago when a connecting arch to the mainland
crashed into the sea, stranding two people. (They were rescued by
helicopter.)
</P>
<P>
   Paved lookouts near the roadway afford close inspection of
London Bridge and nearby formations known as the Arch and the
Grotto. At the Grotto, paths lead to rock pools.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Ocean Road ends when it merges with Highway A1 near
Allansford, about a half-hour drive past Port Campbell. But as at
the beginning, treasures extend beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Warrnambool, 15 minutes farther, seems huge with its 30,000
residents, street lights and _ reality check _ McDonald's
restaurants. But this seaside city allows pause for reflection,
especially at its Flagstaff Hill Maritime Museum, whose focus is
Shipwreck Coast history.
</P>
<P>
   Between May and October, female southern right whales migrate
from the subantarctic to calve in ``nursery'' areas just off
Warrnambool's Logan Beach. They often swim within 100 yards of the
shore and can be observed from a platform in the dunes or from the
beach. (Males and young females stay farther out to sea.)
</P>
<P>
   One last specialty meal is in order here. While not the ritziest
place in town, Fishtales Cafe serves an eclectic array of 12
pastas, 25 burgers and five Thai green curries. Among the
sandwiches are an Arab Burger (with lettuce, tomato, spicy
eggplant, meat, sambal, burned onions and aioli), an Irish Fish
Burger, a Falafel Burger, a Lentil Burger and a Cajun Burger.
</P>
<P>
   Between Warrnambool and the pretty fishing village of Port
Fairy, a one-way loop road winds through Tower Hill State Game
Reserve, whose setting in an extinct volcano allows kangaroos,
koalas, emus and water birds to roam freely and often within clear
view.
</P>
<P>
   Point Fairy, once one of Australia's most important seaports,
retains its colonial architecture and provides an enchanting
conclusion to the three-day excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Backtracking? Not necessary, except as far as Allansford. From
there, express highways get you to Melbourne in three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, that is, you want to play one more round of golf with
the kangaroos.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1321EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
