<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8070 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRALIA-2TAK     01-17 1312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AUSTRALIA-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA: THE GREAT OCEAN ROAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGLESEA, Australia _ As the foursome arrived at the Anglesea
Golf Club's 10th tee, the first to play reached into his bag and
selected a club.
</P>
<P>
   He took a practice swing, then surveyed the course for hazards.
No, not a creek or ravine. Not a sand bunker. Living, moving
hazards.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 yards ahead, half a dozen kangaroos hopped across the
fairway. Twenty or more 'roos chowed down in _ no, on the right
rough. Others napped beneath gum trees to the left.
</P>
<P>
   From the edge of the tee box _ barely 10 feet away _ a lone
kangaroo stared ahead so intently that an observer could easily
imagine its wanting to advise: ``Scrap the driver for a 2-wood.
Trust me; I live here.''
</P>
<P>
   Once each golfer had taken his turn, the animal hopped away, not
bothering to say whether it was impressed.
</P>
<P>
   Even for nongolfers, visiting the Anglesea Golf Club _ where
more than 1,000 eastern gray kangaroos reside in a native bushland
setting _ is a highlight of an excursion along Australia's Great
Ocean Road.
</P>
<P>
   It's one of many highlights.
</P>
<P>
   From Maine to Oregon, the United States is blessed with wondrous
scenic roadways beside its seas. But only here, at the southern tip
of mainland Australia in the state of Victoria, can you play with
the 'roos and pray with the apostles.
</P>
<P>
   The Twelve Apostles is a name accorded the most celebrated of
several spectacular rock formations carved out of soft limestone
headland by crashing ocean waves. The sculptures rise from the sea
to guard the Shipwreck Coast, one segment of the Great Ocean Road.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the 155-mile road (B100), which begins about an hour's
drive west of Melbourne, introduces treasures so appealing and
diverse that the biggest challenge is determining where to allow
the most time.
</P>
<P>
   Test (or simply admire) waves of 15-20 feet at Bells Beach,
mecca for Australian surfers. Spy for whales near the small city of
Warrnambool or for multicolored parrots and cockatoos during a
leisurely bushwalk in a national or state park. Climb to the top of
150-year-old Cape Otway Lighthouse and savor panoramic vistas.
Discover a sandy beach for sunning, swimming and, if you pick the
right spot, blissful solitude.
</P>
<P>
   Don't skip mealtime, either. For lunch, choose a sun-drenched
sidewalk table at the Sea-Grape in the typically enchanting coastal
hamlet of Apollo Bay. As you linger over the menu, chances are an
amiable Aussie will mosey past and whisper: ``G'day, mate. Here's a
tip: You can't go wrong with the local whiting fillets.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's right.
</P>
<P>
   Appetite whetted? Let's take a tour. Although it's possible to
traverse the Great Ocean Road in one frantic day, don't make that
mistake. You could easily spend a week here. But given all the
other sights to see on this continent, compromise is essential.
</P>
<P>
   We'll settle for three days. Keep your camera within arm's
reach. And be prepared to brake for 'roos and wallabies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DAY 1: MELBOURNE TO LORNE &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Great Ocean Road is a tribute to Aussie spirit, dedicated to
those who perished in World War I and constructed largely by
thousands of ex-servicemen during a 15-year period beginning in
1918.
</P>
<P>
   The two-lane highway is paved throughout. A few stretches bend
and climb dramatically and hug the sea, recalling California's
Highway 1 near Big Sur. But other segments veer inland for miles
and include long straightaways. At one moment the road is
surrounded by rain forests, at another by rolling pastures, at
still another by rugged cliffs and tranquil coves.
</P>
<P>
   The first requisite for exploration is a vehicle. Renting a car
at Melbourne Airport is neither complicated nor expensive.
U.S.-based firms are represented. Specify if you desire a car with
automatic transmission.
</P>
<P>
   Like Britons, Australians drive on the left side of the road;
the driver sits on the right side of the car. Most folks quickly
get the hang of it. Just keep your cool when the windshield wipers
activate each time you think you're signaling a turn.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the Princess Highway (M1) southwest from Melbourne to
Geelong (a 45-minute drive), where two stops are recommended before
you get on the Great Ocean Road.
</P>
<P>
   One is the Geelong Otway Region tourism office, about five miles
east of town, whose staff can provide free brochures and advice.
</P>
<P>
   The other is the waterfront _ facing Corio Bay, not the ocean _
in downtown Geelong. Its decor includes more than 100 brightly
painted bollards, wooden sculptures that depict characters from the
city's past and modern-day community figures such as police
officers, lifeguards, football players and fishermen. Nearby is the
National Wool Museum.
</P>
<P>
   A 20-minute drive south leads to Torquay, Australia's ``Surf
City'' and eastern gateway to the Great Ocean Road. Many of the
world's best-known surfing-industry manufacturers are represented
here, and the Surfworld Australia museum honors the sport's
pioneers and more recent stars.
</P>
<P>
   Just past Torquay, signs point the way to Bells Beach. Even if
you aren't inclined to ride the waves, easily accessed platforms
high above the sea allow stellar views. Other area beaches, better
protected from ocean swells, are ideal for swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Continue 20 minutes to the west and you'll be in Anglesea, a
village whose 2,000 human residents generate less attention than
its kangaroos.
</P>
<P>
   Don't fret about formalities at the Anglesea Golf Club. Members
are as accustomed to dealing with wide-eyed tourists as to playing
amid the 'roos. Though a private club, Anglesea welcomes guests;
greens fees for 18 holes are only $17 U.S., for nine holes about
$10.
</P>
<P>
   Kangaroos are usually visible from streets around the course
(about half a mile off the Great Ocean Road). They are particularly
active near sunset; park along Golf Links Drive, and you're likely
to see as many as 100 'roos grazing on fairways and greens, even as
golfers approach to putt. During sunny periods, the animals often
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Anglesea member Kevin Sadler says he's never seen a
kangaroo get hurt. ``We were getting set to tee off one day, and a
big herd of kangaroos was directly in front of us,'' Sadler
recalls. ``I said, `Maybe we should play around them,' and my
partners said, `No, go ahead.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I teed off, and the ball went directly at a kangaroo. It just
ducked its head, and the ball sailed right above. Pretty smart
'roo, right?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on bluffs overlooking the ocean, Anglesea also is
notable as a center for hang-gliding. Several motels beckon, but
press on for another half hour to Lorne. You'll endure dozens of
twists and turns and temptations to pause at overlooks, but the
reward for perseverance is an evening in the Great Ocean Road's
only resort community.
</P>
<P>
   Compact Lorne, on the shores of Loutit Bay, isn't fancy and has
only about 1,500 permanent residents. But during peak tourist
periods, it bursts with activity. Mountjoy Parade, a wide
beach-front boulevard lined with restaurants, cafes and boutiques,
offers a Mediterranean flair. Comfortable and inexpensive lodging
is available near the water.
</P>
<P>
   Whether your evening repast features a Greek salad, Tasmanian
salmon or a Szechwan stir-fry, a late-evening seaside stroll is the
perfect ending to an eventful day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAY 2: TO PORT CAMPBELL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How about a picnic breakfast to jump-start the journey's second
leg? Visit a European-style bakery/deli along Mountjoy Parade, then
adjourn to a gently sloping hillside just west of town overlooking
gentle waves leading to sandy beaches leading to rich green forest.
Rudyard Kipling was so inspired that he wrote about Lorne in his
poem ``Flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Now get ready for exercise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
