<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8077 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-17 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE THE MOST OF LIMITED TIME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most travelers have felt the quandary: Too much to see. Too
little time.
</P>
<P>
   If only I had a penny for every cruise passenger who, after one
hectic day in a port, sighed wistfully, ``I only scratched the
surface; I must come back and stay a week.''
</P>
<P>
   And while ``If it's Tuesday, this must be Belgium,'' bus tours
can provide grand overviews, Brussels, Paris and Amsterdam too
frequently fade into one big blur at the end of the road.
</P>
<P>
   My predicament last summer involved Melbourne, Australia's
second-largest city _ and a strong rival to Sydney in its
cosmopolitan appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The timetable allowed two weeks on a continent about the size of
the United States. And this was my first visit.
</P>
<P>
   I can only imagine the difficulty a first-time traveler to our
country endures in organizing a two-week _ or two-month _ vacation.
How could you skip New York? Washington, D.C.? Philadelphia? What
about San Francisco? Hollywood? The Pacific Coast Highway?
Yellowstone National Park? The Rocky Mountains? New Orleans' French
Quarter? Space centers in Houston and Florida? Walt Disney World?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SETTING PRIORITIES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to Australia, I targeted Sydney as a must. In
almost every survey travelers name Sydney their favorite
destination worldwide, and the 2000 Olympics (Sept. 15-Oct. 1) will
shine an even brighter spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Barrier Reef represents one of the world's premier
natural wonders, and how could I resist spying for birds and
butterflies _ and crocodiles _ elsewhere in Queensland? Touring the
Great Ocean Road in Victoria not only introduces spectacular
scenery but provides an appreciation for diverse outdoor wonders.
So I penciled each into the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving home, I reluctantly conceded that the Outback
must be saved for another visit. Kangaroo Island and Tasmania, too.
And Perth on Australia's west coast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PLANNING FOR MELBOURNE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what about Melbourne? I was utilizing the city as a gateway
for the Great Ocean Road. I could squeeze in one day _ a Sunday _
but was that fair? To me or Melbourne?
</P>
<P>
   Reasoning that others may face a similar dilemma while
scheduling side trips during the Olympics, I decided to go for it.
And I followed a philosophy that has worked for me in similar
situations.
</P>
<P>
   First, I secured a map of the city's public transportation
system. Old-fashioned trams _ efficient and fun _ access most
Melbourne districts. On one route, trams continually circle the
inner city at approximate five-minute intervals and cost nothing. A
small charge allows exploration of other attractions.
</P>
<P>
   I hopped on the circular tram first. And wherever the spirit was
moved _ at the State Library, the ornate and historical Palace
Theater, lovely Parliament Gardens, the towering spire of St.
Patrick's Cathedral _ I hopped off. And on again.
</P>
<P>
   After gaining an orientation, I began weaving on foot through
the heart of the city. To the Block Arcade, central Melbourne's
most opulent shopping complex. To a small music store where I
invested in two CDs featuring a favorite Aussie singer _ recordings
unavailable at home. To Chinatown for a scrumptious lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Tram No. 8 helped me fulfill another objective. I've usually
found that the pulse of a city _ and its people _ is best felt in
its public parks and gardens. Melbourne laws require that
one-fourth of all area be ``green,'' and open spaces abound in all
directions, none more prized that the Royal Botanic Gardens. More
than 50,000 plants and scores of bird species and animals thrive in
a peaceful oasis dotted with lakes and ponds, beautifully manicured
lawns and walking trails.
</P>
<P>
   As a bonus, Tram 8 also stopped at the National Gallery of
Victoria and Victorian Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   Come evening, another kind of exploration awaited. The Colonial
Tramcar Restaurant _ an elegantly refurbished 1927 tram _ cruises
Melbourne suburbs while passengers feast on pepper crusted
kangaroo, Tasmanian salmon, ginger-spiced chicken, and apple and
cinnamon crepes.
</P>
<P>
   A few steps from my hotel headquarters _ the Centra Melbourne,
situated along the Yarra River and convenient to trams and
restaurants _ a sparkling new entertainment center proved an ideal
location to wind down after dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Fulfilling? Yes. But I was left longing for more. Especially
when a new acquaintance said, ``Too bad you didn't make it to an
Australian rules football game.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe next time. It's the traveler's lament.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For more information about Melbourne, call the Australian
Tourist Commission at 800-369-6863. Access the ATC's Web site at
www.australia.com and the State of Victoria's site at
www.tourism.vic.gov.au. These sites may also prove helpful:
www.melbourne.vic.gov.au; www.mcmb.com.au;
www.melbourne.citysearch.com.au; and www.melbourne.hotelguide.net.
For information about the Colonial Tramcar Restaurant, e-mail
tram(at)ocean.com.au; or call (03) 9696-4000 within Australia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
