<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8082 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-MUSIC-TYRELL-HNS &LR;      01-17 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-TYRELL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVE TYRELL OFFERS A NEW TAKE ON OLD STANDARDS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL D. CLARK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Steve Tyrell can't help it. Boosting the careers of
other singers is his nature _ even if it's at the expense of his
own vocal career.
</P>
<P>
   After three decades of producing songs for Elvis Presley, B.J.
Thomas, Linda Ronstadt, Rickie Lee Jones and many others, Tyrell
has finally come full-circle on a singing career that began in his
native Houston in the late '60s. His rebirth _ the result of a
happy accident that found him singing ``The Way You Look Tonight''
for the ``Father of the Bride'' soundtrack _ has earned him a
record deal, a just-released album titled ``A New Standard,'' and a
future behind the mike.
</P>
<P>
   So what does Tyrell, a man with a new lease on musical life,
spend the majority of his time talking about?
</P>
<P>
   Others.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas. Ronstadt. Presley. Tyrell touches on them all through
the course of a conversation. He tries to stay focused about his
own CD of big-band gems sung in his soft, slightly roughed-up
tenor, but the hits just keep on coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought B.J. Thomas was the best singer to come out
of Houston, '' says Tyrell, who produced the singer through the
halcyon days of ``Raindrops Keep Fallin' on My Head'' and ``Hooked
on a Feeling.'' ``Some of the best things I've ever been involved
with have a mind of their own and just take you along for the
ride.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, then Tyrell's career in music has been one
giant Texas Cyclone. It's hard to fault a guy who put his own
singing career aside for a production career that has taken him
from the studios of Presley's last Memphis recording sessions to
writing with Elvis Costello's most recent collaborator, Burt
Bacharach. He's also a soundtrack innovator who has adapted music
for movies from ``An American Tail'' to ``The Brady Bunch Movie,''
and the mind behind the idea of having celebrities sing songs built
for animated movies so they could be radio hits.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrell should be writing a book, not recording a CD. But after
30 years of fine-tuning other people's voices, he finally found his
own.
</P>
<P>
   All this time it had been hiding in songs that Frank Sinatra and
Irving Berlin made famous like ``I've Got the World on a String''
and ``I've Got My Love to Keep Me Warm.'' All it took was a demo
made for ``Father of the Bride'' and some cajoling from band leader
Louis Bellson and his wife, Stephanie, to get ``A New Standard''
made.
</P>
<P>
   It also didn't hurt that jazz heavyweights like Joe Sample,
``Toots'' Thielemans and the late Harry ``Sweets'' Edison offered
up the use of their ivories and horns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a such a thrill to meet all these national treasures,''
says Tyrell, who's in his 50s. ``This was the last recording that
`Sweets' ever made, which makes it special.''
</P>
<P>
   The road to ``A New Standard'' started in 1991 when Tyrell was
hired as the music producer for the comedy remake of ``Father of
the Bride'' starring Steve Martin and Diane Keaton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to choreograph music before a movie is shot,'' says
Tyrell. ``We knew we wanted a heartfelt version of `The Way You
Look Tonight' for the scene when Martin first sees his daughter
dancing with her new husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knew, though, who would sing this hanky-grabber. Sting
and many other names were mentioned, but until a decision was made
Tyrell thought he'd record his own version for utility purposes
around the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started playing my rendition for a co-worker outside of the
sound studio on my car radio,'' says Tyrell. ``Soon, Martin and
Keaton and the rest of the cast were outside listening. It was
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyrell ended up not only singing the version played over the end
credits with a 100-piece band (perhaps a first for a guy hired to
produce the music) _ he also appeared in the movie as the wedding
singer and sang two more songs, ``Give Me the Simple Life'' and
``On The Sunny Side of the Street'' for the sequel three years
later. All three songs appear on ``A New Standard.''
</P>
<P>
   To this point Tyrell, a blues man, had never cracked the great
American songbook. The last time he'd sung on a record at all was
as a blues-loving teen-ager playing the Houston rock club circuit.
</P>
<P>
   As a student at St. Thomas High School _ classmates may remember
him as Steve Bilao _ Tyrell's primary interests were the prep
baseball team and blues bands that he would play in at night, like
C.L. and the Pictures and the Art Boatwrights.
</P>
<P>
   Influenced by Chuck Berry and Bobby ``Blue'' Bland, Tyrell had a
few hits around Houston with ``Pay Day Some Day'' and Phil
Spector's ``Young Boy Blues'' in the early '60s. His recordings
were often picked up in Atlanta or Nashville but never made a
splash nationally. After graduating, he jumped to the other side of
the soundboard and found success quickly.
</P>
<P>
   He went to New York City and rose to head of A&AMP;R (artists and
repertoire) and promotions at Scepter Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own singing career didn't take off back then,'' says
Tyrell. ``The next best thing I could do was help friends from
Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   He started producing tracks for Dionne Warwick, the Shirelles
and Barbara Lynn, but within six months he brought his Houston
singing peer to Scepter. Country-rock star B.J. Thomas was more of
a pop singer, but he soon scored a hit with a cover of Hank
William's country classic ``I'm So Lonesome I Could Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   He would follow up gold with the Burt Bacharach and Hal
David-penned ``Raindrops Keep Fallin' On My Head,'' which took the
1969 Oscar for Best Song for ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance
Kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Houstonian, Mark James, was Tyrell's next project. He
never made it as a singer, but a few of his songs are now pop
culture masterpieces. The James-written, Thomas-sung ``Hooked on a
Feeling'' was a Top 10 hit. ``Suspicious Minds'' and ``Always On My
Mind'' were picked up for another singer: Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Memphis started getting hot again, and Elvis decided he was
coming back there to record for the first time since the Sun
Records days,'' says Tyrell. ``I like women, but he was a
breathtaking cat. He looked like a Greek god.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyrell remembers a gentleman in the studio, a guy who liked to
be one of the guys. He remembers a man who called ``Suspicious
Minds'' his favorite song to record, and who threw great New Year's
Eve parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some rules to being around Elvis that were mostly
the rules of the Colonel (Tom Parker),'' says Tyrell. ``He was a
very isolated person, but I never saw him (act) nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The James song ``Moody Blue'' was the name of Presley's last
album and single before he died. It was published by Tyrell.
</P>
<P>
   There are other moments in Tyrell's producing career he's quick
to talk about:
</P>
<P>
   _ How he made the song ``Somewhere Out There,'' for the animated
movie ``An American Tail,'' an Oscar- and Grammy-winning No. 1
single after he was told by studio suits that nobody wanted to hear
a song sung by mice played on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   _ How young newlyweds everywhere have danced to his ``Father of
the Bride'' songs at their wedding receptions.
</P>
<P>
   _ How he's done production for Blood, Sweat and Tears; the
``Darkwing Duck'' cartoons; and last year's NBC biopic on Sonny and
Cher, ``And the Beat Goes On.''
</P>
<P>
   And on, and on, and on.
</P>
<P>
   But what about your own music, Steve?
</P>
<P>
   ``People told me after `Father of the Bride' that I should do an
album of standards, but it didn't have any resonance with me for a
long time,'' says Tyrell. ``Now I want to spend the rest of my
career doing this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot how nice it is to make your own record and artistic
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
