<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-REBORN-CEMETERIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE STARS GO AFTER THE FINAL CURTAIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: WITH HOLLYWOOD-REBORN-MAIN AND HOLLYWOOD-REBORN-WALKING) 
 
 
By CAROL BIDWELL 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No visit to historic Hollywood would be complete without seeking
out the final resting places of stars who shone so brightly long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect place to start is Hollywood Forever, the town's
original cemetery, on the south side of Santa Monica Boulevard
between Gower Street and Van Ness Avenue, backed up to Paramount
Studios.
</P>
<P>
   Until about a year ago, the cemetery _ opened in 1897 _ was
called Hollywood Memorial Park. New owners have renamed it and are
working on $7 million in renovations. Many cemeteries that hold
stars' remains won't point out specific graves, but here a friendly
staff will steer sightseers to stars' final venues.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find Tyrone Power's white marble bench, the impressive
tomb of Cecil B. DeMille, Douglas Fairbanks Sr.'s outdoor
sarcophagus and reflecting pool, and the crypt of the original
Latin lover, Rudolph Valentino. Also buried at Hollywood Forever
are voice artist Mel Blanc, Columbia Pictures chief Harry Cohn,
gangster Benjamin ``Bugsy'' Siegel, producer Jesse Lasky, directors
John Huston, Victor Fleming and William Desmond Taylor, and actors
Adolphe Menjou, Janet Gaynor (winner of the first best-actress
Oscar), Virginia Rappe (who died in a wild San Francisco orgy with
comic Roscoe ``Fatty'' Arbuckle), Eleanor Powell, Peter Finch,
Peter Lorre and Norma Talmadge.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other Southern California cemeteries where
Hollywood luminaries are buried:
</P>
<P>
   FOREST LAWN GLENDALE (1712 S. Glendale Ave., Glendale): Humphrey
Bogart, John Gilbert, Errol Flynn, Spencer Tracy, Tom Mix,
directors George Cukor and Vincente Minnelli, Mary Pickford, Sammy
Davis Jr., Walt Disney, George Burns, Gracie Allen, Jeanette
MacDonald, Clara Bow, James Stewart, Theda Bara, W.C. Fields, Clark
Gable, Carole Lombard, Jean Harlow, Harold Lloyd, Norma Shearer and
producer David O. Selznik.
</P>
<P>
   FOREST LAWN HOLLYWOOD HILLS (6300 Forest Lawn Drive, Los
Angeles): Bette Davis; Charles Laughton; Liberace; ``Woody
Woodpecker'' creator Walter Lantz; Lucille Ball; George Raft;
Dorothy Lamour; George ``Gabby'' Hayes; Buster Keaton; Stan Laurel;
and Harriet, Ricky and Ozzie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   HILLSIDE MEMORIAL PARK (6001 Centinela Ave., Los Angeles): Al
Jolson, Eddie Cantor, Jack Benny, Jeff Chandler, Michael Landon,
makeup giant Max Factor, Lorne Greene, Vic Morrow and the main
Stooge, Moe Howard.
</P>
<P>
   HOLY CROSS CEMETERY (5835 Slauson Ave., Los Angeles): Bing
Crosby, Bela Lugosi, Rita Hayworth, Sharon Tate, Charles Boyer,
Jackie Coogan, Jimmy Durante, gossip columnist Louella Parsons,
director John Ford, Rosalind Russell, movie pioneer Mack Sennett,
Mary Astor, bandleaders Lawrence Welk and Spike Jones, John Candy,
Ray Bolger and Mario Lanza.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN VIEW CEMETERY (2400 N. Fair Oaks Ave., Altadena):
``Superman'' George Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNT SINAI MEMORIAL PARK (5950 Forest Lawn Drive, Burbank):
Phil Silvers, writer Irwin Allen, composer David Rose, singer
``Mama'' Cass Elliot, Lee J. Cobb and Herschel Bernardi.
</P>
<P>
   WESTWOOD MEMORIAL PARK (1218 Glendon Ave., Los Angeles): Marilyn
Monroe, Natalie Wood, Eva Gabor, writer Truman Capote, Dean Martin,
Burt Lancaster, Eve Arden, Donna Reed, Jim Backus, rocker Frank
Zappa and 20th Century Fox Studio founder Darryl Zanuck. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
