<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8098 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS &LR;      01-17 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
  
 US ASSESSES COSTS OF MIDEAST PEACE
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Middle East juggling act is taking place this
week, and President Clinton is cast as the juggler.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has micromanaged Middle East peace talks to a far
greater degree than any president, faces a set of dual negotiations
involving Israel and Syria, and Israel and the Palestinians. And he
must grapple with shaping a multibillion-dollar package of military
sweeteners for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a quarter-century, starting just after the 1973
Yom Kippur War, US presidents and secretaries of state have argued
that Middle East peace efforts should move ahead on all tracks at
once. That wish is finally coming true _ but some US officials,
concerned about cost, say it may be a case of being careful what
you wish for.
</P>
<P>
   Two US officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
administration is considering a $15 billion to $17 billion package
for Israel. One especially difficult question is whether to include
the F-22 Raptor stealth aircraft, a $166 million plane that is
still being tested and that is forbidden by law to be sold to
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
   The second round of the Israel-Syria talks begins on Wednesday
in Shepherdstown, W.Va. On Thursday, the Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat arrives at the White House for a private meeting with
Clinton, who afterward will orchestrate a meeting between Arafat
and the Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, and probably himself.
</P>
<P>
   For Barak, who pledged after his July election that he could
advance peace talks on all fronts, this is a test of his ambition.
For Clinton, desperate for a lasting legacy that doesn't include an
intern, this is his last stab at being a Middle East peacemaker in
the mold of former President Carter. He has 11 months left to try.
</P>
<P>
   His subordinates feel some pressure. ``Pressure can be
helpful,'' said one US official involved in the talks. ``By
definition, there is pressure if the president is running out to
West Virginia and looking over your shoulder all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Clinton spent more than 70 hours over nine days at the
Wye River Plantation, Md., talks between the Israelis and
Palestinians, to gain a deal that only nudged the process along.
This month, he spent 25 hours over five days at Shepherdstown, W.
Va., often in a role of counselor trying to open dialogue between
enemies. For Wednesday, when Israel-Syria talks resume, the
president has blocked off seven hours for Shepherdstown.
</P>
<P>
   Some say he's right to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you rather him living in the New York suburbs with
Hillary?'' said Richard W. Murphy, the director of Middle East
Studies at the Council on Foreign Relations and a former longtime
US diplomat. ``We have spoiled the Arabs and the Israelis with the
level of American government interaction ever since 1973. Clinton
is different in the sense that he's more involved at a much earlier
point. Time will tell whether he looks extremely wise or he looks
like a fool. If it works, the payoff is huge.''
</P>
<P>
   At several US agencies, the work leading to this week has been
intense. One diplomat flew to the Gaza Strip to talk with Arafat.
Clinton called the Syrian president, Hafez al-Assad, from his new
home in Chappaqua, N.Y. After much debate, the US team decided to
hold the next round at Shepherdstown despite complaints from
``senior officials who had to share rooms'' at the Clarion Hotel
and Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
   Senior officials even schemed about ways to stop delegation
members from speaking to the media. One adviser wanted to know if
it was legal to jam cellular phone transmissions over the
conference center airspace. (It is not.)
</P>
<P>
   For Israel and Syria, the deal is about returning the Golan
Heights to Syria in exchange for normalized relations and security
guarantees. For Israel and the Palestinians, the talks are about
tackling the thorniest issues remaining in the half-century of the
Arab-Israeli conflict: the future of Jerusalem, the creation of a
Palestinian state, the return of Palestinian refugees, and the
sharing of scarce water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The Israel-Syria deal might be wrapped up in a few months,
according to Barak and outside observers. That, in turn, would
presumably lead to an Israel-Lebanon deal, which would call for the
withdrawal of Israeli troops from south Lebanon and effectively rob
Hezbollah guerrillas of a cause.
</P>
<P>
   If all this falls into place, Israel would be ringed by
countries with whom they have made peace.
</P>
<P>
   That stunning reality would likely thaw diplomatic, cultural,
and economic relations with the far reaches of the Arab world,
ending the Arab-Israel conflict as it been defined since the
creation of Israel in 1948. The conflict would revert to its roots,
moving away from a state-to-state battle and toward a communal one,
between distrustful Israeli and Palestinian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians had hoped to arrive in Washington at a lull in
the Israel-Syria talks because its leaders fear being overshadowed,
capturing less of Clinton's attention.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, in fact, canceled a meeting with Clinton scheduled for
this Friday because he thought the Israelis and Syrians would still
be in the area. After the new meeting was set for Thursday, the
Israelis and Syrians ruined his plans by restarting talks this
week.
</P>
<P>
   But US officials don't share his concerns. Neither do several
former US ambassadors and several Arab world diplomats in
Washington, who think that the two tracts are intersecting
precisely because many factors are in line for dealmaking, even for
key parts of an Israeli-Palestinian agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Said Nabil Fahmy, Egypt's ambassador to the United States:
``This is not stage-managed, nobody tried to put this together for
this week in Washington. This is a good coincidence. There is
promise in the Syrian track, promise in the Palestinian track. They
are both moving together at the same time. This is a first. And
this is not a mere coincidence. It is caused by the changing
reality in the Middle East, a reflection of how the Middle East has
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time,'' said Abdulwahab Al-Hajjri, Yemen's
ambassador to the United States. ``What we should do right now is
try to encourage everybody to go ahead and show our support. We
think it's moving and it's going to continue to move.''
</P>
<P>
   But few say an Israeli-Syrian peace deal, for instance, would
rapidly change the political, military, or economic realities.
Israel, by all measures, enjoys a qualitative advantage,
economically and militarily.
</P>
<P>
   And Israel's strategic military advantage in the region, backed
by its nuclear capability, should grow after an Israeli-Syrian
deal. While the United States has talked with Syria about upgrading
its military, the Syrian demands pale next to the Israeli ones.
Israel presented a list of items that Pentagon specialists put at
$17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It includes unrestricted access to US satellite imagery,
Tomahawk missiles, Apache helicopters, Blackhawk helicopters,
Hercules planes, and completion of missile defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   And US officials are reported to be considering whether to push
for delivering the F-22 fighter to Israel as well. The national
security adviser, Samuel R. Berger, asked senior Pentagon officials
recently to clarify the sales prohibition, attached by Congress for
the last three years, according to the two US officials who spoke
on condition of anonymity, and who stressed that the discussions
were at a preliminary stage.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter last July, the US Joint Chiefs of Staff called the
F-22 the ``aircraft we are counting on to guarantee control of the
skies in the next century.'' Because of the strategic importance of
the planes, and because of Israel's record of technology transfers
to other countries, many conservative congressmen are likely to
object to any sale of F-22s.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior Pentagon officials also have voiced concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of back-door stuff going on now with the White
House on Israel's proposal,'' a Pentagon official said. ``Some
people here are scared to death that we're going to be giving away
all kinds of big missile defense systems and F-22s.''
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, a National Security Council spokesman, declined to
comment on Israel's requests, but added: ``We take Israel's
security needs as one of our core foreign policy principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the Pentagon announced that Lockheed Martin Corp.
has been awarded a $1.34 billion contract to build 50 F-16D fighter
jets for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Rubin, the State Department spokesman, has said
repeatedly that any reports on assistance are premature, but the US
official involved in the talks said the financial discussions would
be arising soon. The official said: ``Don't you think Israel has to
have a concrete idea of what it's going to get before it signs
anything?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1344EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
