<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8099 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-PIANO-TEACHER-ART-BOS     01-17 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANO-TEACHER-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036 . )  
 PIANO TEACHER OFFERS SPONTANEOUS COMPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sunday piano recital, an invitation-only affair, was about
to start. The guests, who included Nobel Prize-winning Harvard
chemist William Lipscomb and prominent jazz composer George
Russell, took their places and studied the program, all original
compositions.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm, interesting. There was one piece called ``The Evil Genie''
and another intriguingly named ``Pancakes on Mars.'' There was
``World Peace, Food and Presents,'' a nod, evidently, to the
holiday season, and the postmodern-sounding ``Floured Child.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid silence, the first performer, Jenna Lipscomb, daughter of
William, took her place confidently at the Steinway grand piano,
and with great composure rendered a rhythmic version of ``Wild
Horse Dancing.'' The audience burst into applause.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's not every 11-year-old who writes her own music,
albeit with major assistance from her teacher, Ben Schwendener.
</P>
<P>
   But then Schwendener, 37, is no ordinary piano teacher. A jazz
composer and member of the jazz-rock group Falling Objects, he
offers students what he calls a ``customized education'' in piano.
You won't find any standardized beginning-level piano method books
in Schwendener's third-floor Boston studio, with their pictures of
cute frogs hopping over notes, or clowns juggling clef signs. You
won't see any smiley-face stickers proclaiming ``Wow!'' or ``Good
job!'' on students' music after they've tackled a new piece.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Schwendener's piano students (four adults, 14 children,
ages 7-15) all receive a blank composition book. The rest is up to
them _ and their teacher. During the first lesson, he talks to them
about their musical interests and abilities, figures out their
strengths (strong rhythmic sense? melodic inclination?), and he
helps them write their own pieces, based on themes they plunk out
on the piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I'm the artistic director'' as well as piano
teacher, Schwendener says. ``I have yet to buy stickers for my
students; they can stick anything they want to on their music,
because everything they do is a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, his students learn how to read music and the rudiments of
theory, and are gradually introduced to the musical masters. But
they don't start their musical training the traditional way,
through scales or finger exercises. ``I don't go down that road,''
says Schwendener.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, aiming to broaden their musical experience, he goes the
improvisational route, indicating even to the youngest students
that their musical instincts are worthwhile and relevant, and that
they don't have to be a Bach or Bartok to compose a meaningful
musical theme. He might throw a scale into the lesson now and then,
but it's a scale on which to improvise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to demystify the compositional process and encourage
improvisation and ear training,'' said the upbeat, boyish-looking
Schwendener in an interview after the recital, which featured 11
enthusiastic students playing an assortment of tunes from blues to
a tango, a Celtic dance, a new arrangement of a Burt Bacharach
tune, and variations on a song by John Lennon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately,'' he says, ``it's the organic process of creating
new music that appeals to me. I love the way all students are all
different, and every student has different ideas about how the
themes develop.''
</P>
<P>
   He maintains that every child has an innate creative ability
that can be expressed musically (though piano may not be the
perfect outlet for them at the time, he allows), and that profound
ideas can be conveyed in the simplest terms, even by a little
person. Witness the creation of ``Flower Fox,'' a happy little folk
ditty he wrote last year with his daughter, Elodi, then 3. It is
based on three notes _ E, F, and C _ that Elodi picked out on the
piano. She might not have been aware of it, but her dad harmonized
her notes, using the inner modal harmonies of the F Lydian scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's `Flower Fox'!'' she said to him excitedly,
spontaneously naming it.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the piano recital everyone seemed excited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben has a way of bringing out the best in people,'' says
Jenna's father, himself a classical clarinetist. ``He tries to find
out what students are interested in and reaches them that way,
through the composition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We made up pieces together; they're really cool,'' Jenna
beamed.
</P>
<P>
   Hovik Papazian, 14, of Belmont, was all smiles after his
performance of three pieces, which included a variation of the song
``Money'' by John Lennon, and an impressionistic homage to Erik
Satie called ``Eiffel Down.'' Schwendener has been working with
Papazian since he was 5. Now, says Schwendener, Papazian is ``a
self-motivated, creative pianist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I hear something on the radio and tell (Ben) about
it, and he changes it around,'' says Papazian, describing how they
work together. ``But he prefers creating things, like jazz. We've
tried something traditional, like Bach, and I was able to play it,
but it's different. You can't mix it around, and if you make a
mistake you can't cover it up, really. I might have missed out on
some stuff, like technical things, but I've also gained. With Ben,
you can be free with the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Piano students, however, represent only a fraction of
Schwendener's work. He records albums with Falling Objects and
teaches composition and piano at the Longy School of Music and New
England Conservatory of Music (from which he graduated in 1986 with
a degree in jazz composition). He teaches a graduate course in
creative and critical thinking at UMass-Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He also started a pilot program, though his nonprofit
organization called Gravity Arts, to provide customized education
to an unlikely population: corporate employees. The idea is to
assist employees who play or have played an instrument _ at any
musical level _ in forming an ensemble, by custom-composing music
for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are corporate softball teams, why not a corporate
ensemble?'' Schwendener reasons. ``How many people are there in
corporations who have played a musical instrument and love it but
don't have some sort of venue in which to express it?'' he says.
``This teaches diversity. It teaches creative problem-solving. It
provides employees with a response to their creative needs.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a surprise to learn that such an innovative musical thinker
was trained in a fairly conventional way _ method books, stickers
and all. ``None of my early piano teachers was comfortable with
improvisation,'' says Schwendener, who grew up in Okemos, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   He joined a jazz band in high school and was increasingly drawn
to jazz, rock music, and improvising. He moved to Boston in 1982 to
study at the New England Conservatory with the imminent jazz
musician and musical theorist Russell, and was heavily influenced
by the composer's Lydian Chromatic Concept of Tonal Organization,
the first modal theory of music coming out of the innovative jazz
tradition. Based on the Lydian scale and a ladder of intervals of
fifths, it made possible a new approach to improvising.
</P>
<P>
   Russell himself made an appearance at the recent children's
recital, dazzling the audience with his story of how he came to
write ``Cubano-Be, Cubano-Bop'' for Dizzy Gillespie in New York, a
piece that was performed at Carnegie Hall. ``What I heard here
today was amazing. Thank you,'' he told the children. ``You're all
fine young people, and bright lights like you will pass your
knowledge along to everybody. That's the way it seems to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1345EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
