<HEADER>
A8101 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      01-17 1465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
  
 FOOLISH TO PASS UP MATCHING 401(k) PLAN  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 26, a recently admitted attorney, and am currently
earning $36,000 a year at a Boston law firm. My legal education has
left me with $95,000 in student loan debt. One loan, for $55,000,
is very flexible and repayments can be indexed to my income. The
other $40,000 requires payments of $500 per month for 15 years.
Both have interest rates of 7.5 percent, and can be repaid without
penalty. In addition to this, I have about $3,000 in credit card
debt at 9 percent. After rent, the state loan payments, and
assorted other payments, I'm not left with much, so I am deferring
payment on the larger loan, with interest subsidized while I am
still eligible for this. What sort of general long-term investment
strategies would you recommend for me? Now that I am finally out of
school I am anxious to get on with my life and make some real
estate investments while I am still young and can enjoy them, but I
realize my debt is going to be an albatross for some time. Should I
be doing anything now to invest for retirement, such as making a
monthly 401(k) contribution, or should I be more concerned with
using what disposable income I have to pay off my credit card and
student loan debt? My employer would match 50 percent of any
contributions to the 401(k) that I might make, up to 3 percent of
my salary. Does it make any sense at all to put money into
investments that probably would not earn much more than the
interest rate I am paying on my student loans?
</P>
<P>
   D.H., Newton, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Of course it does. I know your financial situation is tough,
but can you afford to turn your back on a free $520 a year?
</P>
<P>
   If you invested that 3 percent into the 401(k), or $86.66 a
month, and your employer added a further $43.33 each month, after a
year you would have $1,560, and the advance in the portfolio would
be equivalent to an investment paying more than 108 percent. Even
the credit card debt seems insignificant in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the second year, your $1,560 balance would have to
pull its own weight, but if you continued at that $86.66 rate and
got the same 50 percent match, by the end of the second year you
would have a total of $3,119; again, presuming no portfolio growth,
the employer match would provide the equivalent of a 25.5 percent
interest rate on the entire 401(k) balance.
</P>
<P>
   Since you say there's not much left after your current expenses,
and I've already (at least on paper) tapped 3 percent of your
pretax income, the question of the next step may be moot.
</P>
<P>
   But if there's still a little money left over, I would focus
first on getting rid of the credit card debt, then on the student
loans. For the moment, I'd forget about real estate or other
investments that would go beyond the level that wins you the
maximum 401(k) matches. If you're good at your profession, your
financial rewards should advance at a steep pace, and what now
seems a mountain of debt will soon enough seem manageable, then
insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, take a look at your loan schedules and payments. My
calculator says that a 7.5 percent loan of $40,000 would require a
monthly payment of only $365 to be paid off over 15 years; if you
reversed the balances, a $500 monthly payment would be close to the
right figure to pay off a $55,000 balance over 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have the responsibility for, but lack the authority to
change, a relative's $616,000 portfolio, consisting of seven
stocks. Two of them _ an oil company and a utility _ are just
keeping their heads above water. But the remaining five _ another
oil, three more utilities, and an industrial stock _ are worth even
less today than at the end of 1995. When I push the broker for
improvement, all I hear is a lament about the potential long-term
capital gains for the owner, who is an unusually alert 100-year-old
woman. What do you recommend?
</P>
<P>
   B.B., Sylvania, Ohio &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I cannot fathom how you might have responsibility for this
portfolio, but no authority to do anything about it. If you have no
authority to make any change, you really don't have the
responsibility for it.
</P>
<P>
   But in any event, I would discuss the situation with the person
who is responsible for handing your relative's taxes, just to make
sure the broker is correct.
</P>
<P>
   I would start by asking whether a relatively small portion of
the underperforming stock positions might be sold each year without
terribly punitive tax consequences.
</P>
<P>
   If the answer is no, as indeed it might be, I see little you can
do. If the answer is yes, I'd ask the tax expert to write to the
broker, spelling out how much of the stocks might be sold in any
given period, what the tax consequences would be, and his or her
recommendation of a course of action.
</P>
<P>
   But you should also bear in mind that underperforming utilities
tend to have handsome yields, and if you are simply looking at the
value of the principal and ignoring the dividends that have been
paid to your relative, you are missing a big part of the overall
picture. That is particularly true if they are preferred stocks.
</P>
<P>
   If you still think this portfolio is all that terrible after
considering the tax and yield situations, the next time you talk to
the broker, you might mention that at the end of January, 1995, the
Dow Jones utilities average stood at 193.12, compared with 297.78
entering this week, offering a strong argument that some of these
issues probably could have been sold long ago and the capital gains
taxes paid, with your elderly relative still gaining on an
after-tax basis.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest that you do not go to your elderly relative, whatever
the situation. Most centenarians aren't all that concerned about
money (provided, of course, that they have enough of it) and even
if your relative is unusually alert for her age, all you are likely
to do is stir up a lot of unnecessary anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be closing on the sale of my house at the end of the
month, and as a result I am going to receive $70,000, which will be
used as the down payment on a new house that won't be completed
until June or July. In the meantime, I would like to receive the
best return possible on this cash. What do you recommend?
</P>
<P>
   C.F., Attleboro, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I suggest you take the dull, safe route of putting the cash
into a CD or a money market fund.
</P>
<P>
   What might you gain if you decided to take a moderate risk,
putting the funds in a short-term bond fund that delivered 6
percent, rather than a rate of around 5 percent from cash-type
investments? Something like $300 to $350.
</P>
<P>
   What might you lose if the bond market headed south because of
higher interest rates, or the fear of them? Probably not awfully
much _ but still, there's the possibility of losing $1,000 or so,
even if you chose a conservative fund.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way: By agreeing to buy the new house, you have
established a very short-term liability. Following the traditional
principle of investing, these funds should accordingly be invested
in a very short-term asset. The time period is simply too short to
win a significant advantage by taking chances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 29, married, and live in an apartment. We have $4,000
invested in Legg Mason Value Trust and add $150 a month. We have
stocks valued at $7,000 and $10,000 in bank savings. I contribute 6
percent of my earnings to a company-matched 401(k) plan. We want to
buy a house in the next six to eight months, but want to invest as
aggressively as possible. Our combined earnings are $72,000 a year.
What would be the best approach to take toward investing while
saving for the house?
</P>
<P>
   S.S., Gloucester, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The critical thing is to decide what the purpose of each of
your current portfolio assets is, and then to tailor the investment
to that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   With the projected home purchase less than a year away,
short-term CDs, money markets, or even bank savings are appropriate
for that money, and, as I discussed in the letter above, nothing
very much more aggressive is appropriate. Then isolate which
accounts you consider as your retirement savings, and put these in
growth-oriented stock accounts or stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   Isolate a fairly small portion of your portfolio as emergency
savings, and keep that in a liquid vehicle similar to what you will
be using to save toward your real estate down payment.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, if either the Legg Mason account or the individual
stock holdings are ultimately going to be used for the down
payment, the time to sell them is now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
