<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING HER CLAWS INTO FELINE RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This morning I saw that during the night one or perhaps both of
the cats had managed to separate a big piece of fringe from the
edge of an oriental rug. Nearby lay the damp, mutilated fringe,
Sunday part of a handsome carpet, today just another cat toy.
</P>
<P>
   I took a deep breath and told myself once again that cats will
be cats. A gnawed rug is a small price to pay for their
companionship. Which brings me to why I could never vote for
Hillary Clinton. During that unctuous performance on David
Letterman's ``Late Show'' the other night, she admitted that first
feline Socks has been declawed.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it's not the only reason I could never vote for her, just
the latest. But it's as good as any, and symbolic in a way of her
whole ethos.
</P>
<P>
   How would she like it if somebody cut off the ends of her
fingers? Because that's what declawing amounts to. Here's a partial
description of the operation, from ``The Cornell Book of Cats,'' by
the faculty and staff of Cornell University's Feline Health Center:
``The nail is not pulled; instead, the end bone of the digit
holding the claw is amputated at the joint . . . the feet are
bandaged, and several days of hospitalization are required.''
</P>
<P>
   Declawing is at best controversial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad and frustrating that this is a tolerated
procedure and that people don't know it's cruel,'' says Barbara
Stagno, Northeast director of In Defense of Animals. ``People think
that if veterinarians are willing to do it, it couldn't be
inhumane. But if people knew what was involved in declawing, most
of them wouldn't opt for it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Letterman's show, Clinton explained that Socks had been
declawed to prevent him damaging White House furniture, ``like
George Washington's chair.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added, ``I didn't want to have to explain what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Socks ever succeeded in scratching any
national treasures. Could the declawing have been a preemptive
strike, based on the species-ist assumption that all cats are
destructive?
</P>
<P>
   And what of Buddy, the presidential dog? Has he never scratched
a White House door? I bet he still has all his toenails. When he
misbehaves he turns on the charm and all is forgiven. Just like a
dog. Just like his owner, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   There are ways other than surgery to discourage cats from
tearing apart your house. Scratching posts. Behavior modification.
Little plastic caps that can be affixed to the cat's nails,
assuming the cat will stand for it. Mine won't. Actually, nothing
I've ever tried has succeeded in stopping the little devils from
shredding the furniture. But I know some of these methods have
worked for others.
</P>
<P>
   Cats use their claws for grooming, climbing, and protection, as
well as scratching. Declawing is not in the best interest of the
cat, but of the owner. It's often a last resort for people who've
tried other methods of curbing a cat's destructive behavior. The
best that can be said of declawing is that it's preferable to
getting rid of the cat. ``We love our cats,'' says Stagno, ``but
some of us love our furniture more.''
</P>
<P>
   True cat love transcends even shredded upholstery. Our furniture
is their furniture, too. Actually, as cats see it, it's their
furniture, period. Cartoonist Nicole Hollander once summed up a
cat's view of the world with the line, ``Everything here is mine.''
It's all too true in my house.
</P>
<P>
   Scratching is normal cat behavior, a form of self-expression.
``Animal behaviorists believe cats scratch objects primarily as a
function of communication,'' writes Amy D. Shojai in ``The Purina
Encyclopedia of Cat Care.'' ``Scratching leaves scent behind on the
object, as well as visible marks, and both communicate that the cat
has been there. It also conditions claws and tones muscles.''
</P>
<P>
   As you might imagine, my cats' claws are in beautiful condition.
I wish I could say the same for the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
