<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8104 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-VORES-BOS &LR;      01-17 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-VORES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AN AMERICAN BORN IN AN ENGLISHMAN'S BODY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Hoose and the Cantata Singers thought that the best way to
celebrate the new century was to commission a new piece, and the
composer they chose was Andy Vores.
</P>
<P>
   The result, Vores' ``World Wheel,'' is a piece that opens with
the ``Big Bang'' and then circles around 4,000 years of history.
The texts come from 2000 BC, 1000 BC, from the first century AD,
from 1000 AD and from living 20th-century American poets. The range
of musical styles and references is necessarily less diverse but
nevertheless pretty encompassing _ in the 20th-century alone they
range from Schoenberg and Stravinsky to Reich and Glass, with a bit
of James Brown too.
</P>
<P>
   Vores is unabashed by the word ``eclectic.'' ``I have very
catholic tastes,'' he says with a grin, ``and I don't think the
choices and disciplines of composing need to consist of an attempt
to filter out influences. They're going to be there, but I think it
all comes out sounding like me.'' He knew he was writing for the
Cantata Singers and David Hoose, so he knew there was no reason to
hold back. ``I do not think that David likes to feature singers and
small ensembles from the chorus as soloists, so I put some of that
into the piece, and I know Sandy Sylvan's voice, so his sound was
in my ear as I wrote. But mostly, writing for the Cantata Singers
meant I could do anything I wanted to because there's nothing they
can't do _ in this piece they clap, moan, and shout, and they sing
a lot too.''
</P>
<P>
   Vores's orchestration omits clarinets because he knew that he
would share the program with a Bach Cantata, but he did include an
electric guitar and synthesizer that Bach wouldn't have called for.
The score roams through and re-creates the characteristic sounds of
several different musical cultures. ``The piece has got a big
reach, from the beginning of time to the end of time _ all in 45
minutes of big, exciting noise. The piece really revels in various
kinds of sound,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``World Wheel'' is a big piece in a big year for the 43-year-old
composer, who is also writing pieces for Boston Musica Viva
(``Umberhulk'') and Triple Helix, the extraordinary piano trio.
Triple Helix will play the premiere of ``Dark Mother'' on its
Celebrity Series's Emerging Artists concert April 16 in Jordan
Hall. Vores has written pieces for so many Emerging Artist and
Celebrity Series concerts _ the Borromeo Quartet, soprano Dominique
Labelle, and soprano Kendra Colton _ that he has been named
composer-in-residence for the Emerging Artist series.
</P>
<P>
   Vores was born in Wales and went to university in Lancaster,
England; in those days he played drums and keyboards in rock bands.
At Lancaster he came into the orbit of the composer Edward Cowie
and decided that's what he wanted to do himself: write music. He
arrived at Tanglewood as a student in 1986; there he met the
talented collaborative pianist Patricia Thom, who is now his wife,
and the administrator of the Walnut Hill School in Natick. Vores
has lived in this country ever since. ``I think I was an American
born in an Englishman's body,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Britain has more elaborate support systems for composers than
there are in this country, and more avenues to bring new work
forward more prominently. But Vores has not regretted his decision
to remain in America. ``The British musical scene is very cliquey,
and to that degree depressing. And most British composers complain
all the time about the same things American composers complain
about _ they can't get everything they want. I find the atmosphere
in America much less oppressive. There is a kind of house style in
English music _ bright, spiky, brittle, woodwind heavy _ that is
used by everyone, from the very talented, like Thomaas Ades and
Julian Anderson, on down the list. But it is really just one kind
of sound, and it is not my kind of sound _ I'm just not into that.
When I was at Tanglewood, I wrote a piece with a key signature, and
it was a kind of liberation. I discovered I didn't need to be
afraid I was going to be attacked by ravens!''
</P>
<P>
   Vores has been a popular figure on Boston's new-music scene for
most of the last 15 years, and he has achieved his prominence the
hard way, because he hasn't supported his composing by taking on a
full-time academic position. For many years, he worked as a music
copyist for other composers, although the music-copying business
has dried up these days because of developments in computer
software; now he teaches one seminar at Walnut Hill and relies on
the commissions that keep steadily coming in.
</P>
<P>
   Vores met David Hoose in 1989 and Hoose conducted the premiere
of Vores's delightful Virginia Woolf opera, ``Freshwater,'' at
Boston University in 1994. ``Freshwater'' seemed to have a future
as a workshop/adventuresome-small-company piece, but so far it
hasn't been produced since the premiere, although there have been
some near misses. Vores was particularly disappointed when a
production on the Isle of Wight, the setting for the opera, fell
through when the fund-raiser got sick. Through the years, Hoose and
Vores have spoken about the possibility of writing something for
the Cantata Singers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took the millennium to bring it about,'' Vores said. ``I
made a proposal and then we argued about texts for a while. I
should not say `argued.' We discussed texts, and then I wrote it.
When David asked me for a formal proposal, I had a library full of
texts I wanted to use some day. They didn't have much to do with
each other, so my first job was to create a framework within which
they could meet up and begin to mean something together.''
</P>
<P>
   The piece now falls into six movements, including the opening
orchestral ``Big Bang.'' ``Before and After Time'' features texts
from the Enuma Elish and the Egyptian Book of the Dead. ``The
Created Universe'' assembles texts from the Odyssey and the
Upanishads. ``Apocalyptic Visions'' draws on Suetonius's life of
Nero and the New Testament book of Revelations. ``Distant Shores''
sets passages from the Anglo-Saxon poem ``Deor'' and the Japanese
classic ``The Pillow Book of Sei Shonagon.'' The final section,
``Future,'' sets poems by Peter Davison, Anne Waldman, and Liesel
Mueller. The music links and interprets the texts, associating each
movement with one of the primal elements (earth, air, fire, water);
a characteristic interval generates and governs the music in each
section, and in the end, the work returns to its beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Vores's Musica Viva piece, he says, ``is being written even as
we speak. It is a low and growly piece, but I hope a different kind
of low and growly piece. There is so much heavy, dark music in this
world; I want to write a fizzy dark piece! I chose an unusual
ensemble of low instruments for this because I am so tired of
hearing the new-music ensemble that has become standard since
Schoenberg's `Pierrot lunaire.' That's a great ensemble, but I
don't see any need for me to write for those sounds again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark Mother,'' for Triple Helix, is a response to the myth of
Demeter and Persephone. ``It's not a narrative piece, but it
depicts the emotional landscape of that story. It begins with music
of burgeoning, unstoppable abundance. Then it moves into a section
of mourning, one long line that moves down from the top of the
violin to the bass of the cello. The third movement brings stasis,
and in the fourth movement we hear the invention of all the
seasons, which pass by in a procession to a kind of springlike
English round tune that gets faster and faster until the end. The
members of Triple Helix _ Bayla Keyes, Rhonda Rider, and Lois
Shapiro _ said they wanted a virtuosic piece, and that's what they
got.''
</P>
<P>
   Vores looks for nothing from his audiences beyond a degree of
open-mindedness. ``I don't care what people bring into Jordan Hall
_ although I would prefer they didn't bring their candy wrapped in
cellophane, their noisy bags from Stop and Shop, or their beepers
and cell phones! Actually at the end of `World Wheel,' they can
beep away all they want, because no one will hear them!''
</P>
<P>
   Vores is more eloquent on the subject of what he hopes the
audience will take away from next weekend's performances. ``One of
the reasons I wrote this piece is to recognize how far from an
absolute our own culture is. Some of the ancient civilizations long
outlasted ours, but they were transitory _ just as ours is likely
to be. I wasn't particularly interested in creating a politically
correct multicultural event. But I wanted to find expression for
the idea that no matter how alien a culture might feel to us, when
a culture comes down to individuals, their concerns are always the
same as ours are. This is not a revelation, of course, but I hope
the audience will like how the music sounds and get excited by it.
I want the audience to know how user-friendly my music is; I hope
people will find it worthwhile _ and then come back for more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
