<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HOLLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING THE LANGUAGE OF FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If film is truly an international language, count Polish-born
director Agnieszka Holland among its true multilingual talents. She
speaks seven languages and has made movies in four of them (Polish,
English, German, French). She has been nominated for Oscars for
``Europa, Europa'' and ``Angry Harvest,'' and is noted for the
serious nature of her films. (On her wish list: a comedy.)
</P>
<P>
   Holland's latest film, ``The Third Miracle,'' a spiritual
detective story set in Chicago, is in English. It stars her friend
and collaborator Ed Harris as a lapsed Catholic priest questioning
his faith, and Anne Heche as a feisty intellectual foil and
potential love interest.
</P>
<P>
   What are the advantages and disadvantages of working in English?
</P>
<P>
   ``My English is, of course, kind of basic,'' she says during an
interview at a Back Bay restaurant. ``It means I can feel the truth
of the acting, but I cannot really tell you the reality in the
dialogue _ I don't feel totally free in that. But English is, for
anything dramatical, for theater and for movies, one of the best
languages because it is very direct, very energetic, with natural
energy to it. And another advantage is that so many people over the
world understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland, the daughter of a nonpracticing Jewish father and a
nonpracticing Catholic mother, has, cinematically, dealt with
spiritual issues in the past. ``The Third Miracle'' concerns Father
Frank Shore's attempts to verify miracles performed in the name of
the late mother of Roxanna, Heche's character. Roxanna is an
adamant nonbeliever who feels she was mistreated or ignored by her
mother _ even as everyone else seems to consider her saintly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Third Miracle'' presents startling tales of mysterious,
unexplained healings, of Madonna statues that bleed, and of
skepticism about it all. It is the task of Father Frank, a
semiretired postulator (i.e., spiritual sleuth), to return to his
calling, that is, to investigate and determine whether the woman
should be recommended to move up the heavenly ladder toward
sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   Holland, 51, became interested in the Catholic Church as a
teenager, growing up in postwar Poland. It was a form of rebellion.
Her Communist parents ``would march against the Catholic Church for
many reasons,'' Holland recalls. ``I went to the church and the
religious classes in secret. It was kind of my opposition to their
very materialistic point of view, and it was kind of exciting, you
know, to be a martyr for the faith. I really had a strong sense of
the mystical and metaphysical content. And I was extremely touched
by the Gospel, the New Testament.''
</P>
<P>
   In her 20s, Holland moved away from the church. She questioned
the moral behavior of some of the priests; she was repulsed by an
anti-Semitic strain she felt the faith contained. But, she says,
``the questions the institution asks you are important to me and
that remained with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland, who also spoke via telephone from her daughter's home
in Los Angeles after the Boston interview, read the novel ``The
Third Miracle'' by American writer Richard Vetere, and, she says,
``had quite a strong reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had doubts (about filming it), of course,'' she continues,
``but what attracted me was the challenge: How do you make a
serious religious movie without doing it in a kind of horror, or
sexually colored, or special-effects way, to make it in a very
human way?'' She refers to ``The Exorcist'' and ``Priest'' as
movies that have gone down those particular paths.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A socio-psychological story
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Third Miracle'' begins with the German bombing of a
village in Slovakia during World War II. Quickly, Holland cuts to
1979 and we meet Father Frank, who has left the priesthood and
lives in a Chicago halfway house.
</P>
<P>
   ``What attracted me to `The Third Miracle' was that it doesn't
have a very clear kind of narrative form or style,'' Holland says.
``It starts very realistic, kind of a socio-psychological story.
And it changes to (be about) a real man,'' that is, Father Frank.
</P>
<P>
   Casting Harris was an integral part of getting the picture made.
She had directed him previously in ``To Kill a Priest'' (irony
noted, with a smile) and felt Father Frank was Harris and Harris
was Father Frank. ``That character is the main interest of the
story to me,'' says Holland. ``And when Ed decided that he was
interested, that he wanted to do it with me, then I knew it was
worth it to try. I knew one thing: I would not succeed with this
movie if I didn't have the actor who is soulful and deep enough to
make credible the struggles of this character.''
</P>
<P>
   The trust and friendship they had, she adds, gave them ``the
courage to go the places which are not obvious.'' Harris did not
demand the kind of money he earns in big budget Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Third Miracle'' takes a series of twists, turns, and
shifts of emphasis as it delves into the internecine struggles of
the church's politicized hierarchy debating the validity of the
miracles and the checkered life of the potential saint. And you
feel Father Frank's conflict. He is torn between doubt and faith
(``someone who needs constant proof,'' says Holland) and, in the
physical realm, he is severely tempted by Heche's character. Father
Frank ``is not asexual,'' says Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Of Heche, she says, ``I think Anne is definitely one of the most
unique and talented actresses of her generation. And she's very
courageous. She doesn't have problems trying different things,
going over borders. And she has an incredible temperament. She
gives energy and life, which was extremely important in this story,
which has kind of a serious sense and kind of a depressed tone.''
</P>
<P>
   There is resolution in ``The Third Miracle,'' but some issues
are left open. Will ``The Third Miracle'' be a difficult movie for
people?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, for some people, maybe,'' Holland admits. ``There is not
a clear conclusion and that can be a problem because they are,
unfortunately, used to a very simplistic kind of story _ bad is
bad, right is right. But what I've seen from the (advance)
screenings is the people react quite emotionally. If you are able
to accept this kind of a subject, I think that the emotional
content of the movie is strong enough to take them on a journey.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the Catholic Church's response, says Holland, ``I don't
have that information, but I have the impression that it was quite
positive. Some reviews in Catholic newspapers were kind of nice.
Some priests were really touched because they found it an accurate
description of their problems. . . . We are not so sure about the
bishops. But what I love about the Church is that is it such a
complex institution, with all kinds of people and dimensions that
are so numerous _ political, economical, spiritual.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland does not make fun of those who do believe in miracles.
``I think it's fantastic, and I don't have these feelings that they
are backward and naive at all because they need some knd of `higher
power' to go with their life. Some people have the gift to believe
in it, and what was interesting for me was always when I met the
real intellectuals who are the believers. I met several people like
that, some highly regarded intellectuals who don't have doubt that
this exists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always something to discourage us, yet on the other
hand, I was always more attracted to the people who are struggling,
who don't take anything for granted and need to constantly check
the reality of their faith and their decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Holland believe in miracles?
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, I am a typical person, like (Harris's)
character. I do believe and I don't believe. It's troubling. It's
not only (the question of) the miracles, there's also the existence
of something with such a strong definition like a `God.' Of some
kind of afterlife, of some kind of metaphysical presence. It is,
for me, an emotional and psychological game, at times. I cannot
tell you that I do believe, but I can tell you that I am open. . .
. I think it is too boring to accept (that) everything is dependent
on a rational explanation. I was too long living in a Communist
country to accept that. If miracles don't exist, you have to create
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
