<HEADER>
A8110 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-VISION-ART-BOS &LR;      01-17 1593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VISION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TECHNIQUE MAY HALT VISION-LOSS CONDITION IN ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036 . )   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Snaking beneath the thin retina at the back of the eye, tiny
blood vessels grow where they shouldn't be growing, leaking blood
and fluid and buckling and damaging the light-sensitive tissue in
tens of thousands of people each year.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of this process, referred to as the ``wet'' form of
age-related macular degeneration (AMD), the central zone of vision
blurs and darkens, leaving a ring of less-sharp peripheral sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Living with macular degeneration means living in a half-veiled
world,'' wrote Henry Grunwald, former editor in chief of Time, in a
recent account of his struggle to cope with this insidious disease.
</P>
<P>
   Until the last few years, there was no treatment for wet AMD,
except for blasting the abnormal blood vessels with a powerful
laser, which inevitably damaged the retina.
</P>
<P>
   But a new procedure conceived in Boston and tested at eye
centers in the United States and abroad is expected to be approved
by the US Food and Drug Administration, possibly as soon as next
month.
</P>
<P>
   Called photodynamic therapy, or PDT, it attacks the rogue blood
vessels, which doctors fill with a light-sensitive dye that is then
activated by a laser that is beamed through the pupil. This
chemical reaction destroys the tiny vessels and seals off the
bleeding, without damaging the overlying retina's vision cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first treatment (for wet macular degeneration)
that's been shown effective in large clinical trials,'' said Dr.
Joan Miller, an eye surgeon at the Massachusetts Eye and Ear
Infirmary, where the procedure was developed. Miller and her
colleague, Dr. Evangelos S. Gragoudas, suggested as far back as
1991 that PDT, which has previously been used in treating cancer,
might be a novel weapon against wet macular degeneration.
</P>
<P>
   AMD, in its wet form and the more common but less severe ``dry''
form, is the leading cause of severe vision loss in people over 50,
affecting an estimated 25 to 30 million people worldwide. Most of
the serious vision loss is caused by the wet form, which involves
the leaking, abnormal blood vessels. It strikes about 10 to 15
percent of all AMD patients.
</P>
<P>
   The exact cause isn't known, but risk factors, in addition to
age, may include genetics, smoking, cataracts, excessive sun
exposure, and a diet low in certain antioxidants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Macular'' in AMD refers to the macula, the circle of
densely-packed light-sensing cells in the center of the retina,
which are used for reading and detailed vision. When the macula is
damaged, a person loses central vision, often forcing him or her to
give up driving, making reading difficult or impossible, and
blotting out the details of faces.
</P>
<P>
   Patients often become dependent on low-vision aids _ like
magnifiers and reading machines _ and on human helpers. As their
world shrinks, they may become withdrawn and depressed.
</P>
<P>
   The new treatment, PDT, is not a cure. Nor does it bring back
vision that's been lost. But in many cases it can prevent the
disease from worsening _ for how long isn't yet known _ and it has
even slightly improved sight in a small number of volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neil Bressler, a Johns Hopkins School of Medicine
ophthalmologist, said that while the treatment won't enable
patients to resume driving, for example, it will help preserve
vision, ``so that it's more likely you can do more things for
yourself, like using magnification aids to read your bills, so you
don't have to wait for your daughter to come over and read them for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Eye and Ear's Miller and Gragoudas carried out
animal tests that demonstrated the effectiveness of PDT and
established treatment guidelines. They then led clinical tests that
began in 1995 and produced favorable results that CIBAVision, of
Duluth, Ga., submitted to the FDA seeking approval to commercialize
it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first patients to be treated in the clinical trial
was Suzanne Deuchler, 70, of Aurora, Ill. She said recently that
PDT treatments at Mass Eye and Ear have enabled her to continue her
political lobbying work in Illinois, where she is a former member
of the state legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have pretty much held my own'' against the disease since
entering the PDT clinical trial in 1996, she said in a recent
interview after her latest dye-and-laser treatment. Following a few
sessions, she's actually found her vision not just stabilized but
improved slightly. ``I could look at the hands and numbers of my
watch, and they were much sharper,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Regan, a 67-year-old electronics engineer, got PDT
treatment in his left eye, which was virtually blinded by wet
macular degeneration.
</P>
<P>
   After several treatments, he says, ``I have now recovered a
great deal of the sense of an image. It's poorly defined; it's
mottled and distorted as if looking through a Coke bottle bottom _
but it's better than it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those most enthusiastic about PDT caution that it is not a
magic bullet for wet AMD. Only about 30 percent of people with the
problem will be good candidates, based on the location of the
leaking vessels. In addition, because the vessels often grow back,
most patients in the trials have needed repeated treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``I think the enthusiasm is totally justified, and
I think it will be widely used,'' said Dr. Carmen Puliafito,
director of the New England Eye Center, where about 100 macular
degeneration patients underwent PDT treatment as part of the
clinical trials. ``There was nothing we could do about this in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   PDT treatment takes only a half-hour or so, and begins with an
intravenous injection of the light-sensitive dye into the patient's
arm. The dye makes its way through the circulation and accumulates
in the abnormal blood vessels beneath the retina. After 15 minutes,
the doctor shines a low-powered laser through the pupil: when it
hits the dye in the abnormal blood vessels, the dye releases
substances that destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   The patient has to wear dark glasses and stay away from sunshine
and fluorescent lights for a few days, but otherwise there are no
apparent side effects.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, researchers published results of the latest phase of
the PDT clinical trials, comparing patients who received the
light-sensitive drug and laser treatment to those who got an
inactive placebo drug by injection.
</P>
<P>
   One year after treatment, 61 percent of those who received the
active drug had a small or no loss of vision, compared to 46
percent of those on the placebo. That's significant, though not
dramatic. But in a subgroup of patients who had what's called the
``classic'' form of wet AMD, meaning that the errant blood vessels
are growing under the center of the retina and their extent is
well-defined, the results were stronger: 67 percent of the treated
volunteers lost little vision, compared to 39 percent of placebo
patients.
</P>
<P>
   There's similar optimism at CIBAVision, which is marketing the
treatment under the name Visudyne. (A separate company, QLT
PhotoTherapeutics of Vancouver, makes the Visudyne dye.) ``We feel
confident'' that the agency will act favorably, said Stephen Lang,
a marketing executive with CIBA Vision. The procedure is expected
to cost about $1,500 per treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Because most AMD patients are on Medicare, the cost of
treatments _ and retreatments _ presumably will fall mainly on the
federal government. Reimbursement policy won't be set until the
treatment wins FDA approval, said a spokesman for the U.S.
Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Some eye specialists want to see more data on PDT's
effectiveness before they wholeheartedly endorse it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not clear how much you're gaining'' in extra months or
years of vision, said Dr. Michael Marmor, a retina specialist at
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it turns out that 80 percent of people stabilize with
useful reading vision for five years, then it would be
worthwhile,'' said Marmor, speaking on behalf of the American
Academy of Ophthalmology. ``But if you're only prolonging useful
vision by three to five months, then I don't think it's
economically reasonable in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Marmor, however, called the technique ``powerful'' and said
research should continue in hopes of improving PDT's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   What is not clear from the trials so far is how frequently
patients may need retreatments to shut down maverick blood vessels
that regrow following PDT. In the clinical trials, most patients
needed retreatment, some as often as every three months. Miller at
Mass Eye and Ear says that after several treatments the blood
vessels may be less prone to re-forming, but only longer followup
will determine that.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other efforts to combat wet AMD continue. Some
researchers are working with angiogenesis inhibitors, substances
that curb the growth of new blood vessels. None has yet proven
successful, but research go``There's huge interest in
angiogenesis inhibitors here,'' said senior scientist Ann Elsner at
the Schepens Eye Research Institute in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   What has driven her to spend the past 12 years trying to find
answers to macular degeneration, she said, ``is that we see the
awful outcome every day. It's just a huge public health problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
