<SLUG> BC-SCI-GIRL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT MCLEAN, LIVES INTERRUPTED _ AND HEALED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The urge to write about crossing the line into a ``parallel
universe,'' and her nearly two-year stay at McLean Hospital in the
1960s, came to Susanna Kaysen while she was penning a novel about
an anthropologist living in foreign lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded me of being plopped down'' at the Belmont, Mass.
psychiatric hospital, said Kaysen, 51, author of the 1993 memoir
``Girl, Interrupted,'' which became a surprise bestseller and
serves as the basis for the new movie of the same name starring
Winona Ryder.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the day the movie opened nationwide, Kaysen
returned to McLean to talk about her experiences there to current
and former patients and staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be back at McLean. It's such a pleasure to just
(be able to) leave,'' said Kaysen to laughter. More than 350 people
attended the meeting, titled ``Psychiatric care from the consumer
point of view: Past, present and future.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaysen was admitted to McLean with ``borderline personality,'' a
diagnosis that she only learned about years later, and that she
eloquently dissects and ultimately discards in a chapter of her
book.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview and during the talk, Kaysen described the good
and the bad aspects of her hospital stay, which began after she
made a brief visit to a psychiatrist as a teen-ager in the
turbulent 1960s, seeking ``a rest,'' she said, and help with
self-destructive thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   While Kaysen spoke of her hospitalization more than 30 years
ago, another former patient talked of her healing stays at McLean
in the 1990s, and staff members discussed how care has changed in
the last 30 years, with patients more involved now as partners in
treatment and diagnosis, new medications, and insurers' limits on
lengths of stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many things I loved about the old McLean,''
particularly the number of staff available to complain to, Kaysen
said during the talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I had a bad time there. Some of it I hated. Some
of it I didn't hate. . . . Like most things in life, it was a mixed
experience,'' she added in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, Interrupted'' provides a snapshot in time, in America,
and in psychiatric care, featuring vignettes of fellow patients and
of life on a locked ward.
</P>
<P>
   But it also addresses universal themes of emotional pain and
healing, and highlights some of the issues that are still debated
in psychiatry today: ambiguous diagnoses, questionable or unproven
treatments, and the role that patients play in their own healing.
</P>
<P>
   Girls and young women who have perhaps had some of the same
suicidal thoughts and self-destructive behaviors that Kaysen did as
an 18-year-old have been some of the biggest fans of the book.
</P>
<P>
   Winona Ryder, who plays the young Kaysen, knew she wanted to
make a movie based on the book after she read it, she has said in
interviews. The movie, loosely based on the book, was filmed at a
hospital in Pennsylvania. McLean declined to serve as the location
for the filming to protect patient confidentiality, although the
hospital allowed a film crew to take environmental shots.
</P>
<P>
   And while many things have changed at McLean and other
psychiatric hospitals since the 1960s, Kaysen's questioning of the
diagnosis she was given and other aspects of her hospitalization
resonates with many psychiatrists and patients.
</P>
<P>
   One professional man who checked himself into McLean one
Saturday night last year, because he was feeling anxious and having
trouble with the medication he was taking for manic depression,
criticized the hospital for not letting him leave the next morning,
as promised, when it turned out that no doctor was available to see
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was upsetting,'' said the man, who did not want his name
used. While his other experiences with McLean have been positive,
this one was clearly not. He ultimately was able to sneak out of
the unit.
</P>
<P>
   McLean is a storied place of lives interrupted, and often
healed. Poets Sylvia Plath and Robert Lowell were once hospitalized
there. So were musicians Ray Charles and siblings James,
Livingston, and Kate Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   One of James Taylor's early songs, ``Knocking 'Round the Zoo,''
is said to have been about his experience there as a teen-ager, and
his better-known ``Fire and Rain'' is also said to have been
inspired by that period.
</P>
<P>
   And the nursery rhyme ``Mary Had a Little Lamb'' was written in
the 1800s about a McLean nurse who once had a lamb that followed
her everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard psychiatrist Stephen Bergman _ who used the pen name
Samuel Shem to write the 1997 satirical novel ``Mount Misery,''
which some say is loosely based on McLean _ criticized today's
psychiatric hospitals for spending too little time establishing
human connections with patients, and too much time giving them
medications, largely as a result of insurance restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   If a teen-age girl today facing the same issues that Kaysen
confronted in the 1960s needed psychiatric care, ``what would
happen to her now? She wouldn't even get admitted,'' said Bergman,
who knows Kaysen and called her book ``wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if psychiatric care has changed because of insurance,
Kaysen concluded her remarks last Friday at the Belmont hospital by
saying, ``I'm glad that there's still a McLean.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
