<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HILLARY CLINTON'S GAME OF SOFTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN LYNCH  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Essentially, politics is about being liked. You
lose elections if you rub people the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   And, since most people who run for office aren't at all like the
rest of us _ they tend to be tougher, hungrier for power and more
eager for attention _ politics is also about artifice. It's about
conveying the often erroneous impression that you're a nice person
even though many of the personal traits you'll need to win election
aren't nice at all.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no surprise that Hillary Rodham Clinton popped up on
David Letterman's show the other night, exuding warmth and wit
while maintaining steadfast aloofness from any more penetrating
media setting. She even had her own ``Top 10 List.'' If you watched
this thing, you wouldn't have been surprised to see the first lady
burst into a chorus of, ``Lullaby of Broadway'' or launch into a
stand-up routine. (``Take my husband _ please.'')
</P>
<P>
   New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani also has done Letterman on
several occasions. He even popped up once in drag for a ``Saturday
Night Live'' gig. There's a long tradition of this sort of stuff.
Candidate Bill Clinton played his sax on Arsenio Hall's program.
Even Richard Nixon once went on Jack Paar's show to play the piano
and, years later, on ``Laugh In'' to mutter darkly into the camera,
``Sock it to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Once, when asked if he agreed that Lionel Barrymore was
America's greatest actor, Franklin Delano Roosevelt disputed that
assessment. America's greatest actor, the president said, was
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, today's seamless web of entertainment, journalism
and politics has distinctly disturbing overtones. It's not that
there's anything really shameful about President Clinton revealing
on MTV what type of underwear he wears _ briefs, not shorts _
especially considering his other, more disturbing proclivities. But
it is undignified. Abe Lincoln had a vibrant sense of humor, but he
surely wouldn't have answered that. Harry Truman would have sent
the kid on MTV to his room with no TV.
</P>
<P>
   Why do the politicians do it? To sell themselves. They do it
because they perceive that we demand it. They do it because they
understand that getting elected in a nation of television addicts
requires connecting with those entertainment junkies _ to the
people who know Letterman but never heard of Tim Russert, Sam
Donaldson or Jim Lehrer.
</P>
<P>
   Which is fine except, more and more, politicians who used to
seek news coverage now avoid it. They now understand that they can
get out their messages just the way they want them presented
through paid advertising provided by contributors who always want
something back in the form of tax dollars. And now they're moving
with great glee to settings like the Letterman show where they know
they'll be pitched softballs _ where they know, essentially, that
nobody will ask them a hard question, nobody will try to reveal to
the public anything about them that they don't want revealed.
</P>
<P>
   So, now Larry King _ the unchallenged champion of the softball
pitchers _ passes for a journalist in the eyes of so many.
Meanwhile, Hillary Clinton refuses any substantial news interview
in New York, where she's supposed to be running for the U.S.
Senate. She uses Secret Service agents to keep reporters at bay as
though they were ... well, mere citizens.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad for democracy. Ultimately, it's bad for anybody who
believes that people have a right to information that'll better
enable them to govern themselves. The problem is that so many
people demand nothing of politicians but smiles and yuks. In the
end, though, it's not about who's warm and amusing.
</P>
<P>
   It's about who can do the job.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 14:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8115 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-TEXAS-CAMELS-2TAKES-H     01-17 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CAMELS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ENJOYING A TEXAS CAMEL RIDE, HUMPS AND ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Photos available on Wieck database)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EMILY SPICER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIG BEND RANCH STATE PARK, Texas _ It's midmorning in September
and the West Texas sun is already shining hot on the back of my
neck.
</P>
<P>
   The silent, sparkling slow sunrise is over, and I stand outside
the corral, kicking up dust with my boots, waiting.
</P>
<P>
   There is no wind, no birdsong, and no highway noise. Just the
sound of six very annoyed camels getting saddled.
</P>
<P>
   Camels. West Texas. Me.
</P>
<P>
   It's day two of this trail ride and the absurdity of the
situation _ me on a camel in Texas _ hasn't worn off. It doesn't
matter that I know camels were used by the cavalry in Texas before
the Civil War. Yes, camels were in competition with horses as part
of an experiment to see which made the better pack animal.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a very long time ago, and camels really do look
strange crossing the desert of West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Braaaaaaangh,'' fills the still, dusty air, drowning out the
confused braying of the camels' equine neighbors. I watch the
saddling process, my eyes fixed on Brutus, the camel I will ride.
</P>
<P>
   He is nearly 4 feet taller than I am, tied to a rail in the
corral. He's already been saddled, and waits, silently, looking
down his nose at me, the plebian who is about to mount him. I wipe
a little sweat off my upper lip and try to look cool by perching my
cowboy booted foot on one of the bottom rails, the way I have seen
mean hombres do in old Westerns.
</P>
<P>
   My foot slips off, pitching me forward like Chevy Chase doing
his best Gerald Ford schtick. Brutus simply turns and looks the
other way.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think it's a good sign. And today, I want nothing but
good omens.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, the first day of the trail ride, I spent six hours on
a camel and now my nether region is numb, chafed and bruised. I
have no idea what another six hours will do to me. Do people
spontaneously break in half the way some spontaneously combust?
</P>
<P>
   What really frightens me is that yesterday was the easy ride
according to Doug Baum, the owner of this camel outfit. Baum has
owned and operated the Texas Camel Corps for six years,
participating in parades, school programs, cavalry march
re-enactments across the state, and organizing trail rides through
state parks. In the past he had rides through Arizona, but is now
concentrating on Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Today is the challenging ride where we go up steep hills, and
(more frighteningly) down steep hills where the camels have a
tendency to trot. Up and down. And that makes me go up and down.
And I just don't know if my bottom can handle that.
</P>
<P>
   My neurotic flow is interrupted when Baum shouts at me from the
corral, ``Hey, Emily, you're up!''
</P>
<P>
   Ohmylordhelpmeplease.
</P>
<P>
   I walk through the corral to Brutus, who sits kneeling in the
center. I try to walk with a confident swagger. Can't horses smell
fear? Maybe camels can, too. Unfortunately, Brutus misreads my cool
mosey for a simple case of bowlegged saddle soreness, and he
doesn't look impressed. Of coarse, the beast has a schnoz the size
of the Texas Panhandle, which would give anyone a perpetually
haughty, mildly repulsed look.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I can win him over with a flawless mount. Left foot in the
stirrup, swing the right leg over, land as softly as a pile as
feathers, I think, repeating Baum's advice.
</P>
<P>
   But my leg doesn't quite clear Brutus' 6-foot hump, and I land
more like a lump of lead. A very sore, nervous lump of lead. I
swear that camel shakes his head at me.
</P>
<P>
   I brace myself for liftoff as Brutus stands, back end first,
then the front. He takes his first step, I settle onto the hard
metal and leather saddle, and pain is instant. But then,
gloriously, comes the numbness.
</P>
<P>
   Like the day before, I am the last in line on the ride. I have
an intriguing view of five camel rumps when I look straight ahead.
So instead, I try to take in the scenery around me: sharp red rock
peaks against a clear blue sky and miles of brown earth. We covered
12 miles the first day, and should do nine miles today.
</P>
<P>
   The sway of Brutus' walking combined with the silence and clean
air and humbling surroundings to lull me into a peaceful,
contemplative state. Even with five other people on the ride, the
single-file nature makes conversation a little difficult.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
