<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8119 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-TEXAS-CAMELS-2NDTAKE-     01-17 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-CAMELS-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BIG BEND RANCH STATE PARK, Texas: x x x a little difficult. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I find that when I don't actually think about how my head is 14
feet off the ground and that a snake could dart out at any moment
and spook the camels, then I'm actually quite calm. Luckily the
couple of snakes, quails, jackrabbits and turkey buzzards that we
saw were far enough away not to spook the camels.
</P>
<P>
   Still, simply entertaining thoughts like those are an
irresistible invitation to disaster.
</P>
<P>
   We've maneuver a couple of hills without incident. But then we
veer off the trail and head through acres of thick, sharp-thorned
scrub to reach a dry creek bed that we'll follow to our next stop
for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Camels don't have hooves. They have thick, wide feet that are
designed to keep them afloat on sand. So rocky, uneven terrain is
not their ideal environment. And because they are tied to each
other caravan-style, when one camel loses his footing and starts
sliding/trotting down the side of a steep hill, getting close to
plunging into a ravine, the other camels follow.
</P>
<P>
   From my vantage point at the back of the line, I watch,
petrified, as that problem strikes just three camels ahead. It
really does look like a train wreck. Chug starts to panic about
getting through a narrow downhill pass and runs into Irenie, the
camel next to him. When he does, he slams the foot of Bobbie
Alford, the rider, into the metal frame of Irenie's saddle. She
screams.
</P>
<P>
   I guess Chug didn't want that to happen again, because at the
next narrow pass, rather than play follow-the-camel, he decides to
blaze his own trail along the edge of a ravine. In the process, he
loses his footing and almost sends them both over the edge. Really
panicked now, he freezes there, his rope pulling other camels
closer to the edge, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Brutus, realizing what's happening and anticipating his own
downfall, carefully steps to the side with no direction from me,
avoiding the five-camel pileup. Pileups are bad because when camels
aren't moving forward, they want to kneel down, or ``coush.'' And
when one goes down, all the others start getting ideas, and then
it's so hard to get them all up again at the same time and moving
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Brutus, however, letting his true noble side shine, stays up,
even when all the camels around him are dropping like fumigated
flies. Brutus, the bane of my trip, has become my hero. I lean
forward, risking being impaled from the metal saddle horn, and pat
his hump. I think he turns to look at me and I swear he was
winking. (So what if I can only see one eye?)
</P>
<P>
   After that, he steers clear of thorny branches rather than
suspiciously head toward ones at my face level. After that, I feel
much more calm and in control. I'm even rather entertained by the
drama of subsequent pileups. I think Brutus and I bonded.
</P>
<P>
   So when I get off that camel for lunch, the swagger in my walk
is more than just crippling pain and swelling. I'm a real cowgirl.
I am tough. Man, I rode that camel.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO:
</P>
<P>
   Doug Baum and his Texas Camel Corps are organizing the next
trail ride for March on the Friday Ranch, 20 miles northwest of
Uvalde. Trek dates are March 11-12, 13-14, 16-17 and 18-19.
</P>
<P>
   Camels and riders will cover 20 miles over two days and will
camp out the first evening. Meals will be provided by a camp cook.
</P>
<P>
   Local flora and fauna will be highlighted along the trail. Sites
include American Indian mounds, an old Spanish mine and scenic
overlooks of the Nueces River. Birding is reported to be good at
the ranch. Each ride is limited to six people and the all-inclusive
cost is $650.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, contact Baum at 254-675-4867 or e-mail
texascamelcorps(at)htcomp.net
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
