<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-CHARITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARITY FINDS A HOME ON THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In years past, Arthur Schmidt cultivated what might be called
``a paper bag strategy'' for his charitable giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw all the requests from nonprofits into a paper bag and
started sifting through them in mid-December,'' said Schmidt,
president of Philanthropic Research Inc. in Williamsburg, Va. ``But
that's pretty stupid, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he tossed out the paper bag and made his donations on
the Internet. He is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, charity has exploded on line, with
scores of Web sites being launched to promote charitable giving and
to raise funds in a variety of ways. Some shopping sites, such as
www.greatergood.com and www.igive.com, donate a small commission
from sales to the buyers' favorite cause, while other sites serve
as clearinghouses for donations.
</P>
<P>
   Technology not only makes it easier for individuals to donate to
their favorite causes 24 hours a day, seven days a week, but it
also provides users with more information than ever before, forcing
nonprofits to be more accountable to their supporters.
</P>
<P>
   In October, for instance, Schmidt's organization launched
www.guidestar.org, a Web site that posts the IRS forms that
charities file with the federal government, providing instant
access to information about how nonprofits use their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is the next big wave,'' said Jennifer Dunlop,
senior vice president of the American Red Cross. She said
e-philanthropy, as the trend is called, is the biggest change to
hit the fund-raising world since CNN began broadcasting in the
early '80s, beaming news about international disasters into living
rooms at all hours of the day. ``That caused a huge philanthropic
outpouring in this country, and this is going to be just as big,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The field is too new to gauge across the board, but it is
growing substantially. In fiscal year 1998, the Red Cross raised
$170,000 on its Web site; in fiscal year 1999 (which ended July 1),
that figure grew to $2.5 million. Likewise, the America Online
Foundation's philanthropy portal, www.helping.org, has raised
$500,000 for thousands of nonprofit organizations since it started
up in October, said AOL Foundation president David Eisner. And a
site called www.charitygift.com, a new service that enables people
to present charitable donations as gifts, raised $160,000 in its
first eight weeks of existence.
</P>
<P>
   New sites emerge every day. This month, local philanthropist and
businessman Steve Grossman is debuting www.givenation.com, a
charity portal that aims to create a community of givers. On the
site, users can read news about philanthropy, make credit card
gifts to hundreds of nonprofits, and establish memorials for family
and friends. ``This is a huge opportunity to create a nation of
givers,'' said Grossman, the former head of the Democratic National
Committee. ``Americans are charitable people, and if they are shown
a way to give efficiently and effectively, we think they will do so
in droves.''
</P>
<P>
   Givenation and sites like it aim to attract users like George
Gagliardi, a Web-savvy Concord, Mass. consultant. Last year, he and
his wife gave about $8,000 to charity, almost of all of it through
the Internet. ``I like to do things as efficiently as possible,''
he said, adding that he researches charities at www.give.org, a
site run by the National Charities Information Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Internet provides great educational potential for
motivated donors, it is also plagued with the potential for fraud.
``We are advising people to do their homework,'' said Sara E.
Melendez, president of Independent Sector, a Washington-based
coalition of nonprofit organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually anyone can set up a Web site to shill for a cause,
bona fide or bogus. ``You can imagine that someone could come up
with a Web site that tugs at your heartstrings and purports to do
all kinds of charitable things but that only exists in the mind of
the Web site designer,'' said Karl Emerson, director of
Pennsylvania's Bureau of Charitable Organizations and president of
the National Association of State Charity Officials.
</P>
<P>
   There are no rules governing charity on line, he said, and so
far, Internet fund-raisers are not required to register with state
officials, a requirement for telemarketers and direct mail
solicitors. At its recent annual meeting, Emerson's association
drafted a policy for regulating charity on line, but it will be
months before any final guidelines are issued.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, it's anything goes on line, particularly at the
shop-for-a-cause sites, which vary dramatically. Some of the sites
pocket as much as 50 percent of the commissions from sales
generated on their sites, and others enable customers to donate to
such questionable ``charities'' as The Broken Nose Fund, a Maine
man's personal plastic surgery cause.
</P>
<P>
   And it's hard to tell the difference between the on-line
ventures. AOL's helping.org is a nonprofit organization that
channels 100 percent of its donations to charity. But other similar
sites are for-profit ventures; some commercial operations make
their money through advertising and e-commerce, but others pocket a
percentage of each donation. Givenation will collect a modest fixed
fee, ranging from $2.50 to $5 per donation. But some sites keep
much more, which worries some in the nonprofit community.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is possible to fund-raise efficiently and effectively
and make a profit, well, that's the good old American way,'' said
Melendez. ``But if the profit starts to eat away at what I would
like to see going to the charity, then we need to take a second
look and monitor it closely.''
</P>
<P>
   The market is ripe for both idealists and opportunists; while
some sites are clearly profit-driven, others like helping.org and
givenation.com aspire to harness the power of the Internet to
effect sweeping social change. Yet, the most high-profile attempt
to encourage social activism on line failed dramatically last year.
NetAid (netaid.net), a joint effort of the United Nations
Development Program and Cisco Systems, was announced with great
fanfare as a portal to promote social activism and fight extreme
poverty. The Web site's debut was heralded by President Clinton and
South African President Nelson Mandela, and the site was feted with
three star-studded concerts. Despite all the hoopla, the concerts
raised only $12 million, relatively small compared with other
high-profile concert benefits. More important, the site has failed
to reach its stated goal of attracting a committed community of
volunteers and activists.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the philanthropy sector, a field traditionally slow to
change, are betting that the Internet will transform their business
irrevocably. But with Internet ventures, there are no guarantees.
``The jury is still out, and we'll have a lot more information next
Christmas,'' said Schmidt. ``At that point we'll have a better
indication of whether this is about fulfilling the incredible
promise or about the short, happy life of philanthropy on line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
