<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Jan. 18:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Mozdok, Russia) _ Russian troops assaulted
Grozny with major air and artillery strikes, as officials vowed to
capture the Chechen capital by Feb. 1. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Peace talks between Syria and
Israel, scheduled to continue on Wednesday, may be postponed after
Syrian radio reported that there is little point in resuming the
talks unless Israel first pledges to a total withdrawal from the
Golan Heights. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-PRESIDENT (Santiago) _ A profile of Ricardo Lagos, the
newly elected president, whose personal history mirrors the
evolution of Chilean politics since the 1973 coup. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   PINOCHET-BRITAIN (Madrid) _ The Spanish government agreed Monday
to forward to Britain a Spanish judge's request that Gen. Augusto
Pinochet undergo new medical tests to determine if he is truly
unfit to stand trial. By Al Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TIBET (Beijing) _ The rift between China and the Tibetan
government in exile widens after China announced that it had
enthroned a 2-year-old boy as one of Tibet's most important
religious leaders. The exiled Tibetan government in India denounced
the move, saying that the Dalai Lama did not recognize the boy as a
new ``living Buddha.'' By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-HOLOCAUST (Berlin) _ The mayor of Berlin said he would
not attend the dedication of the site for a new Holocaust Memorial.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONFEDERATE-FLAG-PROTEST (Colombia, S.C.) _ An estimated 20,000
people marched Monday, Martin Luther King Day, to protest the
Confederate Flag. By David Firestone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE-PIPELINE (Dateline to come) _ A plan to convert an
existing pipeline from crude oil to gasoline has stirred an unusual
controversy in Texas, a state where oil once was king.
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-GIULIANI (New York) _ Martin Luther King Day
observances with Hillary Clinton and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. By
Adam Nagourney and David W. Chen. (Story will also move in the
``p'' political category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRESIDENCY (Washington) _ The scene in the White House
as President Clinton enters his final year in office. By David E.
Sanger and Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-SECURITY (Washington) _ The Transportation Department is
re-thinking plans to test if airport security measures discriminate
against minorities after the Arab American Institute said the test
would be worse than the problem it is meant to detect. By Matthew
L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   IOWA-DEBATE (Des Moines) _ Coverage of the last debate before
the Iowa caucuses, with an overview of the week ahead in politics.
(Debate scheduled for 6 p.m. EST). By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CAMPAIGN (Atlanta) _ Vice President Al Gore observes Martin
Luther King Day in Atlanta. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-JOKES (Manchester, N.H.) _ A look at Sen. John McCain's
skills as a stand-up comic. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   FORBES-CAMPAIGN (Des Moines) _ Even though Steve Forbes has been
written off as a realistic presidential contender by most political
pundits, the Forbes campaign continues its seemingly never-ending
swing through Iowa , filled with the enthusiastic belief that one
day, if the breaks just fall their way, Forbes might actually
occupy the Oval Office. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   VOTING-RATES (Des Moines) _ The $1,000 limit on presidential
campaign contributions, enacted in 1974 in reaction to the
corruption of Watergate, now serves chiefly to clear the field
before anyone gets to vote, according to two prominent Republican
dropouts. Lamar Alexander and Dan Quayle, while praising
front-running Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, contended in separate
interviews that the narrowed field, combined with the scramble of
states to hold early primaries, is a major factor in the declining
voting rates: just 49 percent of adults voted in 1996. By Adam
Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A complete Science budget will move later &LR; . &UR; ) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-PREVENT (Undated) _ Over the years, researchers have
found hundreds of drugs to slow the growth of cancer. But they have
found virtually nothing that can prevent cancers from forming. Now,
however, scientists at the National Cancer Institute say they have
a promising candidate, an aspirinlike drug that is commonly used to
treat arthritis pain. By accident, scientists found that such drugs
might also prevent cancer. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INCOMPETENT-PEOPLE (Undated) _ A Cornell researcher has
found that most incompetent people do not know that they are
incompetent. In fact, people who do things badly, researchers
found, are usually supremely confident of their abilities _ more
confident, in fact, than people who do things well. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GLAXO-SMITHKLINE (London) _ Updates on the Glaxo-Smithkline
deal. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-ZONE (Quito, Ecuador) _ In Latin America, Ecuador has
never been regarded as an economic power or innovator. But by
deciding to replace Ecuador's currency with the U.S. dollar,
President Jamil Mahuad has suddenly thrust his nation onto
centerstage of a heated, continent-wide debate about monetary
policy and economic relations with the United States. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ The merger of America Online and
Time Warner promises to hasten the arrival of the day when music is
distributed digitally through the Internet rather than through
record stores. But there are numerous obstacles to overcome before
consumers routinely download music instead of buying compact disks.
By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA-EARNINGS (Chicago) _ Motorola reports fourth-quarter
earnings. By Josh Barbanel.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECONOMY (Sao Paulo) _ An overview of the Brazilian
economy as the year anniversary of the decision to devalue the
country's currency approaches. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-PHARMACEUTICALS (Tokyo) _ In another sign of
deregulation's ability to pry open Japan's economy and breath new
life into businesses here, Boehringer Ingelheim, a large German
pharmaceuticals company, began a tender offer Monday for shares of
SS Pharmaceuticals Co., a Japanese drug maker. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
