<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8127 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-GORE-IOWA &LR;      01-17 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-GORE-IOWA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PUSHES TO MAXIMIZE AN IOWA WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLOAN, Iowa _ He offered to help a farmer having problems with
his ram. He repeated, word for word, one man's advice on how to
reassure voters who were concerned about scandal. And he promised a
person who had undergone surgery to become a woman that he would
learn about transgender issues.
</P>
<P>
   During a three-day visit to the first-in-the-nation caucus
state, Vice President Al Gore is trying to seal the deal, making
pledges all the way from Davenport to Sioux City, looking for a big
win eight days from now. Even his opponent, Bill Bradley, expects
Gore to prevail here Jan. 24, but the question is how wide the win,
how big the push will be going into New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   And here is how Gore is putting the finishing touches to the
Hawkeye State: Staying positive, staying away from pesky national
reporters, and allowing others to do the dirty work.
</P>
<P>
   Down a gravel road, past fallow corn and soybean fields, Gore
visited with several hundred voters in Jon Roarson's frigid barn.
The vice president brought along Senator Tom Harkin, an Iowa
Democrat featured in a television commercial for Gore, and a New
Jersey farmer named Roy Etsch.
</P>
<P>
   Gore talked fluently about agricultural trade policy,
countercyclical crop payments, and the reason the bottom has fallen
out of the hog market. He left it to Harkin and Etsch to come in
for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   On crop insurance, ethanol, price supports, and flood relief,
Bradley voted against family farmers, Harkin said. The vice
president, he said, stood with the farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell you these things because I think you ought to know
it,'' Harkin said, comparing the information to a homebuyer finding
cracks in the foundation of a house.
</P>
<P>
   Etsch, an older man whose hearing has declined, delivered the
coup de grace. He said Bradley never cared about farmers, even
though New Jersey is home to 9,000 family farms. He said Bradley
was unavailable to meet with farmers when he served in the Senate,
and told of the time he once finagled an appointment, only to
arrive in Washington to be stood up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt even today he knows the difference between corn and
soybean,'' Etsch said. Though he said he is not looking to cause
trouble, and he always voted for Bradley in Senate races, Etsch
said he was certain what would happen if Bradley became president:
``He'd forget about the agriculture community completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Caucuses are not like primaries, where people vote and leave.
Instead, Iowans gather together in homes, schools and churches,
debating the virtues and flaws of the candidates for hours on end
before a vote is taken. It takes time and commitment to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   It also takes organization. And that is why Gore has visited
with activists and labor leaders in meetings large and small,
simultaneously imploring, thanking, and energizing his troops.
</P>
<P>
   One stop was at the United Auto Workers local in Waterloo. In a
squat, tan building by the highway, Gore thanked the members for
their early endorsement of his candidacy over Bradley last year,
despite resistance by their national leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget it _ ever,'' he said, reminding them that he
supports a $1-an-hour increase in the minimum wage, a strengthened
National Labor Relations Board, and strong antitrust enforcement on
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   And he begged the crowd not just to vote, but to bring their
families, friends, and neighbors, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what you can do. You know what you can do,'' Gore said.
``I need your help and I need it now _ 12 days, two hours, and
seven and a half minutes are left until the caucuses begin. I need
you and I'm counting on you.''
</P>
<P>
   In between his meetings with the voters, Gore steered clear of
the busload of reporters trailing behind and tried to avoid gaffes.
Answering questions from Iowans is the preferred technique, as Gore
likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   In Cedar Rapids, for example, Gore stood under hot stage lights
at Coe Community College's theater in the round, promising to take
every question, no matter how long it took. He stayed for more than
three hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going anywhere,'' he declared. ``I'm staying right
here. If necessary, I'll stand here till 7 p.m. on the evening of
the 24th.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Wilson, a farmer with a gift for metaphors, told Gore about
the problem he's been having with his 300-pound ram, which, he
informed the vice president, is a male sheep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since I put him in with the ewes, the female sheeps, he
has taken the position that I am not allowed to go into the pen,''
Wilson said. ``Every time I step into the pen, he will charge into
me and ram into me over and over until I leave the pen.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he hadn't yet made his point _ that he's feeling battered
by federal farm policy _ Gore was itching to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well you know, as eager as I am to win the support of caucus
goers, I promise you I will try to help you with this,'' he said,
laughing at the absurdity.
</P>
<P>
   More seriously, an older man described himself as a fan of the
Clinton administration's accomplishments, yet still unsure how to
vote in the Democratic contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that your ability to win the election is reduced
by your association with the Clinton scandal,'' he said, referring
to the president's affair with an intern. ``I think you have to
come up with some way to make a statement that says you're
separated somehow in order for you to be elected. And I have a
suggestion for that statement, which is something along the lines
of, `I wouldn't have done that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Without hesitation, Gore replied: ``I wouldn't have done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not every voter received a ready answer, or even a
lengthy one. When a heavy-set woman with broad shoulders and
scraggly blonde hair asked Gore if he would cover transgender
people in the employment nondiscrimination act, he was slightly
flummoxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will have to educate myself on that,'' he promised.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1409EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8128 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MCCOURT-LIMERICK-BOS &LR;      01-17 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCOURT-LIMERICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIMERICK RISES FROM THE `ASHES' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMERICK, Ireland _ Finally, there is something that everyone
here agrees on about ``Angela's Ashes'': It rains too much in the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, if it rained as much in Limerick as it did in that film
poor Frankie McCourt would have drowned and never wrote his book,''
said Harry Leahy, 75, a retired doctor, after watching the movie at
the Savoy, a stone's throw from the scenes of ``Angela's Ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank McCourt's bittersweet memoir of growing up poor won the
Pulitzer Prize, has sold more than 6 million copies, and has been
translated into 25 languages. Its story of crushing poverty and
human resilience has touched hearts across the world.
</P>
<P>
   But in Limerick, the squalor and cruelty that McCourt so vividly
described touched a raw nerve. There remains a small but persistent
minority who accuse McCourt of exaggerating his family's suffering
and the humiliation they endured at the hands of Limerick's elite,
especially the Roman Catholic clergy and laity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the vast majority in this city of 100,000 seem to accept
McCourt's harsh account of life in the lanes of Limerick in the
1930s and 1940s. Rather than debate whether the Redemptorist
priests and the teachers at Leamy School were as mean as McCourt
recalls them, most people here seem determined to capitalize on
Limerick's newfound status as a place known by tens of millions of
people throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Limerick's name recognition will only grow with the release of
Alan Parker's film adaptation of ``Angela's Ashes,'' which opened
here Friday and opens across the United States this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect more people will see the film than read the book,''
said John Leonard, tourism development manager for Shannon
Development Co. ``We want to be ready for the people who will come
here after seeing the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Limerick's efforts to exploit the success of ``Angela's Ashes''
are in their nascent stages. The only tangible sign is a walking
tour of sites mentioned in the book, organized by a local community
group. Leonard and other business leaders say Limerick has
benefited from ``Angela's Ashes'' by attracting thousands of
curious tourists who otherwise would not come here.
</P>
<P>
   Just 10 miles from Shannon Airport, Limerick used to be an
industrial port on the Shannon River which tourists passed through
on their way to the lush countryside of Kerry or West Cork. But
those who have read ``Angela's Ashes,'' and even some who are just
vaguely aware of its wide acclaim, have traveled here in the last
few years, seeking out the lanes where McCourt's twin brothers
died, his father walked in a fruitless search for work, and his
mother persevered despite overwhelming grief and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, there is little left of the dark, dank Limerick
that tortured Frank McCourt. None of the squalid tenements where
the McCourts lived still stand. Leamy School is now Leamy House, a
business center. South's pub, where McCourt's father squandered the
food money and where McCourt had his first pint in a rite of
passage fondly recalled in the book and film, is still there. But
these days, the pub is full of suits who work at the Dell Computer
plant, not blackened-faced workers from Suttons coal yard, which
has since closed.
</P>
<P>
   The firm grip that the fire-and-brimstone Redemptorists had on
much of the local population has greatly diminished, a point
underscored by the Utopia Sex Shop on Ellen Street.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said the three churches here that were featured in
McCourt's story refused him permission to film. Brendan Halligan,
editor of the Limerick Leader, disputes that, saying that one
church offered to move a wedding back an hour to accommodate the
filmmakers ``but that wasn't good enough for Mr. Parker and his
crew.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people in Limerick like to point out that Parker was forced
to go to Cork and Dublin to film scenes of squalor that no longer
exist here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I get someone from Cork in my taxi, I remind them of
that,'' cabbie Pat O'Connor said with glee.
</P>
<P>
   At the film's premiere here Wednesday night, Limerick's Mayor
Jack Bourke praised the movie, but suggested it should not have
been shot here at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film should not have been made in Limerick as we do not
have such derelict hovels,'' said Bourke. ``They could only use
certain parts of Limerick and go to Dublin and Cork to shoot the
hovels and lanes as we don't have that in Limerick anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   That Bourke had to raise a fuss to get a premiere staged here at
all fed a well-honed inferiority complex that many McCourt critics
harbor. Originally, the film was going to be premiered in Dublin.
After Bourke complained, the film's distributors belatedly agreed
to simultaneous premieres in Dublin and Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of Ireland, which is second only to the United
States in world software production, Limerick has boomed over the
last 10 years, progress quite unrelated to ``Angela's Ashes.''
Still, Limerick suffers from an image problem that is also
unrelated to the place so richly captured by McCourt. In the 1980s,
an Irish comic dubbed it ``Stab City,'' a catchy putdown that
remains especially popular with Dubliners, even though the Irish
capital has more crime per capita than Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Gleeson, research executive for the Limerick Chamber of
Commerce, spent three years studying the city's image and concluded
that most Irish people have a negative perception of Limerick. She
said interviews with tourists revealed that their negative view of
the city was almost always introduced or reinforced by
conversations with Irish people.
</P>
<P>
   McCourt's critics blame him for perpetuating that negative
image, but Gleeson said her research did not reveal that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think `Angela's Ashes' can do nothing but good for
Limerick,'' said Gleeson, 28. ``It put us on the map. And my
research showed that a lot of what Frank McCourt said was true.
Limerick was more fervently religious than other cities back then.
The poverty was bad. Even my dad went to school without shoes. Some
people are embarrassed by that, but that's the way it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Gleeson is among those who believe the city has been slow to
capitalize on the interest in `` Angela's Ashes.'' A $3.5 million
public-private project to boost the city's image called Limerick
2005 aims at changing that.
</P>
<P>
   There is talk of creating an Angela's Ashes Trail, but so far
the only tourist attraction is a walking tour organized by the St.
Mary's Development Program, a community group that uses the $6 fee
to help the poor and elderly of the city's oldest parish. John
O'Regan, 38, the group's liaison officer, said that about 800
people from all over the world have taken the tour since it was
created in 1997, but he hopes the numbers will rise dramatically
this year because of the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tour takes people to the places that Frank McCourt
described in the book, but it also shows them the Limerick of
today,'' said O'Regan.
</P>
<P>
   The tour's altruistic roots did little to appease the likes of
Paddy Malone, who called the tour organizers and accused them of
being ``a front for Frank McCourt.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone, a classmate of McCourt's, disputes McCourt's
recollections and complains that he wrote about people without
their permission. In 1997, Malone stood before McCourt during a
book-signing at O'Mahoney's bookshop here and tore up a copy of
``Angela's Ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Malone and the other begrudgers were nowhere to be seen a
few months ago when McCourt returned to sign copies of the sequel,
`` 'Tis.'' David O'Mahoney said he and his brother, Frank, put on
extra security at their bookshop, but a feared protest never
materialized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a tendency to pay too much attention to the
begrudgers,'' said David O'Mahoney. ``The vast majority of people
in Limerick loved the book and will love the film.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Mahoney's, Limerick's biggest bookshop, has sold more than
6,000 copies of ``Angela's Ashes,'' about 10 times more than any
previous bestseller, and 1,200 copies of `` 'Tis.'' In contrast,
two books written by Gerry Hannan, a radio show host who is
McCourt's fiercest and some say most opportunist critic, have found
a distinctly minority audience. O'Mahoney said Hannan's ``Ashes,''
which views Limerick through more rose-colored glasses, has sold
500 copies, while Hannan's own sequel, `` 'Tis in Me Ass,'' has
sold just over 100.
</P>
<P>
   Like Frank McCourt, most of Limerick has moved on, even
physically. For centuries, the city's buildings turned their backs
on the Shannon, the river whose damp brought misery to impoverished
families like the McCourts. Now, the city has been largely rebuilt
to face the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turning around to face the Shannon has opened new vistas for
Limerick,'' said Gleeson.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the film, meanwhile, has created a new dilemma
for the begrudgers, who can't decide what bothers them more, that
``Angela's Ashes'' was written by an American, or filmed by an
Englishman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1411EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
