<HEADLINE>
ELDERLY HIT HARDEST BY OUTDATED PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frances White recently received a letter from AT&AMP;T, warning that
she had a past-due account that was about to be turned over to a
collection agency.
</P>
<P>
   White, 82, alarmed by the threatening tone of the letter, called
her son, Kevin O'Connor. O'Connor looked at the letter and made a
shocking discovery.
</P>
<P>
   He learned that his mother had been leasing since 1984 a black,
rotary-dial phone manufactured in 1962. For what she was paying on
the lease, nearly $55 a year, she could have bought five phones and
have money left over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' said O'Connor, of Boston. ``Her phone
belongs in a museum.''
</P>
<P>
   What's even more amazing is that White is not alone. Sixteen
years after the breakup of AT&AMP;T Corp., approximately 3 million
Americans, a disproportionate number of them elderly, are still
leasing 3.5 million phones at rates that make no sense, given the
price of phones today.
</P>
<P>
   Lease rates range from a low of $4.45 a month for a basic corded
phone to $21 a month for a full-feature, two-line cordless phone
with an answering machine. Staples carries a corded General
Electric phone for $9.99 or a cordless 900 megahertz VTech phone
for $29.98.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said he wanted others to make sure their parents were
not victims of phone leasing. He described his mother as forgetful,
which may explain why she missed a lease payment on her phone. But
he said the reason she leased her phone all those years was
probably out of habit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother gets a bill in the mail from a company like AT&AMP;T and
she just pays it,'' he said. ``I don't think she knew she was
leasing a phone until she got this letter.''
</P>
<P>
   After O'Connor expressed his anger to AT&AMP;T Consumer Leasing
Services, the company canceled his mother's lease, forgave the
past-due amount, and let her keep her old phone without paying a
$9.35 ``recovery charge.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T Consumer Leasing is owned by Lucent Technologies of Murray
Hill, N.J., a company spun off from AT&AMP;T in 1997. Lucent licenses
the AT&AMP;T name for its leasing business.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lucent spokesman John Skalko, the 3 million
customers who lease phones ``tend to be somewhat more senior.''
While he declined to discuss whether leasing a phone made economic
sense, he said the company is not taking advantage of the elderly.
He said the lease arrangements are spelled out in the bills
customers receive. Those bills have been separate from customer
phone bills since Lucent was spun off from AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an individual customer's choice,'' Skalko said. ``As long
as there is demand for the service, we will continue to provide
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Baker, a senior adviser at the public policy institute of
the American Association of Retired Persons in Washington, was
critical of Lucent for not doing more to stop phone leasing. He
said AARP tries to educate members about the high cost of leasing,
but each year, he said, the organization gets a handful of letters
from people who have discovered their parents had been leasing
their phones for years.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said the Federal Trade Commission used to put out booklets
on the disadvantages of phone leasing, but he said the agency has
moved on to other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys conducted by the AARP indicate that people over 65 are
more likely to lease their phones, a practice Baker called
``ridiculous.'' Only 2 percent of those under 65 lease their phone,
but the percentage rises to 4 percent for people between 65 and 75
and to 6 percent for those over 75.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these people have had AT&AMP;T for their whole life,'' he
said. ``They get a bill and they pay it.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, AARP surveys indicate 75 percent of people over 65
continue to pay the most expensive basic long-distance phone rates
rather than switch to a discount plan. ``It's basically
confusion,'' Baker said. ``They see all the ads and the fine print
and they don't want to deal with that, so they stand pat.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, when AT&AMP;T was forced to divest its local phone
operations, consumers initially were given three options: buy their
AT&AMP;T phone equipment; lease it; or return it and buy a phone from
another company. After that initial period, customers could only
lease their AT&AMP;T phone or return it and buy a phone from someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans quickly discovered the economic advantages of
owning their phones. But White kept paying the lease as she always
had. ``I never had any problem with it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Skalko said White could have traded in the black rotary-dial
phone for a newer model at any time, although, he said, her monthly
charge might have increased slightly.
</P>
<P>
   But White never asked for a new phone. O'Connor bought her two
new phones over the years, but each time she found a problem with
the new phone and asked for her old black rotary-dial phone back.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said that if he had known his mother was leasing her
phone, he would have insisted she get rid of it. But he never knew
until he read the letter from AT&AMP;T. His mother continues to use her
black rotary-dial phone, but now realizes she was taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paid all those years for nothing,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
