<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8134 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-BERNSTEIN-BOS &LR;      01-17 1748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BERNSTEIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERNSTEIN'S UNSUNG SHOWS GET THEIR DUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leonard Bernstein's ``West Side Story'' became an American
classic on its opening night in 1957. Recognition for ``Candide''
came more slowly. The show opened on Broadway in 1956. It became a
cult favorite, but didn't begin to reveal its full stature until
revivals in the late 1970s, and it wasn't really until 1989, the
year before Bernstein's death, that the work achieved the musical
shape the composer had envisioned from the beginning. Over the last
decade ``Candide'' has entered the regular repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of Bernstein's first two Broadway shows, ``On the Town''
and ``Wonderful Town'' was as ambitious or as fabulously successful
as ``West Side Story.'' Still, both of them ran longer than the
original production of ``Candide'' did, although neither has built
anything like a comparable post-Broadway life. The similarity of
their titles may have worked against the shows, and the books and
lyrics have become dated, with songs in both shows that now require
footnotes. Also there are no megahits in either score; Bernstein, a
bit defensively, said he didn't intend to write independent hits _
instead he wanted the songs to grow out of character and situation,
as in an opera. A few songs such as ``Lonely Town,'' ``Lucky to Be
Me,'' ``A Little Bit in Love,'' and the politically incorrect ``A
Quiet Girl'' inspire affection and have enjoyed modest but
permanent success.
</P>
<P>
   Today these shows stand as an undervalued part of Bernstein's
compositional legacy _ the books may have dated, but Bernstein's
music still seems perpetually fresh, and more likely to endure than
some of his more ambitious, not to say portentous, works.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Simon Rattle's new recording of ``Wonderful Town'' features
a prestigious cast headed by Audra McDonald and Thomas Hampson, and
appears on an international label, EMI. It is abundantly good
enough to redirect attention to this delightful score and maybe
even lead to new attempts to keep it stageworthy. Unexpectedly,
however, the actual performance is aced by a year-old two-CD set on
a comparatively obscure British label, JAY, which has also produced
notable complete recordings of ``On the Town,'' ``West Side
Story,'' and ``Candide,'' as well as such other shows as ``Pajama
Game'' and ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   The origins of the piece lay in a series of comic sketches
Ohio-born Ruth McKenney wrote about her first years in New York in
the 1930s with her younger sister, the captivating Eileen. (In a
bizarre footnote, the real-life Eileen married the novelist
Nathaniel West and died with him in an auto accident in 1940.)
McKenney's sketches had been collected into a best-selling book,
``My Sister Eileen,'' transformed into a hit play, and then into a
popular movie that starred Rosalind Russell as an incomparably wry
Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, Russell, was under option for a musical version in
which she would re-create her film role of a decade before. A first
attempt at a score, by Leroy Anderson, with lyrics by Arnold B.
Howitt, did not win the star's favor. Bernstein came into the
project because his friends Betty Comden and Adolph Green had
recently come on board as rescue lyricists. They weren't sure he
would be interested; he had promised his mentor, Serge
Koussevitzky, music director of the Boston Symphony, that he
wouldn't write for Broadway anymore and would instead concentrate
on additional ``important'' orchestral works such as the
``Jeremiah'' Symphony. But when Comden and Green mentioned the '30s
setting, Bernstein was off and running; he cried out ``Eddie
Duchin!'' and headed straight for the piano.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's option had only weeks to run, so the collaborators
wrote their part of the show in little more than a month. Of
course, they were used to working together. Along with Judith
Tuvim, who later became Judy Holliday, they had appeared as a
musical-satire act called ``The Revuers,'' and, of course, they had
collaborated on ``On the Town.''
</P>
<P>
   The show tried out in New Haven and then, a week later, opened
at the Colonial Theater in Boston in January 1953; Jerome Robbins
came on board at the Colonial to work on the choreography,
reportedly because a male dancer had dropped Russell during a
number. After ``Wonderful Town'' hit New York at the end of
February, it ran for 559 performances _ after Russell left the
show, even the firepower of her successor, Carol Channing, was not
enough to keep it going for more than three additional months. In
1955, there was a ``Wonderful Town'' film with Betty Garrett and
Janet Leigh as the sisters, but it featured new songs not by
Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   In 1958, Russell, then 50, reprised one last time for a
television ``spectacular'' the wisecracking role she had first
played in 16 years before. The original Broadway cast recording of
``Wonderful Town'' was on Decca; it briefly appeared on CD, but it
is not currently available. The TV soundtrack, on Sony, features
Jacquelyn McKeever instead of Broadway's Edie Adams as Eileen.
Russell's ripe baritone remains uniquely cherishable (according to
Humphrey Burton's Bernstein biography, Russell described her voice
to a newspaper reporter as ``so bass, it's viol''). Russell had the
advantage, and disadvantage, of a major career and star image
behind her, an image that is permanent because it remains
accessible on film. What remains on record even for those who have
never heard of her or recall her dazzling presence, is one of a
performer's most important assets _ an impeccable sense of rhythm
and timing, which are as important to an actor as they are to a
singer. Russell's rhythm is more musical than that of many
professional singers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lively and detailed annotation in the JAY set
by theater historian Jeffrey Dunn, there have been occasional
revivals of ``Wonderful Town'' since 1958, with such lively
personalities as Kaye Ballard, Elaine Stritch, Nanette Fabray, and
Lauren Bacall in the Russell role. In the '80s, there was a London
revival with new orchestrations replacing the originals, and the
New York City Opera brought the show into its repertory a few years
ago. The London revival was recorded, but the new versions are the
first important recordings of the original score in 40 years, and
the JAY version is the first-ever complete recording of the music _
in includes all the underscored dialogue, including the scene of
``Ruth's Stories,'' and, in an appendix, alternate versions of ``A
Little Bit in Love'' and ``Christopher Street.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderful Town'' boasts a wonderful score composed in the
eclectic blend of Gilbert and Sullivan, Stravinsky, Copland,
Duchin, and a host of other things that came out sounding like
Leonard Bernstein's own natural voice. There are ballads, novelty
numbers, Cole Porter list-and-rhyming songs, a Latin number
(``Conga!''), an Irish parlor ballad (``My Darlin' Eileen''), jazz
(``Swing!''), and satire (``Ballet at the Village Vortex,'' ``The
Wrong-Note Rag,'' ``Pass the Football,'' and the extraordinary
``Conversation Piece,'' which ends with a volley of soprano
coloratura that anticipates ``Glitter and Be Gay'' in ``Candide.'')
It does make a difference to hear the score complete, in the JAY
recording, because ``Wonderful Town'' is not just a ``number''
show; it is through-composed, with many internal cross-references.
</P>
<P>
   The Rattle recording has strong singers in all the roles _
Rodney Gilfrey, who sang Stanley Kowalski in Andre Previn's ``A
Streetcar Named Desire,'' takes three supporting parts. But not
everyone seems happily cast. Kim Criswell, a fixture on Broadway
revival recordings, has a terrific set of pipes, but she never does
much besides blast away with them, and as Ruth she overdoes the
Louis Armstrong rasp and growl; she has plenty of pep, but her
performance is generic. Audra McDonald has an even better voice and
she goes far deeper into her songs, but her best qualities aren't
helpful in this particular part. There's no way this infinitely
sophisticated artist can sound like an innocent ingenue from Ohio;
she lacks the ability to be spontaneous and casual. The coloratura
at the end of ``Conversation Piece'' is an a different acoustic
from the rest of the ensemble, and it sounds overdubbed. Thomas
Hampson sings resonantly but the aura of narcissism that invariably
surrounds his performances doesn't make him a very attractive hero.
The players from the Birmingham Contemporary Music Group are
terrific, and there is lots of rhythm, drive, and character in
Rattle's work, although there is an equally important element of
relaxed, loosey-goosey ``Revuers''-style improvisation, that eludes
him and his cast.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the singers in the TER-Jay version work out better than
their counterparts with Rattle. Rebecca Luker, Magnolia in the
Harold Prince revival of ``Showboat,'' is delightfully fresh as
Eileen, and she shares with Barbara Cook the ability to make
coloratura sound conversational. Her ``A Little Bit In Love'' is
simultaneously wistful and fulfilled. Karen Mason, one of
Broadway's Norma Desmonds in ``Sunset Boulevard,'' brings much more
shading to Ruth than Criswell does. And Ron Raines sounds like a
hearty Broadway leading man, not like a slumming opera star _
although this Broadway singer can produce a more ringing high note
on the word ``fish'' than Hampson can. Conductor John Owen Edwards
is a Broadway specialist and a good one; you might not want to hear
him conduct ``Parsifal'' or ``Pelleas et Melisande,'' where he
would be unlikely to compete successfully with Rattle, but he is
more idiomatic in Bernstein than Rattle is.
</P>
<P>
   These second-generation recordings of ``Wonderful Town'' ought
to play as important a role in establishing the stature of the
score as the post-original-cast recordings of ``Candide'' did. Now
only one of Bernstein's Broadway scores remains virtually unknown:
``1600 Pennsylvania Avenue,'' a 1976 flop which for Bernstein
represented the greatest professional embarrassment of his career _
few of his musical intentions made it to opening night, and the
show was never recorded. In 1977, the Bernstein estate commissioned
``A White House Cantata,'' which collects the music and arranges it
into performable form. Conductor Kent Nagano led a number of
performances in Europe, but what the piece needs to put it on the
map is a recording.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
