<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GLAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GHOSTLY GLOW IGNITES A HEART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
SO I AM GLAD 
By A. L. Kennedy. Knopf 
276 pp. $23. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A.L. Kennedy is a fierce and enchanting writer with a voice as
smoky as dry ice, and God save Scotland for exporting her fiction
to America. A Glaswegian born in Dundee in 1965, she's both
joyously irreverent and surprisingly wise; she will write
unflinchingly about pornography, religious mysteries, and domestic
abuse in the same long breath, managing to link those discrete
territories by their commonalities of power and longing. Her
characters are modern versions of the Southern grotesques of Carson
McCullers or Flannery O'Connor _ bruised and lonely people who,
once Kennedy has had her way with them, come to seem achingly
familiar and even ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Alienation is her province, in other words, a condition she
reminds us is universal by applying it to the walking wounded or
the comically strange: a woman who, let down by faith, perceives
herself as ``God's widow''; an unhappy pastry chef who finds
comfort by standing outside a flour mill in the middle of night.
Though the plots of Kennedy's work often sound like eccentricity
for its own sake, they're actually foils for the more serious
subject of reaching past the wreckage toward a human hand _ a wedge
of literary hope that Kennedy renders with searingly careful prose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Original Bliss,'' appearing here a year ago, was America's
first introduction to Kennedy's work; accordingly, ``So I Am Glad''
may seem like a fast-issue second novel. But in fact its original
publication precedes that of ``Original Bliss'' by a couple of
years, having been issued in Great Britain in 1995. Kennedy's
prolific output includes three novels and two story collections,
and one assumes that all her work will eventually be available in
America, given her longstanding reputation abroad and her recent
discovery here.
</P>
<P>
   As with ``Original Bliss,'' which charted the unlikely collusion
of a self-help guru and a battered wife, ``So I Am Glad'' concerns
a meeting of two minds from wildly disparate worlds _ in this case,
an emotionally sovereign young woman named M. Jennifer Wilson (the
``M'' stands for Mercy) and a rumpled fellow who seems to be the
ghost of Cyrano de Bergerac. The narrator of this tale, Jennifer
insists from the outset that her calculatedly calm inner state _
one in which sex, emotion, and connection have little play _ is
simply the way the model arrived from the factory: that nothing bad
ever happened to her to create this insularity, that her social
responses, when she can figure them out, are studied fabrications.
So we have both Jennifer the ice queen and Jennifer the unreliable
narrator; we already see through her frosty facade, and already
mistrust her guarded delivery of it.
</P>
<P>
   Then a guy falls into her life, in a manner of speaking,
emanating a ghostly glow and suffering amnesia; all he remembers,
he tells her, is ``the absence of God _ a faraway disinterested
ache, a faint taste of intellect on the edge of time.'' But what
does Jennifer care if our newcomer is a bit zany? She herself is an
expert in knowing how to pass, and, given her insularity, her
criteria for friends are not all that demanding. Known as Martin
because he's mistaken for a new housemate by the same name, the man
eventually reveals himself to Jennifer as Savinien _ first name of
Cyrano de Bergerac, and as romantic a 17th-century fellow as you
ever found in a 20th-century Glasgow kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   However implausible this sounds as the plot of a novel, the
story of ``So I Am Glad'' insinuates itself in the reader's
consciousness with fluid ease. Soon enough, one is not only taken
with the burgeoning courtship between Savinien and Jennifer, but
entranced by the complexity of the design that Kennedy has wrought.
Some of this immersion is achieved because she is wickedly funny
(on the romantic limits of onanism, for example, where ``we didn't
send flowers, we never phoned'') and wickedly wicked (rarely has
sadomasochism been explored to such sad-scary effect). And some of
the novel's power derives from its intellectual underpinnings: In
casting Cyrano as the ultimate modern suitor for a frozen heroine,
Kennedy constructs an elegantly parallel universe shifting between
two historical periods _ where physical violence, political
cruelty, and moral depravity walk the same streets in similar
garbs. But even these accomplishments might belong to the realm of
cleverness without Kennedy's vast skill as a portraitist. Both her
dialogue and her descriptive prose have the precision of a fine
surgeon; there are no wasted words here, and consequently an
absolute reality created in the end.
</P>
<P>
   And Jennifer, of course, with her touchingly untrustworthy
defense mechanisms, gets to offer the transformative possibilities
of love as well as fiction. A ``professional enunciator'' by trade,
she's a radio voice who has found great succor in her soundproof
world: She can articulate and control to her heart's content, and
nobody can get to her when the studio door is closed. Remote by
effort, she is never coy, and it's not long before the reader
learns the early reasons for her castle of reserve. But Savinien,
with his physical shortcomings and tender integrity and great,
great love for the world and Jennifer, penetrates that silent
arena; the result is not just a love story, but a swipe of great
passion against the loneliest realm of all, which is despair. ``You
are the person who makes me mind the empty spaces I have,'' she
writes Savinien, ``and the empty rooms.'' Is there a better or more
simple definition of earthly love?
</P>
<P>
   Cursed and blessed with the consequences of loving her ghostly
Savinien, Jennifer becomes something of a writer _ a choice her
Cyrano has long understood. ``It's something to do, to write, isn't
it?'' he tells her. ``When life has baffled an author and hidden
its possibilities, then he can always write.'' With its narrator
often giving us a glimpse of Jennifer and Kennedy both, ``So I Am
Glad'' is carefully generous with such commentary, finding in its
romance flung between the centuries a remarkably affecting novel
about love and courage. About getting lost at the darkest edges of
the seas, and finding the way back toward light.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is chief book reviewer for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
