<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CHILLI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHILLI' OF TLC: FEUD, WHAT FEUD? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bad behavior usually translates to great publicity for pop
groups. But at a certain point the rewards of coddling the
designated wild child's antics are obscured by the toll inflicted
on everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Take TLC, the female R&AMP;B-rap trio that has just been nominated
for six Grammys, including album of the year for 1999's
``Fanmail.'' Lisa ``Left Eye'' Lopes _ the self-described Crazy in
the ``CrazySexyCool'' triumvirate _ has been generating headaches
and headlines for years: fights with the police, arrests for
disorderly conduct, and of course the infamous accidental torching
of her boyfriend's mansion. Last year Lopes sent a letter to the
group's record company, LaFace, threatening to quit TLC, which
temporarily froze the notoriously money-troubled group's finances.
She later said it was an attention-getting ploy. And then there's
the string of canceled interviews, ruined photo shoots, and missed
television appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows that Lisa is the one who rebels,'' says Rozanda
``Chilli'' Thomas on the phone from Atlanta. Thomas is the
smooth-voiced, Sexy third of TLC who sings the recent hits
``Unpretty'' and ``No Scrubs.'' Everyone also knows how Thomas and
Tionne ``T-Boz'' Watkins (the Cool piece of the puzzle) feel about
Lopes's behavior, since the two made their displeasure very public
in an Entertainment Weekly article last November. ``Evil,''
``selfish,'' and ``heartless'' were just a few of the descriptives
used. Lopes shot back with a challenge to release three competing
solo albums. And so on and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the brink of a national tour, a subdued Thomas _ clearly
tired of addressing the group's internal strife _ is backpedaling
hard. ``Every group goes through stuff,'' she says
matter-of-factly. ``You have to agree to disagree. That writer at
Entertainment Weekly? It was just his lucky day.'' Thomas says that
the group is not, as rumored, on the verge of a breakup. But her
claims ring of retreat more than conviction. ``TLC is such a
priority for me that I don't even think that way. I can't see a
breakup. If there is one, it's far away.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a good thing for the music world. With ``No Scrubs''
and ``Unpretty,'' TLC released a pair of stellar pop-soul songs
that sport not only catchy hooks, but also serious messages. Both
have struck nerves with a surprising cross-section of music fans _
men included, even though both tracks come across as feminist
anthems and have inspired their share of gender feuds. `` `No
Scrubs,' '' says Thomas, ``is not male-bashing. It's talking about
a certain kind of guy that a lot of guys don't even like'' _ the
type that mooch off their mothers, ignore their kids, and can
generally be found, as the lyric goes, ``hangin' out the
passenger's side of his best friend's ride/ tryin' to holler at
me.'' ``And every woman,'' Thomas points out, ``has had that
experience, of being in the car and some guy drives up and tries to
talk to you. That's why it was so big.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unpretty,'' a deceptively delicate ballad about the perils of
relying on others to form your self-image, displays a new level of
introspection for TLC. ``This group has gone through so much stuff,
how could you not come out more mature?'' Thomas says. Indeed, in
addition to the group's well-publicized conflicts, Watkins is
struggling with sickle cell anemia, and Thomas is trying to balance
career and motherhood; she's raising her 2-year-old son in Atlanta
with TLC producer Dallas Austin. ``To me, it's Part 2 of
`Waterfalls,' '' Thomas says, referring to TLC's 1994 hit from the
10-times platinum ``CrazySexyCool.'' ``It's really talking about
something very universal.''
</P>
<P>
   But she's quick to point out that trying to match past successes
is something TLC couldn't imagine on the heels of a five-year
recording hiatus, during which the group filed for _ and ultimately
recovered from _ bankruptcy. ``My main goal for `Fanmail' was to
never get caught up in what we sold before. I just wanted people to
embrace us again.'' With 4 million copies of ``Fanmail'' sold so
far and a handful of Grammy nominations sure to fuel the fire, TLC
has little to worry about in terms of fan support. The question is
no longer whether they'll be embraced by an audience, but whether
they'll embrace each other. ``TLC has chemistry,'' says Thomas.
``It's natural. It's magical. That's something you can't take away.
We could go out,'' she insists, ``and do our thing forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1421EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
