<HEADER>
A8145 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-NATHAN-LANE-IN-ISNT-S     01-17 1420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATHAN-LANE-IN-ISNT-SHE-GREAT-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATHAN LANE, SHOW-BIZ ANIMAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Nathan Lane with Bette Midler in a scene
from ``Isn't She Great.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Nathan Lane is getting catty.
 &HT;    The actor, who provides the voice for Snowbell the cat in the
holiday hit ``Stuart Little,'' claims that the titular mouse was
given a much nicer trailer on the set than he was.
 &HT;    It's tough being a cat in a mouse picture.
 &HT;    ``Even though Stuart was computer-generated,'' Lane says, ``we
still had mice around the set to remind us of their habits. When no
one was around, I would whisper to them, `Steel traps, boys.'''
 &HT;    Actually, Lane says more seriously, ``Stuart Little'' was his
favorite book as a child.
 &HT;    ``I can recall details, like them lowering Stuart into the
kitchen sink on a thread to retrieve Mrs. Little's wedding ring,''
he says. ``It didn't end happily. Stuart goes off and searches for
his true love. I kept thinking, `Ugh, he's never gonna find her.'
 &HT;    ``Even then I saw the futility of love,'' the actor says,
rolling his eyes. ``I thought, `How many 4-inch women are there out
there?'''
 &HT;    Lane has some previous experience with mice, having starred in
``Mouse Hunt'' (1997). Given the box-office success of ``Stuart
Little,'' as well as the crowd-pleasing mouse in ``The Green Mile''
(1999), mouse movies seem to be hot in Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``Oh goody, you've spotted the trend,'' Lane jokes. ``Now the
only thing left to do is `The Rat Pack' and `Mighty Mouse,' and
then I can retire. Then I've done the entire rodent catalog of
films.''
 &HT;    In the meantime, the versatile star of ``The Bird Cage'' (1996)
and the voice of Timon in ``The Lion King'' (1994) plays a
different kind of Hollywood animal in his new movie, ``Isn't She
Great,'' a biopic of the pop novelist Jacqueline Susann (Bette
Midler) which will open Jan. 28.
 &HT;    Lane plays Susann's husband, Irving Mansfield, in a cast that
also features John Cleese, David Hyde Pierce, Stockard Channing,
John Larroquette and Sarah Jessica Parker. The film, with a Paul
Rudnick screenplay that focuses on the creation of Susann's most
famous _ and most scandalous _ book, ``Valley of the Dolls''
(1966), is based on Barbara Seaman's biography, ``Lovely Me: The
Life of Jacqueline Susann'' (Seven Story Press, 1996).
 &HT;    ``It's not that sordid Michelle Lee cable movie that was on a
few months ago,'' Lane says. ``Frankly, I couldn't take my eyes off
that one, because it was mesmerizing in its total vulgarity and
horribleness. It was like every trashy story you've ever heard
about Jacqueline and Irving.''
 &HT;    To prepare for his role, Lane watched old television interviews
with Mansfield.
 &HT;    ``I watched old Dinah Shore shows,'' he says. ``When he talked
about his wife, you just saw the love. And they were real
show-business animals _ everything was about show business. But he
was so devoted to her that Irving wanted Jackie to be as famous as
she wanted to be.
 &HT;    ``You have to admire their guts and determination.''
 &HT;    The story, set in the 1960s and 1970s, includes Susann's
well-publicized feud with Truman Capote, who once said that she
``dressed like a truck driver in drag.''
 &HT;    ``There is a scene where we watch Truman saying these things on
television,'' Lane says. ``And Bette and I throw things at the TV
screen.''
 &HT;    The raucous Midler was a natural to play Susann, the actor adds.
 &HT;    ``She's a ball of fire,'' he says. ``It's a wonderful role for
her _ she gets to be funny and flashy, plus she gets to have a
hospital deathbed scene. And, frankly, what more could any actor
ask for in a movie?''
 &HT;    Lane grew up in Jersey City, N.J., a world away from the glamour
of show business.
 &HT;    ``It was a family where you had to grow up fast,'' he recalls.
``My father was a very self-destructive person. And it was very sad
_ he was an alcoholic who died when I was 11. He essentially drank
himself to death.''
 &HT;    Unpopular and overweight, Lane found a saving grace in his older
brother, Dan, who took him to see plays in New York. Fascinated, at
age 18 Lane moved to New York to pursue his dream of being an
actor.
 &HT;    He lived in a cramped apartment with ``about 10,000 other
struggling actors,'' he jokes. ``Rent was very cheap _ we each paid
$1 a month.''
 &HT;    Lane was working delivering singing telegrams when he got his
first break, a short-lived 1982 television series with Mickey
Rooney, ``One of the Boys.'' The cast also included future stars
Meg Ryan and Dana Carvey.
 &HT;    Although the show bombed, Lane found doors opening, especially
on Broadway. A series of increasingly prominent stage roles led to
his acclaimed star turns in ``Guys and Dolls'' (1992), ``Love!
Valour! Compassion!'' (1994) and ``A Funny Thing Happened on the
Way to the Forum'' (1996).
 &HT;    Along the way, Lane began to be seen in a variety of films _
including, ironically, a bit part in the television movie
``Jacqueline Susann's Valley of the Dolls'' (1981). His most
memorable films include ``Frankie and Johnny'' (1991), ``Addams
Family Values'' (1993) and ``Jeffrey'' (1995).
 &HT;    The small screen, however, has not proven so kind: Lane's recent
television series, ``Encore! Encore!'', was canceled after only a
few episodes.
 &HT;    Back on the big screen, Lane co-stars in Kenneth Branagh's
upcoming ``Love's Labour's Lost,'' a musical version of the
Shakespeare classic that also features Branagh, Matthew Lillard and
Alicia Silverstone.
 &HT;    ``We're singing and dancing and doing the Bard,'' Lane says. ``I
get to sing `There's No Business Like Show Business.' I play the
clown character _ he's a vaudevillian who is down on his luck. He
walks around with this little suitcase of rubber chickens.''
 &HT;    And no, Lane says, there's nothing to the English tabloid rumors
that Branagh and Silverstone dated during filming.
 &HT;    ``We were working seven days a week,'' he says. ``I don't think
either one of them had time for an affair. We were working very
hard.''
 &HT;    Lane's return to Broadway, co-starring with Victor Garber in
Stephen Sondheim's new musical ``Wise Guys,'' was recently derailed
when the production was shut down for retooling. In the meantime,
he's weighing movie offers, including a possible sequel to ``The
Bird Cage,'' which he still regards as his biggest career break.
 &HT;    ``Of course that movie, and last year GQ magazine named me as
one of their Men of the Year,'' he says.
 &HT;    Lane heaves a fake sob.
 &HT;    ``It was very moving to me,'' he says, smiling. ``As you know, I
was the Theater Man of the Year. So you can only imagine what an
ugly battle that was. It was between me and Carol Channing, and
they gave it to me!''
 &HT;    And his prize?
 &HT;    ``I got a free trip to GQ Land, where you can see anorexic
supermodels in their natural habitat,'' Lane says. ``However,
you're not allowed to feed them.''
 &HT;    He's delighted to get a laugh.
 &HT;    ``The best feeling is to make other people laugh,'' he says.
``When I hear laughter, something clicks in my head. I think, `This
is what I really love more than anything else in the world _ just
the feeling of people having a great time.'
 &HT;    ``You really can't ask for more.''
 c.2000 Cindy Pearlman
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Isn't She Great,'' consult the
official Website at www.isntshegreat.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
