<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8149 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-SHARON-STONE-IN-SIMPA     01-17 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARON-STONE-IN-SIMPATICO-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARON STONE, INDIE QUEEN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Sharon Stone in a scene from
``Simpatico.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    These days the biggest stars shine in some of the most unlikely
places.
 &HT;    Take, for example, Sharon Stone, blossoming indie queen.
 &HT;    Arguably the sexiest screen siren of the 1990s, Stone made her
name in the big-budget likes of ``Total Recall'' (1990), ``Basic
Instinct'' (1992) and ``The Specialist'' (1994). Lately, though,
she's been seen most often in far more modest productions such as
``The Mighty'' (1998) and ``The Muse'' (1999).
 &HT;    Her latest film, ``Simpatico,'' which will open Jan. 21, is
another independent feature.
 &HT;    What gives?
 &HT;    ``I believe that these kinds of films, in 10 or 20 years, will
have filmic value,'' Stone says during a conversation at New York's
Essex House. As always, the 41-year-old actress is a live wire,
talkative and forthright.
 &HT;    ``I believe that we're actually doing work to be proud of, and
work that will stand the test of time,'' she says. ``Even though I
like to get paid sometimes, too, this is far more interesting to me
at this time in my life than a paycheck.
 &HT;    ``Also, the emotional rewards, the spiritual rewards ... it's
ethically rewarding,'' the actress says. ``It's an odd thing to
say, but it is.''
 &HT;    Based on the Sam Shepard play, ``Simpatico'' stars Jeff Bridges
as Lyle Carter, a wealthy horse breeder, with Stone as Rosie,
Lyle's reclusive, alcoholic wife. Nick Nolte plays Vinnie, an old
pal of the couple who's now a total lush. When Vinnie decides to
right old wrongs and betray long-buried secrets, the trio's lives
are thrown into a life-threatening spiral.
 &HT;    Rosie is a highly volatile character, the actress says.
 &HT;    ``It's a very dangerous place to live, psychologically,'' she
says. ``And, unlike the character, I haven't been loaded for 25
years to numb it.''
 &HT;    Stone credits the film's writer/director, Matthew Warchus, for
providing the emotional safety net required by such a demanding
role.
 &HT;    ``He made it safe for me to go there,'' she says.
 &HT;    Whether or not audiences go there along with Stone, Bridges and
Nolte remains to be seen. ``Simpatico'' is dark, disturbing stuff,
and Stone knows it.
 &HT;    ``People are either enraptured with the movie or they're
confused by it,'' she says. ``They're emotionally torn up by the
movie, and they either like that or they don't.
 &HT;    ``Shepard writes for the intellectual,'' she adds, ``but very
few people write for the intellectual from an emotional standpoint.
I think that's extraordinary. For me, that was about as challenging
a kind of work as there is.''
 &HT;    Although Stone feels strongly about her character and the
caliber of her co-star's performances, she admits that
``Simpatico'' is probably not a movie for everybody _ though she
points out that many classics, including Martin Scorsese's ``Raging
Bull'' (1980), haven't found their audiences right away.
 &HT;    ``Like any movie, it doesn't have to be for the moment it's
made,'' she says. ```Raging Bull' didn't win an Oscar, and now it's
probably considered one of the finest films that's ever been
made.''
 &HT;    Stone will follow ``Simpatico'' with several intriguing
projects. She'll join Woody Allen in director Alfonso Arau's
pitch-black comedy ``Picking Up the Pieces'' and get romantic with
Billy Connolly in ``Beautiful Joe.''
 &HT;    The actress will also share the small screen with Ellen
DeGeneres in ``Misconceptions,'' a segment of HBO's anthology ``If
These Walls Could Talk 2'' written and directed by DeGeneres'
lover, Anne Heche.
 &HT;    ``I think they're just great,'' Stone says. ``Ellen is just the
most wonderful comedienne and Anne is so smart and such a great
actor. The script she wrote was great, and I knew she'd be able to
direct.
 &HT;    ``It was so much fun because it was all girls, a girl crew, a
girl assistant director,'' Stone adds with a laugh. ``I have to say
I really enjoyed that kind of experience. I've seen the piece, and
it's marvelous.''
 &HT;    In ``Picking Up the Pieces,'' Allen dismembers his wife (Stone)
and buries her body parts throughout Mexico. When someone discovers
Stone's hand, it immediately becomes a religious icon.
 &HT;    ``It's more than a cameo,'' says Stone, who made her movie debut
with a fleeting bit as a crazed fan in Allen's ``Stardust
Memories'' (1980). ``I have a few scenes in flashback, and I have a
really terrific scene where I come back from the dead and talk to
Woody in his jail cell. I'm in my baby-doll nightgown, with two
feet of red hair, seven-inch heels, a fake fur coat and a dog in my
handbag.
 &HT;    ``That scene is why I took the part.''
 &HT;    As for ``Beautiful Joe,'' the film was both a joy for Stone and
one of the most difficult experiences of her career.
 &HT;    ``Billy Connolly is so, so great to work with,'' she says. ``It
was such a pleasure.''
 &HT;    But with only five days of filming to go, Stone received
devastating news: Her husband, San Francisco newspaperman Phil
Bronstein, had suffered a heart attack. She rushed to his side,
only to return to the movie set shortly thereafter.
 &HT;    ``I had to come back, and I had to come right back,'' she says.
``Legally I had to come right back to work, and that was
horrifying. I couldn't stand being there _ every second was just
hell. I wanted to get the hell out of there and get back home.
 &HT;    ``But every other day on the film was the most extraordinary
experience.''
 &HT;    The actress is happy to add that Bronstein has recovered
admirably.
 &HT;    ``He's fabulous,'' Stone says, practically shouting. ``He's
better than ever.''
 &HT;    On a note nearly as positive, it's widely believed that Stone
will secure an Oscar nomination as Best Supporting Actress for her
comic turn as the flamboyant title character in Albert Brooks'
comedy ``The Muse.''
 &HT;    If it happens, Stone makes it abundantly clear that she'll be
more than pleased.
 &HT;    ``Honey, I want to be nominated for everything,'' she jokes. ``I
want to be nominated for cleaning my house. And I should be.''
 &HT;    Even if the Oscar should come her way, however, it's still a
fact that ``The Muse'' didn't ring up great numbers at the box
office. Stone's recent films have been at best middling successes,
and there's no denying that her career could use a solid hit _ if
only to help draw moviegoers to her more adventurous independent
films.
 &HT;    ``I'm sure it would be a good idea,'' the actress says, nodding,
``but maybe I'll get recognition for `The Muse' in a way that will
do that.
 &HT;    ``If I can get recognition for my work first, that's more
interesting to me,'' she adds. ``Yes, I like when movies are hits _
who doesn't? But it's wonderful to be recognized for your work
first.''
 &HT;    Stone pauses.
 &HT;    ``I think my work in `Basic Instinct' holds up today,'' she
says, ``but I'm still not recognized, today, for my work in that.
Maybe when I'm 60 ...
 &HT;    ``Well, I'll probably still be threatening,'' she admits.
``Maybe when I'm dead.''
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
