<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNTRY-SINGER-FAITH-HILL-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATTER OF FAITH: FAITH HILL AND THE POWER OF A SONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of country singer Faith Hill.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    The fundamental things may still apply, but a kiss is more than
just a kiss.
 &HT;    Just ask Faith Hill. Her million-selling 1998 hit, ``This
Kiss,'' launched a wave of success that has seen Hill vault from
mere country-music stardom to become the most significant pop-music
crossover this side of Shania Twain.
 &HT;    The song sparked sales of more than 3 million copies of Hill's
third album, ``Faith,'' helped her snare five Academy of Country
Music Awards and earned her a spot alongside Cher, Whitney Houston
and Tina Turner on VH1's ``Divas Live '99.''
 &HT;    Moreover, it provided a springboard for her new album,
``Breathe'' (1999), to debut at No. 1 on the Billboard charts,
selling nearly 250,000 copies in its first week of release.
 &HT;    In other words, the 32-year-old Hill is no longer merely the
wife of country singer Tim McGraw, the mother of their two
daughters and her husband's perennial opening act. She's a star in
her own right.
 &HT;    Despite her meteoric rise, Hill has kept herself grounded
through family life. She takes her daughters, 2-year-old Gracie and
1-year-old Maggie, on the road with her, and brings the family
together whenever she can.
 &HT;    Some singers come to resent the success of their biggest hits,
feeling overshadowed by their own songs, but Hill appreciates
everything ``This Kiss'' has done for her.
 &HT;    ``It just kind of shows the power of a song,'' she says. ``It's
continuing to be played, across the board _ even around the world.
It was a huge record in Germany, South Africa ... just
everywhere.''
 &HT;    Hill recounts a friend's supermarket encounter with a teen-ager
who spotted Hill on the cover of a country magazine.
 &HT;    ``The girl shouts _ `Mom! The ``This Kiss'' girl ... is country!
Did you know that? Do you believe that?''' Hill says, laughing. ``I
thought it was hysterical.''
 &HT;    But beneath Hill's laughter lies the age-old lament of the
artist who resists being pigeonholed.
 &HT;    ``I don't want to be pegged as anything,'' she says. ``I just
want to be respected as an artist that's trying to do great music.
I really don't see any crime in that.''
 &HT;    Some in Nashville do, however. Like mass-audience breakouts
Twain and Garth Brooks before her, Hill has been attacked for
betraying the faith, forsaking her country roots to chase broader
pop success. Critics have slammed her new provocative, skin-baring
image, her Vogue photo sessions and her recent deal to be one of
the faces of Cover Girl cosmetics.
 &HT;    Hill pleads guilty as charged _ except for that part about
betraying the faith.
 &HT;    ``I don't forget where I come from,'' the singer says. ``I'm not
trying to be anybody else. I'm not trying to be Shania, I'm not
trying to be Whitney Houston or anybody else.
 &HT;    ``I have an incredible respect for the establishment of country
music,'' she insists. ``I was inspired by it. It molded and shaped
who I am today _ but so did a lot of other sounds.''
 &HT;    Gospel was the first music that the former Faith Perry, the
adopted daughter of a factory worker and a retired bank employee,
sang while growing up in Star, Miss. Her mother remembers Faith as
a prodigy who belted songs at age 3 and gave her first public
performance at 10, for a women's-club luncheon. Soon she had taught
herself to play guitar and write songs.
 &HT;    After one semester of college, Hill left home in early 1987 to
pursue her star in Nashville. Doors did not open, and she soon
found herself on the very fringes of the industry, working in the
T-shirt booth at the annual Fan Fair festival and then at the
receptionist's desk at a music-publishing company.
 &HT;    Hill, who was married for four years to songwriter Dan Hill,
later landed a job sending out mail-order souvenirs to Reba
McEntire's fans. She auditioned to be one of McEntire's backup
singers, but lost out to Paula Kaye Evans _ who was killed, along
with most of the group, in a 1991 plane crash. Hill, meanwhile,
honed her skills in clubs and was signed by Warner Bros. Records in
1992.
 &HT;    Her first two albums _ ``Take Me as I Am'' (1993) and ``It
Matters to Me'' (1995) _ did well, but didn't reach beyond the
country realm. For ``Faith'' she added a second producer _ Byron
Gallimore, who also worked with McGraw and Jo Dee Messina _ to
handle some tracks along with her longtime collaborator Dan Huff.
 &HT;    ``I realized I didn't have to necessarily record with just one
producer on an album,'' Hill says. ``That opened up this whole
other world of thinking.''
 &HT;    Meshing two producers with different styles proved difficult,
Hill admits, ``but they each brought something that made a great
partnership.''
 &HT;    In the wake of ``Faith's'' success, the team remained intact,
with song selection and recording for what would become ``Breathe''
going on even as Hill staged her first tour as a headliner last
summer.
 &HT;    ``I want to grow on stage as well, so when I go and choose a
song for a record, I think about how it's going to translate to my
fans from the stage,'' she says. ``I tour _ that's part of who I am
right now. I wanted to make an album that was going to be fun to
bring to the road.''
 &HT;    That doesn't mean ``Breathe'' is without tender moments. Hill
recorded Bruce Springsteen's quiet expression of devotion, ``If I
Should Fall Behind,'' while her duet with McGraw on ``Let's Make
Love'' makes married love seem positively sinful.
 &HT;    ``It's a very romantic, very sensual song,'' Hill acknowledges
with a laugh. ``We weren't groping each other or anything like
that, but we certainly meant what we were singing. It was a special
moment for us _ it was nice just being in there together, doing
it.''
 &HT;    Hill plans to hit the road for another tour in support of
``Breathe,'' and she hints that McGraw might join her as a
co-headliner.
 &HT;    If ``Breathe'' sustains the breakthrough she made with
``Faith,'' Hill is entirely aware that the Nashville backlash will
only intensify. But she's prepared for whatever her critics may
dish out.
 &HT;    ``I'm strong,'' she says. ``I just want to do what I do and stay
focused. I don't think they are going to stifle me ... I feel very
comfortable where I am now, and I'm very proud of the record. What
is on that record is just a collection of songs that I really,
really loved and had fun with.
 &HT;    ``I'm just growing and being who I am right now,'' she
concludes. ``That's all I can ever be _ or ever want to be,
really.''
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Faith Hill, consult her official
Website at www.faithhill.com. And don't forget to visit The New
York Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate
for information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
