<HEADER>
A8153 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-TIM-MATHESON-IN-THE-W     01-17 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIM-MATHESON-IN-THE-WEST-WING-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON VICE: TIM MATHESON FINDS A HOME IN `THE WEST WING' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Tim Matheson in a scene from ``The West
Wing.'') 
 By BRIAN HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be released in Canada before Jan. 23. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan's success notwithstanding, it's not easy for an
actor to make it to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Matheson knows that firsthand. Despite an impressive resume
with more than 100 credits, Matheson had to audition for the role
of Vice President John Hoynes on the new hit political drama, ``The
West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he says, he didn't mind trying out for the part.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of agents said to me, `You shouldn't have to audition,
they should just hire you,''' he recalls. ``But I said, `These are
the best people in town, and they're not just going to hire
somebody _ they're going to want to see them.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've got no false pride about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The people in question were ``West Wing'' executive producers
Aaron Sorkin and Thomas Schlamme. Sorkin is the author of ``A Few
Good Men'' (1992) and ``The American President'' (1996), as well as
the creator of ``Sports Night,'' while Schlamme has produced
``Chicago Hope'' and ``Tracey Takes On.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a big fan of all their work, and they were both there,''
Matheson recalls. ``So we played around with the material, and it
just worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers are equally pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were incredibly lucky to get Tim for this role,'' Sorkin
says. ``He actually looks like a vice president, if you know what I
mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Matheson based his vice-presidential portrayal not on current
veep Al Gore, or on recent incumbents such as Dan Quayle or George
Bush. Instead he reached back 35 years to Vice President Lyndon B.
Johnson, later president after the murder of President John F.
Kennedy in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   The often-tense Johnson-Kennedy dynamic _ the two had been
rivals for the Democratic nomination in 1960 _ is reflected in the
strained relationship between Hoynes and President Josiah Bartlett
(Martin Sheen).
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnson was a man of incredible ego and accomplishment,''
Matheson says. ``And he felt he'd been usurped by a younger, less
experienced, more glamorous politician in Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The fictional vice president is younger than his real-life
model. But, like Johnson, Hoynes brings to his office a wealth of
political experience which he feels isn't utilized by the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got his own, strong agenda,'' Matheson says, ``and
perhaps doesn't hide it as much as he should, in light of the fact
that the president treats him shabbily.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent episodes, Bartlett's animosity toward Hoynes has been
attributed to Hoynes' having wavered before accepting Bartlett's
offer of the vice-presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``You shouldn't have made me beg,'' Bartlett said.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout from that incident has left the president and his
staff trying to keep the outspoken Hoynes on a short leash.
</P>
<P>
   It's essential to the story line, Sorkin says, that the audience
realize that the vice president is not merely a figurehead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president is a major part of the overall presidency,
despite what people think,'' the writer/producer explains. ``A lot
of people in the U.S. think that the veep doesn't really do
anything _ that's not how it works on our show.''
</P>
<P>
   Matheson agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes for good conflict, which in turn makes for good
drama,'' the actor says. ``It's good character development and a
lot of fun to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Matheson can rightfully call himself an authority on
characterization, having played scores of roles in his three
decades in film and television. Best known for ``National Lampoon's
Animal House'' (1978), Matheson actually had a flourishing career
well before then _ in fact, that film came near the halfway point
of his career to date.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, one of his first credits was a guest spot on
a 1962 episode of ``Leave it to Beaver.'' He was 15 _ though he
managed to escape the various hazards that have tripped up numerous
other former child actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky not being on a huge hit show or being a kid star
like Gary Coleman or so many others,'' he says, ``because they face
a huge burden overcoming the identities they've created.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Matheson is concerned, there are only two choices for
a child actor once he or she hits the teen-age years: get out of
the business or make the transition to adult actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The smart ones, like Jodie Foster and Kurt Russell, who were
both stars, both quit for a while,'' he says. ``Whereas with me, I
hit my lean years and made the transition by doing more voice work
offscreen.''
</P>
<P>
   As his teen years passed, Matheson dutifully went to school
before moving on to the big screen and films such as ``Divorce,
American Style'' (1967) with Dick Van Dyke and ``Yours, Mine and
Ours'' (1968) with Henry Fonda and Lucille Ball.
</P>
<P>
   His career continued during the 1970s with regular work on
dramatic series such as ``Bonanza,'' ``The Quest'' and ``How the
West Was Won.'' Then came ``Animal House,'' a film he recalls as a
welcome change of pace.
</P>
<P>
   Bored with being typecast as the nice guy next door, he adds, he
``wanted to break out. Before `Animal House' I'd never done
comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, ``Animal House'' led Matheson to more comedy
roles during the 1980s, including the lighthearted series
``Tucker's Witch'' (1982-1983), as well as the feature films ``Up
the Creek'' (1984) and ``Fletch'' (1985).
</P>
<P>
   But while most of the scripts he was offered were comedies,
Matheson strove to maintain balance, to escape being pigeonholed as
either a comedian or strictly a dramatic actor. He also took on
regular stage work, to be sure that he didn't evolve into purely a
movie or television actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything an actor can do to broaden his range is a valuable
tool and will lead to longevity,'' he says. ``I try to keep growing
and learning and changing because, really, it gets boring
otherwise. Even the audience gets bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Range is all very well, but it surely doesn't hurt that the
53-year-old father of three has remained remarkably youthful, a
fact he attributes more to genetics and makeup than to anything
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, if you have a really good cameraman, you can look
younger longer,'' Matheson adds.
</P>
<P>
   To judge by its ratings, ``The West Wing'' is in for a long run,
which means Vice President Hoynes will be around for a while _
which suits Matheson fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working on `West Wing' has been incredibly rewarding,'' he
says, ``because it's an adult show with bright, intelligent,
literate dialogue and multifaceted characters ... which you just
don't find on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, for that matter, very often in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Brian Hartigan is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada, based in
North York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The West Wing,'' consult the
NBC Website at www.nbc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
