<HEADLINE>
HOW AMERICANS LAUNCHED A NAVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
MILLIONS FOR DEFENSE 
The Subscription Warships of 1798 
By Frederick C. Leiner 
Naval Institute Press, 262 pp., illustrated, $36.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On April 3, 1798, President John Adams sent to Congress
documents detailing the efforts of three French officials to extort
a ``loan'' of 1 million pounds and a bribe of another 50,000 pounds
to secure American merchant ships from seizure by French
privateers.
</P>
<P>
   The incident became known as ``The XYZ Affair'' for the coded
names of the three French officials involved in the shakedown
attempt, and it gave birth to the slogan ``Millions for defense,
but not a penny for tribute.'' It also moved Congress, on June 30,
to authorize President Adams to accept ``any armed vessels . . .
offered to him for the use of the United States, to be employed in
public service.''
</P>
<P>
   The dates are significant, as Frederick C. Leiner notes in his
first-rate account of a little-known chapter in American naval
history, because of what happened during the two months between
them.
</P>
<P>
   In ports up and down the coast, local merchants and ship owners
were already subscribing money to build such ``armed vessels.''
Newburyport _ whose merchant fleet had been particularly ravaged by
privateers _ would be laying the keel for the 20-gun Merrimack on
July 9, barely 10 days after the Senate passed the authorization
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, writes Leiner, a Philadelphia lawyer and naval
historian, the public's ``support for strong measures of defense
outpaced the government,'' not only in subscribing money to build a
navy, but in refurbishing coastal defenses and mustering the old
militia companies. And, as the events in Newburyport suggest, doing
so with patriotic enthusiasm _ with only a slender hope of
profiting from the 6 percent interest on the net cost of the ship
to be paid ``at the convenience of the government.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Merrimack was launched on Oct. 12, Leiner writes, ``the
town celebrated with a `Music on Launching Day' concert, in which a
company of Boston musicians introduced a new piece, `The New
Federal Song _ Hail Patriots All.' After the concert, well-heeled
Newburyporters gavotted at a ball.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, 10 locally subscribed ships were built, in Newburyport,
Salem, Boston, Providence, New York, Philadelphia, Baltimore,
Charleston, and a group of Virginia towns. At sea, they joined the
three government-built frigates, Constitution, Constellation, and
United States.
</P>
<P>
   None of the subscription ships long survived the ``Quasi War''
with France: They fell victim to the Jefferson administration's
military cutbacks. But several, principally the Essex and the
Boston, took part in major naval engagements, with most of their
assignments involving convoy duty in the Caribbean, where the
French maintained a large fleet. Leiner writes with obvious
enthusiasm about the fighting at sea _ his account of the Boston's
victory over the French navy corvette Le Berceau off Guadeloupe
could have come right out of C. S. Forester's ``The Captain from
Connecticut.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is right to have focused on the on-shore fund-raising
activities, for that is what makes the story of these vessels so
unusual. When ``the subscription frenzy swept into Boston,'' Leiner
writes, 34 merchants met in an office on State Street on June 27
and immediately pledged $75,000. When the pledges reached $115,250
two days later, the Columbian Centinel boasted that ``Boston will
outdo every city in the union in this demonstration of federal
patriotism.'' In all, 103 merchants and civic leaders pledged
$136,000, with William Phillips (later a lieutenant governor and
president of Massachusetts General Hospital) pledging $10,000 _ the
largest individual gift in the entire country.
</P>
<P>
   Of almost equal interest is the technological enterprise that
was sparked. In the building of the Boston, Leiner writes, Paul
Revere discovered a method of melting down scrap copper and
reworking it into bolts and spikes. And that, Leiner writes, led in
turn to Revere's opening of the nation's first copper-rolling mill
to make sheathing for the hulls of American naval vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the patriotic merchants, the hero of these events is John
Adams. He correctly gauged the public reaction to the French
attacks on American shipping _ and their attempt to use those
attacks as the basis for extortion. And having once set the
military reaction in motion, he took a personal interest in seeing
it carried out, inviting the captain of the Merrimack to dinner at
his home in Braintree, attending the launching of the Boston, and
playing a role in choosing its officers.
</P>
<P>
   Leiner properly gives Adams the last word: The subscription
ships, he told a joint session of Congress on November 22, 1800,
``called suddenly unto existence by a great national exigency,
(have) raised us in our own esteem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
