<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE DOT-COM FOUNTATION OF YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You know you're getting old when ... fill in the
blank. If you forget what you were going to fill in, well, never
mind.
</P>
<P>
   I had a birthday on Jan. 10, and let's just say I turned the age
President Clinton will be when he leaves the White House. But
that's not so bad, because he spent at least a year acting like an
18-year-old in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   It's all relative, and you can be as old or young as you want to
be.
</P>
<P>
   That's what a smash-hit Web site called RealAge.com teaches you,
while simultaneously selling vitamins and a personalized ``age
reduction'' plan.
</P>
<P>
   You know you're getting old when you call up RealAge.com and
take the on-line test that compares your chronological age with
your ``real age.''
</P>
<P>
   As you type in ``no'' to whether you eat five or more servings
of fruit or vegetables a day, you can watch a little dial show your
``real age'' increase.
</P>
<P>
   Who even knows what a serving of fruit is?
</P>
<P>
   I didn't lie on the test, and still my ``real age'' came out 1.8
years younger than Bill Clinton will be when he leaves the White
House. I don't mean 19.2.
</P>
<P>
   The RealAge test is easy on the system. That's good because
stress increases your ``real age.'' You don't feel shamed into
lying. Men only have to admit to drinking two or more alcoholic
drinks per day and women only have to admit to one or more.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows why women are cheated out of a drink. Neither amount
of alcohol seems like much of a consolation for old age. And
nowadays it seems binge drinking is a sign of youth.
</P>
<P>
   I think what you drink is a more important sign of age.
</P>
<P>
   Trust anyone who drinks a cosmopolitan to be under 30.
</P>
<P>
   Another question asked whether I used seat belts all the time
and had airbags in my car.
</P>
<P>
   The site later told me that if I took those precautions I could
reduce my ``real age'' 3.4 years.
</P>
<P>
   But wait a minute. It's mainly teen-agers who are ejected from
cars because they aren't wearing seat belts, so shouldn't you be
younger if you don't buckle up? And those teen-agers remain forever
young.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Roizen designed the RealAge test based on life
expectancy data from 25,000 medical studies, not how young we
really feel or act. Roizen is 53 chronological years old and claims
to be 38 in ``real age,'' according to his own test.
</P>
<P>
   But then, I'd be feeling pretty young if I had a Web site and
book recommended by an Apple.com review and, better than that,
Oprah Winfrey, who came out pretty young herself on the test.
</P>
<P>
   Wealth, for everyone but Steve Forbes, is the best age reduction
plan. It can give you health and a heck of a makeover.
</P>
<P>
   The RealAge test probably should just ask what your income is _
the higher it is the more years it takes off. Instead the test asks
if we have high blood pressure, eat tomato products, get depressed
and have a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   That's not funny. Even Sen. Strom Thurmond, ``real age'' 296, is
going to say yes and get some years taken off because some study
somewhere says a sense of humor keeps you young.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know someone's real age, ask them if they find
``South Park'' funny. I only know a few people over the
chronological age of 50 who do, and I'm not admitting who we are.
</P>
<P>
   The RealAge test also asks how fast you drive over the speed
limit, with alternatives ranging from 4 mph over the limit to 15 or
more mph over the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Your ``real age'' on the test declines with your speed, even
though in real life the slower you go the older you are.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know how young people really are, and not just
their life expectancy, I wouldn't ask what vitamins they take.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a lot of vitamins is a sure sign of wanting to live
forever, which in turn is a sure sign of not being young anymore.
The young assume they're going to live forever. That's why they
drive fast and binge drink.
</P>
<P>
   If I were designing a ``real age'' test, I certainly wouldn't
ask if people get 90 minutes of sustained exercise a week and say
that walking counts, the way the folks at RealAge did.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety minutes of sustained skateboarding means you're young,
not walking. Only people like me, with 100-year-old knees, consider
walking exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with being human is that we age awfully unevenly.
And the most complex part of us, the brain, ages more unevenly than
all the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the skull of one 54-year-old man can reside the knowledge
and charm of a 70-year-old, the ambition of a 30-year-old, the
responsibility of an 8-year-old and the appetite of a 16-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Mr. President, one encouraging age-reduction tip on
the RealAge Web site was that you can lower your ``real age'' 1.6
years by means of regular sex _ ``within the context of a
monogamous relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Or you can just buckle up, drive slowly and try to have a sense
of humor about things.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
