 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Tuesday, Jan. 18,
2000.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS _ DES MOINES, Iowa _ Democratic presidential
candidates Al Gore and Bill Bradley debate Monday at the Brown and
Black Forum. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS-BAXTER _ DES MOINES, Iowa _ Commentary and color from
the Iowa Democratic debate. (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MLK-WRAP _ ATLANTA _ Wrapup on King Holiday festivities,
including annual SCLC parade in downtown Atlanta, King's hometown.
(McCarthy, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   COKE _ ATLANTA _ Advancer to Coca-Cola board meeting Tuesday.
Jack Stahl, who heads the soft drink makers North America and Latin
America operations is expected to be named president and chief
operating officer, the No. 2 position behind Douglas Daft, who is
expected to be named chairman. (Unger, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   UPS _ ATLANTA _ UPS is dipping a Big Brown toe into financial
services. The cash-rich delivery giant has started extending loans
to customers, offering advance payment on accounts receivables and
even leasing office equipment. The goal is to help shipping
customers grow into bigger shipping customers, while making money
on the financing at the same time, said Bob Bernabucci, chief of
UPS Capital Corp. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   BLOODLESS _ Bloodless surgery started as a way to treat those
who refused blood transfusions for spiritual reasons. But now, more
patients and doctors are interested in bloodless surgery as a way
to avoid tainted and dwindling blood supplies. In fact, some
statistics indicate that this was the first year that more patients
cited medical reasons _ instead of spiritual reasons _ for their
desire to undergo bloodless surgery. In response, Atlanta Medical
Center has started this month a program that can convert up to 99
percent of its operations _ even open heart surgery _ into
bloodless surgical procedures, using a combination of surgical
techniques, drugs and a machine that sucks up, cleans and
circulates the patients' own blood. (Lore, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHY-MEDIA _ Internet site; four great fitness videos.
(McKenna, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
