<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: I will be lost without my little metal
watch-band calendars (thin metal strips with a monthly calendar
printed on them). I look for the date more than the time on my
watch! I used to get them as promotional gifts from suppliers, then
found them in Christmas catalogs such as Miles Kimball. M-K didn't
show them this year. Can you help? _ E.F. Merrill
</P>
<P>
   A: I do not know why these are so hard to find, but I have two
sources. Pick up a metallic and gold tone reversible calendar,
12-month set ($5.55 plus shipping) for 2000 from Jackson Office
Supply, 3680 Kinsman Blvd., Madison, WI 53704, or by calling (608)
284-0082. Sets ($5 each, three for $13.50, including shipping) also
are available until Feb. 1 from Gifts to Go, P.O. Box 55607,
Riverside, CA 92517. Q: What can you use to safely remove tree sap
from your car without ruining the paint job? _ Peggy P.
</P>
<P>
   A: Splattered bugs and bird droppings are more toxic to your
car's paint than tree sap. Older paint not well-protected by
regular waxings is more susceptible to damage. Vernon Warren of
Warren's Auto Detail uses WashThinner (pick some up at Auto Zone)
if the sap is a few weeks old. He follows with a hand wax. Ronnie
Herzog at Advanced Mobile Detail carefully scrapes hardened sap
with his fingernail and follows this with a complete wax using
McQuairs Cleaner and Wax. McQuairs eliminates any little marks left
by fingernails. Q: What is the travel range (outdoors) of a pet boa
constrictor in an urban environment? Signs went up in our
neighborhood asking to help locate a 7-foot-long snake that escaped
about two blocks away. I can go into my thoughts later about the
boneheadedness of keeping a reptile that size in an apartment (or
anywhere else). I'm concerned about looking out my door and seeing
it wrapped around my geraniums or, worse, my toddler. Could you ask
your experts if my nervousness about a loose creature is
reasonable? Are there precautions to avoid a surprise visit? I'm an
animal lover, but I draw the line at something that can squeeze the
life out of a 3-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   _ J.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: Boa constrictors are generally non-aggressive snakes,
according to the folks at Zoo Keeper, an exotic pet shop. These
snakes do not attack unless repeatedly bothered. Reptiles are
cold-blooded, so cool weather makes them lethargic (read S L O W).
Two blocks is a long way to travel under these conditions. The boa
is probably looking for a warm spot _ next to an outdoor heater or
car engine. There is no effective way to look for the missing
snake. A 7-foot snake could possibly attack a toddler. But little
tykes are never left unattended.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many months did the ex-Miss America Vanessa Williams
reign before she resigned? Three? _ O.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Nope, 10 months. Vanessa Williams was crowned Miss America on
Sept. 17, 1983. Winner of both the swimsuit and talent contests,
she made history as the first African-American Miss America. After
the publication of her controversial photos in Penthouse magazine,
Williams resigned on July 23, 1984. Williams was replaced by New
Jersey's Suzette Charles. Q: My mother and I have been looking for
a dress for her to wear at my wedding. We found a fabulous
off-white dress. I have seen many mothers wearing white or cream in
magazines. My dress is ivory but not identical to the color we
chose for my mother. I do not care if she wears it, but I don't
want her to feel uncomfortable because a few whisper, ``She
shouldn't be wearing that color.'' _ B. B.
</P>
<P>
   A: It is your day. What you say goes _ attire for the mother of
the bride or groom, flower girls, etc. With more bridesmaids in
black and other non-traditional colors these days, the rules are
fluid. One caution: When photographs are taken, the color might
blend with your gown, so place a flower girl or tuxedoed member of
the wedding party between you and your mother. Q: I have a Persian
cat named Tuffy, and he is always a challenge to groom. I would
like to find a place that offers training so that I can groom him
safely, especially to get his fur unmatted.
</P>
<P>
   _Chris Brown
</P>
<P>
   A: Persians have long hair that presents unique grooming
problems. Even though cats are self-groomers, long-hair cats rarely
control matting without human assistance. Babette Ellis of Exmoor
Pet Services offers consultations on how to groom your cat that
include at-home tips as well as a regular professional schedule.
She warns customers never to bathe a pet with matted hair (it
exacerbates the problem). Mats can be untangled, brushed out or cut
out. Remember, feline skin is very sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the ``com'' stand for in e-mail addresses? Someone
asked me and I was unable to answer, but bet you can. My guess?
``Commerce.'' _A.O.
</P>
<P>
   A: You are close. ``Com'' stands for ``commercial
organization,'' a domain, an area address, in computer-speak. Other
common organizational domains are: ``edu,'' educational
institution; ``gov,'' government; ``int,'' international
organization; ``mil,'' military; ``net,'' networking organization
and ``org,'' nonprofit organization. Organizational domains were
developed as part of the addressing scheme before networks were
worldwide, which explains geographic domains such as ``au'' for
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who do I write to get a copy of my father's Navy records from
World War II? He served in the Pacific theater.
</P>
<P>
   _ Joe G.
</P>
<P>
   A: ObtainStandard Form 180, which is available online at
www.chinfo.navy.mil/navpalib/people/faq/.www/records.html or by
contacting the National Personal Records Center by mail at 9700
Page Blvd., St. Louis, MO 63132 or by phone at (314) 538-4141.
Requests by someone other than the veteran must include the
specific relationship and proof of death. Q: Help me figure out how
to deodorize the seat-belt shoulder strap on my new-used car. The
previous owner was a little too fond of Shalimar, and it's embedded
in the weave of the strap. I've had the car professionally
detailed, but no improvement. _B.H.
</P>
<P>
   A: Introduced in 1925 by Guerlain, Shalimar has always been a
very popular scent. Auto detailing guru Chris Kuehne of Auto Image
notes shoulder straps, especially on newer-model cars, are one of
the few items you cannot simply wash. Try his cleaning method to
render your car's seat belts a Shalimar-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   Go to a do-it-yourself carwash. Extend the shoulder belt as far
as possible and close the door on it. Most of the shoulder-strap
seat belt should be outside the car. Wrap the belt's metal buckle
in a towel to protect the paint.
</P>
<P>
   Use upholstery shampoo and a pressure hose to wash the belt.
Towel dry and drive home. Extend the belt again, close the door and
let the sun dry it thoroughly. Kuehne's only caution? Do not let
upholstery shampoo dry on your car's paint.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
