</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-CIVILRIGHTS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New exhibit at King historic site spotlights children's civil
rights fight
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Have you ever thought about what you can do to make
the world a better place?
</P>
<P>
   Ruby Bridges did. In 1960, she became the first black student to
attend an all-white New Orleans elementary school. She was only 6
years old.
</P>
<P>
   Her brave integration of the school is profiled in the new
``Children of Courage'' exhibit. It opened last week at the
visitors center of the Martin Luther King Jr. National Historic
Site in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Along with people like the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and Rosa
Parks, who fought for civil rights, were young school-aged people
like Bridges who made sacrifices to make the world a better place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stories of the young pioneers in the civil rights movement
told in this exhibition will inspire today's youth and help them
realize that they, too, can make a difference,'' said Donald
Greene, president of the Coca-Cola Foundation. A grant from the
foundation paid for the exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit documents the important role children played in the
civil rights movement. It will be permanent, along with the current
exhibit exploring civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives the children an interactive way to look at what it
was like to grow up under segregation. When you try to tell someone
that there were white and black water fountains, they have a hard
time believing it,'' said Frank Catroppa, superintendent of the
King historic site.
</P>
<P>
   The interactive exhibit uses computers and photos. Visitors can
ask questions and solve problems like those the children of the
civil rights movement faced.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the exhibit, students are asked who will be the
leaders of tomorrow. When they open a window, they see a mirror
with their reflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``This adds a new dimension to the story being told at one of
the country's premier national historic sites and conveys Dr.
King's message of justice, equality and nonviolence to all the
world's children,'' said Robert Stanton, director of the National
Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1980, the Martin Luther King Jr. National
Historic Site honors King's life, legacy and teachings. The site,
which is part of the National Park System, contains the home where
King was born; Ebenezer Baptist Church, where he preached; the
Martin Luther King Jr. Center for Nonviolent Social Change; King's
grave site; Fire Station No. 6 Museum; and the residential and
commercial districts of the Sweet Auburn community.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   Where: Martin Luther King Jr. National Historic Site, 450 Auburn
Ave. N.E., Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   When: Generally, it's open
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m. to 5 p.m. until Memorial Day weekend; from then until
Labor Day, it's open 9 a.m. to 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: There is no entrance fee.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (404) 331-5190 or
</P>
<P>
   (404) 331-6922.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
