<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8179 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH18-COX     01-17 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL, Time Warner unite
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ America Online (AOL) and Time Warner announced this
week that they will join forces _ or ``merge.'' (Think Woody
teaming up with Buzz Lightyear.)
</P>
<P>
   AOL is the company that many of us use to log onto the Internet
and to check our e-mail. Time Warner creates magazines, movies and
TV shows. It also owns Atlanta's CNN, Cartoon Network and World
Championship Wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   After the companies combine, AOL will be able offer its online
customers Time Warner's news and entertainment. In turn, Time
Warner will be able to distribute its material on the Internet
through AOL.
</P>
<P>
   What does the merger mean to you? With this and other media
mergers, like Disney's takeover of ABC, it means we're getting our
news from fewer sources.
</P>
<P>
   Some people think that's bad. Others don't think that's a
problem. They say the mergers make the companies stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The government still has to approve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   BOY STAYS IN U.S. _ FOR NOW
</P>
<P>
   The battle continues over a 6-year-old Cuban boy whose mother
died bringing him to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Elian Gonzalez, was found on Thanksgiving clinging to
an inner tube in the water off the Florida coast. His mother,
stepfather and eight other people had drowned while fleeing from
Cuba by boat. Many Cubans risk their lives to make the 90-mile
crossing between the United States and Cuba because they believe
their lives would be better in this country. Cuba has a Communist
government.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the U.S. immigration service said the boy should
be returned to his father in Cuba. It set a deadline of last Friday
for his return.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno lifted the deadline to give
Elian's Miami relatives a chance to fight for the boy in court.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Cuban mothers marched last week to protest the boy
not being returned.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKER TALKS TO BLACK LEADERS
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves relief pitcher John Rocker is trying to make up
for insulting comments he made about foreigners, gays and others.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the pitcher said in a Sports Illustrated
article: ``The biggest thing I don't like about New York are the
foreigners. You can walk an entire block in Times Square and not
hear anybody speaking English.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker apologized last week on the ESPN sports cable channel for
the comments and denied being a racist.
</P>
<P>
   He said teammates Andruw Jones, Bruce Chen and Odalis Perez, all
minorities, had lived with his family in Macon. ``If I was a
racist, would I want a black guy living in my house and would I
invite him to come to my house?'' Rocker asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rocker got advice from former Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young and
baseball legend Hank Aaron on how to deal with hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
