<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Late to the game, Apple adds series of Net-based services
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Apple announced a dizzying number of new initiatives
at the recent MacWorld Expo in San Francisco. It's no wonder some
got lost in the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at one in particular that, although it received
little attention, is very important to Apple.
</P>
<P>
   This initiative is called iTools, and it's an effort to raise
Apple's profile and usefulness on the Internet. In essence, iTools
is a collection of six free Internet-based consumer services.
</P>
<P>
   The services include electronic mail, a database of ``kid-safe''
Web sites, file storage, and space to build and maintain a Web
page.
</P>
<P>
   None of these services is unique. If anything, Apple is late to
the game in offering them. Many other sites, including Microsoft's,
are offering all or more of these services.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, though, Apple can distinguish itself by how well it
executes Internet-based services. At first glance they certainly
look classy.
</P>
<P>
   There's one caveat when it comes to using them right away. A
user must have Apple's latest operating system, OS 9. Other
operating systems won't work.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find iTools as a tab on Apple's redesigned Web page. The
new design features a platinum look similar to that of the
company's operating system. Along the top of the page is a series
of tabs. Click on the one named iTools, and you'll go to a page
that briefly describes each of the four services and asks you to
register in order to use any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in brief, is a description of each of the new services:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mac.com: You can now send and receive e-mail through Apple's
Web site. It works pretty much like the other such services on the
Net.
</P>
<P>
   _ KidSafe: Apple has built a database of 55,000 sites it has
tested for appropriateness for kids. Signing onto KidSafe blocks
you from going to any other sites. It works in the reverse manner
of a filter. Instead of filtering out sites, it simply offers safe
ones. The site does filter incoming e-mail, chat room
correspondence and online games for inappropriate language and
images.
</P>
<P>
   _ IDisk: This service provides 20 megabytes to users. That is
not a lot, but it is free. It's also accessible from wherever you
access the Internet. IDisk also lets you share and export files and
images with others. You could, for example, store a picture of your
family and then copy it into an electronic card to send to friends.
</P>
<P>
   _ Home page: With this service you can build and maintain a
personal Web page.
</P>
<P>
   _ ICards: This where you can import photos from iDisk and create
electronic cards to send through the Net.
</P>
<P>
   _ IReview: This is a separate page where members of iTools can
post and read reviews of various products, Web pages and services.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
