<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Merger fallout uncertain
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the past week, all the pundits and analysts have
been busy trying to figure out how the AOL-Time Warner merger will
change our lives, raise our cable rates, increase the hole in the
ozone or help the Cubs win the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   It is tempting to talk about the potential of this new
enterprise and the role TV/Internet guru Bob Pittman, AOL's
president, could have on the digital music revolution as well as
broadband content development, but the results of the deal remain
to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   So instead, I'd like to ``take a moment'' as they say on ``Ally
McBeal'' and remember that AOL and Time Warner have been
insinuating themselves into our lives long before Steve Case, Ted
Turner and Gerald Levin were all smiling and clapping in front of
the scariest pile of media logos ever collected in one place.
</P>
<P>
   When I finished college, I went to work for Little, Brown &AMP;
Co.'s college textbook division. It was fun for a while, but I soon
discovered all the disparaging things GenX author Jay McInerney
said about low-level publishing jobs were true, and I decided to
move on. I resigned on Monday, and on Wednesday employees were told
that the company would merge with motion picture giant Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction at the staid Boston publishing house was one of
sheer horror. Editors were stuffing their resumes into fax machines
faster than you could say ``Bugs Bunny.'' The very idea that the
company founded by Henry Luce, which published such venerable
magazines as Time and Life and had such noted talents as Norman
Mailer, Ellen Gilchrist and Ansel Adams, was going to join up with
a movie studio was just appalling.
</P>
<P>
   My boss, a wonderful editor named Alex, just shook his head and
murmured, ``The writing was right there on the wall, and I wasn't
wearing my glasses.'' The new Time Warner divested its textbook
division and a few other moldy properties and continued its march
toward the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   I moved to New York City about the time America Online was
gaining mainstream popularity. It was also the subject of much
ridicule for its ``carpet bombing'' marketing technique for
packaging AOL diskettes in everything except cans of Campbell's
soup.
</P>
<P>
   My boss had a box of AOL diskettes under his desk, which he
collected from all over the place. It was a great curiosity, and
people loved to look at all the versions and types and colors of
AOL disks that were actually in circulation. Marc was devastated
when the janitorial staff mistook his collection for trash. I
suspect ``Antiques Road Show'' would probably be interested in that
box now.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, people liked AOL, even the Web geeks who usually
had another Internet provider to get them out to the Web. (AOL
hadn't done any of its famous deals with Netscape or Microsoft
yet.) Every month founder Steve Case would write a letter to
members that would be featured prominently on the AOL welcome
screen, and people read them.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about ``Steve'' like they knew him. The service had
only 4 million or 5 million members then. People were known to have
actual conversations online without being accosted by potential
child molesters, credit card thieves or rowdy teens with stupid
screen names.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, AOL went to a flat-rate pricing plan that was
novel in the industry. The crush of subscribers who logged on for
hours on end just because they could nearly brought the system to
its knees. People were livid. They were doing everything from
circulating online petitions to e-mailing Steve Case personally to
complain.
</P>
<P>
   You see, back in 1997, millions of people thought they could
just drop a note to Steve, and that he might read it and actually
do something. Usually what you got back was a form letter, but
still it was something.
</P>
<P>
   AOL had the knack of making millions of people all feel like
part of one big happy but slightly dysfunctional family. I actually
know several couples who met on AOL and not in a romance chat room,
either. A group of people used to meet every Sunday night to talk
about alternative rock music, and I never missed a week.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times also sponsored a moderated book chat that was
one of the best book groups I've ever dropped in on. AOL connected
people, almost in the same way the pictures from the old Life
magazine used to, which is one reason all the pundits say this
merger makes so much sense.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually AOL's troubles led Case to television to convince
users that the dial-up debacle would never happen ever, ever again.
Nevertheless, he threw the door wide open for upstarts like
MindSpring, EarthLink, AT&AMP;T's WorldNet and a host of other Internet
service providers to offer Net access without endless busy signals
and mail server crashes and with customer service people who might
actually help you.
</P>
<P>
   But somehow, people stayed loyal to AOL. The service continued
to grow and develop into something that not just first-time Net
users but seasoned and cynical veterans might like, with
innovations in Web access, electronic commerce and instant
messaging across the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at the start of the 21st century, AOL, the online service
I've been using since I got my first PC, is merging with Time
Warner, the company I was working for when I got my first PC. AOL
Time Warner has grown from being a print publisher to a movie,
cable, news, sports, music and now Internet provider.
</P>
<P>
   Is it too big? Who knows? Probably, but I still remember when
people thought that Time magazine and Warner music and CNN all
being owned by the same company was unthinkable. I wonder how much
they'll want for a piece of Microsoft?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
