<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cutting edge gadgets for 2000
 &HT;    By Gregory Kallenberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News ServiceThe first Consumer Electronics Show of
<TEXT>
the third millennium was held last week in Las Vegas. The
conference shows off the cool gadgets and gizmos you'll be seeing
this year and beyond. Gadgetry is in hyperdrive, with some 7,000
new products on the way. Here are the best of the best, the cutting
edge of the cutting edge due out this year. A cautionary note: The
products' release dates and prices are tentative and, at the time
of electronics show, could not be confirmed. That means not
everything is guaranteed to hit store shelves. Some gadgets may be
destined to only exist on the shelves of their creators:
<P>
   GENIUS CALLING
</P>
<P>
   Who: Ericsson, www.ericsson.com
</P>
<P>
   What: R380 Smart Phone. The Smart Phone is the size of an
average mobile phone but has a flip keypad which transforms the
communication device into a palm-sized computer. The phone is
totally jammed with features including Internet capability and PDA.
The R380 will feature a calendar, address software, WAP browser
(which enables you to see Web pages without the graphics) and
handwriting recognition software. The phone is also voice-activated
for the hands-free executive in you. Oh, and if that's not enough,
the R380 can also be an MP3 music player.
</P>
<P>
   When: Tentatively June/July (in limited areas)
</P>
<P>
   How much: to be announced
</P>
<P>
   STRAIGHT SHOOTER
</P>
<P>
   Who: JVC, www.jvc.com
</P>
<P>
   What: GR-DVL9800. This is the top-of-the-line JVC digital video
camera to be released this year. The camera has been reduced in
size and now is about the size of your hand. The optics have been
totally overhauled and the camera lightened. It will double as a
true digital camera. While other digital video cameras capture
images off the tape, the JVC captures high resolution XGA digital
stills on a separate, removable MultimediaCard. This will let the
user film and photograph simultaneously. The camera comes with an
automatic pop-up flash.
</P>
<P>
   When: February
</P>
<P>
   How much: $1,400
</P>
<P>
   AURAL ORB
</P>
<P>
   Who: Morel, www.morel.co.il
</P>
<P>
   What: Soundspot SA-2. This 4.5-inch speaker won a CES
``Innovations'' award for its design and superior sound. The tiny
orb speaker was developed to be integrated into home theaters.
While its physical profile is almost nonexistent, the sound is
fantastic. This is due to Morel's own, super-secret audio
technology, cryptically called EVC (external voice coil). The
result: speakers that would make any audiophile rapturous.
</P>
<P>
   When: March
</P>
<P>
   How much: $530 a pair
</P>
<P>
   LI'L BUDDY
</P>
<P>
   Who: Cygnion, www.cygnion.com
</P>
<P>
   What: Cybergenie. The winner of a CES Innovations award, this
digital phone assistant is part Cadbury the butler, part Rosie the
Robot. Using telephony technology, this cordless unit delivers
customized call answering, up to 20 individualized voice mail
boxes, memo recording and conference calls. But that's just the
beginning. Cybergenie can also access your E-mail and faxes and
read them to you over the phone. As a bonus, the Cybergenie can
call you whenever a voice mail, E-mail or fax comes in and read it
to you. The system is especially designed with the small office and
the home office users in mind.
</P>
<P>
   When: End of this month
</P>
<P>
   How much: $500 (one cordless handset is included), $130 each for
additional handsets.
</P>
<P>
   PLAY BOY
</P>
<P>
   Who: Sony, www.sony.com
</P>
<P>
   What: NW-MS7. The Memorystick Walkman is essentially a beefed up
MP3 player with amazing sound and phenomenal recording
capabilities. The unit _ which is the width of two pens lying
side-by-side, a little taller than a cigarette pack and weighs 2.5
ounces _ is packaged with a 64-megabyte removable Memorystick card
(Sony's proprietary memory device). The Memorystick Walkman will
enable you to download an hour's worth of music in just over three
minutes and is USB compatible.
</P>
<P>
   When: February
</P>
<P>
   How much: Expected retail price around $400
</P>
<P>
   MOBILE MEDIA
</P>
<P>
   Who: Alpine, www.alpine1.com
</P>
<P>
   What: IVA-C800. This motorized in-dash multimedia station for
the car has a 6.5-inch LCD screen that can be used as a graphic
stereo interface, DVD videos and Alpine's brand new GPS system. The
unit comes with a AM/FM tuner, two A/V inputs and a dedicated
navigation input. The mechanics are smooth and the screen releases
at the touch of a button. The multimedia station also features
Alpine's Versatile-Link technology for the easy hookup of portable
MP3 players and video game systems.
</P>
<P>
   When: March
</P>
<P>
   How much: To be announced.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
