u e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN18-C     01-17 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Will the geeks inherit the earth?
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The fate of a brand-new, first-rate TV series is
often fragile. Especially if it's different, it needs all the help
it can get. And in this age of new technology, cybersurfers may be
the key to salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Take ``Freaks and Geeks,'' for example. This funny, poignant and
painfully realistic look at high school life in the '80s debuted on
NBC last fall to resounding critical acclaim. Time magazine crowed,
``Television has rarely gotten adolescence as hilariously,
soul-crushingly right as in this bittersweet paean to Midwestern
childhood.'' Rolling Stone called it ``one of the season's best
shows.''
</P>
<P>
   But from the beginning, the deck was stacked against ``Freaks.''
Scheduled in the dead zone of Saturday nights, the show quickly
sagged to the bottom of the ratings and was yanked in early
November. In response to fervent begging by producers and the
heartfelt pleas from a small but wildly loyal band of fans,
``Freaks and Geeks'' was relaunched in a new time period _ Mondays
at 7 _ last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is such an ax hanging over our heads,'' creator-producer
Paul Feig said in a fast-paced phone call from his office recently.
``The network has told us we have to get an 8 share. If we do, the
network will order four more episodes. If not, we'll have to shut
down production and wait to see how the rest of our episodes do.
We'll just have to keep our fingers crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a tiny light at the end of the tunnel. Last Tuesday
morning's Nielsen ratings gave the show an 8 share _ not a smidgen
more. Despite days of on-air promotions and frantic Web activity,
the return of ``Freaks and Geeks'' didn't soar as NBC hoped. But it
didn't crash either, despite pre-emptions for telethons and sports
events in several parts of the country, including here, where the
San Antonio Spurs took the time slot. The rating was enough to
prompt NBC on Wednesday to give the green light for more episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Before the show's return, Feig (who based the show on his
high-school experiences) and his geeky gang of writers tapped into
the network of fans that buzz around the show's Web site. The
cyberspot (freaksandgeeks.com), launched before the show's debut,
has a bulletin board, chat room, direct lines to the producers,
story information and biographies of cast and crew. Fans share
their own ``geek'' experiences with each other and with the
writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we would have a good Internet presence,'' Feig says.
``The Internet is filled with outsiders, just like the kids in our
show. It's an easy way to keep in communication. I get on at least
once a day, not so much to get story ideas as to fact-check the
ones we have and answer questions.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ratings began to sag last fall, Feig and executive
producer Judd Apatow (``The Larry Sanders Show'') used the site to
orchestrate a write-in campaign to the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured that was our best shot,'' Feig says. ``It's not
really advertising so much as a forum we invite people into. We
have a nice village of people, but that's not enough. We're urging
them to spread the word about our move to Monday nights.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time the Internet has been used to promote
entertainment. Last summer, ``The Blair Witch Project'' stirred
such a ruckus on the Internet that it changed the face of movie
marketing. But it didn't introduce the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought Internet marketing to the attention of a lot of
people, but it had already been used by a lot of people,'' says
Deborah Hamberlin, NBC's vice president of corporate advertising.
``It just made it more mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   When ``The X-Files'' was struggling in 1993, for instance,
creator Chris Carter and the rabid army of X-philes stirred up
interest on the Web, which was filled with the sort of people _
sci-fi loving freaks and geeks, that is _ who would appreciate the
show.
</P>
<P>
   Now just about all TV series have Web sites, although most are
pretty basic. An exception about five years ago was the elaborate
Web-only episodes of NBC's cop drama ``Homicide: Life on the
Street.''
</P>
<P>
   For the return of ``Freaks and Geeks,'' NBC hired Interactive
Agency to promote the show on the World Wide Web. But the show's
own Web site remains the principal hub of activity. It may be the
first time a network has actually pleaded with viewers via the Web
to spread the word.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a guerrilla marketing campaign,'' says Hamberlin.
``We're hoping to put that core fan group to work. There are lots
of them, and they're passionate about their program. I think this
approach only works on things that have a passionate fan base. What
the Internet can do that other media cannot is engage a group of
people talking amongst themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, the show's Web site was oozing praise for the
previous night's episode and pleas for NBC to keep the show going:
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't cancel this show! ... It deserves a chance, and I
hope the network gets behind it and promotes it.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the big deal about a high school show, especially one
about nerds and weirdos? Well, it's strikingly real, sort of a
cross between ``The Wonder Years'' and ``The Real World.'' The kids
don't look or act like Hollywood actors. They have unkempt hair,
bad skin and crooked teeth. And the story lines spring from real
life, not from some fantasy of what teen life should be.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this show, the teens actually talk like teens,'' states one
chat room fan.
</P>
<P>
   Set in a suburban high school in 1980, the show focuses on the
funny and often touching lives of two teens trying to survive class
and cafeteria crises. On the freaks side is Lindsay Weir (Linda
Cardellini), a sophomore who used to be a clean-cut intellectual
but now hangs out with a rebellious crowd. The geeks are led by
Lindsay's freshman brother Sam (John Daly), who is woefully small
and immature for his age and constantly battling a bully. Sam's
friends include the cocky science nerd Neal (Samm Levine) and the
hilariously geeky Bill (Martin Starr).
</P>
<P>
   One of the best episodes found Sam and the geeks struggling with
whether freshmen are too old to go trick-or-treating.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's episode reintroduced the show with an episode about
Lindsay and pals trying to get fake IDs, and Sam and pals worrying
that a pretty new girl will dump them as soon as she meets the
popular in-crowd. In a subplot, the siblings' excruciatingly
realistic parents try to lure them into family activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created you, and we deserve respect. ... I'm fed up,'' the
father bellows. ``We're going to be close from now on, whether you
like it or not!''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who have been watching are mostly those who grew up
in the '80s, who remember what it was like in high school at that
time,'' Feig says. ``But it's a broad spectrum, from teens and kids
to people _ probably parents _ in their 40s. What we need to do now
is educate people to realize it's not a kids' show. We want to
appeal to the `Seinfeld' and `Simpsons' crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, in a perfect world where quality TV succeeds, should just
be a matter of getting the word out _ electronically or face to
face.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
