u k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN18-COX     01-17 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schools get failing grade for passing over teacher
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ ``I went to college seven years for this? No
pay? No job? And worst of all, no respect?'' That's my frustrated
friend Gail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yup.'' That's my erudite answer which loosely translates to,
``I've been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gail's husband died when her three children were small. She
raised them on her own and then, after the last one had flown the
nest, went back to college to finish the education that marriage
and babies had interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta' get that degree'' was the mantra that kept her going
through summer rains and winter snows as she wound old Phred's
speedometer to the max with her almost two-hour each way daily
commute. Phred was the green Subaru that finally threw itself on
its back, wheels up, and refused to haul another history book to
Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Gail persevered, replacing Phred with Phoebe, a red Toyota.
``Without that piece of paper I'll never have a decent job,'' she'd
remind herself when the drive, the workload, and the expense
threatened to overwhelm her.
</P>
<P>
   So, just like the U.S. Postal service, through sleet and double
pneumonia, Gail forged on until seven years later she had the
education and the piece of paper with Cum Laude stamped in the
lower left corner to prove that not only had she paid her tuition
and showed up for class, but that she'd busted her backside (and
Phred's and Phoebe's) and distinguished herself right nicely in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Credentials in hand, Gail began visiting schools within a
15-mile radius of her home. Then a 20-miles radius. When she
reached 40-miles with the same answers, she became a little
discouraged. It seems no one needed a 53-year-old history teacher
with a master's degree but this was her lucky day _ they all needed
substitutes and would (SET ITAL)love(END ITAL) to add her name to
their list. She said OK, and now one school or another uses her
almost every day _ 60 bucks and no benefits.
</P>
<P>
   So where are the full-time jobs, she wonders. Were all of the
rumors she'd heard of a teacher shortage just that? Rumors?
</P>
<P>
   And when an opening for a full-time classroom teacher comes up,
what happens? A 23-year-old with a bachelor's degree and lousy
grammar probably lands the job because she's lower on the pay
scale.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's like the high school principal who refused to hire
me when I was 54 and fresh out of college. His illuminating comment
to his coaching buddies was, ``Wa-aal, if we gotta' work with 'em
(women) they might as well be young and good lookin'.'' Nice guy,
huh? I was kind of annoyed with him until I figured out what his
problem was _ his brains had slid to his belly.
</P>
<P>
   If school administrations weren't constantly threatened with
penury they wouldn't have to go for the ``cheap'' as opposed to the
highly qualified. And what about the states now demanding that
teachers have in hand, or at least in sight, a master's degree?
Who's going to pay for that?
</P>
<P>
   It would seem to me that any school administrator with a
half-way intelligent board of education backing him (or her) must
be aware that a 53-year-old teacher is a wise investment, bringing
a lot more to the classroom than a piece of paper and a mini-skirt.
What about life experience? What about dignity? And what about the
fact that few 53-somethings request maternity leave?
</P>
<P>
   Gail had been looking forward to having her very own classroom,
and through the years has amassed a rather respectable collection
of reference books that she had planned on sharing with her
students. Her dream was to stimulate learning and maybe make a
difference in a few kids' lives. Now she's trying to find a used
book store to take them off her hands because she knows there's no
classroom in her future.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the teaching profession has lost a potentially
valuable member _ one with much to contribute. Of course, it has
gained a sub, at least for a while, until the lack of pay and
benefits and the daily threat of being eaten alive by a bunch of
15-year-olds loses its charm and sends yet another highly qualified
teaching candidate to work in a bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   Smart move, Bozos.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
