<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8193 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-TOOLS18-COX     01-17 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-TOOLS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Compton's strong on basics, but hits a few wrong notes
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Compton's Encyclopedia 2000 is a handsome production,
easily navigated and full of information. Not all of it is good
information, but that is true of most encyclopedias.
</P>
<P>
   Every electronic encyclopedia I've examined, and that includes
virtually all of them, has its weak points and strong points. Like
most of them, Compton's is aimed at the elementary and secondary
school student.
</P>
<P>
   More attention is paid to things these students are apt to need
than to more arcane matters. I usually check on the treatment of a
lot of arcane stuff, and I'm usually disappointed. That situation
continues with Compton's.
</P>
<P>
   Flamenco receives its usual treatment _ that which you might
expect from a modern dance scholar who has barely heard of the
stuff. There is, however, a few seconds of flamenco guitar audio.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the articles are unsigned, and thus there is no one to
blame for this sentence in the article on shooting: ``The early
marksmen on the frontier, however, competed only with rifles
because they believed that accurate shooting with pistols and
revolvers required little or no skill.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the clueless would believe such a thing, and frontier
marksmen may have been unwashed, unkempt and even unlettered, but
as a class they were scarcely clueless.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, absent this blunder, the section on
marksmanship is surprisingly long, detailed, interesting and
lacking in political innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   Every encyclopedia has a time line, but I particularly enjoyed
Compton's. It is easy to browse, can be set up in different blocks
_ years, centuries and so forth _ and is quite detailed.
</P>
<P>
   The audio portions of the encyclopedia are the most amazingly
mixed bag I've encountered yet. On the good side, there's a lot of
it. Some of it is authentic. For instance, the little portion of
Dvorak's symphony ``From the New World'' is played by an orchestra
and not a synthesizer or MIDI instrument. The caption announced
that ``you can hear the music of the black American slaves on this
segment.''
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of fact, you can't. This is the opening of the
symphony, not the ``Going Home'' portion that some argue was
inspired by spirituals.
</P>
<P>
   Mozart's ``Eine Kleine Nachtmusik'' gets orchestral treatment,
but I can't figure out what's happening in the opening theme of the
``Jupiter'' symphony; it sounds dimly like an orchestra, but
there's a piano in it. The famous ``Queen of the Night'' aria from
``Magic Flute,'' we are told, has ``some of the highest notes ever
written for soprano.'' It's a good thing for the kids that this is
pointed out, since there's no soprano to be heard. In fact, the
human voice is notably missing from all the music.
</P>
<P>
   I thought I was reasonably familiar with the work of Beethoven,
but here we are presented with something called ``Nature,'' without
opus number, played by a piano and what might be a hurdy-gurdy or
an abused cat. It is a marchlike affair, and if Beethoven wrote it
I doubt he would thank Compton's for resurrecting it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a pity that music is treated by most of the encyclopedias
in such a cavalier way, as it is one of the most important
advantages the electronic versions have over print.
</P>
<P>
   However, all this carping seems excessive when, according to the
publisher's Web site at www.shopmattel
</P>
<P>
   .com/, this two-disc encyclopedia can be ordered for $15.
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of hundred movies and animations, including
some of those dandy 360-degree rotating scenes. One of them,
startlingly, is of the High Museum in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   For the intended audience of schoolchildren intent on subjects
like geography, science, social studies, history and the like,
there is more than enough here to see them through. Compton's seems
particularly strong on modern history, and there are several
thousand links to further information on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
