 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, Jan.
18.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NORTON-ART-DONATE (Undated) _ Peter Norton, the California
software entrepreneur and his wife, Eileen, who are art collectors,
have announced that they are donating nearly 1,000 works by more
than 450 artists to 29 institutions. Most of the works are from the
1990s. In sheer numbers, this is one of the largest gifts of
contemporary art by a private donor. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   SEX-MUSEUM (Undated) _ On the list of 29 institutions receiving
art from Peter and Eileen Norton is the nascent Museum of Sex in
Manhattan. Its president and chief executive describes the intent
of the museum, which does not yet have a home, as a center for the
study of ``the history and evolution of human sexuality.'' It is to
be the first of its kind in this country. By Michael Kimmelman.
(With NORTON-ART-DONATE)
</P>
<P>
   CREATIVE-HISTORY (Undated) _ Not only have all artists
manipulated history to forge theater and cinema, the greatest of
them all, William Shakespeare, did it too. And if Shakespeare
allowed himself to invent scenes that never happened and to put
words into the mouths of historical figures who never said them,
then isn't it more or less the same thing when filmmakers do those
things today? A Critics Notebook. By Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-BOOKS-AWARDS (San Antonio, Texas) _ As the nation observed
the birthday of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., the American
Library Association announced Monday that two of the most
prestigious prizes for children's literature, the Newbery Medal and
the Coretta Scott King Author Award for excellence by
African-American writers, were both going to ``Bud, Not Buddy,'' by
Christopher Paul Curtis. By Eden Ross Lipson.
</P>
<P>
   MOZART-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ In ``Mozart: A Cultural
Biography,'' the scholar Robert W. Gutman tries to give the reader
a down-to-earth portrait of Mozart as a highly professional
musician who used his genius to assimilate and transform the
artistic currents of the day. By Michiko Kakutani.
</P>
<P>
   TV-EVEREST-REVIEW (Undated) _ Tuesday night's installment of
``Nova'' on PBS tugs you into two real-life dramas that unfolded,
75 years apart, on the frozen slopes of Mount Everest. By Ron
Wertheimer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE (Will move in `a' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTARCTICA-ROBOT (Undated) _ Humans have long ventured to
Antarctica to study and make discoveries on the icy continent. Now,
a new breed of explorer _ a metallic robot crammed with wires and
electronics _ is poised to add its name to the annals of polar
history: Nomad, the meteorite hunter, a four-wheeled machine built
by Carnegie Mellon University's Robotics Institute in Pittsburgh.
By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANTARCTICA-BIKE (Undated) _ Two bicycles designed and built
specifically for the harsh conditions of Antarctica are to undergo
formal testing at the South Pole this week, part of a program to
make life a little easier _ and perhaps a bit more fun _ for those
who spend long, dark winters at the remote outpost. By Warren E.
Leary.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-CANCER-PREVENT (Undated) _ Over the years, researchers have
found hundreds of drugs to slow the growth of cancer. But they have
found virtually nothing that can prevent cancers from forming. Now,
however, scientists at the National Cancer Institute say they have
a promising candidate, an aspirinlike drug that is commonly used to
treat arthritis pain. By accident, scientists found that such drugs
might also prevent cancer. By Gina Kolata. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INCOMPETENT-PEOPLE (Undated) _ A Cornell researcher has
found that most incompetent people do not know that they are
incompetent. In fact, people who do things badly, researchers
found, are usually supremely confident of their abilities _ more
confident, in fact, than people who do things well. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEW-SEA-CREATURES (Undated) _ Creepy things from beneath the
sea are cliches of modern exploration, but the abyss has now
produced a surprise so bizarre as to have touched off hot
international debate: tiny, mysterious, apparently living creatures
far smaller than any known bacterium _ so small as to strain the
limits on what is needed for independent life. By William J. Broad.
(With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TROPICAL-RAINS (Undated) _ Scientists at the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration are refining new methods to
chart how much rain is falling in a major tropical storm. By Robert
Saar. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EDGERTON-PHOTOS (Undated) _ Dr. Harold E. Edgerton was a
wizard of invention who changed the way people see things. The
flash of his camera opened up hidden worlds of motion as his
photographs revealed the drama hidden in the commonplace. This
month, MIT Press released a multimedia CD-ROM, ``Exploring the Art
and Science of Stopping Time: The Life and Work of Harold E.
Edgerton.'' By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MASS-HYSTERIA (Undated) _ Stampedes of anxiety can spread
rapidly among healthy people. Outbreaks have occurred around the
world since at least the 14th century. In past eras, some were
triggered by thoughts of demons, possessed states and religious
events. Nowadays, the triggers are usually fears of exposure to
hazardous substances and pollution. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FAT-DIETERS (Undated) _ As everyone around me goes on
high-protein diets, I ask a question: If these diets, waxing and
waning in popularity for nearly 140 years, are so great, why are so
many people fat? An essay by Gina Kolata.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Americans are now living about
three decades longer than they did at the start of the last
century. But for far too many older Americans, the so-called Golden
Years are tarnished by diseases that seriously undermine the
quality of those extra decades _ diseases that with tools now at
hand are usually preventable, postponable or detectable at a
curable stage. By Jane E. Brody. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPEEDSKATING (Undated) _ A novice learns to speedskate. By
Julie Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Your science questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ The Vital Signs column, with items
on fetal anemia, thumb-sucking in children and eating disorders.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-HILL-PISTONS (Undated) _ Sports of the Times column on Grant
Hill of the Pistons. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-PISTONS (Undated) _ Detroit at Knicks, 4 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NETS-76ERS (Philadelphia) _ Nets at Philadelphia, 2 p.m.
EST.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PLAYOFFS-CONTENDERS (Indianapolis) _ On Pro Football column
discussing the four teams still in the hunt. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-JETS-OWNERSHIP (Undated) _ The NFL owners will meet in New
York Tuesday to approve Robert Wood Johnson as the new Jets owner.
By Gerald Eskenazi.
</P>
<P>
   BKW-RUTGERS-CONNECTICUT (Storrs, Conn.) _ The two best teams in
the Big East meet for the first time this season. By Joe LaPointe.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
