u k BC-AIDS-EDITORIAL-COX     01-17 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-EDITORIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. frankness could help Africa
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The attention Washington has focused on the AIDS calamity in
Africa during this, the month the United States chairs the U.N.
Security Council, is long overdue.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers from the biological battlefront south of the Sahara
are staggering: 14 million people dead so far, 23.3 million
infected, 11 million children orphaned by the disease. Life
expectancies in affected countries have plunged from 60 to 40 years
within a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Health experts worry that more people may die of AIDS in
tropical Africa in the coming decade than were killed in all the
wars around the world during the entire 20th century. The United
Nations does not exaggerate when it calls this ``the worst
infectious disease catastrophe since the bubonic plague,'' which
wiped out a fourth of Europe's population during the mid-1300s.
</P>
<P>
   But no one at last week's Security Council meeting on AIDS
needed a briefing on the casualty toll. What the diplomats wanted
to hear was what the United States, the richest and most
scientifically advanced nation, was going to do to help stem this
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore announced the Clinton administration is
pledging an additional $150 million, subject to congressional
approval, for HIV screening and prevention programs and for orphan
care. That's a fraction of what the United States spends to fight
AIDS here at home, but its contribution to Africa shouldn't be
dismissed as inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS prevention measures do work. In Uganda and Senegal,
infection rates have dropped dramatically, thanks to candid
nationwide education programs.
</P>
<P>
   The more plain-speaking on this issue, the better. Gore engaged
in some of it himself in a Boston Globe interview urging African
cultural changes: the acceptance of sex education, the practice of
abstinence or of safe sex and the stigmatizing of promiscuity.
Coming from the American vice president, that's strong stuff.
African leaders too often resent frank talk on this subject, but
public awareness about how to stop the transmission of the HIV
virus is essential to their people's survival.
</P>
<P>
   Can the United States and other advanced countries do more? Yes,
there's a joint effort under way to develop an affordable AIDS
vaccine for distribution to poor nations in Africa and Asia, but
that may be years away. In the meantime, the most effective and
cheapest way to fight AIDS is to change the behaviors that
encourage its spread.
</P>
<P>
   This editorial originally appeared in The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
