<HEADER>
A8258 &Cx1f; tad-z
b f BC-COKE18-COX     01-17 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke's new president addresses upcoming changes in today's
meeting
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wall Street will be keeping an especially close eye on
Coca-Cola today as new company President Doug Daft attends his
first major board meeting since becoming a director last month.
</P>
<P>
   The board is expected to announce that Jack Stahl will become
president of the world's largest soft-drink company in April, when
Daft assumes the top spot of chairman and chief executive officer.
He'll replace M. Douglas Ivester, who is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl, 46, is a 20-year company veteran. He is currently in
charge of operations in North America and Latin America, which
account for about half of the company's revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expect the board to discuss at least two other
important issues, with announcements possible later this week or
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first board meeting where Daft and the new
management team will be presenting, reviewing and assessing the
year 2000 operating plans,'' said Andrew Conway, an analyst with
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   One key issue is whether to cut costs and how to do it. Analysts
said the company could decide to reduce the number of jobs at
corporate headquarters in Atlanta, as well as abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Daft and all the new group presidents will be
assessing what's adequate in terms of staffing and looking at where
they may be overstaffed,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said it is examining ``every aspect of
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also expect the board to discuss whether the company
should write down the value of its bottling assets in Russia, where
economic instability has hurt sales. Coke has invested between $500
million and $700 million there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were to take the charge, it sends a signal that
soft-drink growth in the Russian market seems elusive,'' Conway
said.
</P>
<P>
   By taking a write-down and charge now, analysts said, Daft could
put the bad news behind him before he assumes the top spot in
April. Essentially, any fourth-quarter charge would be on Ivester's
watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clean-up time,'' said Manny Goldman, global beverage
analyst with Merrill Lynch. ``You want to go into the new year
pristine, from a financial standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is expected to announce fourth-quarter and annual
results by the end of the month. For the fourth quarter, most
analysts are predicting earnings of 28 cents to 30 cents a share,
excluding any one-time charges. That would compare with 24 cents a
share in 1998's fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   If the company takes a write-down now, depreciation costs would
be lower in subsequent quarters. That would help boost future
earnings, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's stock closed Friday at $61.06 1/4, up 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
