u f BC-BIZMAGS18-COX     01-17 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZMAGS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS MAGAZINES: AOL-Time Warner merger draws accolades from
Business Week
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The theme that dominated the business press in 1999 shows no
sign of disappearing in the early editions of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Business Week (Jan. 24) wasted no time awarding ``men of the
century'' accolades to two high tech leaders in a new century just
a few weeks old.
</P>
<P>
   The business weekly profiles America Online Chief Executive
Steve Case and President Robert Pittman, who last week announced
AOL's purchase of Time Warner in the biggest merger ever proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the ascendence of the Internet economy were not clear
enough already, the Jan. 10 announcement . . . should be taken as
proof positive,'' says Business Week.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine contends that Case, Pittman and Time Warner Chief
Executive Gerald Levin ``have a chance to reshape the world of
information and entertainment, digital or otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, this is also Business Week's annual mutual fund
report, which rates and ranks the performances of about 3,000
funds.
</P>
<P>
   In a case of deja vu, computer pioneer Steve Jobs and Apple
Computer seem to be leading the industry again, according to a
Fortune (Jan. 31) profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every PC manufacturer is trying to copy the iMac in one way or
another,'' Jobs says of the new Apple computer.
</P>
<P>
   His objective is to link the iMac and the Internet with a new,
easy-to-use system that will provide a wide variety of free Web
services for users.
</P>
<P>
   As for the surge in new Internet companies, Jobs says the
problem is not the number of businesses, but the number of
entrepreneurs who fail to stick with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when these people sell out, even though they get fabulously
rich, they're gypping themselves out of one of the potentially most
rewarding experiences of their unfolding lives,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Upside (February), a technology publication, warns that high
tech companies can no longer be politically aloof now that the
government has finally discovered technology.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine offers a guide to the ins and outs of doing
business in Washington, including a list of ``who you need to know
in D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   A new kind of supermarket
</P>
<P>
   For some investors, online mutual fund supermarkets such as
Charles Schwab and ETrade are the greatest invention since the
salad bar. But Working Mother (February) cautions individuals to be
careful, since ``one-stop, do-it-yourself shopping isn't right for
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But for those who meet the tests, these supermarkets ``let you
help yourself to hundreds of funds from a vast, diverse array.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
