<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8275 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-PLUG-POWER-HNS &LR;      01-17 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLUG-POWER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     INVESTORS GIVE VOTE OF CONFIDENCE TO DEVELOPER OF ALTERNATIVE
POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CLAIRE HUGHES  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Plug Power, a two-year-old startup company with
no marketable product and mounting losses, has made millions for
investors and generated real buzz on Wall Street. And it's not even
a dot-com.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, which hit the street at $15 per share in
October, was trading at $55 at the close of business Friday _ a 267
percent increase. It reached a high of $79 per share Jan. 7 after
mentions in Business Week and on Microsoft Corp.'s Money Central
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Latham-based company is poised to produce the first compact,
affordable fuel cell to power homes. That is a product some company
investors and industry analysts predict will be as widespread one
day as personal computers are now. The General Electric Co.
estimates the fuel-cell market to be a ``multibillion-dollar
opportunity by 2010,'' said GE spokeswoman Janice Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the ``PG'' _ personal generator.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attention that Plug has gotten has certainly sparked
interest in the (fuel cell) sector, and probably gotten some other
people that are not publicly traded thinking about it,'' said
Samuel Brothwell, who follows the electric industry for Merrill
Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The stock is making some executives wealthier, including Plug
Power President Gary Mittleman; board director Walter Robb, a
former GE executive; and George C. McNamee, who is chairman of Plug
Power, chief executive officer of Latham-based Mechanical
Technology Inc. and co-chairman of investment banking firm First
Albany Cos., which owns a large stake in Mechanical Technology Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power was founded by Mechanical Technology, a maker of
precision instruments for industrial and aviation markets, and the
Edison Development Corp., an affiliate of Detroit Edison,
Michigan's largest electric utility. It plans to have a
dishwasher-size fuel cell on the market next year, and eventually
to sell them for $3,000 to $5,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel cells take hydrogen from another fuel source, such as
natural gas, and convert it into electricity. The result is power
that's more environmentally friendly than current sources: the only
byproducts are heat and water.
</P>
<P>
   While the technology underlying fuel cells has been around for
more than 150 years, only recently have researchers believed the
devices could be made affordable.
</P>
<P>
   Current trends in the electric industry also are making it a
good time to be a fuel-cell developer. Nationally, the $220 billion
industry is undergoing deregulation, which means that consumers
will increasingly be comparing power options rather than just
signing up with their local utility monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   And the need for dependable power has become more critical as
homes and businesses become ever more reliant on computer
technology _ increasing the pain of a short blackout from mere
nuisance to minor catastrophe, Brothwell said.
</P>
<P>
   That has more consumers and businesses looking for backup power
sources.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, fuel cells could be cost-effective in 16
to 17 states where electricity rates are high, according to a
report on Plug Power from investment banking firm Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   Internationally, the market may even be wider, Merrill Lynch's
Brothwell said. In countries where the electric grid is spotty,
people and businesses in poorly covered areas may be willing to pay
a premium for fuel cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real opportunity is perhaps outside the U.S.,'' Brothwell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanical Technology and Edison Development were not the only
ones to see this burgeoning market when they established Plug Power
in June 1997. But the company is seen as the most likely to get a
residential fuel cell to market first, something seen as critical
to its success. Canadian-based Ballard Power Systems is closer to
getting a fuel cell into cars. Spokane, Wash.-based Avista Labs is
working on a similar product as Plug Power's, but Goldman Sachs
believes the company has no distribution partner.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power's distribution partner, on the other hand, is GE,
whose brand and powerful marketing muscle span the globe. Brothwell
said the partnership gives Plug Power ``instant credibility'' among
both investors and future customers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GE Power Systems of Schenectady, which has been broadening its
range of power equipment under the division's president, Robert
Nardelli, looked at other fuel-cell developers before investing in
Plug Power, Smith said. Plug Power's proximity to GE Power Systems'
headquarters and GE's Research and Development Center in Niskayuna
were part of the reason the multinational company chose the Latham
company, Smith said. But the main reason was that it appeared to be
ahead of competitors in its likelihood of getting a new appliance
in the hands of consumers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   GE invested $37.5 million in the company, for a 12 percent
stake, according to Goldman Sachs. Nardelli also joined Plug
Power's board.
</P>
<P>
   Another Plug Power strength mentioned by investors and analysts
is its management team's ability to combine technological know-how
with a solid sense of the market. Unlike some scientifically
oriented companies, Plug Power has always had an eye on what
consumers would want, and has developed demonstration models even
as it continues to refine its research.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came up with a desire of what they wanted to have when
they were finished, and then they are taking the technology and
developing it to meet the constraints of the marketplace,'' said
Lee Stewart, president of the energy transportation services unit
at Southern California Gas Co., which invested $7.5 million in Plug
Power last April.
</P>
<P>
   The company has stocked its board with prominent business and
government leaders, like Nardelli, Robb, Detroit Edison Chairman
Anthony F. Earley Jr. and retired Army Gen. John M. Shalikashvili,
former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   The management team, led by former Edison Development Corp.
executive Mittleman, does face some challenges in merging its
high-tech vision with marketplace realities.
</P>
<P>
   Plug Power's price projections rely on reduced production costs
and increased demand for its fuel cells over time. When its fuel
cell hits the market next year, it could cost $7,000 to $10,000,
according to Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the predicted demand, the company also will have to
change its primary focus from research to manufacturing. With that
will come a rapid increase in staff at a company that has already
grown since June 1997 from 22 to more than 325 employees.
</P>
<P>
   It also has some technological hurdles, not all within its
control. While Plug Power may get its fuel cells to market, those
operating on natural gas or propane also require a processor that
separates the hydrogen from other components of the fuel. The
company is working with developers of such processors.
</P>
<P>
   And it will likely continue to post losses _ and need more cash
to keep operating. Goldman Sachs estimates the company's losses,
already topping $30 million, will pile up through 2004 and that
Plug Power will need another $400 million in funding by then.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts watching the company nonetheless believe it has an
excellent chance of meeting these challenges in an industry that
will become increasingly prominent in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   That certainly has some investors pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit and watch and we're pleasantly surprised that the
market is taking notice,'' Stewart said. ``It's real fun to
watch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
