<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KILLER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SENSE OF INEVITABILITY AT THURSTON HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE KILLER AT THURSTON HIGH 
Produced by: Michael Kirk, Miri Navasky and Karen O'Connor 
On: PBS 
Date: Tuesday at 10 p.m. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stated premise of the engrossing ``Frontline'' report, ``The
Killer at Thurston High,'' is that Kip Kinkel, the Oregon boy who
in 1998 killed his parents and then gunned down scores of
schoolmates, wasn't a conspicuously troubled kid. The narration
introduces the chronicle as an account of a life of promise
nurtured in a comforting community by loving parents.
``Understanding what happened inside that family,'' we are told,
``takes us on a journey to an apparently unremarkable past.''
</P>
<P>
   But this really isn't so.
</P>
<P>
   What we see and hear in this thoroughly reported and skillfully
produced 90-minute portrait of Kip Kinkel reveals something quite
different. The substance of this deeply probing reconstruction of
his early years is at odds with, and far smarter than, the often
simple-minded narration. Look closely enough, the documentary seems
to say implicitly, and you will perceive signs of a very troubled
youngster long before his explosive despair led to patricide,
matricide, the bloody shooting murders of two Thurston High
schoolmates, and the maiming of several others.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the picture that emerges is of a family startlingly out
of balance: on one side, the parents, both widely respected high
school Spanish teachers, and their popular and accomplished
daughter Kristin; on the other, the dyslexic, lonely, gun-obsessed
son who hoarded books on bomb-making and occasionally got into
trouble with the law. What gives this film dramatic power is, in
fact, the darkening sense of inevitability that develops as it
reveals telling facets of Kip's boyhood and adolescence, especially
his painfully difficult relationship with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kinkel, says a colleague, was a legendary teacher, even a
showman. Also seen as stern and ``a bit of an autocrat,'' he was an
accomplished athlete who put a high premium on physical prowess. In
a clip from a Kinkel home movie, he praises his daughter's
gymnastic feats, then suggests the younger Kip do a cartwheel
himself. On the videotape he announces that Kip, who falters, needs
to work harder. It seems that Bill, and sometimes his wife Faith,
pushed and needled Kip to accomplish things he didn't have the
tools to master. Through connections with the coach, Bill made his
reluctant 120-pound son play on the high school football team.
</P>
<P>
   Kip's mother had to prevail on her husband to allow Kip to get
psychotherapy. And the therapist _ notwithstanding an unfortunate
interest in guns that he shared with Kip _ diagnosed ``a major
depressive disorder'' and presribed Prozac. He also suggested that
Bill Kinkel ``lighten up'' on his son.
</P>
<P>
   The point isn't, finally, that Bill Kinkel is responsible for
Kip's homicidal behavior, but ``The Killer at Thurston High''
clearly implies that the father's detachment, displeasure, and
shame helped fuel Kip's self-loathing and churning fury. ``I am
always alone . . . I hate myself for what I have become,'' the boy
wrote in a journal to which the ``Frontline'' producers were given
access. This, along with an eerie police videotape showing the
murdered parents and the police department's audiotaped interview
with Kinkel after the school massacre, as well as numerous
interviews with colleagues and family friends, lend the film
urgency, specificity, and the texture of reality.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently no one saw Kip's writings, which expressed pleas for
help and an overwhelming desire to kill people. And he ammassed the
means _ an enormous cache of rifles, pistols, and knives _ but,
remarkably, no one saw the weapons either.
</P>
<P>
   In its way, this resourceful, real-life ``Frontline'' tells a
tale as strange and dark as ``American Beauty,'' with its
superficially placid family seething with explosive problems. But
as strong as it is, and as valuable for its insights into the mind
and background of a young mass murderer, the film would have been
better without its hokey-sounding and openly editorial narration.
</P>
<P>
   It states, for example, that ``those who loved (Kip) believed
they were making the right choices'' and ``still, they could not
keep him from slipping away.''
</P>
<P>
   Such glib presumption doesn't belong in a documentary as
otherwise complex and unsettling as this.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
