<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-COMPETITION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL CLIBURN PIANO COMPETITION ROLLS OUT NEW RULES FOR
2001
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The upcoming version of Fort Worth's Cliburn Competition in 2001
will present the most drastic changes that the world's most
prestigious piano contest has undergone since its founding in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest change is in the judging procedure, which will lead
to the possibility of more than one gold medal being awarded. Under
the new procedure, ranking will be determined by the awarding of
points from 1 to 25, rather than the old yes-no voting system. If
the two top competitors in the final round are within a close
range, yet to be determined, both will be awarded the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Musicians at the top level are not better than one another,
they are different from one another,'' Cliburn Foundation executive
director Richard Rodzinski said recently. ``The small differences
in points assigned to them may be statistically insignificant.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodzinski discussed the possible changes with members of the
Cliburn's international advisory committee, including pianists,
prominent teachers, presenters, past jurors, past winners, music
critics and directors of other competitions. The one change that
drew the most reservation and questioning was the possibility of
awarding more than one gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference from past competitions will be the complete
change of location from Ed Landreth Auditorium on the Texas
Christian University campus and the Fort Worth Convention Center to
Bass Performance Hall, where all events of the competition will now
be held. Because of the smaller size of the new hall, each of the
six finalists will perform his or her final program of two
concertos twice, in order to accommodate the large audience
expected for the finals.
</P>
<P>
   The three top winners will each receive a cash prize of $20,000,
further reflecting the philosophy of equality at the top. Because
of the huge demand for Cliburn medalists and finalists on
performance series around the world, and because of the need for a
less hectic schedule for the medalists, the Cliburn Foundation will
not present the gold medalist in recital at Carnegie Hall as part
of the prize.
</P>
<P>
   In another significant change, rather than commissioning a
single work from one composer, a committee of 25 American music
professionals will nominate American composers who will be asked to
submit piano solo works; up to five of these works will be sent to
the competitors. The work selected most often for performance in
the semifinal round will receive a grand prize for composition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to encourage the creation of music that meets the
approval of performers,'' Rodzinski said.
</P>
<P>
   Conductor James Conlon will return to conduct the Fort Worth
Symphony Orchestra and Fort Worth Chamber Orchestra in the final
round; the Takacs String Quartet, which has not appeared at the
competition before, will accompany competitors in the chamber music
section of the semifinal round.
</P>
<P>
   As in the 1997 competition, a live screening jury will hear
applicants perform in sites around the world before advancing
approximately 30 pianists to compete in Fort Worth in May and June.
</P>
<P>
   The main competition will be broadcast live on the Internet,
possibly in video format, though the technical possibilities have
not yet been fully settled.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, the competition will be limited to serious
pianists between the ages of 18 and 30.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for the 2001 Van Cliburn International Piano Competition
will go on sale in late summer of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
