<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NFL DRAFT IS NEXT STOP FOR STRUGGLING 49ERS  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Deep into the divisional round of the playoffs
and with the added intrigue of five head-coaching vacancies around
the league, what better time to speculate on something that won't
happen for another three months, the NFL draft?
</P>
<P>
   We thought you'd agree.
</P>
<P>
   The draft is the subject of much interest hereabouts because the
49ers own the third pick overall. Whether they will use it is
another matter altogether because of general manager Bill Walsh's
penchant for trading down to acquire more picks.
</P>
<P>
   Old Trader Bill could go either way on April 15. The 49ers need
an impact player on defense in the worst way, but they also need
help at several positions. Namely, cornerback, defensive end,
offensive tackle and quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Cerrato, fired by Walsh when he took over as GM a year
ago, is now in position to help the 49ers. Now player personnel
director of the Washington Redskins, Cerrato has three first-round
picks to use or offer in trade.
</P>
<P>
   He's proposed a deal to his old team that would give Washington
the 49ers' No. 3 pick in exchange for the Redskins' 12th and 24th
picks later in the first round. It might be an attractive offer to
Walsh because the 49ers, always jammed up tight against the salary
cap, wouldn't have to give the 12th or 24th pick as big a signing
bonus as they would No.3.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal goes through, it would give the Redskins the second
and third selections in the round after Cleveland picks No.1. If
the Browns go for Florida State wide receiver/kick returner Peter
Warrick to jazz up their offense, the 'Skins would then be in
position to take both of Penn State's defensive gems, end Courtney
Brown and linebacker LaVar Arrington.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they won the NFC East, the Redskins are deficient on
defense, as are the 49ers. San Francisco finished 28th in total
defense. Washington was 30th, ahead of only Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, the Heisman Trophy winner might
not be the first running back chosen. Wisconsin's Ron Dayne is a
limited talent who would do well playing for a slug-it-out offense
like Kansas City's or Pittsburgh's. Alabama's Shaun Alexander
projects as a better all-around running back than Dayne.
</P>
<P>
   ``You draft a guy like that and you need to have a pounding-type
offense,'' Browns VP Dwight Clark said of the Great Dayne. ``He'll
be a first-round pick. I'm not exactly sure how high yet. He's a
big, powerful guy with great feet.
</P>
<P>
   He certainly can be very successful in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 49ers to be successful in this new century of ours, they
must do the draft right, whether they stand pat at No.3 or trade it
for more picks. This is a team that needs quality and quantity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1646EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
