<HEADLINE>
&HT;     S.F. BOAT SHOW BLENDS THE NEW WITH THE OLD _ THE REALLY OLD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM STIENSTRA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN Francisco _ The biggest toy store ever assembled opened its
doors on Friday, but hidden away in the back are the real
treasures.
</P>
<P>
   The toy store, in this case, is the San Francisco Sports and
Boat Show at the Cow Palace, renovated this year with 1,000 new
boats, hundreds of motors and gear in eight halls, along with halls
featuring adventure travel, fishing and golf.
</P>
<P>
   But the real treasure is not the new but the old, an exhibit of
18 classic wooden boats, some of the finest and most beautiful
crafts of the past 100 years. They include boats by Chris-Craft and
Garwood, several trimmed in mahogany, all oiled and polished,
complete with the old inboard engines.
</P>
<P>
   These are the classic luxury ``motorboats'' of the 1940s and
'50s that became world-famous at Lake Tahoe and San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow it feels just right. Just as Harley-Davidson has had
tremendous success developing retro models, perhaps the boating
industry will take the clue and someone will build a boat that has
all the modern techno goodies, but is made out of wood with classic
looks and lines. A few canoe manufacturers have tried this already
and sell all they make, despite the higher cost.
</P>
<P>
   There haven't been wood boats at the Sports and Boat Show for
more than 25 years, so many visitors will have the chance to see a
classic mahogany Chris-Craft for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   These are blue-ribbon examples, better than showroom new. Even
the engines have been polished.
</P>
<P>
   The show opened Friday for a 10-day run, and the first thing you
see in the lobby is for youngsters, the Tommy Smothers Yo-Yo
School. At first I thought this was ridiculous, after all, Yo-Yos
at a sports show, right? But with champion Yo-Yo guys demonstrating
their amazing tricks and skills, hey, everybody watches.
</P>
<P>
   The floor of the main arena is filled with boats, banners and
engines. Yamaha managed to inveigle the top spot at the head of the
main arena, showing off its full line of new 4-cycle outboards. The
new low-emission 4-cycle outboards are the big talk of the show,
especially as some lakes prohibit 2-cycle motors, and all the major
outboard manufactures showed up this year: Honda, Mercury, Mariner,
Johnson/Evinrude, Suzuki and Yamaha.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the main arena is a 46-foot Hunter
sailboat/yacht, the Queen of the Show, for sale for a
quarter-million simoleons. The way a high-roller was looking at it
on Friday, it might be sold by the end of the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Its mast is so high that it appears to be poking a hole into the
stratosphere. According to show manager Tom Randall, the yacht was
transported into the main arena on Tuesday, with the mast brought
in separately on a big rig, lifted by a 45-ton crane into position,
then locked, bolted and rigged.
</P>
<P>
   Gone this year are the speedboat hall, the benched dogs and
ornate gun displays. New is golf, with an opportunity for visitors
to play nine holes in a miniature golf course. And back is Howard
Arneson of San Rafael, Calif., and his 175-mph jet boat,
occasionally seen ripping across San Francisco Bay and out to the
ocean.
</P>
<P>
   A fishing tackle supermarket is being operated by Fisherman's
Warehouse (can you believe on Friday I bought yet another fishing
rod), and nearby is a 40-foot aquarium stocked with fish from the
Delta. Out through the door is the Fishing Seminar Theater, with
four seminars a day, highlighted by Barry Canevaro on fishing the
Delta for striped bass and sturgeon.
</P>
<P>
   I will be closely watching the prices of what dealers call,
``the family package,'' that is, boat, trailer and motor, ready to
go. Typically by the end of the weekend, one dealer will come up
with a package that sells like hotcakes. I'll be looking, then
reporting back on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
