<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPEEDSKATING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPEED SKATING: GO FAST, TURN LEFT, NO BRAKES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich . )   (Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JULIE WALSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skating single-file only inches apart from one another, all
perfectly in sync, a group of 10 skaters zips past me. ``Track!''
someone yells as the group approaches the turn. That's speed
skating etiquette warning all slower skaters to move out of their
way.
</P>
<P>
   I am one of about 25 skaters warming up for the Flushing Meadows
Speedskating Club's practice at the World's Fair ice rink in
Flushing Meadow Park, Queens. The club, as well as speed skating,
are two of New York's best kept secrets.
</P>
<P>
   It's my fourth session on speed skates. I'm not as fast or as
graceful as the others, but I'm focusing on my form and technique.
Several friendly, experienced skaters, along with the club's coach,
have told me just to work on basics: skating low with knees bent,
leaning over at the waist; centering body weight over the middle to
rear of the blades; shifting hips from side-to-side; skating on the
edges of the blades; and pushing each skate sideways rather than
backward.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time since I started skating that my edges are
finally gripping the ice _ a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Two of my cycling teammates had discovered speed skating and
kept telling me what a blast it was.
</P>
<P>
   All I knew about speed skating were the names Eric and Beth
Heiden, Dan Jansen and Bonnie Blair. From watching the Olympics, I
knew they skated fast and won lots of Olympic gold medals.
</P>
<P>
   Although I had never tried this oldest form of ice skating, I
grew up in northern Michigan doing figure and hockey skating in our
backyard, on frozen lakes and secluded ponds surrounded by sand
dunes. Although some 14 years have passed since I last wore skates,
I thought speed skating would be exciting, and a new and different
way to maintain fitness during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   With speeds up to 35 miles per hour, speed skating is the
fastest self-propelled sport. In speed skating, there are two
disciplines: long (metric) track and short track. Long track is a
battle against the clock as two competitors skate in individual
lanes on a 400-meter oval. Long-track skating dates to the 1800s in
the United States, and was one of the most popular sports at the
first Winter Olympics, in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are only a handful of long-track ovals in the
United States, most speed skaters skate short track. Short-track
racing is done on a 111-meter track set up on a standard hockey
rink. Short track is a pack event in which four to six skaters
start on a line and the first to cross the finish line wins.
Because a hockey rink is all that's required, short-track skating
is becoming popular in Southern states like Florida, Georgia and
California.
</P>
<P>
   I was trying short-track racing.
</P>
<P>
   After lacing my boots, I stepped gingerly onto the ice and
wobbled along with my blades slipping and sliding beneath my feet.
I wore tights, a thermal top, vest, cap, helmet and gloves. Many of
the more experienced skaters wore Lycra skin suits or bike-racing
garb with knee pads, shin guards and neck guards.
</P>
<P>
   My first night, about 20 skaters, ranging in age from 10 to
mid-70s, were on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   At my second and third sessions, I worked more on technique. I
found the crossover turns most challenging. Because you always
skate in a counter-clockwise fashion, the turns require crossing
the right leg over the left in a series of strokes. While
maintaining your speed and focus, the crossover requires leaning
into the turn, hips first with left shoulder dropped, while looking
beyond the turn. Mastering the crossover is the crucial element of
short-track skating.
</P>
<P>
   At my fourth session, a former Korean national team skater gave
me some pointers. His skating was mesmerizing: long, graceful
strokes that appeared effortless. Holding me steady, he bent my
legs until I was in a super-crouched position, then lifted one leg
at a time and moved it slowly through the speed skating stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In this position, the quad of the balancing leg has to support
the entire body weight for several seconds. ``That,'' he said, ``is
speed skating.'' He also had me follow him around the track several
times, keeping my right hand tucked behind my back, only swinging
my left arm back and forth. This helped me keep my shoulders steady
and parallel to the ice rather than moving them side-to-side. These
simple tips improved my skating tremendously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
