<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BLOODLESS-COX     01-17 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOODLESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bloodless surgical techniques catching on
 &HT;    (EDS: With box at bottom of file.)
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Spiritually, Sharon Googer was a vibrant woman, a
Jehovah's Witness who prayed every day. But physically, Googer, 43,
was dying.
</P>
<P>
   A virus had attacked her heart's lining, causing symptoms
including nausea and shortness of breath. ``It was almost as if (my
heart) was encrusted in cement,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But her doctors could offer no assurance that she would survive
the needed operation without a blood transfusion. And Googer
refused to veer from her religious belief barring the use of stored
blood. That left her with two options: prayer and research.
</P>
<P>
   Both worked, she said. Googer discovered a new bloodless
surgical program that began earlier this month at Atlanta Medical
Center. The program uses a combination of drugs, surgical
techniques and special equipment to reduce the amount of blood lost
during surgery and hence the need for blood transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   Within six days, Googer was recuperating at home, healthy in
body and soul.
</P>
<P>
   But bloodless surgery offers potential benefits beyond those
relating to religious requirements. As scientists track more
blood-borne illnesses and hospitals struggle with dwindling blood
supplies, the technique is gaining favor with both patients and
health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 there were only a handful of bloodless surgery centers
in the nation; now there are almost 100. And those who run the
programs say that between one-fourth and one-half of the patients
using them are not there for religious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is catching attention on a global scale,'' said Irene
Kopen, co-founder of the National Association for Bloodless
Medicine and Surgery at St. Vincent's Hospital in Cleveland. ``The
general public now knows the risk of transfusion. And they want to
avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some hospitals have been using some bloodless techniques and
equipment for years. ``Most contemporary surgeons make every effort
to preserve blood rather than lose it,'' explained Dr. Stephen M.
Barnett, chief of surgery at Piedmont Hospital in Atlanta. ``And
that does not require a special program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've put together an infrastructure that allows patients to
do one-stop shopping,'' said Dr. Michael Smith, a cardiothoracic
surgeon who performs bloodless surgeries at several Atlanta
hospitals. ``Not only does the program offer all the drugs and
equipment needed, but they have the teams that are committed to
this.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a key element to the success of a bloodless surgical
program, because there is always the risk that a patient could die
without a blood transfusion, Smith said. In some hospitals,
operating rooms have turned into battlegrounds as doctors argue
among themselves about whether to override patients' requests for
no blood transfusions in order to save their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might have a surgeon who's willing to see it through
(without a transfusion), but the anesthesiologist who isn't. Or
vice versa,'' explained Smith. ``In this program, everyone is
committed to the patient's wishes.'' Most operations already have
evolved into less bloody affairs than they once were, a result of
new technologies. Laparoscopic procedures have eliminated the need
for large incisions that might require a transfusion. Also, new
surgeon's tools have greatly reduced bleeding. Harmonic scalpels,
which use vibrations to cut and clot blood; electrocautery, which
burns and seals vessels as it cuts; and gamma knives, which use
radiation to repair problems such as brain tumors without
incisions, are all increasingly common.
</P>
<P>
   But some procedures still routinely require transfusions. Trauma
cases, such as car accidents, gunshot wounds and broken bones,
often need transfusions. And traditionally, open heart surgery has
required about one or two pints of blood, and hip surgery has
needed about four pints.
</P>
<P>
   If a patient must have this kind of care, bloodless surgery
becomes more complex.
</P>
<P>
   Often doctors will use a ``cell saver,'' a device that recycles
a patient's own blood that is lost during surgery, collecting and
cleaning it before returning it to the patient through an
intravenous tube. A host of drugs might also be prescribed in the
weeks before surgery, most notably synthetic erythropoietin, which
stimulates the body to produce more blood. This can protect a
patient from needing a transfusion to replace blood lost during the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, doctors will take steps while operating to reduce
bleeding. Often that includes such measures as lowering the
temperature of the operating room and changing the angle of the
patient's position. In bloodless heart surgery, for example, Smith
said he tilts the operating table by as much as 45 degrees,
lowering the patient's head. This, he has learned, helps the body
maintain proper blood pressure without the need for a heart-lung
machine, which increases the likelihood of transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more meticulous,'' he said. ``But minimally invasive
heart surgery works _ and the patients fare very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are also examining whether fewer transfusions result
in better outcomes:
</P>
<P>
   _ A 1999 study published in The New England Journal of Medicine
found that critically ill patients who received fewer units of
blood had a better chance of survival than younger, less ill
patients who did receive transfusions. The study was conducted on a
group of 838 patients in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   _ A University of Rochester Medical Center study found that
transfusions weaken recipients' immune systems, leaving them two to
five times more likely to suffer postoperative infections.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Journal of the American Medical Association reported in
1998 that a decade-long study concluded that transfusions neither
increased nor decreased morbidity in patients who underwent surgery
for hip fractures. Thus, the researchers said, doctors should
``reconsider'' whether transfusion is advisable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what caught the attention of the doctors,''
said Kopen, of the bloodless medicine association. ``They started
noticing that their patients were doing better when they underwent
bloodless surgery. Their hospital stays were shorter and their
recovery was faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor was the AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jehovah's Witnesses had been demanding transfusion-free
surgery for more than half a century, it wasn't until AIDS erupted
in the 1980s, and the AIDS virus was transmitted through blood
transfusions, that the demand was sytematically addressed. ``We
were a bunch of idiot radicals before the epidemic,'' said Vince
Velluci, chairman of the Jehovah's Witnesses hospital liaison
committee in Atlanta. ``But AIDS hit, and suddenly everyone stood
up and took notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1981 and 1998, almost 5,300 men and more than 4,000
women contracted the AIDS virus through transfusions, according to
the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, health workers were discovering an alphabet
soup of strains of hepatitis, a viral infection linked to blood
products. At one point, they worried only about Hepatitis A, B and
C, but new strains are constantly cropping up, according to the
CDC.
</P>
<P>
   The risk remains low. Because of better testing and screening of
donors, the risk of getting AIDS is about 1 in a million and the
risk of getting hepatitis C is about 1 in 100,000. And a new
technique called nucleic acid testing, or NAT, currently in FDA
review, should lower the risk even further, said Karen Eisele,
spokeswoman of blood services for the Southern region of the
American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   But as testing becomes more sophisticated, fewer donors are
acceptable. And that's led to chronic shortages in blood supplies
here and across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   And blood is not cheap. Hospitals pay about $500 for each blood
unit _ which is little more than a pint _ making bloodless surgery
a far more economical option.
</P>
<P>
   The result: Many hospitals are seeking ways to conserve blood.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, 4 million patients receive transfusions each year,
according to the American Association of Blood Banks. But the
amount of transfusions has dropped by more than 6 percent from 1989
to 1992, according to the Center for Blood Research in Boston. And,
the center said, the trend is continuing, although newer figures
were not available.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, patients have started banking their own blood for
operations _ called autologous transfusions. But that is still not
an option for Jehovah's Witnesses, who believe they cannot accept
blood _ even their own _ if circulation is stopped.
</P>
<P>
   And that has forced physicians and manufacturers to become more
creative, said Melvin Satterfield, co-ordinator for the Atlanta
Medical Center's bloodless surgery program.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to come up with alternatives,'' said Satterfield, who
is also one of the 40,000 members of Jehovah's Witnesses in
Atlanta. ``And so far, it's resulted in better medicine for us.''
</P>
<P>
   BLOOD BOX:
</P>
<P>
   If you are interested in bloodless surgery, there are several
questions that you should ask yourself and your physician, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   _ Determine how committed you are to bloodless surgery. Perhaps
you are only interested in banking your own blood. Or you might
want to use the drugs to pump up the volume of blood before surgery
or request a ``cell saver,'' which conserves and recirculates the
blood lost in surgery.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discuss with your physician how comfortable he or she is with
bloodless surgery. Find out what experience or education they have
had with such surgery. Also make sure they have discussed your
wishes with the other members of the surgical team.
</P>
<P>
   _ Learn more about it on your own. Several Web sites explain the
basics, including the Bloodless Surgery and Medicine Institute at
www.bsmi.net or the University of Medicine and Dentistry of New
Jersey's bloodless surgical program at www.umdnj.edu/univhosp/. And
if you want to know why a Jehovah's Witness refuses blood in
operations, check out the ``Medical Care and Blood'' section of
www.watchtower.org.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
