<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-6     01-17 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-675(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS RENEW THEIR ASSAULT ON GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Map  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOZDOK, Russia _ The Russian military on Monday renewed its
assault on Grozny as the Kremlin sought to bring its siege of the
Chechen capital to a speedy and decisive end.
</P>
<P>
   Under clearing skies, Russian aircraft and artillery bombarded
the city in a furious effort to soften up the rebel resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Russian aircraft carried out a record number of attacks on
Grozny. On Monday, the city was aflame, with plumes of smoke rising
into the sky. Russian television showed the ruins of a red brick
house where a sniper had been positioned, vivid testimony to the
firepower now raining down on the city.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second major Russian offensive against the Islamic
rebels in the city, who have stubbornly refused to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   The first began in December, as Russian forces sought to seize
the city by early January. That Russian attack faltered after young
and sometimes inexperienced Russian troops were bloodied in
firefights with battle-hardened rebels, who hid in cellars and
among the ruins of the city. Bad weather also hampered air and
artillery strikes.
</P>
<P>
   As the fighting inside the city reached a stalemate, Russian
authorities announced a pause in their barrage against Grozny,
asserting that they wanted to respect Russian Orthodox Christmas
and the end of Ramadan, the Muslim religious holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Now Russian troops have regrouped and decided to try again.
Touting the new offensive, Lt. Gen. Gennadi Troshev, the deputy
commander of Russian troops in the Northern Caucasus region, said
there would be ``radical changes'' in the strategy for taking the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Troshev did not say what the changes would be. But they seem to
involve a sharp escalation in air strikes and artillery barrages
even though the city is still occupied by thousands of civilians.
After weeks of boasting that it would conduct a commando style
operation to grab back the city, Russia now seems to have turned to
brute force to capture the Chechen capital.
</P>
<P>
   Official Russian government estimates of the number of civilians
trapped in Grozny range as high as 40,000. Many of the civilians
are simply too old, too injured or too frightened to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Chechnya's civilians has been a major concern for
Western governments and organizations, including the Council of
Europe, which has hinted it might expel Russia if it did not temper
its assault on areas where civilians reside.
</P>
<P>
   David Russell-Johnston, the president of the council's
parliamentary delegation, met in Moscow on Monday with Russia's
acting president, Vladimir Putin, and other senior Russian
officials to urge a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expressed the views that have already been set out by the
assembly in resolutions concerning a cease-fire, concerning
negotiations, concerning the free movement of refugees and access
to humanitarian organizations,'' Russell-Johnston told reporters
after a meeting with Yegor Stroyev, the speaker of Russia's upper
house of parliament. ``We are looking for some way of ending the
conflict ... soon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell-Johnston received a polite reception from Putin, but
there was no indication that the Russians were interested in his
proposals. The Kremlin arranged for him to conduct a fact-finding
mission in the North Caucasus just as it did in December for Knut
Vollebaek, the chairman of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, whose appeals for a cease-fire were also
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the international community to show an understanding
of our position, by relying on facts about the real situation from
truthful information and not from propaganda,'' Putin said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Grozny was the scene of some of the Russian military's bitterest
setbacks in the first war in Chechnya, which lasted from 1994 to
1996 and resulted in the de facto independence of the breakaway
republic. Humiliated by their defeat, Russia's military commanders
have set a high priority on taking it back.
</P>
<P>
   Russian generals have refused to set a deadline for capturing
the city, but Nikolai Koshman, the Russian vice prime minister who
administers the Russian-controlled areas of Chechnya, said in an
interview that he plans to move to Grozny by early February.
</P>
<P>
   A fighter under the command of Bislan Gantamirov, the Chechen
paramilitary leader who is allied with Moscow, said his forces
planned to operate in the city within two weeks. But similar boasts
have been frustrated in the past by determined rebel resistance.
</P>
<P>
   There are no reliable figures on the number of rebel fighters in
Grozny. Estimates by the Russian military have varied from 500 to
several thousand.
</P>
<P>
   Though they are vastly outnumbered, the rebels have proved to be
tough foes, fighting from fortified positions in the city. Russian
casualties have climbed substantially as a result.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military still insists that it does not plan to
``storm'' Grozny, a phrase that recalls the disastrous Russian
assault on the city at the start of the first Chechen war when a
Russian armored column raced to the center of the city and was
wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the military describes its Grozny operation as an
``activization of military actions.''
</P>
<P>
   There does not appear to be anything subtle about the new
Russian tactics, however. When Troshev was asked last week why
Russian forces might be more successful this time, he smiled and
pointed at the clearing skies as Russian warplanes streaked
overhead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
