<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8304 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-ANTARCTICA-BIKE-N     01-17 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-ANTARCTICA-BIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BIKES BEING DEVELOPED FOR USE AT THE SOUTH POLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(HLW) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine trying to do wheelies on a bicycle at the frigid South
Pole. Depending on one's point of view, this would take extreme
biking up _ or down _ to a new level.
</P>
<P>
   Such an idea is no longer fantasy. Two bicycles designed and
built specifically for the harsh conditions of Antarctica are to
undergo formal testing at the South Pole this week, part of a
program to make life a little easier _ and perhaps a bit more fun _
for those who spend long, dark winters at the remote outpost.
</P>
<P>
   Called the Ice Prowler, this custom model bicycle was engineered
and built by advanced design students at the Art Institute of
Pittsburgh. Students at the institute have worked on projects for
six years in collaboration with the Center for Astrophysical
Research in Antarctica, or CARA, a consortium of universities that
builds and operates a variety of telescopes on the continent.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the student projects has been on ways to make life
better for those working on Antarctica. After consulting with
researchers and technicians who winter there, through months of
perpetual darkness and cold, students have designed a two-piece
glove that keeps researchers' hands warm while they work with small
objects and a mask that warms inhaled air while venting moisture
that could otherwise fog goggles.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen M. Butler, head of the graphics design program at the
institute, is in Antarctica to test the bicycles, where he will
evaluate their traction, control and ease of use. He is to use
specialized testing criteria developed by students, including a
heart-rate monitor to check a rider's exertion and comfort, to
examine the performance of each bike on snow and ice. Butler said
he also hoped to make a satellite telephone call to the class so
that students could participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the tests, I hope to spend most of my time talking to
people and seeing how they actually work and live at the South
Pole,'' Butler said before leaving on his trip. ``I hope to come
back with ideas for new projects we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   People stationed on Antarctica have tried bicycles before, but
with limited success. Conventional mountain bikes with
2.5-inch-wide tires work during the summer season on well-traveled
paths but bog down in the winter's drifting snows and oppressive
cold. Winter temperatures averaging 76 degrees below zero also
result in plastic parts' cracking and cables' breaking, disabling
brakes and gearshifts.
</P>
<P>
   A practical reason for having bicycles on Antarctica is to help
staff members at the university consortium's observatories, which
are three-quarters of a mile from the main station. The telescopes
are isolated in an area known as the Dark Sector to keep light
pollution and stray electromagnetic radiation from fouling their
observations. Workers walk to and from the observatories several
times a day at about 3 or 4 miles an hour; bicycles could triple
this speed.
</P>
<P>
   The challenging Ice Prowler project has taken two years between
conception and putting two bikes on Antarctic ice. The students
designed and tested new types of frames, wheels, gears, seats and
other components until settling on the best parts for a
low-maintenance bicycle that could be used by people clad in
cumbersome cold-weather gear riding outside in extreme
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   The students settled on a squat-looking design built around
aluminum mountain bike frames donated by Hanebrink Bicycles of Big
Bear Lake, Calif. They chose high, wide handlebars and
stubby-looking metal wheels fitted with vulcanized rubber golf-cart
tires with treads cut in a special V-shaped pattern. The bikes also
have a simple, single-speed gear system, quick-release switches
that let gloved hands easily adjust seat and handlebar height, and
a metal, disc brake operated by a handlebar lever
</P>
<P>
   Bill Farrell, an industrial design instructor who supervised the
project, said the students tested other types of tires, including a
hollow, molded resin model and one made of steel mesh that worked
like a rolling snowshoe. ``These tires were more exotic and
expensive, but not necessary,'' he said, ``The off-the-shelf option
seems good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The group also tested several designs for seats that would not
compress insulation in the rider's clothing, resulting in a cold
bottom. One bike has a plastic-shell seat covering a foam interior
while the other has a sculptured, solid wood seat that Farrell said
worked surprisingly well in preliminary tests.
</P>
<P>
   After the trials, the researchers will leave one or both
bicycles at the pole for the coming winter season and hope to send
a refined production model that has all the bugs worked out next
year. This type of cycle has commercial potential, for ski resorts
or for winter cross-country riding, that could give students the
added experience of bringing a new product to market, Farrell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real value of this is the experience the kids are getting
out of it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
