<SLUG> BC-SCI-CANCER-FAMILIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY SHARES ITS HISTORY OF DISEASE TO HELP OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Sidebar with SCI-CANCER-PREVENT)  
 (bl)  
 By GINA KOLATA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   People with familial ademomatous polyposis, or FAP, have had
long, sad family histories. Relative after relative has died of
colon cancer. Parents with their colons removed in young adulthood
passed the disease on to their children, who had the same terrible
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Scruggs, a 45-year-old nurse who lives in Ellisville,
Miss., said that was what happened in her family. The first she
knew of FAP was when her mother died of colon cancer on Jan. 10,
1966, at age 35. Ms. Scruggs, the oldest of five children, was only
10 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't understand until Mama had it that it was all
genetic,'' said Ms. Scruggs. Now, she can trace the disease to her
maternal great-grandmother, who died at 55 from what seems to have
been colon cancer. Doctors had said she was having ``spells'' and
``locked bowels.'' Her grandmother also had colon cancer, as did
her mother's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scruggs, her two brothers and her two sisters developed
polyps. One brother recently developed cancer in his rectum even
though his colon had been removed. Two of Ms. Scruggs' four
children have polyps.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Scruggs along with her brother, her sister and her son
joined a study by the Searle pharmaceutical company. Their motive
was to help other people with FAP, she said. ``We can see the
adverse effect it has had on our lives, physically, emotionally,''
she said. ``If we can help one other person, it is worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
