<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8323 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     01-17 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE SCENE SHIFTS, SOME ROLES GET LEFT BEHIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Kellie Martin's announcement last week that
she'd had enough of ``ER'' came as a surprise only to those who
thought she'd jumped ship long ago. Martin was brought in last
season to inject the aging drama with the youth, vitality and teary
sentiment that's her stock in trade, the stuff she'd brought to
series like ``Life Goes On,'' ``Christy'' and ``Crisis Center,''
where she'd been the marquee name.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' was a different monster. It already had big names, not to
mention more viewers than any other series. So after a few choice
introductory episodes, Martin's Lucy Knight, a first-year resident
with a penchant for overstepping her emotional bounds while
tripping over her inexperience, was relegated to the bin of Things
That Aren't Working.
</P>
<P>
   With more new faces to write for this season (Michael Michele,
Ming-Na Wen, Maura Tierney, Goran Visnjic, the Croatian version of
George Clooney) and a heavy dose of guest stars (Alan Alda and
Rebecca De Mornay), ``ER's'' writers, to put it gently, simply lost
Lucy. She was barely there, whizzing through the corridors, being a
bit player in everyone else's bulging story lines.
</P>
<P>
   It happens, producers, writers and stars say: Characters brought
on with fanfare and high possibilities slowly disappear, as what
looked good on paper looks like a failure on the air. Eventually,
producers no longer feel the creative need to have the character at
all, or the star reads the writing on the wall and bolts.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is that more evident than on the rookie drama ``West
Wing,'' which is trying to find airtime for eight regulars. By next
season, both Rob Lowe and Moira Kelly could be gone. Not because
creator and executive producer John Wells isn't satisfied with
their work _ he is. It's because the maximum time given others
leaves them with little to do.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's displeasure with screen time has been the most rumored,
though when confronted the other day about his future on the drama,
he pleaded the Fifth in Hollywoodspeak. (He answered the question
by answering a totally different question.)
</P>
<P>
   Part of a ``West Wing'' panel at the television critics press
gathering in Burbank, Lowe looked painfully glum, rarely cracking a
smile even after the crowd of usually jaded reporters went into
feet-stomping applause for Martin Sheen to do his impersonation of
Sinatra. (He didn't, saying it works only on the set.) The panel
over, Lowe dashed out a side door. Aaron Sorkin, who along with
Wells executive-produces ``West Wing,'' a behind-the-scenes look at
a White House administration, tried to play down the controversy,
saying Lowe had never expressed a concern over story lines. At
least not to him.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping into a sports analogy, as always, Sorkin said his cast
is an all-star team: Everyone is capable of getting the ball, but
they all can't have it at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look. This is an extraordinary cast. It's, you know, a
blessing and curse to have this embarrassment of riches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So producers go with the ones who will keep making them rich,
which is part of both Sheen's and Lowe's and even Kelly's problem.
Unlike Sheen and Kelly, though, Lowe was brought in as an
``unwritten lead,'' an innocuous billing in which you're part of an
ensemble cast but the series is really being written around you.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Lowe was to ``West Wing'' what George Clooney and
Anthony Edwards were to ``ER'' _ leader of the pack. But here's
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen's President Bartlett was to be talked about but not seen
(''But we were afraid it would be contrived, like the next-door
neighbor on `Home Improvement,' '' says Sorkin). So the series of
guest spots was conceived.
</P>
<P>
   Then the response to Sheen was so strong that Sorkin began to
wrap story lines around the president. The focus shifted. And it
shows. Lowe's once-promising story line involving a legitimate
relationship with a prostitute has become stagnant, redundant and
insignificant.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Miller, a senior vice president for Warner Bros. who
oversees casting for both ``ER'' and ``West Wing,'' says none of
the situations is unique. She confirmed that Lowe was initially
pegged as a centerpiece of ``West Wing'' (''His reading simply blew
us away,'' she says). ``But ... once the shooting starts, things
start to happen with your character and other characters. Writers
discover secondary characters because something great is happening.
And maybe the emphasis is no longer on the person where it
started.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' such a discovery has helped that NBC show
become the funniest sitcom on TV. Because sitcom casts are usually
smaller (''Will &AMP; Grace'' has but four main players), the
possibility that supporting player Sean Hayes would push Eric
McCormack and Debra Messing out the door isn't an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an actor it's a hard thing to talk about because it works
both ways,'' says Hayes. ``It's just that if you're the secondary
character getting a lot of screen time or the lead of an ensemble
getting all the lines, that's great. But when you're the loser,
it's an unfair system.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Miller: ``It's not necessarily the actor's fault, the
writers' fault, the producers' faults. Sometimes it's not the right
choice. Sometimes the show's dynamic changes and those changes
affect everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Moira Kelly says she'll return to her film career. Kellie Martin
is headed back to Yale to finish her senior year. Who knows what's
up with Lowe? Meanwhile, ``ER'' fresh blood Michele and Ming-Na
will roll the dice with the country's No. 1 program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned over the years to take it one day at a time,''
says Ming-Na, making her second tour of duty on the medical drama.
``Even if you get here on time, know your lines, do good work, get
along with your co-workers, your fate is often in the hands of
others. You can't sweat it. Me? I enjoy the ride until the ride is
over. Then I'll go looking for loose change to get on another
one.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
