<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8324 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOZART-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     01-17 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOZART-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOZART: A CULTURAL BIOGRAPHY': OBSCENE CHILD GIVES WAY TO A
METHODICAL GENIUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Publication notes at end of review.)  
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few artists have been as relentlessly mythologized as Mozart. He
has been portrayed as an emblematic figure of the Enlightenment, as
the Romantic embodiment of natural man, as an irresponsible Don
Juan and as a vulgar, sophomoric vessel for the voice of God.
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``Mozart: A Cultural Biography,'' the scholar
Robert W. Gutman tries to strip away such contradictory legends to
give the reader a down-to-earth portrait of Mozart as a highly
professional musician who used his genius to assimilate and
transform the artistic currents of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman's Mozart, in fact, is a near-antithesis to the ``obscene
child'' depicted in Peter Shaffer's play ``Amadeus'' and a
decidedly happier, better-adjusted man than the one depicted in
Maynard Solomon's 1995 psycho-biography.
</P>
<P>
   Gutman dismisses speculation that Mozart might have been
murdered by the rival musician Salieri or by Masons angered by his
exploration of Masonic mysteries in ``The Magic Flute''; illness
(possibly rheumatic fever), he thinks, ``invaded a system weakened
by overwork.'' He also assails the popular belief that Mozart died
a defeated, disillusioned man, contending that the composer's
precarious finances were ``ameliorating'' in the weeks before his
death and that he ``stood at the high point of his fame'' in his
final months, the ``current of his genius'' flowing ``in full
spate.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the reader, Gutman's cheerful portrait of
Mozart as an ``affectionate and generous man'' who ``played his
role in the human comedy with honor,'' ``goodness of heart,
unaffected charm, winning ways, and self-humor'' fails to grapple
with many of the complexities of the historical record. While many
of the points Gutman wants to make are similar to those made by the
musicologist H.C. Robbins Landon in ``Mozart's Last Year'' (1988),
he does not write with that author's fluency or rigor.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Gutman's assessments of Mozart's inner life feel
platitudinous or contradictory. In one chapter, he writes that
Mozart ``postured as a matter of course'' in his letters, disguise
becoming reflex. In another, he describes Mozart as having ``a
liberated personality'' redolent of the ``equivocal identity not a
few of his operatic characters would insinuate.''
</P>
<P>
   In a third, he asserts that Mozart's character ``remained of a
piece, an intense fusion under control and without Goethe's morbid
strain.'' ``If, as Felix Mendelssohn observed,'' Gutman writes,
``there were many Goethes, there was only one Mozart, steadfast in
his central bent.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Mozart's music, Gutman _ the author of an
earlier book on Richard Wagner _ fares only marginally better.
Although it is clear that he is on intimate terms with Mozart's
oeuvre, he does not use his expertise to communicate the qualities,
texture or magic of individual works: he assumes a large degree of
familiarity, on the reader's part, with the librettos of Mozart's
operas, and he also takes for granted an appreciation of the
composer's symphonic and chamber music work.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, such works are rarely assessed _ or even described
_ in any meaningful way; instead, the reader is simply given an
awkward mix of pedantic asides and fuzzily portentous encomiums.
Gutman writes, for instance, that Mozart's work opens ``vast vistas
of universal moral law and ultimate truth and assumes the quality
of a summons through the Red Sea.''
</P>
<P>
   Where Gutman's book is more useful is in delineating the
cultural backdrop to Mozart's achievement, and the musical
environment in which he came of age. Gutman sketches the
Enlightenment Zeitgeist into which Mozart was born and the
proto-Romanticism that developed in its wake, showing how both
movements unconsciously shaped the composer's developing aesthetic.
In addition he describes how Mozart fluently assimilated the styles
of his predecessors, and in doing so, raised ``German eclecticism
to commanding heights.''
</P>
<P>
   Mozart's development as a composer, Gutman contends, was from
childhood onward ``in no way meteoric, but gradual and
consistent'': he seldom demonstrated ``immediate mastery of the
untried,'' but proceeded by an ``implausibly orderly and
homogeneous process.''
</P>
<P>
   With his ``polyglot vocabulary,'' Gutman goes on, Mozart
gradually began to command ``a style deceptively simple on the
surface but filled with intricacies and elegances, a style of
cultured grace that did not exclude a distilled sensuality so
complex, penetrating and compelling as to ennoble as it seduces.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gutman sees it, Mozart's psychological development proceeded
along a similar arc. Like many earlier biographers, he depicts the
young Mozart laboring under the thumb of his formidable father,
Leopold, who exhibited him ``like a dancing bear'' before the
wealthy and titled. In his 20s, Gutman observes, Mozart rebelled
against his father, breaking away from his tyrannical rule to start
a family and career of his own in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   While other biographers have argued that the shadow of his
father continued to haunt Mozart, Gutman asserts that the composer
possessed ``a strong, balanced core fortified by humor'' and that
he gradually emerged ``from under the mountain of psychological
distress his family had piled upon him.''
</P>
<P>
   His final letters, written while he was composing the Requiem
and the clarinet concerto, Gutman contends, reveal a man ``basking
in praise; busying himself with creating two of the loftiest
productions of the human mind; sending his wife almost daily
messages overflowing with fun, love, and plans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I search in vain for the guttering candle of Mozartean myth,''
Gutman writes; ``to the end, he preserved Candide-like qualities:
evergreen expectations, a passion to love, and muscle to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   That Gutman can reach conclusions so at variance with those of
many earlier scholars not only points up the gaping holes in the
historical record but also underscores the subjectivity of
biography writing, and the contradictory ways in which genius is so
often processed by the clattering machinery of history.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   MOZART: A Cultural Biography
</P>
<P>
   By Robert W. Gutman
</P>
<P>
   839 pages. Harcourt Brace &AMP; Co. $40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
