<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8327 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MASS-HYSTERIA-2TA     01-17 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MASS-HYSTERIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERIOUS ILLNESSES OFTEN TURN OUT TO BE MASS HYSTERIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Ill., Conn., Calif.)   (Science Times)  
 (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phenomenon can be frightening and is more common than most
doctors believe.
</P>
<P>
   A person smells or tastes something funny and soon complains of
feeling ill. Minutes later, witnesses also feel strange. The
outbreak spreads like a chain reaction. Many go to a hospital. But
after physical examinations and dozens of blood tests, nothing
significant shows up. Health officials are summoned but find no
cause. A few days later, relapses and possibly a new wave of
attacks may occur. When the all-clear is given, the diagnosis is
mass hysteria, also known as epidemic hysteria, mass psychogenic
illness and mass sociogenic illness.
</P>
<P>
   Stampedes of anxiety can spread rapidly among healthy people.
Outbreaks have occurred around the world since at least the 14th
century. In past eras, some were triggered by thoughts of demons,
possessed states and religious events. Nowadays, the triggers are
usually fears of exposure to hazardous substances and pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, outbreaks of mass hysteria can be difficult to
distinguish from bioterrorism, rapidly spreading infection and
acute exposure to a toxin or other environmental hazard. And rising
public concern about biological terrorism and rapid spread of news
of outbreaks over the Internet are likely to increase the
challenge, if not frequency, of mass hysteria for health officials.
</P>
<P>
   There is no standard definition because the range of symptoms is
so vast. It includes headache, nausea, vomiting, light-headedness,
fainting, anxiety, numbness, tingling and even spasms of laughter.
Although death rarely occurs, if ever, onlookers have summoned
priests to give last rites.
</P>
<P>
   Mass hysteria tends to occur at schools, hospitals, other
workplaces and small communities, and can trickle on for weeks. For
unknown reasons, women are affected more often than men. No one
knows how many incidents occur because they are rarely described in
scientific journals.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Matthew Cartter, an official of the Connecticut Department
of Health, said skeptical editors and scientists rejected a report
of a mass hysteria outbreak that he submitted to medical journals
in 1986. Cartter said he concluded that ``some reports like mass
hysteria are better told as stories than as scientific studies.''
</P>
<P>
   An exception is a 1998 outbreak in a high school in McMinnville,
Tenn., where 170 students and teachers ended up in the hospital,
according to a report in Jan. 13 issue of The New England Journal
of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the costs of caring for patients and investigating
outbreaks, mass hysteria often has political, social and economic
implications. For instance, in Belgium last summer, 250 people,
including many schoolchildren, complained of sickness after
drinking Coca-Cola. The incident prompted the biggest recall (2.5
million bottles) in Coke's 113-year history and cost the company at
least $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although most children in Belgium recovered quickly, parents say
that some still suffer from headaches, knee pain and exhaustion.
The outbreak ``was no psychological or mass hysteria,'' the
director of one affected Belgian school said, but some doctors
suspect otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, it has had some hallmarks of mass hysteria,'' said
Dr. William Schaffner, chairman of the department of preventive
medicine at Vanderbilt Medical School in Nashville and a member of
the team that investigated the Tennessee outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Mass hysteria outbreaks have affected school choruses, day care
centers, jazz festivals, marching bands and train passengers.
</P>
<P>
   A mass hysteria outbreak occurred during a true epidemic of
poliomyelitis in Los Angeles in 1934 when nurses caring for the
patients at Los Angeles County Hospital thought they, too, had
developed polio.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, a flurry of people in Mattoon, Ill., reported becoming
paralyzed after a man squirted them with a gas. The police failed
to catch the man, who became known as the ``mad gasser of
Mattoon.'' In 1956, a report in The Lancet raised the possibility
that staff members of a hospital in London had developed a new type
of encephalitis. But a re-analysis of the cases published in 1970
in The British Medical Journal showed that the outbreak was mass
hysteria, a diagnosis the Lancet authors had not considered.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to distinguish between symptoms caused by poisons and
mass hysteria, doctors seek certain clues. For example, people
exposed to an irritant gas usually cough and have reddened eyes and
irritation of other mucous membranes. But those involved in mass
hysteria generally do not.
</P>
<P>
   Even when doctors suspect that their patients suffer from mass
hysteria, they must examine all to be sure that one or two do not
have an organic illness.
</P>
<P>
   Mass hysteria is generally diagnosed by excluding all known
infectious and noxious agents, a costly process. So, experts debate
whether limits should be put on investigating each outbreak,
particularly when the diagnosis is suspected from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Mass hysteria illustrates the well-known difficulties of proving
and disproving a negative. For example, not doing a thorough
investigation invites concern that the ``true'' cause was
overlooked and possible legal action. Yet because mass hysteria is
such an emotionally charged problem, a detailed investigation that
does not verify suspicions of a poisonous gas may still fail to
satisfy those involved.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Because published reports of mass hysteria have rarely discussed
treatment, doctors are unsure how to tell patients that no organic
cause could be found for their symptoms. The presence of
ambulances, television cameras and workers in protective clothing
can all add to the anxiety, confirming suspicions of a dangerous
situation, experts say. And the anxiety may be rekindled when
officials make inquiries after the symptoms disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Publicity also contributes to the outbreaks. So experts are
uncertain how public anxiety should be alleviated.
</P>
<P>
   A major puzzle is why so few textbooks and medical schools deal
with the phenomenon. Schaffner said he could find only one
reference in standard textbooks, a single sentence referring to the
Salem witch trials. So Schaffner urged his team to publish an
account of the high school outbreak that occurred on Nov. 12, 1998,
to raise awareness of the problem among health workers.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after a teacher said she smelled gasoline in her
classroom at the school in McMinnville, Tenn., she experienced a
headache, nausea, shortness of breath and dizziness. As the
classroom was being evacuated, students and staff members
complained of similar symptoms. A fire alarm was sounded and the
school was evacuated. Emergency medical crews put the teacher and
several students in ambulances in view of other students and
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, 80 students and 19 staff members with similar symptoms
went to the emergency room at a local hospital. For most of them,
symptoms disappeared after they left the school premises and
breathed oxygen. The teacher and 37 others were admitted; doctors
found no organic cause of their symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   After the fire department, gas company, and officials the
National Institute of Occupational Safety and Health found no
problem in the school, it was reopened on Nov. 17. But that day, a
new wave of symptoms occurred, and another 71 people went to the
emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Government agencies were summoned for an even more exhaustive
investigation. Epidemiologists found that 69 percent of those
affected in the outbreak were female. In comparison, 52 percent of
the overall school population of 1,825 students and 140 staff
members were female.
</P>
<P>
   One-fourth of those affected reported a fever; but an elevated
temperature was documented in only one, and it was 100 degrees
Fahrenheit. Of the 186 ill, 120 or 65 percent reported an unusual
odor at the school and they used more than 30 words such as sweet,
burning and sewer gas to describe it in a questionnaire. Those ill
were from 49 different locations in the school.
</P>
<P>
   But health workers who scoured the premises could identify no
gas or other hazardous substance to account for the symptoms or
odor.
</P>
<P>
   The team did not include a psychologist or psychiatrist because
members did not know one locally with expertise in the problem or
what that person's role would be.
</P>
<P>
   Although those involved in mass hysteria experience real
symptoms, which persist in some, the individuals are usually not
re-examined to determine the long-term effects.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the scientific journal Epidemiologic Reviews in 1997,
Dr. Leslie Boss, a NIOSH official, observed: ``Often no attempt to
understand the illness further is made beyond publishing the
results of the investigation. Failure to do so may result in the
inability of health officials to prevent further outbreaks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
