<SLUG> BC-HEALTHY-MEDIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Internet site of the week
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents to be need help and information _ and new and repeat
parents usually have things they need to buy as well. The Internet
has recognized both of those needs, offering up slates of sites
that combine consumer information and e-commerce with lists of baby
names and offers of electronic gift registries.
</P>
<P>
   One site that does a good job of balancing commerce and
information is BabyCenter (www.babycenter.com). It has plenty of
commercial links _ and offers of free stuff _ from its
infant-centric sponsors Carter's, Beech-Nut, Pampers and others.
But it also offers solid data on prenatal research, stages of fetal
development, relationship issues and other concerns of those who
are parents or want to be. And it has cool interactive utilities,
including an ovulation predictor, a calculator for infertility
risks and weekly newsletters that automatically deliver information
for every week of pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Are you aware that . . .
</P>
<P>
   January is Cervical Health Awareness Month, intended to raise
awareness of screening for cervical cancer. Pap tests can screen
for the cancer, which is easily treatable in its early stages but
kills 4,800 women in the United States every year. For information
about cervical cancer, contact the American Cancer Society at
www.cancer.org or 1-800-227-2345.
</P>
<P>
   M.A.J. McKenna writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
</TEXT>
