<HEADER>
A8331 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-NEWSSTAND18-COX     01-17 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ON THE NEWSSTANDS: Author reflects on freedom in this week's
Book magazine
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Emory University professor Ha Jin talks with Jerome
Kramer of Book magazine about life after winning the National Book
Award for his novel ``Waiting.'' A Chinese expatriate, Ha Jin says
most Americans do not fully appreciate the freedom they have here.
``I think if you travel to another country, you can see the
difference,'' he says. Also of note is an interesting look at books
written by political candidates. Just because every presidential
hopeful feels a compulsion to put his thoughts down in a book
doesn't mean the urge should be acted on, says contributing writer
Marc Herman. Every candidate, it seems, from Gary Bauer to Donald
Trump, has a book on the shelves. Such tomes can backfire, Herman
writes. ``They provide, after all, a public record of a candidate's
beliefs, something politicians aren't always served by.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the vows: Can two very different people make a marriage
work? That's the question Life ($3.99) tries to answer by talking
with couples such as Celine Dion and Rene Angelil and other
seemingly mismatched husbands and wives. There is a 26-year age
difference between Dion and her spouse, but, says the singer,
``Most of the time, he acts more like a kid than me.'' And, in an
introductory essay, Cokie Roberts, co-anchor of ABC's ``This
Week,'' and husband Steven V. Roberts, a political analyst for CNN
and PBS, write about their 33-year ``mixed marriage.'' Cokie is
Catholic, Steve is Jewish. During the December holidays they top
their Christmas tree with a Hebrew star.
</P>
<P>
   The big merger: The newsweeklies are all abuzz about the
AOL-Time Warner deal, but most Americans apparently are not as
excited. According to a Newsweek ($3.95) poll, only 25 percent of
adults say the merger is good for the country, and only 18 percent
say it is good for them personally. Not surprisingly, Time ($3.95)
is more upbeat in its coverage of the deal, but the magazine
attempts to maintain a semblance of fairness with pro and con
viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Art imitates life: Playing a bad-girl character in the film
``Girl, Interrupted'' apparently was not a stretch for Angelina
Jolie. In an interview with Jane ($2.95), the actress talks about
her wild life of drug use and knife collecting, and addresses the
rumors about her bisexuality and eating disorders. And, in a Time
profile, Jolie is described as a ``female James Dean'' by Columbia
pictures chairwoman Amy Pascal.
</P>
<P>
   Bits and pieces: In case you haven't heard, Oprah Winfrey's new
magazine has been dubbed O, the Oprah Magazine, and will debut
April 17 with a circulation of 850,000. The magazine will cover
beauty, fashion, heath, fitness and spirituality and will, no
doubt, feature many covers with Oprah's picture. . . . The great
Cosmopolitan cover-up is under way at Kroger stores, but there are
other mags that deserve to be wrapped as well. The February issue
of Glamour ($2.99) features the usual cleavage cover with teases
touting ``23 Erotic Ways to Make Sex With Him Sweeter'' and ``Sex
and Size: Is He Too Big? Are You?'' Beyond the erotica, however,
there's an informative interview with Vice President Al Gore about
his plan to woo women voters.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
