<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV23-NY     01-17 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT DREAD PLACE FROM WHICH NO BUMBLER RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Jan. 23)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(Eds: The word AT in parentheses has been used in the final graf
instead of the symbol, which is nontransmittable to many newspaper
systems.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After I expressed my intent to explore an area that strikes
terror of embarrassment into so many hearts, a colleague warned,
``I wouldn't go there if I were you.''
</P>
<P>
   Linguistic exploration rejects such faintheartedness. We will
now deal forthrightly with the cliche that has been embraced by the
squirming squeamish:  &UR; Don't go there &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Its literal sense is of no concern.  &UR; There &LR; , meaning ``a
place,'' can be construed as an adverb modifying  &UR; go &LR;  or a noun in
its own right. But the figurative sense _ of some undiscover'd
country from whose bourn no shamefaced traveler returns _ is what
has gripped the bromide set.
</P>
<P>
   It can mean ``We'd better not talk about that.'' Or ``If our
conversation reaches that subject, you will be uncomfortable and I
will be chagrined.'' Or ``Now you're getting into a touchy
subject.'' Or more severely, ``Beware _ you are approaching a taboo
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewing Dan Quayle, the former vice president, last spring,
before he withdrew from the presidential race, the Times reporter
Melinda Henneberger noted this intelligent man's abiding need to
prove he was not stupid. ``Waking up from a nap on the campaign
plane, he asked what I was reading,'' she wrote, ``and it was `Anna
Karenina.' He squeezed his eyes shut, opened them again a second
later. `Russian, right?' Then, a look of relief. Why, oh why, does
he  &UR; go there &LR; ?''
</P>
<P>
   Where is  &UR; there &LR;  in this figurative sense? It is not uncharted
territory; on the contrary, it is a subject area all too well
charted or remembered for its embarrassments by the person not
eager to get back to that place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect this may have had its origin in psychobabble,''
writes Stephen Rosen of New York. ``Where does it come from?''
</P>
<P>
   Let's  &UR; go there &LR; . David Barnhart, editor of the Dictionary
Companion that bears his name (I like that archaic locution),
suggests that the proto-phrase for the expression is ``I don't want
to  &UR; go that route &LR; .'' If so, the meaning has changed from ``way of
getting there'' to ``being there, unhappily.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lexicographic listing I can find is in ``Da Bomb!'' _
the March 1997 dictionary of slang compiled by Judi Sanders'
intercultural communication class at the California State
Polytechnic University in Pomona. It defined  &UR; Don't even go there &LR; 
simply as ``Do not say that'' and the shorter  &UR; Don't go there &LR;  as
``Don't talk about it or mention it.'' ( &UR; That's da bomb &LR; , by the
way, is synonymous with the no-longer-so-cool  &UR; cool &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   Tom Dalzell, the California slanguist, has no citation to offer
but opines that `` &UR; don't go there &LR;  started with black drag queens
and then found its legs with Ricki Lake,'' the talk-show host.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Popik of the American Dialect Society found a 1994 usage
of the imperative warning by the comic Martin Lawrence, talking to
Entertainment Weekly about his Fox sitcom. ``We started using the
expressions `You go, girl!' and ` &UR; Don't go there &LR; !''' Lawrence
said, ``and no one in television was doing that. No one. Now a lot
of Fox shows are using the same stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that its roots and overusage have been exposed, we can hope
for the early demise of the cliche. As Yogi Berra once put it,
``That place is so popular that nobody  &UR; goes there  &LR; anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   POO-TEEN
</P>
<P>
   He may be with us for a while, so let's get his name right: The
acting president of Russia is Vladimir Putin, pronounced POO-teen.
``The stem for Putin's name is derived from  &UR; put &LR; , meaning `path'
or `road,''' notes Albert Weeks, a New York University professor
emeritus now living in Sarasota, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Marat Akchurin of the American Name Society adds: ``The meaning
of  &UR; Putin &LR;  was `the one who was born on the road'; that is, the
mother was traveling when the birth took place. So, within the
current political context in Russia,  &UR; Putin  &LR; could be taken to mean
`transitional.''' Another possible etymology is the verb  &UR; putat &LR; ,
meaning ``to swaddle, bind'' and, by extension, ``to confuse, make
ambiguous, entangle.''
</P>
<P>
   Can it be connected to  &UR; Rasputin &LR; , the derisive name for the
swinging Russian monk, Grigory Novykh, who dominated the court of
Czar Nicholas II? One meaning of  &UR; rasputye &LR;  is ``debauched,'' but
another is ``crossroad'';  &UR; putin &LR;  without the prefix  &UR; ras &LR;  could
mean ``one-track road.'' Be careful not to read too much into this.
</P>
<P>
   NO MORE PATIENTS
</P>
<P>
   How do you get rid of mental patients in one fell swoop? Put a
more caring way, how do you make the mentally ill feel better about
whatever ails them? Call them  &UR; mental-health consumers &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Here's the idea: A  &UR; patient &LR;  is one being cared for; in a
``doctor- &UR; patient &LR;  relationship,'' the doctor has the power. But in
a ``merchant- &UR; consumer &LR;  relationship,'' the consumer is supposedly
king. When you think of health care as a commodity, to be sold by
medical professionals and bought by ailing purchasers of such
therapies, then the patient is a  &UR; consumer &LR; , the boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a respect thing,'' says Frank McMyne, a board member of
the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill. ``It changes the
relationship. If we are merely  &UR; patients &LR; , it diminishes our
ability to question the kind of treatment we are receiving.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Karen Shore, president of the Coalition of Mental Health
Professionals and Consumers, is more conflicted. ``I call my
patients  &UR; patients &LR; . But to a lot of people who are consumer
advocates,  &UR; patient &LR;  sounds pejorative.''
</P>
<P>
   Her associate Sheri Laribee adds: ``What  &UR; consumer &LR;  stands for
is `someone on a health care plan.' If I am paying for the managed
health care plan, I am the consumer buying insurance. The
managed-care organizations call people  &UR; consumers &LR;  so that they
don't have to think of them as  &UR; patients &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Useless euphemism or realistic relabeling? We're onto a
linguistic-political controversy here. Comments from treaters and
treatees will be welcomed at Safire On Language, New York Times
Washington Bureau, 1627 I St. NW, Washington, DC 20006 or at
onlanguage(AT)nytimes.com. (If you have to wait for a reply, be
consumer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
