<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Jan. 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The frigid air over New England will moderate Tuesday as
sunshine and lighter winds combine with slightly milder air aloft.
A complex front approaching from the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley
should produce snow showers in Ohio, western New York and
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   One center of low pressure will remain near Lake Superior,
producing light to moderate snow in upper Michigan. A new low will
develop in eastern Tennessee causing a wintry mixture from the
southern Appalachians to the Carolina coast. Light snow will cover
parts of Virginia and the higher terrain of the western Carolinas.
Sleet and freezing rain will glaze sections of the central and
eastern Piedmont plateau from northeast North Carolina to northeast
Georgia. The coast will notice occasional cold rain mixed with ice
pellets.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure in the central Plains will be associated with a
mixture of Pacific and polar air. Temperatures will be
near-to-above seasonal levels. A surge of arctic air will reach the
border states Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A stream of moisture from the Pacific will bring clouds and
showers to much of the West Coast and the central Rockies. Winds
ascending the eastern Rockies should combine with high-level
moisture to induce showers in Kansas Tuesday afternoon. Valley rain
and mountain snows will be common in the southern two-thirds of
California and across parts of Nevada, northern Arizona, Utah and
western Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Gales and rain will approach the Northwest coast as an offshore
storm pushes slowly eastward.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Direct Discharge
</P>
<P>
   Monday morning saw the temperature dip to 8 degrees at Central
Park in New York, the lowest reading since January 19, 1997. The
afternoon temperature struggled to reach 16, making it the lowest
daytime temperature there since a cold wave in January 1994. The
entire Northeast shivered as a mound of arctic air plunged directly
south from Quebec. Air masses that follow this trajectory are not
modified by their passage over the Great Lakes, nor are they
tempered by a long descent from the peaks of the Appalachians.
Moderation is expected Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1732EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8338 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-SKI-LAKE-PLACID-HNS &LR;      01-17 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-LAKE-PLACID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     OLYMPIC FAME HAS FADED, BUT LAKE PLACID REMAINS A WINTER
HAVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM REYNOLDS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ The streets have not bustled with this much
anticipation in 20 years, the natives of this tiny Essex County
village will tell you. Banners and signs that welcome the world are
as omnipresent on Main Street as the icicles that hang off
rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   As you stroll down the narrow, curvy main artery of Lake Placid,
a village with some 2,500 residents, you can't help but wonder how
similar it is today to the Olympic years of 1932 and 1980, when the
eyes of the world's winter sports enthusiasts were focused here.
</P>
<P>
   Those eyes have wandered past Lake Placid in recent years, its
luster usurped by places such as Calgary, Nagano, and Salt Lake
City. In the 1990s, international competitions always seemed to be
headed elsewhere, leaving youth hockey tournaments to fill the void
in Lake Placid.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, the down period that followed the 1980 Olympics
appears to be ending. Lake Placid is part of history, but it isn't
history. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an evolution,'' said Ted Blazer, president and chief
executive officer of the Olympic Regional Development Authority.
``But I don't know if I would call it a resurgence.''
</P>
<P>
   In February, the inaugural Winter Goodwill Games begin here, the
biggest on a list of big events that have marked Lake Placid's
reemergence on the international winter sports scene. First there
was the U.S. Ski Team Gold Cup two years ago, then an Ironman
triathlon and a World Cup biathlon event last year. Future events
include the inaugural Winter National Senior Games Feb. 29-March 3,
the ESPN Great Outdoor Games this summer, and the bobsledding world
championships in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``Selfishly, I think we're still the winter sports capital of
the world,'' said the village's mayor, T. James Strack, himself a
former competitive bobsledder. ``If you come here, see the ski
jumps and Whiteface Mountain and the new bobsled run, how could you
not say that? We can handle anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Lake Placid first achieved notoriety as a vacation spot for the
rich and elite, and soon after as a winter sports wonderland, a
distinction it has held for seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   But not even the surrounding 46 mountains in upstate New York,
the mammoth earthy mounds that compose the High Peaks of the
Adirondacks, could protect Lake Placid from ebbs and flows of
success along the way. It is a two-time Olympic Winter Games host,
one of only three places in the world with that distinction, but
the residual benefits of being an Olympic city last only so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last four or five years, maybe longer, there's been a
real effort on the part of elected officials to make people aware
how difficult it is to survive in the Adirondacks economically,''
said James McKenna of the Lake Placid Visitors Bureau. ``Sports
seem to mix with the Adirondacks pretty well, and it was a matter
of figuring out how to use sports as an engine to cultivate more
economic activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, thoughts like those weren't necessary. The
1980 Olympics were the stuff of legend, with Eric Heiden's five
speedskating gold medals and the scintillating run by the
miracle-making U.S. ice hockey team secure in American sports lore.
</P>
<P>
   But those memories alone couldn't keep Lake Placid fresh in
people's minds. Instead of moving forward, Lake Placid was falling
off the winter sports radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of that concern,'' Blazer said, ``came determination and
drive to not let that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The venues that separated Lake Placid from the rest of the world
were, in some cases, literally falling apart. Construction of
second homes and condominiums, a trend that exploded in Lake Placid
during the 1980s, essentially ceased in the early 1990s. These were
all bad signs for a village of 3,000 that has an unemployment rate
twice the national average, and where one in five families lives
below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started coming here 10 or 11 years ago, Lake Placid
was a nice little resort town with an Olympic reputation,'' said
Barbara Harubin, a Johnson City resident whose husband, Edward,
runs a summer fishing-tour business in the Lake Placid area, and
whose family vacations in Lake Placid during the winter. ``Then it
seemed like its time had passed, but now it's exciting again.''
</P>
<P>
   Strack disagreed with the notion that Lake Placid's time had
ever passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never in financial trouble; we were in recognition
trouble,'' said Strack, who pointed to lack of marketing and lack
of facilities upkeep as the two factors that led to the village's
failure to attract major sporting competitions. ``We've got a gold
mine here, and we had to put some money back into it to get the
word out again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS. &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lake Placid bid unsuccessfully for the 1992 Olympic Winter
Games, the first blow the village took in the winter sports arena.
Once folks realized that another Olympic year is a long way off, if
ever, they started to get creative with marketing strategies.
Blazer pointed to the Gold Cup, which served as the U.S. Olympic
skiing trials in 1998, as the type of event that Lake Placid would
like to land consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fulfilled their needs before the Olympic period,'' Blazer
said. ``And it fulfilled ours _ a multisport event which was
televised. So the event was created. And I think there's a lot of
opportunity like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's Ironman triathlon fit that bill, as do these
upcoming Goodwill Games, which local officials estimate could pump
$12 million into the Lake Placid region.
</P>
<P>
   Blazer, ever the optimist, points to the upcoming events as
proof that Lake Placid's lull is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other place in the world has an edge on Lake Placid now,''
Blazer said.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic sites such as Chamonix, St. Moritz and Squaw Valley fell
off the list of competitive winter sport havens long ago. Venues in
Sarajevo were destroyed by a war, and venues in Albertville were
dismantled almost as soon as the final gold medal was awarded there
eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Here, though, the village clings to its Olympic heritage, a
distinction that separates it from its similar-sized neighbors in
the hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that always kept us going was our Olympic Training
Center, which always kept the athletes coming here,'' Strack said.
``As long as we could keep that thing active and going, there was
always hope that someone would see the beauty of the area and the
facilities we have here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
