<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8339 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-LABBE-COLUMN-1500(2TA     01-17 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-1500(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MANY WAYS, 1900 WAS A DOPPLEGANGER OF 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Change had come so fast and had been so radical no one seemed
certain where reality stopped and fantasy began.''
</P>
<P>
   Observations at the dawn of the year 2000?
</P>
<P>
   No. It's documentary writer and producer Judy Crichton's
observation about the dawn of 1900 from her book, ``America 1900:
The Turning Point.''
</P>
<P>
   PBS recently rebroadcast its three-hour documentary based on
Crichton's 1998 book. The parallels between the last year of the
19th century and what the United States is experiencing now, the
waning days of the 20th century, are downright eerie.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1900: Publishing magnate William Randolph Hearst predicts that
``the powers of the wind, the sea, the rivers and the sun will be
chained _ so that the air will no longer be fouled with smoke for
which men have worn out their lives in coal mines.''
</P>
<P>
   2000: If only ol' Willie had been correct about what was to
come, because America is still wrestling with air fouled with smoke
_ and ozone, and nitric oxides, and sulfur dioxide, and particulate
emissions, and ...
</P>
<P>
   Technology has helped reduce the number of men wearing out their
lives in coal mines, but not this country's dependence on fossil
fuels.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1900: One of the technological advancements that was supposed to
help with that fouled air debuts on New Year's Eve in the streets
of Boston: electric cabs. But the use of electric-powered vehicles
is impractical beyond a few major cities for a plethora of reasons,
premier among them lousy roads (there were only 10 miles of
concrete road in America in 1900) and a lack of access to
recharging facilities.
</P>
<P>
   While most urban areas are rapidly installing electrical
infrastructures, primarily to replace gas street lamps so they
could take human lamplighters off the city payroll, electricity in
the home and even in many businesses is not common. (Many New
Yorkers fear they will be electrocuted in their beds when the lines
are run into their houses). Rural electrification worth noting
doesn't occur for another 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Electricity is expensive, and gasoline _ basically a waste
product of petroleum that is often burned off at the wellhead to
get to the kerosene for lamps _ is cheap. At 5 cents a gallon, it
trumps electricity's cost of more than 20 cents per kilowatt-hour.
</P>
<P>
   And believe it or not, gas-powered vehicles are considered a
leap forward in environmental and community health. Remember, they
are replacing the horse, whose byproduct stinks, attracts
disease-carrying flies, creates a dust that contributes to
respiratory problems and eye irritations, and makes the streets a
slippery mess when it rains.
</P>
<P>
   2000: Electric cars are re-emerging in the transportation
industry in large part because of the growing environmental
concerns of consumers. As the federal government continues to
threaten sanctions on urban areas that aren't doing enough to clean
up the air, consumers are increasingly calling for clean, green
alternatives to gas-powered cars.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Ford Motor Co. announced that it will soon sell a
plastic-bodied, hatchback car powered by electricity. Called the
Th!nk City, the car reportedly can travel at 55 mph. Ford already
sells electric versions of the Ranger pickup, and General Motors
offers an electric version of its EV1 coupes. The price on most
electric vehicles, however, is still big enough to choke a horse.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1900: The election campaign of 1900, with President William
McKinley and challenger William Jennings Bryan heading up the dance
card, is the most ambitious and expensive in history. The contest
costs more than $5 million; add in the congressional campaigns, and
the estimate is more than $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   2000: One candidate alone in this year's presidential election
has raised three times what was spent on all the congressional
races 100 years ago. Texas Gov. George W. Bush has a campaign war
chest of $67 million _ and counting.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and Democratic challenger Bill Bradley
have raised $24 million and $19 million, respectively. Republican
candidate Steve Forbes came into the race with $16 mil of his own
money. Add in the funds for McCain, Hatch, Bauer and Keyes ... and
they called the 1900s the Gilded Age.
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to tell what the final tab will be _ the first
primary doesn't roll around until Feb. 1 _ but what do you want to
bet that historians will be able to write, ``The election campaign
of 2000 was the most ambitious and expensive in history''?
</P>
<P>
   Which leads us to ...
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1900: One political analyst, commenting on the need for campaign
finance reform, concludes that even ``if a presidential candidate
was nominated only to reform this very system, his managers to
elect him would have to spend millions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   2000: Reform seems just as unlikely in 2000 as it appeared in
1900. Presidential hopefuls John McCain and Bill Bradley attempted
to make a bipartisan push against soft money in this year's
high-stakes race by co-hosting a most unusual news conference in
New Hampshire. Both men cast aspersions on the current campaign
finance system and pledged to work for reform.
</P>
<P>
   The problem remains that precious few other pols are willing to
work with them. Americans would be wise to maintain their
skepticism about the promised disappearance of big bucks from the
political scene in this lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1900: Bryan, a former U.S. representative from Nebraska, runs
against President McKinley _ for the second time _ on an
anti-imperialism platform.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Bryan lambastes McKinley for buckling to the media hype
and consequent public outrage over the deaths and suffering caused
by the stalemate between Spanish forces and revolutionaries in
Cuba. McKinley's intervention, the 100-day Spanish-American War,
sees the U.S. destroy the Spanish fleet in Santiago Harbor, seize
Manila and occupy Puerto Rico. The U.S. eventually annexes the
Philippines, Guam and Puerto Rico, which become the country's first
foreign holdings.
</P>
<P>
   2000: Reform Party presidential candidate Pat Buchanan is
running on a protectionist, isolationist platform that would make
Bryan bust his buttons.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is ``replicating, with alarming exactitude,
the course that brought the British Empire to ruin,'' writes
Buchanan in his book ``A Republic, Not an Empire.'' Buchanan
contends that the nation suffers from compulsive interventionism,
and he even harks back to McKinley's days in office when the
country got involved in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   His hero? William Jennings Bryan, who lost in his presidential
bid against McKinley and quit as President Wilson's first secretary
of state when he thought Wilson was preparing for war.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1900: The United States gets more than banana plantations and a
multi-island paradise when it annexes the Philippines. Manila is
viewed as the gateway to China, a flowering economic opportunity
just waiting to be plucked by American coal, oil and railroad
barons with money to burn. With a population of 500 million, China
is eyed with capitalistic hunger by megacorporations as the next
big export market.
</P>
<P>
   2000: My, how time doesn't change everything. Free-traders are
pushing hard for China's inclusion in the World Trade Organization,
and for Congress to approve permanent normal trade relations with
the communist country. With a population of 1.2 billion, China is
being eyed with capitalistic hunger by megacorporations as the next
big export market.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1900: Americans with money are ordering groceries by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   2000: DotComGuy is being paid by corporate sponsors not to leave
his apartment for a year, ordering everything he needs by Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal. This would have been news had it taken place even 10
years ago instead of today. Anyone with a telephone line, a
computer modem and a street address can do this in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
