<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-RIVER-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFE BUT FUNNY `RIVER' RUNS THROUGH EL PORTAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
 
 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH HOLLYWOOD _ A new theater opening can be like one of those
festive family get-togethers where nobody wants to mention that the
conversation is a bit predictable and the cuisine is on the lean
side.
</P>
<P>
   So it was at Friday's coming-out party for the El Portal Center
for the Arts, the beautifully reconfigured 1920s movie palace that
aims to become the crown jewel of the bustling NoHo Arts District.
Goodwill and high spirits flowed freely as the opening-night crowd
of well-wishers oohed and aahed at the sinuously elegant complex,
which should be fully up and running by February.
</P>
<P>
   It may take longer, though, to get a solid fix on the new
center's artistic agenda. To launch its inaugural Mainstage season,
the El Portal is presenting ``Over the River and Through the
Woods,'' a warm and fuzzy domestic comedy by Joe DiPietro, the
Norman Rockwell of under-40 contemporary playwrights. While in some
ways this valentine to Italian-American family values makes for a
safe, suitable choice to christen the new theater, it was clear
from the wobbly acoustics that the 390-seat Mainstage _ the largest
of the El Portal's three peformance venues _ still needs some
fine-tuning. A drop ceiling may be necessary to keep the actors'
voices (miked, Friday night, to little avail) from bouncing around
the cavernous interior.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Asaad Kelada's production of DiPietro's good-natured
comedy is as solidly crafted as set designer D. Martyn Bookwalter's
sprawling imitation of an aging Hoboken, N.J., household, where the
entire play is situated. Like the play itself, that towering set is
a modest idea writ large.
</P>
<P>
   It's here that Nick Cristano (Stuart Fratkin), 29 and single,
has come to break the bad news to his two sets of grandparents that
he's getting a promotion and moving to Seattle. To his proudly
parochial relatives, who regard Chinese food as a culinary
conspiracy and VCRs as a high-tech plot, the rainy West Coast city
might as well be on Mars. Why does their beloved grandson want to
fly the coop when everything he could want _ love, understanding,
homemade ravioli _ is right there in his back yard?
</P>
<P>
   ``Tengo famiglia'' _ ``I have family'' _ intones Nunzio (an
admirably low-key Joseph Campanella), the wryer of the two
white-haired patriarchs (Joseph Cardinale is the other). This
phrase becomes the play's mantra as the grandparents hatch a scheme
transparently to keep Nick's apron strings tied by matching him up
with a nice Irish-American lass. Shannon O'Hurley's bright-eyed,
slightly offbeat performance in this by-the-book role helps spice
up a script that sometimes mistakes the generic for the universal.
</P>
<P>
   So, also, does the smooth, understated professionalism of
Campanella, co-star Carol Lawrence (looking smashing), and
Cardinale and Erica Yohn as Nick's maternal grandparents. Fratkin,
meanwhile, finds just enough self-centered arrogance to put a
wrinkle or two in Nick's gee-whiz affability.
</P>
<P>
   Less a tightly interlocking sequence of events than a series of
convivial set pieces, ``Over the River'' is an affectionate,
forgiving look at one man's past _ and a hopeful glimpse of his
future. Like Neil Simon, DiPietro's comic gift lies not in what he
has to say about life but in how he says it _ with a generous gift
for inducing laughter and a kind word for all. Let that serve as a
blessing for L.A.'s newest theatrical family. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
What: ``Over the River and Through the Woods.'' &QL; 
Where: El Portal Center for the Arts, 5269 Lankershim Blvd., North
Hollywood. &QL; 
When: Through Feb. 6. Performances at 7 p.m. Tuesdays and
Wednesdays, 8 p.m. Thursdays and Fridays, 2 and 8 p.m. Saturdays, 2
and 7 p.m. Sundays. &QL; 
Tickets: $35 to $42. Call (800) 233-3123. &QL; 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1745EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
