<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-MARRIAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SERVICE MARKS ANNIVERSARY OF CONTENTIOUS LESBIAN UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Two weeks before a hearing that could put
them on trial, a group of United Methodist ministers has publicly
reaffirmed their audacious blessing of a lesbian couple a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The service, held Saturday in Sacramento's Memorial Auditorium,
celebrated the anniversary of the ``holy union'' of Jeanne Barnett
and Ellie Charlton. It also cast a spotlight on the upcoming
hearing and on a California ballot initiative against gay marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to honor Jeanne and Ellie, who stuck their necks
out last year and publicly proclaimed their love for each other in
the midst of a homophobic society,'' said the Rev. Don Fado, the
Sacramento pastor who led 67 other Methodist clergy in the ceremony
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are also here ... to make our statement to the world
again,'' added Fado, pastor at St. Mark's United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   The union ceremony made national waves because of the number of
ministers who put their jobs on the line in opposing the Methodist
policy banning such blessings for same-sex couples.
</P>
<P>
   The action also divided the Methodist Church on the issue of
homosexuality. And it sparked a complaint against the 68 pastors,
all active and retired clergy in the California-Nevada Conference
of the United Methodist Church.
</P>
<P>
   While both the Sacramento-based conference and its bishop,
Melvin Talbert, are on record supporting full equality for
homosexual church members, the complaint launched legal proceedings
within the church that could lead to a mass trial.
</P>
<P>
   A three-day public hearing, by the church's Committee on
Investigation, starts Feb. 1 to determine whether formal charges
will be brought against the pastors, who now number 67 after the
death of one last August.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's service, attended by 25 of the pastors plus
about 200 supporters, Fado said he hoped the hearing would provide
an opportunity for a ``full airing of the issues pro and con.''
</P>
<P>
   During the service, he spoke out strongly for full equality for
gays within the church, calling the position of the 68 pastors the
revolutionary equivalent of the Boston Tea Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's throw out all the T's,'' Fado said, including the ``T
for the totalitarianism that requires others to conform to any one
theology.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett and Charlton, in the twin purple appliqued sweaters they
wore for last year's ceremony, sat to the side and were applauded
by the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's service was a smaller, quieter version of the one
last year, featuring music, speeches, a procession by the pastors
and a poem and song written especially for the couple.
</P>
<P>
   Notaries were on hand to sign up couples as domestic partners
under the new state registry law. And opponents of the March ballot
initiative were gathering donations and seeking volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, Proposition 22, would outlaw state recognition
of gay marriages, should another state ever legalize them.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie McBride, a leading opponent of Proposition 22, exhorted
the audience to do everything in its power to fight what she called
``an insurance policy for bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us honor this celebration by mobilizing ourselves as
lovers, gay and straight,'' McBride said.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing, Feb. 1-3, will draw experts on Methodist scripture,
traditions and ethics from around the country, according to the
Rev. Ron Swisher of Taylor Memorial United Methodist Church of
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Lay people and clergy from both sides of the issue will testify.
The 68 clergy have filed statements with the committee explaining
their actions as acts of conscience required by their Christian
beliefs, and some may also be called to testify.
</P>
<P>
   Swisher, chair of the Committee on Investigation, said the
hearing was highly unusual because of the number of pastors
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Once they've heard all the evidence, the seven clergy members on
the committee will vote on whether the pastors should undergo a
church trial. Punishment could include losing their ordination.
</P>
<P>
   A similar trial in Omaha cost Methodist Pastor Jimmy Creech his
calling, for violating a rule outlawing the blessing of same-sex
couples that the Methodist Church passed in 1998. Until then, it
was up to each minister.
</P>
<P>
   But Creech's trial took place in a different conference which,
unlike the California-Nevada one, did not support equal treatment
of homosexuals.
</P>
</TEXT>
