<SLUG> BC-TROPICAL-RAINS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREDICTING HURRICANES' DEVASTATING RAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (Science Times)  
(DW) 
 By ROBERT A. SAAR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hurricanes are defined by wind speed _ 74 miles per hour or
higher _ but when the storms strike, it is often their heavy,
persistent rain that does the most damage. Such was the case for
Hurricane Mitch in October 1998 in Central America and to a lesser
but still impressive degree for Hurricane Floyd during September in
the eastern United States.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration are refining new methods to chart how much rain is
falling in a major tropical storm. The methods rely on satellites
set up to measure various types of energy reflected by storm
clouds: microwave, infrared or visible light. Since 1978, the
researchers have collected satellite data, largely over the United
States, that allow them to relate these energy levels to the
amounts of rain measured below the clouds by rain gauges and radar.
They say that the satellite estimates fall within 25 percent to 50
percent of the rain gauge results.
</P>
<P>
   Even with such a large margin of error, the satellite estimates
are better than nothing in areas without rain gauges, like remote
mountainous regions where some of the heaviest rain occurs and
where floods originate.
</P>
<P>
   The information can be made available within minutes after
collection and can therefore be used to provide warnings of flash
floods and to assist in relief efforts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
