<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8363 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-2TAKE     01-17 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL-SIGNS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON HEALTH PROBLEMS
</HEADLINE>
 (Science Times)  
(af)  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIAGNOSIS
</P>
<P>
   A Safer, Simpler Way to Test a Fetus
</P>
<P>
   Pregnant women who show signs that their fetuses may have
anemia, which in serious cases can require treatment even before
the baby is born, have traditionally been advised to undergo
diagnostic procedures that involve physically piercing their wombs.
</P>
<P>
   The tests are effective at confirming the disease but can cause
their own risk to the mother or fetus.
</P>
<P>
   Now a new study suggests that Doppler ultrasound may be a
simpler, safer and less expensive way to diagnose fetal anemia.
Researchers at Yale found that the blood in anemic infants moves
faster through cerebral arteries and veins than it does in healthy
infants and that the increased speeds can be detected using a
technique similar to that used by expectant mothers to determine
the health of their babies. The study was published in a recent
issue of The New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors suspect a fetus has anemia when they see irregularities
in the mother's blood. The disease, which causes an oxygen
deficiency in the baby's blood, occurs when the father and mother
have different blood types and the father's red blood antigens are
transferred to the fetus. An allergic reaction can then occur that
can kill the fetus.
</P>
<P>
   The condition occurs in about 14,000 women a year in the United
States; about 1,400 of their fetuses need transfusions.
</P>
<P>
   The current practice is to have women with signs of fetal anemia
undergo either an amniocentesis, the procedure now commonly used
for older women or those with signs of a fetal genetic disorder, or
cordocentesis, in which the umbilical cord is pierced.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do those procedures carry risk to the mother and fetus
but in most cases, they turned out to be unwarranted, said Dr.
Giancarlo Mari, the study's lead author.
</P>
<P>
   Ultrasound takes three to five minutes and poses no risks to
mother or child.
</P>
<P>
   HABITS
</P>
<P>
   For Thumb-Sucking, a Gentle Pull
</P>
<P>
   Pleading doesn't usually work. Nor do threats of dire, if
cosmetic, consequences. Even a good dollop of something yucky
doesn't seem to do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   But could a simple elastic bandage be the cure for nighttime
thumb- and digit-sucking in children? An article in a recent issue
of Pediatric Dentistry says that may well be the case.
</P>
<P>
   The author, Dr. Steven M. Adair, a professor of pediatric
dentistry at the Medical College of Georgia, says the technique has
a success rate of 60 percent. It involves wrapping an elastic
bandage from the mid-forearm to about halfway up the bicep, with
much of the bandage around the elbow, making it more difficult for
the arm to remain bent.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to create a constant, gentle tension that allows the
child to place a digit in his mouth but pulls it out when the arms
relaxes.
</P>
<P>
   Dentists and parents have long tried a variety of methods to
stop digit sucking, from swabbing fingers with unsavory substances
to retainer-like devices that prevent fingers from entering the
mouth. Most children outgrow thumb-sucking, but if it persists it
can cause embarrassment and dental problems.
</P>
<P>
   The bandage technique, Adair said, is not new, but does not
appear to be widespread. It is not, however, for everybody. The
child must express an interest in stopping, and the effort should
not be made when the child is going through a trauma like entering
a new school.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BEHAVIOR
</P>
<P>
   Trouble for Women in the Mess Hall
</P>
<P>
   A recent study of women on active duty in the Army found that
some 8 percent had eating disorders like bulimia or anorexia.
</P>
<P>
   That's not as high as the rate some studies have found among
female athletes, but higher than that found among women in general,
where the rate is about 1 percent to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study was published in the journal Medicine and Science in
Sports and Exercise and was conducted by a captain serving at the
Madigan Army Medical Center in Tacoma, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The researcher, Dr. Tamara D. Lauder, is now working at the Mayo
Clinic in Rochester, Minn.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lauder and her colleagues studied 423 enlisted women and
officers at Fort Lewis, in Washington, over a one-year period.
</P>
<P>
   She first handed out questionnaires to screen for women who
might have eating disorders, and then did follow-up interviews with
the 142 who appeared to be at risk.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, 33 were found to have diagnosable eating disorders.
Many of the women questioned admitted to practices like bingeing,
purging and taking laxatives to keep their weight down _ all of
which can have detrimental effects on health, despite the grueling
daily physical requirements of military life.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers suggested several possible factors for the high
incidence of the disorders. Chief among them were the high pressure
on women in a male environment to pass physical tests and the need
to meet weight requirements that are checked every six months.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lauder said the military should rethink its weight
requirements. ``I think maybe they have to look at whether the
standards are appropriate for all body types across the board and
for all duty roles,'' she said. ``Perhaps the standards should be
more varied.''
</P>
<P>
   PATTERNS
</P>
<P>
   In Hot Pursuit of Lou Gehrig's Killer
</P>
<P>
   A common virus related to those that cause meningitis and polio
may play a role in the debilitating illness commonly known as Lou
Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   While scientists have long suspected that the enterovirus may
play a role in the development of the disease, the new study
appears to provide the strongest evidence to date to support this
case.
</P>
<P>
   Formally known as amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, the disease
gradually paralyzes its victims before taking their lives. The
report, prepared by a team of researchers at the University of
California at Irvine and researchers in France, was published in
the current issue of the journal Neurology.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say they have not established whether the virus
causes or has any impact on the disease, which became known as Lou
Gehrig's disease after striking the New York Yankees star.
</P>
<P>
   Previous experiments into the presence of the virus were
inconclusive or conflicting. But researchers in the latest study
made use of newer, highly sensitive tests that detected the
presence of the virus from just a few scraps of the genetic
material RNA.
</P>
<P>
   When scientists studied spinal cord samples from 17 victims of
the disease, they found evidence of the enterovirus in the motor
nerve cells of 15. The virus was found in only one of 29 people
studied who had died of other causes.
</P>
<P>
   But the authors said many questions remained, among them whether
the enterovirus scraps bring about neuron death or simply represent
an irrelevant, associated phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial accompanying the study said that, if confirmed, the
findings could be useful for treating the disease.
</P>
<P>
   THERAPIES
</P>
<P>
   When a Hug Helps Relieve the Pain
</P>
<P>
   Few mothers need persuading when it comes to hugging their
newborns, but a new study suggests that encouraging them to do so
can help reduce babies' pain during a standard medical test.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after birth, tests are done on blood drawn from a baby's
heel after it is pierced with a lance. A new study on the Web site
of the journal Pediatrics reported that the pain could be reduced
if the baby experienced a skin-to-skin hug with the mother during
the lancing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Larry Gray, a Boston University pediatrician, and colleagues
videotaped 30 babies and measured their heart rates, as the blood
was drawn. Those being hugged cried and grimaced less and had a
smaller heart rate increase than their counterparts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
