<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8370 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-TITUS-FEATURE-LA     01-17 1638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TITUS-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TITUS' DIRECTOR CHALLENGES HERSELF AND MOVIEGOERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Think of it as ``King Lear'' on crack. A snuff film in iambic
pentameter. ``Spartacus'' meets Visconti's ``The Damned'' by way of
``Xena, Warrior Princess'' _ minus the pneumatic close-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead: Pick your own glib pop-culture analogy. Julie Taymor
knows it's all part of the Hollywood promotional game when you're
pushing a story as dark and difficult as Shakespeare's ``Titus
Andronicus.''
</P>
<P>
   Most movie critics were complimentary when ``Titus,'' Taymor's
film treatment of Shakespeare's bleak revenge tragedy, opened
Christmas Day in New York and Los Angeles to qualify for the
Oscars. They praised Taymor's conceptual daring in matching
Shakespeare's 400-year-old text to modern, special-effects-laden
imagery, and heaped praise on the movie's stars, Anthony Hopkins,
Jessica Lange and Alan Cumming.
</P>
<P>
   Cast members say even they were astonished at how Taymor, a 1991
recipient of a MacArthur ``genius'' Fellowship with but two short
films under her belt, took charge of ``Titus''' every detail with
complete assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew exactly what she wanted,'' says Lange. ``And visually
she's extremely creative.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real test, both for Taymor and ``Titus,'' comes Friday
when the film moves into nationwide distribution. Although
``Titus'' is riding one of Hollywood's periodic bouts of
infatuation with all things Elizabethan, that's no guarantee
``Shakespeare in Love'' fans will go ga-ga over the Bard's most
bitterly concentrated meditation on hate and its aftershocks.
</P>
<P>
   And while ``Titus''' bottom-line message is
unmistakablyanti-violence, you might not surmise that from the
surfeit of severed body parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Titus' is not an easy play to direct _ period _ and the
dangers and pitfalls are going toward total grand guignol,'' Taymor
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You read it in the press where people say, `It's his
(Shakespeare's) bloodiest this, and body counts and all,' which is
really missing the point, in a way. This story, I think, is
extremely poetic and moving !ital!about!ital! violence. It's not
that it's just a violent movie, which I don't think it is
particularly, not compared to `Braveheart' and `The Matrix' and
`Pulp Fiction.'''
</P>
<P>
   Point taken. But that still doesn't explain what Disney's
favorite avant-garde director _ the woman who brought ``The Lion
King'' to Broadway _ is doing spearheading one of the season's
least family- friendly entertainments.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the biggest challenge for some of Taymor's viewers may
be deciding which principal character churns their stomach the
least: Hopkins' brutally efficient Roman general Titus; Lange's
vengeful Goth queen Tamora; Cumming's smarmy Roman emperor
Saturninus; Harry Lennix's chillingly merciless soldier of fortune
Aaron the Moor.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Disney tapped her for ``The Lion King,'' Taymor was
an esteemed but decidedly outre director-designer of theater and
opera, known for her extravagantly imaginative productions of Carlo
Gozzi's ``The Green Bird,'' Wagner's ``The Flying Dutchman'' and
``Juan Darien _ A Carnival Mass,'' which she co-wrote with her
significant other and frequent collaborator, film composer Elliot
Goldenthal.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until ``The Lion King'' opened on Broadway in November
1997, that Taymor's celebrity began catching up with her unusual
talents. The big-budget musical, which is due to reach Los Angeles
in September, became a huge hit in New York and later in London. It
netted Taymor two Tony Awards, one for direction of a musical, the
other for costumedesign, and elevated her profile beyond the
non-profit theater world overnight.
</P>
<P>
   What made Taymor decide to tackle such a difficult, high-risk
project as ``Titus'' just when she'd broken into the commercial
mainstream?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do a very serious, important work, with the
greatest writer in the English language and the best actors,'' she
explains. ``And I could attract people like Tony and Jessica and
Alan and Harry with this material. And I think people who came
wanted to take the risk and really believed in this material and
are very excited about it. Because they didn't get paid well.
Nobody got paid well.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, paybacks have a way of taking bizarre turns, as the
characters in ``Titus'' learn to their dismay.
</P>
<P>
   Titus, Shakespeare's doomed protagonist (``hero'' doesn't quite
fit), is a by-the-book military man whose ritual sacrifice of a
Goth prisoner starts a domino chain of bloody retribution. By the
time the curtain falls, most of the major players have been maimed,
raped, murdered, cannibalized or several of the above.
</P>
<P>
   Even some cast members, though they liked the play's
over-the-top quality, were caught offguard by its inordinate
bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first read it, I thought, `What a great yarn,''' says
Cumming, the Scottish actor who won a Tony Award for his
performance as the emcee in the recent ``Cabaret'' revival.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when I saw it, I thought, `Jesus, I can't believe this is
a Shakespeare play.' It's like a sort of snuff film. Too much. And
I loved that. But the film sort of confounds people's expectations,
and the play confounds your expectations of Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   Other actors, such as Lange, thought Shakespeare's script had
some ``big holes in it, to tell you the truth,'' but took to the
story anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the play at all, I'm sorry to admit,'' Lange
says. ``But the script was sent to me, I read the script, then I
read the play. I was kind of amazed. I thought it was really out
there. I liked it right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after the so-called ``revenge dramas'' of the ancient
Roman scribe Seneca, ``Titus Andronicus'' was written around 1594
as a warm-up to the great Shakespearean tragedies that began six or
seven years later with ``Julius Caesar.''
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, ``Titus'' has suffered by comparison with
sacrosanct masterpieces like ``Hamlet'' and ``Macbeth.'' Polite
Victorians blanched at its operatic excesses.
</P>
<P>
   It took Peter Brooks' landmark 1955 production at
Stratford-upon-Avon, with Laurence Olivier, to redeem the play's
reputation. Yet even today it's rarely performed by the leading
British and North American Shakespeare companies.
</P>
<P>
   Taymor, however, thinks that what made ``Titus'' seem ``crude''
and ``unrefined'' to previous generations _ ``that sort of direct,
youthful, angry, nasty, visceral Shakespeare'' _ is exactly what
makes it speak to modern audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare was (writing) for the masses in the Elizabethan
era, and that's much closer to our time now,'' Taymor says. ``You
know, they'd walk down the street and they'd see an execution,
public execution. That was entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from the amoral horror story it's been typecast as, Taymor
considers ``Titus'' to be a bitterly humorous, deeply ethical play
that raises troubling questions about why societies condemn some
forms of violence, but permit or even champion others.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Shakespeare's done is something that is so complex and
disturbing because he explores all the various kinds of violence on
every single level _ from war and that kind of heroic, courageous,
condoned violence to nihilistic violence, to infanticide, to lust,
rape _ and he puts it all on one level. And he says, `If you
justify one, then the result, the cycle of vengeance will just keep
spiraling and spiraling.'''
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize ``Titus''' timelessness and universality, Taymor
decided to shoot much of the film in Rome, where Imperial Roman
grandeur and Mussolini-esque pomposity can be viewed side by side,
where ancient ruins jostle pointedly with monumental fascist
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Other location shooting was done in war-torn Kosovo, enhancing
the film's sense of taking place in a time warp of human tragedy,
extending from the pre-Christian era to the present.
</P>
<P>
   To further that effect, Taymor and her design team blended
costumes, military weaponry, musical motifs and architectural
styles from different historical epochs. They also interspersed the
movie with surrealistic montages, providing a layer of
psychological commentary not found in Shakespeare's original play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that mixture,'' Taymor explains. ``I love to take
something, magical-realist, whatever you want to call it. I love to
open it up and show you different ways of seeing the mundane and
the regular, and that's what art is supposed to do anyway: to put a
different mirror on your life, so you re-examine everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Cast members say that Taymor's creative intensity helped color
the entire film-making experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a fiery set, I'll tell you,'' Cumming says.
``We all got on great, but you know the play is kind of fiery. And
being in Italy is fiery. And making a film in Rome is fiery-fiery!
You know, everyone shouts all the time, and so the whole atmosphere
was kind of hysterical, which was, in retrospect, great for the
movie, but at the time it was like, `Please stop shouting! Don't
give me any more espresso!'''
</P>
<P>
   Taymor hopes that with Fox Searchlight's backing, ``Titus'' may
find an audience beyond the typical ``Shakespeare lover,
sophisticated art-house crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some inner-city high school kids in New York see it
and they said, `Move over, Schwarzenegger,''' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Ah-nold could reprise his Conan the Barbarian persona to
star in Taymor's next project, an opera based on the novel
``Grendel,'' John Gardiner's 1971 reimagining of the medieval epic
poem ``Beowulf'' told from the monster's point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Taymor laughs at her penchant for seeking the present in the
long-ago and far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to have different ways of telling the old story,'' she
says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
