<HEADER>
A8371 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MLK-GORE-COX     01-17 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-GORE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore promises funding to help restore MLK's church
 &HT;    By Ernie Suggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Standing at the very pulpit and in the footsteps of
Martin Luther King Jr., Vice President Al Gore announced Monday
that money would soon pour in to restore Ebenezer Baptist Church to
its original glory.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking at Monday's Martin Luther King, Jr. Annual
Commemorative Service, announced that $500,000 from two private
donors will be added to $500,000 already set aside by the federal
government to restore the historic sanctuary at Ebenezer, where
King, his grandfather, father and brother preached.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also announced that the Clinton administration will ask
Congress for $1.5 million in the 2001 budget to help protect King's
birthplace on Atlanta's Auburn Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``His home is literally the cradle of America's Civil Rights
Movement,'' said Gore. ``This pulpit, this simple place, with
wooden steps, is sacred ground. We must preserve this place and
preserve the spirit of this place for future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was a special guest at Monday's ecumenical service. He was
joined by a host of dignitaries, including Rep. John Lewis, Mayor
Bill Campbell, Gov. Roy Barnes, Bishop Eddie Long of New Birth
Missionary Baptist Church, Sen. Paul Coverdell, and New Jersey
State Secretary DeForest B. Soaries, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of the morning, the rafters of the creaky, old
church shook as speakers took turns praising King. None more
prominently than King's youngest daughter, the Rev. Bernice
Albertine King, the only one to follow him to the pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over the ceremony with her aunt, Christine King
Farris, Bernice King brought the congregation to its feet at least
a half dozen times, harkening memories of her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we move into the 21st century, it's going to be incumbent
upon all of us to realize that while Martin Luther King Jr. was a
great and awesome man, that we too have a calling and assignment in
this life,'' Bernice King said. ``Today, God is calling upon all of
us to look at ourselves and ask the question, `What is it that I am
to do to further the cause of freedom, justice and equality?'''
</P>
<P>
   But her most stirring comments came in defense of her mother,
Coretta Scott King, who has often been criticized for her role in
how King's image is being handled and marketed.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is not worthy of the criticism she has received, and
unless you have cried like she has, had to raise four children
without a husband, with little or no money, then you don't know,''
said Bernice King. ``So I say to my brothers and sisters: 'leave my
mama alone.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. King joked that she could take care of herself, then
reminded the audience that under the Clinton-Gore administration,
blacks have seen many political, social and economic gains. Gore
countered that still not enough has been done and told the audience
not to be satisfied with the successes achieved by King during the
civil rights campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, 32 years after we lost him, America still needs the
soaring dream of Martin Luther King Jr.,'' Gore said. ``Martin,
where are you? We need your prophetic voice, and we hear it now
even from the grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore added that King would not be fully satisfied with where the
country is right now, despite the gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Dr. King were with us, he would celebrate our gains, but he
would then turn us to the hard work that is still undone,'' Gore
said. ``Dr. King reminds us that that truth is marching on. There
is no such thing as partial freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said freedom will come when everyone has health coverage,
teachers are respected and black and Hispanic men aren't stopped on
the highway by police simply because they are black and Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the progress we have made, we still have to renew and
build that beloved community that Dr. King spoke about,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore later joined Mrs. King, Bernice King and Dexter Scott King
in placing two wreaths in front of King's grave.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the most moving and best celebration we have ever
had,'' said Dexter King, chairman of King Center. ``I think we are
kicking this century in good.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Suggs writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
