<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8377 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT &LR;      01-17 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIMID KILLER ASTEROIDS  
 RE-INVENTING RICE  
 THE TINIEST ICE CUBE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Science Times)  
(af) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hooray for Hollywood. All those recent movies about killer
asteroids seem to have scared half of them away. (Think about it:
would you want Bruce Willis and a gang of crazed wildcatters coming
after you?)
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Hollywood cannot take any credit here. What has
happened is that a team of researchers, using improved detection
techniques, has determined that the number of near-Earth asteroids
capable of causing catastrophe is about half that of previous
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, from Yale and the Jet Propulsion Laboratory,
used an automated tracking program in conjunction with a telescope
in Hawaii to search systematically for potential Earth-killers,
which have diameters from about half a mile to six miles.
</P>
<P>
   After searching part of the sky for two years, they used
computer simulations to come up with a total estimate, which, they
report in the journal Nature, is about 700. Previous estimates were
1,000 to 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Earth, the smaller number does not
substantially change the risk factor, which though very small is
real (to paraphrase a popular bumper sticker, just one killer
asteroid can ruin your whole day). But the researchers note that
with the smaller estimate, and with improved detection techniques,
90 percent of these asteroids should be located within two decades,
giving scientists and policy makers a better idea of what, if
anything, to do about them. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin A deficiency is a serious problem in developing
countries, affecting at least 125 million children worldwide and
causing, among other things, partial or complete blindness. It is a
particular problem in cultures where rice is a staple food, as
milled rice contains none of the vitamin.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers in Switzerland and Germany may have come up with a
solution. As reported in the journal Science, they have genetically
engineered rice to produce beta-carotene in the endosperm _ the
starchy, edible portion of the grain. (Beta-carotene is converted
by the body into vitamin A.)
</P>
<P>
   The work required inserting three genes from different sources
into the rice plant, in effect introducing the entire pathway by
which beta-carotene is produced. Most efforts at genetically
engineering plants have involved only one gene.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting rice grains are a golden yellow color and should,
the researchers suggest, provide a significant amount of the
vitamin. The goal is to establish breeding lines of the engineered
rice and make it available to farmers in developing countries. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It might not put much of a chill on your mai tai, but scientists
at the University of North Carolina have created the world's
tiniest ice cube.
</P>
<P>
   The cube, really more of a hexagon, consists of just six
molecules of water in a flat ring, which is the way ice occurs in
nature. Since even a tiny chip of ice contains many billions of
these rings, the research will allow scientists to study the
hydrogen bonding that occurs when water freezes without being
encumbered by all those other molecules.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier attempts to create a single ice ring had failed, with
the molecules' collapsing into a denser, cagelike structure that is
not like real ice. (In nature, ice does not have this problem
because it has a three-dimensional structure that keeps the
molecules in the proper position.)
</P>
<P>
   The Carolina researchers used liquid helium to grow the ice
rings at a very low temperature. Low temperature means low energy,
so the molecules did not have the energy to rearrange themselves
into the cage-like shape.
</P>
<P>
   The research should eventually help scientists understand more
about basic molecular interactions that will help with the design
of pharmaceuticals and other compounds. To that end, the next step
for the Carolina researchers will be to introduce other small
molecules to see how the water molecules interact with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
