<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8381 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-EDGERTON-PHOTOS-N     01-17 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-EDGERTON-PHOTOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO STOPPED TIME AND OPENED WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Neb., Mass.)   (Science Times)  
(af) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Harold E. Edgerton was a wizard of invention who changed the
way people see things. The flash of his camera opened up hidden
worlds of motion: of golf clubs flattening apparently rigid balls,
of drops of milk forming crowns of splattered droplets, of beetles
firing seemingly fluid secretions in what turned out to be rapid
pulses. His photographs revealed the drama hidden in the
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   A born showman, Edgerton communicated his love of science and
discovery to students and peers at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, where he worked and taught for more than six decades.
</P>
<P>
   The luckiest worked with ``Doc'' Edgerton in Strobe Alley, the
campus laboratory where he and his cohorts invented the machines
that illuminated unseen worlds.
</P>
<P>
   A Nebraska native, Edgerton died in January 1990 at 86. But his
work lives on, and this month, MIT Press released a multimedia
CD-ROM, ``Exploring the Art and Science of Stopping Time: The Life
and Work of Harold E. Edgerton.'' The CD ($37.95) runs on Macintosh
or Windows, contains hundreds of Edgerton's photos, explains how
they were made and recounts the inventor's life, often in his own
voice. Made for middle and high school students, and curious
adults, the CD also lets scholars simulate some of Edgerton's
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   His main tool was the stroboscope, which he perfected in 1931.
Like the electronic flash on a camera, the stroboscope fired a
brilliant light. But its flash tube did so repeatedly and quickly
in a series of bursts of very short duration, allowing an
accompanying camera or human eye to capture very fast motions.
</P>
<P>
   Edgerton trained his new tool on a wide range of subjects.
Perhaps the most famous early use of the stroboscope was in a
lawsuit between Lever Brothers and Procter &AMP; Gamble on rival
methods of making soap powder, the CD-ROM recounts. Stroboscopic
movies provided visual proof that while the two methods looked
alike, under the surface they were different. The suit was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1930s, he had embarked on his lifelong effort to
unveil the everyday: tennis players hitting serves, water running
from a faucet, and all sorts of creatures in flight. In 1940, his
flash caught Judy Garland and Mickey Rooney in mid-song, and a
10-minute movie of his, ``Quicker Than a Wink,'' won an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, his strobes were used for aerial
reconnaissance, and after the war, he helped photograph and analyze
the blinding flash of atom bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Later in life, he published many articles and photographs in
National Geographic, including ones revealing the delicate wing
movements of hummingbirds. Some of Edgerton's most enthusiastic
work focused on undersea archaeology, marine life and treasure
hunting, where his innovative lights and cameras often illuminated
inky realms of pitch blackness. It was his camera system that first
illuminated the Titanic's ghostly hulk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man was a lot of fun,'' recalled Emory Kristof, a National
Geographic photographer who accompanied Edgerton on a 1976
expedition to hunt for the Loch Ness monster. ``He would play the
guitar and stay up all night long.''
</P>
<P>
   The main CD-ROM screen shows three doors that lead to three
aspects of Edgerton's life. The Biography door tells his story in
text and films, including those of Air Force reconnaissance and
undersea photography. The Lab door, labeled ``Strobe Alley,'' lets
explorers do experiments on flowing water, bursting balloons and
bouncing balls. The Work Archive door leads to a photographic
exhibit of Edgerton's work.
</P>
<P>
   James Sheldon, a photographer who produced the CD-ROM and runs
the new media program at Emerson College, Boston, said Edgerton
resonated especially deeply with children, making a tour of his
life for students quite fitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an amazing knack to get you to open your eyes and
explore,'' Sheldon said. ``He did that with kids on a constant
basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
