<HEADER>
A8382 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-UPS18-COX     01-17 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS sees bright future in financial services unit
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ United Parcel Service, which has stretched its
strategic horizons beyond basic delivery service in recent years,
is dipping a Big Brown toe into financial services.
</P>
<P>
   UPS is extending loans to customers and offering advance
payments on certain transactions and accounts receivables. It's
even leasing office and warehouse equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Why would the shipping giant bother with such transactions?
</P>
<P>
   ``Cash flow is the lifeblood of any business,'' said Bob
Bernabucci, president of UPS Capital, the subsidiary managing the
raft of new financial products. By helping shippers solve cash-flow
problems, UPS helps them grow into bigger shippers.
</P>
<P>
   The move also fits with UPS' broader strategy of embedding
itself in the business processes of shipping customers _ making it
harder for them to bolt to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Worldwide Logistics subsidiary, for instance,
provides an array of supply-chain management services and is UPS'
fastest-growing unit.
</P>
<P>
   Other UPS subsidiaries sell software to facilitate e-commerce,
which accounts for a growing chunk of the delivery business.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching financial products is the next step in that strategy,
Bernabucci said. The move, which began with UPS Capital's 1998
formation, reflects the change in corporate thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had talked about this five years ago, it would have been
dismissed as a wild idea,'' said Bernabucci, a veteran of UPS'
finance division.
</P>
<P>
   Financing can be a lucrative sidelight for cash-rich
corporations like UPS, which had $27 billion in revenue last year
and pulled off a $5.5 billion initial public offering. A prime
example is General Electric's huge GE Capital Services unit.
</P>
<P>
   UPS Capital is still relatively tiny, with just 62 employees.
Bernabucci said that number could double this year, and a marketing
campaign ramps up this winter.
</P>
<P>
   The unit offers to credit the accounts of cash-on-delivery
shippers within two days of delivery. Normally the process can take
a week or more, tying up precious cash.
</P>
<P>
   Computer giant Gateway is already using the service, but it's
also aimed at making COD shipments more workable for Internet
mom-and-pops whose customers are reluctant to pay for goods in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   UPS Capital also is making advance payments on accounts
receivables, targeting smaller companies that grapple with payment
delays.
</P>
<P>
   The office equipment leasing service provides everything from
copiers and computers to warehouse machinery. UPS doesn't own the
items but will finance leases.
</P>
<P>
   Bernabucci said the unit's goal is not simply to fuel shipping
growth for UPS' core business but to turn a profit in its own
right.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Thurston writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
