A8384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-JAPAN-PHARMACEUTICALS     01-17 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-PHARMACEUTICALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN DRUG MAKER SEES PROFIT POTENTIAL IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In another sign of deregulation's ability to pry open
the Japanese economy and breath new life into businesses here,
Boehringer Ingelheim, a large German pharmaceuticals company,
started a tender offer Monday for shares of SS Pharmaceuticals Co.,
a Japanese drug maker.
</P>
<P>
   Boehringer, which has had a 19.6 percent stake in SS
Pharmaceuticals since 1996, is seeking to capitalize on the
increasing deregulation of the over-the-counter drug market. Its
goal is to attain at least a 33.4 percent stake in the company,
which would give it a seat on the board and a limited ability to
veto decisions, including the ability to thwart other potential
suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the Japanese pharmaceuticals industry has largely sat
out the consolidation that is affecting its counterparts overseas,
deterred by heavy regulation and onerous drug-approval procedures.
</P>
<P>
   But the government is slowly releasing its grip on some parts of
the industry, choosing last April to allow the sale of some
over-the-counter pharmaceuticals in convenience stores. Those
products _ including throat lozenges, antacids, antiseptic creams
and sprays, and vitamins C and E, as well as calcium _ had
previously been available only in pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deregulation of the industry makes Japan an attractive place
for any pharmaceutical company operating on a global basis,'' said
Rolf Krebs, vice chairman of Boehringer.
</P>
<P>
   Boehringer is offering to buy SS Pharmaceutical shares at 1,100
yen apiece, or about $10.44 at current exchange rates, a 41 percent
premium to the closing price on Friday. It will pay a 13.2 percent
premium to buy the company's convertible bonds.
</P>
<P>
   It values SS Pharmaceuticals at 134.6 billion yen, or roughly
$1.28 billion.
</P>
<P>
   SS Pharmaceuticals, which manufactures over-the-counter and
prescription drugs as well as various types of vitamin supplements
and tonics, has a vast distribution network and its own chain of
stores. The company said it learned last week of Boehringer's
interest in increasing its stake.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese company has been particularly successful at
exploiting new distribution channels in the wake of the recent
deregulation. It announced last fall that it expected its profits
for the fiscal year that ends March 31 to more than double on the
strength of sales of metabolic stimulants, or so-called energy
drinks, through convenience stores.
</P>
<P>
   The drinks, which often contain Chinese herbs, snake oil and
other homeopathic types of ingredients, are wildly popular here
despite their often high cost. Their effects are rather like those
of appetite suppressants.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also had great success in repackaging a
27-year-old hangover cure, Hi-Tiol C, as a means of lightening
freckles and other spots on the skin. Sales before the makeover
were about 2 billion yen a year, or about $19 million, but have
risen to over 6 billion yen. ``There is an increase in women
users,'' Yukinobu Kubota, a spokesman for SS Pharmaceuticals, said.
</P>
<P>
   Boehringer has been selling various over-the-counter drugs in
Japan through SS Pharmaceuticals, which is in the midst of seeking
approval for a drug developed by Boehringer to fight chronic
bronchitis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
