<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV19-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVICE FOR OSHA ON THE HAZARDS OF WORKING AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Wednesday, Jan. 19)  
(DW) 
 By DAVID GRIMES Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was hurt and not a little bit offended that the Occupational
Safety and Health Administration backed off the idea of barging
into the houses of people who work at home to make sure they are
complying with all federal health and safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   As one of 20 million Americans who works at home, I can tell you
that a telecommuter's life can be a lonely one and that there are
many of us who would have found the sound of heavy boots kicking in
our front door a welcome interruption to our dull, dreary routines.
</P>
<P>
   Call me an incurable romantic, but to me nothing breaks up the
day like a beefy federal agent leading me away in handcuffs for
having an insufficient wattage bulb in my desk lamp or for leaving
old newspapers scattered about in a way that could cause people to
trip and fall.
</P>
<P>
   The message that OSHA puts out, by rescinding its directive, is
that doing office work at home is not dangerous enough to warrant
its involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Secretary Alexis Herman said as much when she told
reporters that OSHA's concern with work at home has always involved
hazardous jobs such as building fireworks and that she does not
consider working from home at a computer to be ``high risk.''
</P>
<P>
   While I would agree with Ms. Herman that people who work from
home are unlikely to make the kind of mistake that breaks windows a
mile away and creates a 30-foot-deep crater where their house used
to be, our occupation is not without its hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommuting is a lot more than sitting at your kitchen table
in your underwear staring at a computer screen, which is not to say
that these activities are entirely risk-free. (Spilling coffee on
your lap can result in far more painful burns than if you were
wearing pants.)
</P>
<P>
   Even as we speak, I am experiencing discomfort in my wrist from
holding up my head with my hand, trying to think what to write
next. Also, my back is stiffening up from sitting in my
ergonomically incorrect office chair, which even the most
unobservant OSHA agent would surely recognize as an old stool.
</P>
<P>
   I am trying to write fast because a TV show I like comes on at
noon, and that is causing a tension headache directly above my
right eye. Sometimes it is difficult to go back to work after a
hard half-hour of TV watching, and that leads to a mild case of
depression that might require a long nap (possibility of traumatic
nightmares and pillow hair) followed by a dip in the pool (chlorine
blur, swimsuit chafe).
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that means that I miss my deadline, resulting in a
snippy call from my editor, sendingme spiraling into a black hole
of self-recrimination, the only cure for which is 18 holes of golf
(sunburn, compulsive gambling disorder).
</P>
<P>
   All of which explains who so many people who work from home on
their computers describe the life as a ``treadmill' or a ``living
hell'' depending on what kind of cable package they subscribe to.
</P>
<P>
   Just because we don't blow ourselves up on a regular basis like
fireworks-builders do, OSHA seems to be of the opinion that
telecommuting is nothing more than a quiet day in the den where the
biggest hazard is jabbing yourself in the eye with a bologna
sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, nothing could be further from the truth, which is why I
hope OSHA eventually starts sending out agents to make home
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   While he's on his way, if the agent that comes to my house could
pick up a couple of videos and tube of sun screen, so much the
better.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
