<SLUG> BC-STATES-WEALTH-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        DISPARITY OF WEALTH WIDENED IN 1990s, STUDY SAYS 
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Jan. 17 - Despite economic prosperity and low
unemployment, the income gap between the rich and poor widened in
the nation and in Texas in the 1990s, continuing a trend of
disparity of wealth from the 1970s, according to a new report.
</P>
<P>
   While the wealthiest Texans have seen steady income gains over
the past 20 years, the report shows middle and lower classes have
hardly benefited. The richest fifth of Texas families saw their
income jump 23 percent from the late 1970s to the 1990s, but the
poorest fifth of Texas residents saw their incomes fall by 9
percent, and the middle fifth drop by 4 percent, over the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   The state-by-state study, released this week by two left-leaning
think tanks, the Economic Policy Institute and the Center on Budget
and Policy Priorities, is based on the latest Census statistics of
income before taxes. The capital gains tax and the cash welfare
system were not factored in the study.
</P>
<P>
   While the richest fifth of Americans saw their income grow 15
percent from the late 1980s to the late 1990s, the incomes of the
poorest and middle fifths remained relatively unchanged, growing by
one and two percent, respectively. The richest 5 percent of the
country saw their incomes jump 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study said income inequality is caused in part by an uneven
wage scale. ``Wages at the bottom and middle of the wage scale have
been stagnant or have declined over the last two decades,'' the
report said. ``The wages of the very highest paid employees,
however, have grown significantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Veitch, chair of the economics department at the
University of San Francisco, said he was skeptical of the report's
findings that poor families' income stagnated in the 1990s, given
the country's low unemployment rate, rising productivity, low
inflation and a hike in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas and eight other states, including New York, Arizona,
Louisiana, New Mexico and California, the average income in the
late 1990s of the richest fifth of families was more than 11 times
greater than the average income of families in the bottom fifth of
the income scale. For Texas, the top fifth made an average of
$130,302, compared to $11,200 for the bottom fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' trend of declining wages for the state's middle class
over the long term was not replicated nationwide. The middle fifth
of families nationwide have seen their income go up by 5 percent
from the late 1970s to the late 1990s, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, ``it's not just the people at the bottom that are
falling behind,'' said Dick Lavine, senior fiscal analyst at the
Center for Public Policy Priorities in Austin. ``The main issue is
that everybody contributed to the economic growth, but only the top
fifth have really benefited.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavine said in Texas, a lack of access to education is a reason
for the disparity. Also, high technology industries have given a
financial boost to the wealthiest but not the poorest, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
