<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8391 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-EVIL-EMPIRE-MISSILES-     01-17 1973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVIL-EMPIRE-MISSILES-TWO-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WE WILL BURY YOU' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This is Part II of a three-part series by Sergei Khrushchev
about the Cold War from the Soviet perspective. To publish it as a
``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times Syndicate sales
representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By SERGEI KHRUSHCHEV  
 c.2000 American Heritage  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   My father, Nikita Khrushchev, did not doubt the superiority and
greater economic efficiency of socialism over capitalism, and was
sure that sooner or later capitalism would die out and that he
would bury it.
</P>
<P>
   Father wanted to have a look, however fleeting, at what Soviet
life would be like under true communism _ in other words, when
Russians lived no worse than Americans, those very Americans who
dreamed of destroying communism.
</P>
<P>
   But, as he said in one of his speeches in the United States,
``You Americans work better than we do and produce goods that we
can only dream about, so we will learn from you; we will study
diligently. And once we've learned, we'll begin working better than
you. And you will just have to jump onto the running board of the
train of socialism, which is leaving for the future. Otherwise,
you'll be left far behind and we will wave good-bye from the rear
platform of the last car.''
</P>
<P>
   Father believed that the governmental system that gave people
the best living standards would win. That was the sole criterion.
Nothing would help the losing side _ not nuclear bombs, ideological
dogmas or propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   To the end of his life, he was convinced that Soviet socialism
would come out on top, and he died secure in that belief. His goal
was never to win by competition in the field of weaponry. He was
not captivated by the missile race or even by the space race.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his slogan became the ``food race.'' Fences, walls of
buildings and outdoor billboards were plastered with signs,
reading: ``Catch up and pass the United States in per capita
production of meat, milk and butter.'' In fact, we were in no
condition to compete in this sphere. Our people were emerging
painfully from a condition of semistarvation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, only a madman or traitor could neglect the nation's
security during the Cold War. Because we sorely lacked resources,
our most important decision would be how to strengthen the
country's security at the same time as reducing military spending.
</P>
<P>
   Father believed that future local wars could not be waged
without nuclear weapons. This, he thought, made it senseless to
maintain a gigantic army. Nor would it make sense to continue
pouring money into conventional weapons, so he proposed reducing
the Soviet production of tanks, cannons and tactical aircraft. Of
course the military opposed this with all its might.
</P>
<P>
   The military professionals were demanding that the Soviet army,
air force and navy be given equipment precisely symmetrical to all
that of the mighty U.S. military. However, this would have consumed
all our nation's financial resources, leaving nothing in the budget
for housing or to provide people with normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Father chose a different path. He tried to make the admirals and
generals understand that the United States was much wealthier than
we were. If we competed with the Americans on that basis, he
reasoned, we would spend all our resources in vain and bring the
country to ruin, and even then not reach parity.
</P>
<P>
   In one meeting, when the military stood its ground Father
angrily exclaimed, ``You'll leave the country stark naked!''
</P>
<P>
   Father finally decided to make use of his power and authority.
He made the tough decision to formulate an asymmetrical defense
doctrine. He thought that we ourselves could determine the
necessary minimum to ensure the country's security _ and whatever
we didn't need we would ruthlessly eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   He started with the navy. Stalin had planned to build an
oceangoing surface fleet able to compete with America's. Our
admirals needed about 130 billion rubles (roughly $32.5 billion) in
the 1955-'65 period to carry out the second stage of Stalin's
program _ an enormous sum. The only way to get it was to cut funds
for essential human needs.
</P>
<P>
   Discussion of the program continued for about a year with no
progress. Once, Father posed a direct question to the navy's
commander in chief, Adm. Nikolai Kuznetsov: ``If today, and not 10
years from now, you had all the ships you're asking for, could you
defeat the Americans at sea?''
</P>
<P>
   The admiral gave a militarily direct answer: ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   The discussion ended with the decision to stop building a
surface fleet and limit construction to submarines, primarily
missile submarines, and antisubmarine and shore-defense forces.
</P>
<P>
   To this day the Russian naval officers have never forgiven
Father, but he simply would not give them money to waste.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat later, strategic aviation met a similar fate. Its
development was held to a minimum, while preference was given to
ballistic missiles. From then on, our air force officers also
disliked Father.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, by 1956, only one type of Soviet ballistic missile was
being built, the R-5M, with a nuclear warhead of 70 kilotons. The
USSR had a total of 426 nuclear warheads. In comparison, the United
States had an overall nuclear superiority 10.8 times greater.
</P>
<P>
   And so, believing it was necessary to restrain the West from a
possible attack on the Soviet Union, Father decided to resort to
bluff and intimidation. For example, in April 1956, during his
visit to England he casually inquired _ during an official lunch
and again over tea at the fireplace of the prime minister's country
residence at Chequers _ if his hosts knew how many nuclear warheads
it would take to wipe their island off the face of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   An awkward silence followed.
</P>
<P>
   But with a broad smile on his face, Father informed those
present that if they didn't know, he could help them _ and he
mentioned a specific number. Then he added, quite cheerfully, ``And
we have lots of those nuclear warheads, as well as the missiles to
deliver them.''
</P>
<P>
   From then on Father reacted just as sharply to every crisis in
the vicinity of the Soviet Union, whether in the Near East, the Far
East or Europe. By frightening the world with the idea of Soviet
missile superiority, he hoped our side would be taken as equal to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It was in those years that he used the famous phrase, ``We are
producing missiles like sausages.''
</P>
<P>
   When I asked him how he could say that _ we knew, after all,
that the Soviet Union had no more than half a dozen
intercontinental missiles _ Father only laughed: ``We're not
planning to start a war, so it doesn't matter how many missiles are
deployed. The main thing is that Americans think we have enough for
a powerful strike in response. So they'll be wary of attacking
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of the ``global nuclear ballistic missile contest''
was similar. The project required launching a nuclear warhead into
an earth orbit. Then, at the command from earth, it would explode
over an enemy on a trajectory that couldn't be predicted by any
sort of antimissile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   The organization where I worked, which was located in a
carefully guarded area, had several even-more-secret rooms where we
worked on our new superweapon.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, just a few months after we started, Father joyfully
informed journalists at a press conference that the Soviet Union
would soon possess a global missile, a weapon against which no
defense existed. I was profoundly upset and thought of his
loquaciousness as a betrayal of our national interests.
</P>
<P>
   That evening during a walk I voiced my complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't tell me you thought the government would actually allow
someone to launch a nuclear warhead into orbit,'' he retorted with
amazement. ``What if something happened to it in orbit, in space?
We would be hostages to our own thoughtlessness. The global missile
is a propaganda weapon. Let the Americans rack their brains over
what I said.''
</P>
<P>
   Now here is the truth: Such statements by Father were in fact
received with enthusiasm in the West because they made it easier
for the U.S. military to receive additional funds. The missile race
was born and gained strength, as John F. Kennedy entered the White
House. Yet all along this race, which never existed _ or rather, in
which America alone took part _ was an internal U.S. competition to
see which branch of the military could grab more funds from the
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Insofar as there was a real race, the United States always led.
For example, large numbers of the UR-100 (SS-11) light ballistic
missiles were deployed in the Soviet Union, beginning in 1967, five
years later than the analogous U.S. Minuteman I. The CIA surely
knew this, but the myth of Soviet superiority was useful, or seemed
useful, not so much to the Soviets and my father as to the American
military-industrial complex.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower understood this very well. He and Father met at Camp
David in September of 1959. One day, as they were walking and
chatting, Eisenhower brought up the subject of relations with the
military, asking Father how he coped with his generals. Father
reacted cautiously. He was not prepared to discuss such a sensitive
subject with an American president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I'll start,'' said Eisenhower, smiling. ``My military
leaders come to me several times a year to ask for additional
appropriations for new types of weapons. When I reply that the
budget has been approved and printed and there's no place to find
the money, they begin frightening me by saying that the Soviet
Union is already developing such 'toys,' and I'll be responsible if
the United States is defeated in a future war. Naturally then, I
have to give them the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Father replied that he too was often subjected to such pressure
from his own military-industrial complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we should make a secret agreement between us to curb our
military,'' Eisenhower proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be good,'' Father responded. ``But the time has not
yet come.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the moment for confidential relations between Soviet and
American leaders truly had not yet come but by 1959, a great deal
had changed. Eisenhower and Father had learned to talk to each
other, and the first signs of mutual confidence had appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Thus a foundation was built for the future negotiations between
Father and President John F. Kennedy, between Leonid Brezhnev and a
series of U.S. presidents, as well as between Mikhail Gorbachev and
Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   By the time President Kennedy was in office, both sides valued
the need for direct contact. In other words, they had started to
trust each other and believe in the value of a dialogue devoted to
preventing a nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c.2000 American Heritage &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEXT: Part III _ Father, Castro, Kennedy and The Cuban Missile
Crisis &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sergei Khrushchev is a senior fellow at the Thomas J. Watson
Jr. Center for International Studies at Brown University. His book,
``The Creation of a Superpower,'' will be published by Penn State
University Press in the fall of 2000. Sergei Khrushchev and his
wife, Valentina Golenko, reside in Rhode Island. They became
citizens of the United States in 1999.) &LR;
