A8395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-EVEREST-REVIEW-NYT     01-17 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EVEREST-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOST ON EVEREST': CLUES BUT NO ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end of review; check local times)  
 (bl)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday night's installment of ``Nova'' on PBS tugs you into two
real-life dramas that unfolded, 75 years apart, on the frozen
slopes of Mount Everest. At times, the effort to keep the threads
of the two untangled seem as dizzying as the thin Himalayan air,
but you'll find the effort exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   In 1924, when no one had yet climbed to Everest's 29,000-foot
summit, the British adventurer George Mallory (the man who said he
wanted to conquer Everest ``because it is there'') made his third
ascent of the mountain in the company of a countryman, Andrew
Irvine. The two men were last seen by other members of their party
some 1,000 feet below the mountain's summit, the highest point on
Earth. What happened to them and whether they made it to the top
remained mysteries.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, members of an expedition organized by ``Nova'' sought
to solve those mysteries and to add their own names to the select
list of successful visitors to the top of the world. (Sir Edmund
Hillary and Tenzing Norgay, who reached the summit in 1953, are
credited with being the first to do so. Since then, about 600
others have also made it to the top.)
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's hourlong film, ``Lost on Everest,'' is as
deliberate as an experienced climber. It introduces Mallory and his
era, through historical film and photographs, and takes you along
with his modern successors, who are all eager to offer chipper
monologues for the camera, even at such heights. They seem to feel
obliged not only to speak about Mallory but to speak for him as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everest was regarded as the third pole,'' said Graham Hoyland,
a member of the ``Nova'' team whose great-uncle was in Mallory's
group. ``The South Pole and the North Pole had been done, and this
was the last big challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvine's ice ax had been found in the 1930s, and in 1975 a
Chinese climber, who died shortly afterward, reported seeing a body
high on Everest that he described as ``an English dead.'' That body
may be Irvine's and may still be on the mountain, but last year's
expedition chanced upon Mallory's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked over to my right,'' says one of the team members,
Conrad Anker, ``and I saw a patch of white that wasn't a rock, and
it wasn't snow.'' It was Mallory's skin, still showing the
black-and-blue marks of bruises sustained in a fall that may have
led to his death. (The body is shown briefly and discreetly.) His
pockets yielded a knife, a pair of snow goggles, a pencil, a tube
of zinc oxide and other items, but not the camera that the
searchers hoped would tell them whether Mallory reached the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the ``Nova'' climbers, in high-tech gear undreamed of in
Mallory's day, set out for the top, and two made it, but they
couldn't tote their camera on that last leg either. So while the
film, written and produced by Liesl Clark, contains some
breathtaking vistas, that ultimate view, although it has been
filmed by other expeditions, remains just out of reach for Tuesday
night's armchair adventurers.
</P>
<P>
   Everest still holds some secrets. The ``Nova'' climbers are
divided about whether Mallory made it to the top. Maybe Irvine, and
that camera, will someday be found. Then again, maybe some
mysteries are better left unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   NOVA
</P>
<P>
   `Lost on Everest'
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday night
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 13, New York, at 9)
</P>
<P>
   Paula S. Apsell, executive producer. A Nova/BBC co-production in
association with ZDF. Written and produced by Liesl Clark. Produced
for the BBC by Peter Firstbrook.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
