<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8396 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TVTOUR18-COX     01-17 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVTOUR18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPN: The Testosterone Channel
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Hammer locks and guys in masks. A water skier
on a lake of fire. Monster trucks rolling over each other.
</P>
<P>
   UPN is the network of boys and their toys, a place not unlike a
treehouse with a sign reading ``No Gurlz Allowed.'' (OK, they can
watch ``Moesha,'' but then it's back to grapplin' and cussin' and
blowin' things up.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If it has high testosterone, we'll air it,'' says Dean
Valentine, UPN's president and CEO, who with his bald head and
goatee looks like one of the supporting players on the network's
hit ``WWF Smackdown!''
</P>
<P>
   And UPN's strategy has worked like a pile driver. Last season,
the little network was on life support, a laughingstock that didn't
know what it was doing. Now, thanks mainly to adding the World
Wrestling Federation on Thursdays, its ratings are up 36 percent
across the board over last season, at a time when the other five
broadcast networks are all declining in viewership.
</P>
<P>
   UPN still doesn't get much respect, but it gets ad buyers'
attention now, so that's an improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The network is going even further in the Tour de Testosterone.
At 8 tonight, it debuts ``I Dare You! The Ultimate Challenge,'' an
hour of stuntmen and women doing stuff that looks much more
dangerous than it is. One will land an airplane into the back of a
moving truck, another will ski across a lake of fire, and there's
something called the ``Limo of Death.'' Evel Knievel himself will
provide commentary, but the real brains _ if that's the right word
_ behind ``I Dare You!'' is Bruce Nash, producer of such specials
as ``When Good Pets Go Bad'' for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   While UPN promotes the show as if someone might die onscreen in
the next five minutes, Nash says the stunts are carefully planned.
``We want to make sure that it looks death-defying, but that these
daredevils are going to be safe,'' says Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Not content with the ``Limo of Death,'' UPN gets into the
monster truck smash-up business in February sweeps with a special
called ``Monster Trux CQ 2000,'' which could become a series if it
does well. UPN is figuring out characters and stories for the truck
drivers like the WWF does for its wrestlers, the better to whip
folks into a rooting frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   As UPN follows its game plan of male-mania, here are some other
shows in the pipeline:
</P>
<P>
   _ On Feb. 9, WWF's The Rock guest stars on ``Star Trek:
Voyager'' as an alien who has a gladiator battle with Seven of Nine
(Jeri Ryan).
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Hip-Hop Bounty Hunters'' is a new show in development for
fall. ``I think the title of that one says it all,'' laughs Tom
Nunan CQ, president of UPN Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I Spike,'' a series about female spies masquerading as a
professional beach volleyball team. (''Charlie's Angels'' with less
wardrobe overhead, perhaps.)
</P>
<P>
   Blaming the 'do
</P>
<P>
   The WB is instituting a new rule: No more haircuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is cutting their hair again on our network,'' says
Susanne Daniels, president of WB Entertainment, only half in jest,
still reeling from the uproar last fall when ``Felicity'' star Keri
Russell reduced her signature long locks to a cap of tight curls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think it affected the show on some level? Yes,'' says
Daniels. ``It lost some distinctiveness somehow.'' Daniels said the
WB was overwhelmed with negative e-mail from fans when Russell
unveiled her new 'do, which was ordered up by show creator J.J.
Abrams.
</P>
<P>
   Russell was the golden girl of television when ``Felicity''
debuted in 1998, but the WB moved the show to Sunday last fall and
its ratings have plummeted. Apart from the haircut, Daniels said
``the show had a rocky start creatively this past fall.'' It's been
in reruns for several weeks, but comes back at 8 p.m. Sunday with
an offbeat black-and-white episode that's a homage to ``The
Twilight Zone.'' As for rumors that ``Felicity'' might be in danger
of cancellation, Jamie Kellner, CEO of the WB, says simply, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   And Russell is growing her hair back out.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
