<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8399 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-AFC-NOTES18-COX     01-17 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Losing to Jags can be hazardous to health
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Not winning against the Jacksonville
Jaguars has not been a risky endeavor lately. Of the 10 coaches
that lost to the Jags this season, nearly a third left their jobs
by the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Jimmy Johnson was the last casualty, retiring one day
after Saturday's historic 62-7 slamming. Though Johnson had been
slowly sliding out the door in Miami, Jacksonville coach Tom
Coughlin sounded genuinely sorry his team provided the last straw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does it his way,'' Coughlin said of Johnson. ``His formula
is solid. It's been a privilege to coach against him. I have high
regard for his coaching success and the things that he's done. He
will be an individual and a personality that will be missed in our
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two coaches to lose to Jacksonville and later exit
were New Orleans' Mike Ditka, a 41-23 loser Nov. 21, and the New
York Jets' Bill Parcells, a 16-6 loser Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy Taylor
</P>
<P>
   Fred Taylor is healthy. It was best evidenced by his 90-yard
touchdown run and 39-yard touchdown reception against the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   Both showed that Taylor can present major problems for
Tennessee. And Taylor said he isn't 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I felt better in the Cincy game,'' Taylor said. ``I
felt I was quick in the Cincy game and I started to feel like it
was coming back. Against Miami, it was one long run, a couple stops
here and there, another two or three bursts here and there, then
that reception. I didn't feel overly quick _ not as quick as I felt
in the Cincy game _ but I felt good.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed.
</P>
<P>
   He dodged and outran defenders on the 90-yard play. And he broke
tackles on the scoring pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It demonstrated not only his elusiveness, but his acceleration
and what a dangerous threat he is once he's in that secondary,''
said Coughlin. ``He has presence about him. He sees people most of
us might not see.''
</P>
<P>
   A humbling fact
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin doesn't think he team will get a big head about its
55-point victory against the Dolphins. Tennessee defeated
Jacksonville 20-19 in Jacksonville and 41-14 in Tennessee three
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Coughlin said that should be enough motivation for his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will make us very humble,'' Coughlin said of the losses
to the Titans. Despite those two losses and despite the loss of
left tackle Tony Boselli to a knee injury, the Jaguars are favored
by a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Etc. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Jags and Tennessee are 5-5 all-time in head-to-head
competition, counting the Titans' previous life as the Houston
Oilers. Both teams are 4-1 against each other at home. . . . The
Oilers delivered the Titans' first loss in a 10-3 inaugural game at
Alltel Stadium in the 1995 opener. . . . Jacksonville later won its
first game in franchise history 17-16 in the rematch that season. .
. . The Jaguars had Monday off. Though coaches began game-plan
sessions Sunday that should be short work; the teams last played
Dec. 26 the players begin a four-day work week today. ``We won't
overdo it on the field,'' Coughlin said, ``but we'll spend four
solid days in study and preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Stinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
