<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-LIBERAL-LOBBY-NYTR     01-17 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBERAL-LOBBY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS FOE OF CHRISTIAN RIGHT, NEW HEAD OF LIBERAL LOBBY RELISHES THE
FIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
Sean Loughlin is a correspondent for the Washington Bureau of the
NYT Regional Newspapers Group.  
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ralph Neas is no stranger to a tough fight.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Neas confronted death when he contracted
Guillain-Barre Syndrome, a neurological disorder that left him
paralyzed from the neck down for several months. Neas later faced
some initial skepticism when, as a white Republican, he was
selected to head the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights, where
he worked for 14 years. More recently, he and his wife struggled to
have children; Neas, 53, became a first-time father this past
September.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Neas has a new job and what would appear to be another
series of fights on the horizon. As president of People For The
American Way, a liberal-minded civil liberties group, Neas expects
to do battle with the religious right on a host of issues this
year, ranging from the use of school vouchers to the posting of the
Ten Commandments in public buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only so many times in a lifetime where you can be on
the front lines of history and make a difference,'' Neas said,
recalling the advice of a friend when he began his career as a
civil rights activist. ``Thisis another one of those moments where
the battle lines could be drawn in a similar manner.''
</P>
<P>
   With the presidency and Congress up for grabs, Neas _ who left
the Republican party and registered as a Democrat in 1995 because
of what he saw as the ``extreme'' nature of the new GOP leadership
_ views 2000 as a watershed year in the political world. Neas
believes the next president will also have the opportunity to
appoint as many as four new Supreme Court justices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that we've worked for, everything that we've fought
for is at risk if the right takes over the three branches of
government,'' Neas said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1980 by television producer Norman Lear, People For
The American Way was designed as a counterbalance to the rising
influence of religious right groups like Jerry Falwell's Moral
Majority. The group's ties to Hollywood remain strong.
</P>
<P>
   David Altschul, vice chairman and general counsel for Warner
Bros. Records in Los Angeles and chairman of People For The
American Way, was on the search committee that picked Neas to head
the group this past fall. Altschul said that Neas, who began his
job this month, was selected because the organization believes he
can elevate its profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is somebody who is well-respected and well-known in the
political world of Washington and the advocacy world of
Washington,'' Altschul said. ``That's important. Nobody needs to
become accustomed to the world of Ralph.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Neas has been at the forefront of some of the biggest
civil rights battles in modern-day Washington. He led the coalition
that opposed the 1987 nomination of conservative jurist Robert Bork
to the Supreme Court, a fight that he fondly recalls as ``one of
the most important, historic events of the last 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have a dimmer view of that particular battle.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who sits on the Judiciary Committee
and voted against Bork's nomination, criticized the high-profile
campaigns that surrounded the nomination. ``Well, I was not happy
to see the _ let's see if can put this diplomatically _ public
relations battles that went on between those who favored him and
those who opposed him,'' Specter said. ``It was
counterproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Parshall, spokeswoman for the conservative Family Research
Council, said she doesn't know Neas, but she's quite familiar with
his new employer, saying People For The ``UnAmerican'' Way _ as she
preferred to call it _ wants to drive religion out of the public
square.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to make sure America only leans left and only
walks their way,'' Parshall said. ``And that is not the American
way.''
</P>
<P>
   On one point, there is little disagreement. Neas is a dogged and
effective champion for his causes. He presided over the Leadership
Conference on Civil Rights during the Reagan/Bush years, a time
when many conservatives sought to scale back government programs
and laws that helped minorities. Still, civil rights advocates
succeeded in pushing through such measures as the Americans with
Disabilities Act in 1990 and the 1982 Voting Rights Extension Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ralph just out-hustles the competition,'' said Wade Henderson,
Neas' successor at the Leadership Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Bollick, litigation director for the conservative
Institute for Justice in Washington, has crossed paths and swords
often with Neas over the years. He describes Neas as ``profoundly
left-wing'' and a disciple of ``social engineering,'' but he also
calls Neas a worthy adversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was choosing up sides without regard to ideology, I would
certainly choose Ralph,'' Bollick said. ``He is tenacious.''
</P>
<P>
   But Neas isn't always victorious. In 1998, he tried to unseat a
popular Republican congresswoman in suburban Maryland, where he
lives, but was soundly defeated. He considered another run this
year before his wife gave birth to their daughter, Maria.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Neas said he is eager to take on the conservative
Christian movement, describing it as a threat to civil liberties.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's certainly no question that People For The American Way
will continue to take on the Pat Robertsons and the James Dobsons
and the Gary Bauers and the Ralph Reeds and the Pat Buchanans and
those who we think are the leaders of the radical religious
right,'' Neas said. ``Because they continue to be a threat to First
Amendment values, they continue to be a threat to equal opportunity
issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
