<HEADER>
A8402 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-AFC-FEATURE18-COX     01-17 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-FEATURE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ As soon as their part in the AFC
Championship Game scenario had been established Saturday, the
Jacksonville Jaguars already were pondering their preferred path
toward Super Bowl XXXIV in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars had not yet showered from their 62-7 manhandling of
the Miami Dolphins and they were not so quietly rooting for an
appearance from the team that owned them.
</P>
<P>
   What better than to be positioned one win from the Super Bowl?
Easy. An assignment at home against the team that had beaten them
twice during the regular season, the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   When Tennessee beat the Colts 19-16 Sunday, the Jags' mission
became clear.
</P>
<P>
   Is it necessarily a good thing for Jacksonville that the Titans
survived for a third meeting? According to history, maybe not. Of
the 32 occasions when teams have played three times in a season, 18
times the team with the 2-0 record has swept the third. In 14 of
the third meetings, the previously handled team has prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jags never hid from the challenge, and now they have the
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tennessee, for obvious reasons,'' said Jacksonville tackle Ben
Coleman,'' is the team we wanted to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Tennessee, the Jags had compiled a perfect season. With
a second meeting a 41-14 disaster in Nashville in Week 15, the Jags
want to prove to everyone in the NFL that it does not reflect
accurately on their talent. Perhaps the same, as it turns out, that
beating Miami 62-7 isn't particularly meaningful, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have great memories of the last time we played
them,'' said Jags coach Tom Coughlin of the Titans. ``We think the
last game was an aberration. But our players will be humbled
because of that game. . . There's no way around it, though. It
happened. We don't spend a lot of time on it, but we'll throw it
out there again and bring things back to exactly where they were.
That will make us very humble.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially when coupled with the Jags' qualification game to the
NFL's Final Four, the Miami mess that pushed the hastily-retired
Jimmy Johnson from missed tackles to fishing tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee won the first meeting with Jacksonville, 20-19, at
Alltel Stadium, playing without receiver Fred Taylor and losing
four turnovers. In the second loss the Jags' lost offensive tackle
Tony Boselli for the playoffs and allowed quarterback Mark Brunell,
who was intercepted on his first series, to injure his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   After that loss, a pledge by receiver Jimmy Smith seemed to gain
significance as he said, ``We've got some soul-searching to do.
Yes, it's a wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunell's status Sunday is important. He was sacked four times
in the 41-14 loss to Tennessee last month. Playing less than a half
last Saturday with braces on both knees, Brunell should be back to
his full mobility for the final installment against the Titans.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguar defense fell apart in Nashville the last time,
allowing Titans quarterback Steve McNair to pass for 291 yards and
five touchdowns and yielding a 102-yard game to running back Eddie
George.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do a better job defensively than we did the last
time,'' Coughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars were off Monday and will return to practice today.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
