<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ In a major setback for the
Israeli-Syrian peace talks, the Clinton administration announced
Monday that the resumption of the negotiations had been delayed
indefinitely from their scheduled start on Wednesday. The
administration was careful not to blame either side, saying in a
deliberately worded statement by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright that ``their approaches to the next round differ, and as a
result, there is going to be a delay.'' By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Mozdok, Russia) _ The Russian military renewed
its assault on Chechnya's capital Monday as the Kremlin sought to
bring its siege of the city to a speedy and decisive end.
Explaining the new offensive, Lt. Gen. Gennady Troshev, the deputy
commander of Russian troops in the Northern Caucasus region, said
there would soon be ``radical changes'' in the situation in Grozny.
Troshev did not say what the changes would be. But they seem to
involve a sharp escalation in Russian artillery barrages and air
strikes. By Michael R. Gordon. (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-INSPECTIONS (United Nations) _ Rolf Ekeus, the Swedish arms
control expert who uncovered and destroyed large quantities of
Iraqi weapons after the 1991 war in the Persian Gulf, was called
back Monday by Secretary-General Kofi Annan to lead a new
commission created to finish the job more than a year after
monitoring broke down. But Annan did not have the customary
Security Council consensus in making the appointment, nearly 12
hours after a deadline for the nomination had passed. By Barbara
Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-U.S.-BORDER (Agua Prieta, Mexico) _ Tens of thousands of
undocumented Mexicans have crossed into the United States since the
New Year's holidays, provoking detentions on an industrial-strength
scale. This gritty town in the Sonora desert across from Douglas,
Ariz., has been the busiest staging area of the 2,000-mile border.
By Sam Dillon. (With photo and map.)
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE-MEDICINE (Undated) _ Until recently, doctors who
specialized in so-called lifestyle medicine _ elective and largely
cosmetic procedures _ were limited to rarefied corners of the
medical profession. But facing declining revenues because of
reimbursement cuts by managed care companies, thousands of doctors
in New York and across the country are turning to cosmetic medicine
to keep their practices lucrative. By Jennifer Steinhauer. (With
photos.)
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIC-BOOKS-EDUC (Chicago) _ A new program at Wilbur Wright
College, a community college on this city's North Side that caters
primarily to high school graduates considered not ready for
four-year institutions, allows students to earn a special minor or
certificate by taking a concentration of courses on the so-called
great books of the Western canon. What is different is that at
Wright and other institutions, most of them ranked in the middle to
lower end of the national academic pack, are taking steps to
underline such classes and to emphasize that they are critical to a
liberal arts education. By Jacques Steinberg. (With photo.)
</P>
