<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST UP ON JOHNSON'S AGENDA: THE BELICHICK MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   National Football League owners are expected to formally approve
Robert ``Woody'' Johnson as the new owner of the New York Jets
Tuesday at league meetings at the Waldorf Astoria in New York.
Johnson is scheduled to meet with the media at noon, but he is not
expected to address the Bill Belichick issue.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Johnson should expedite the Belichick matter,
however. NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue is expected to ask Johnson
what direction he wants to go regarding Belichick, whom the
Patriots are interested in as coach/general manager. If Johnson
wants to pursue compensation, Tagliabue will relay his wishes to
Patriots owner Robert Kraft. If the sides can't reach an agreement,
Tagliabue will be forced to make a decision on last week's
grievance hearing in which Belichick claimed he was no longer
contractually bound to the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Once Tagliabue has relayed the Jets' wishes to Kraft, he can
mediate a negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots turn from Belichick, they have one fewer
candidate to consider. St. Louis Rams offensive coordinator Mike
Martz agreed to a two-year contract extension with the team Monday.
Martz also was promised the head coaching job when Dick Vermeil
retires.
</P>
<P>
   Reports that Bill Parcells has already turned down big money to
return as coach of the Jets are premature. Parcells has spent no
more than five minutes with Johnson and did not meet with him last
Friday as had been reported.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells is supposed to meet with Johnson Tuesday. If Parcells
sticks to his guns, he will tell Johnson he's not coaching but
likely will recommend assistant coach Al Groh for the job.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick's legal team, led by Jeffrey Kessler, has been trying
to free Belichick from his contract without compensation,
threatening antitrust suits against the league and trying to show
that the Jets elevated Belichick only to head coach and not
director of football operations after Parcells stepped aside. The
Jets claim they did elevate Belichick to the higher title.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick has been spending time with his family over the past
few days and attending some of his children's sporting events. If
he winds up in New England, he likely will replace Bobby Grier,
perhaps with one of his allies _ Baltimore's Phil Savage or New
York's Scott Pioli.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1847EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
