<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-790&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC INDUSTRY EXPECTS MERGER TO ACCELERATE CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For the music industry, the merger of America
Online and Time Warner has struck a chord. It promises to hasten
the coming of the day when music is distributed digitally through
the Internet rather than through record stores.
</P>
<P>
   But that chord doesn't sound the death knell of record stores
just yet. Many obstacles must be overcome before consumers
routinely download music instead of buying compact discs. And there
is a limit to how much one company _ even one as potentially
powerful as AOL Time Warner _ can influence the evolution of
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The promise, of course, comes from the combination of AOL, the
world's largest Internet service provider, with Time Warner's
record company, one of the five giants that dominate the music
business. The merged company is expected to push music online more
aggressively than record companies alone have been doing. And AOL's
expertise in making the Internet easy to use could help make
Internet music downloading less daunting for novices.
</P>
<P>
   ``In combination we think we can help to set the agenda for the
industry,'' said Ted Leonsis, president of the AOL Interactive
Properties Group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, owning both content and distribution does not necessarily
give a company the ability to set an industry agenda. Sony bought a
movie studio after the defeat it suffered in the market with its
Betamax videocassette recorder. Yet Sony still lost a battle to set
standards for the DVD, the digital videodisc.
</P>
<P>
   Even how AOL and Warner Music Group will work together is not
clear. The simple model _ that AOL will become the big Internet
distribution and promotional arm of Warner Music _ has its
limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Leonsis said that AOL will have to work with all record
companies, not just Warner, because consumers would be reluctant to
visit any site that offered only one brand. Besides, fans of a
particular singer or group ``typically don't know what label
they're on,'' said Andrea Fleming, vice president of corporate
marketing for Liquid Audio, an online music company.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Music Group wants to deal with several online retailers,
said Paul Vidich, executive vice president of the group.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Warner might benefit from special promotions on AOL or
from AOL's expertise in developing Internet services. Leonsis said,
for instance, that in the 1980s Warner Music took advantage of
music videos earlier than other record companies because its parent
company owned MTV.
</P>
<P>
   Vidich said Warner Music was already benefiting from a
cutting-edge image from its pending association with AOL. ``In the
last week at least two companies have come to us with ideas and
said Warner is now the perfect partner for them,'' he said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Music, whose labels include Reprise, Elektra and
Atlantic, is perceived in the industry as having been less
aggressive than many of its peers in moving online.
</P>
<P>
   Vidich disputes that notion, saying the company has been
developing a comprehensive system for promoting and selling music
on the Web, including digital downloads, that it will introduce in
the middle of this year. Time Warner has stakes in three start-up
companies distributing music or music videos digitally and is also
becoming a part owner of CDNow, which sells compact discs from its
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Still, moving onto the Internet is not Warner Music's biggest
challenge. The company has slipped from No. 1 to No. 4 in market
share over the last few years because it failed to develop many new
acts. It also lost or got rid of many experienced executives.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is already involved in Internet music through ownership of
Winamp, a program for downloading music, and Spinner, a Web radio
service. But it has not been perceived as a friend of the record
industry, because it has not been avid in fighting Internet piracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been drawing people to their site using content
essentially as a loss leader,'' said Hilary Rosen, president of the
Recording Industry Association of America, which represents record
companies.
</P>
<P>
   She said Spinner had not yet started paying for the music it
transmits and that AOL initially opposed an Internet copyright
protection bill until a compromise was reached. Leonsis of AOL said
the company had always said that it would ``do the right thing'' on
copyrights but that the online world might be different from other
spheres.
</P>
<P>
   Now that AOL is becoming a big music owner, its attitude could
change. ``Now AOL has a multibillion-dollar stake in making sure
that intellectual property is respected on the Internet,'' said Ron
Stone, president of Gold Mountain Entertainment, a Los Angeles
company that manages such acts as Bonnie Raitt and Los Lobos.
``That's the best news out of this merger.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So far, big music companies have moved only gingerly onto the
Internet. Forrester Research, a market research firm based in
Cambridge, Mass., estimates that sales of music through the
Internet this year will reach $1.3 billion, about 10 percent of
total domestic music sales. But virtually all of those online sales
will be of compact discs through electronic commerce sites like
Amazon.com. Only 4 percent of the $1.3 billion, or far less than 1
percent of overall music sales, will be distributed digitally
through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Fear of piracy is just one obstacle. Long transmission times
make it unwieldy to download an entire album using a standard
modem. And music companies have not figured out how to make the
business profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Geiger, chairman and chief executive of Artistdirect, an
online music company, said that the prices some companies are
charging to download a song, $1 to $2 or more, will probably prove
too high for consumers used to getting things free on the Internet.
He said music might best be offered as a subscription service, in
which consumers pay a monthly fee to have access to music on
demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do believe that music is going to evolve into somewhat of a
service,'' said Geiger, whose company is partly owned by Warner and
other big record companies. ``Right now it's product only, except
for radio.''
</P>
<P>
   By going online too aggressively, the music industry could anger
its existing retailers and make its investment in compact-disc
plants obsolete. But executives say that as when CDs replaced vinyl
records, new formats generally increase the size of the overall
market and allow the industry to resell the same songs to existing
customers in the new format.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say electronic distribution is inevitable. AOL Time
Warner might lead the boats, but all will be swept up in the
current.
</P>
<P>
   ``With or without the deal,'' said Danny Goldberg, president of
Artemis Records in New York, ``technology is going to change the
way music is delivered, just as it has in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
