<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO DISCUSS ANTICRIME PLAN IN BOSTON VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN AND ANN SCALES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ President Clinton will visit the Orchard Gardens
housing development in Roxbury Tuesday to preview anticrime
initiatives he will propose in his State of the Union speech
January 27. The president also will meet with street workers who
are attempting to combat youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   It is the second time in recent years that Clinton has chosen to
highlight Boston's success in dealing with troubled youth and to
use the city as a backdrop for new proposals. In early 1997, he
praised Boston's youth programs in a speech at UMass-Boston, in
which he proposed a two-year, $500 million set of initiatives on
youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   Before returning to Washington Clinton also plans to attend a
Democratic National Committee reception in a private home in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Liu, assistant domestic policy adviser in the White House,
said Monday that this time the president will announce $280 million
in new initiatives aimed at improving enforcement of firearms laws.
</P>
<P>
   The money would provide for 500 new agents and inspectors at the
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms, which he said is the
biggest-ever increase in funding for that agency. It also would
finance the hiring of 1,000 new state and local prosecutors, and
100 new federal prosecutors, to pursue armed criminals and other
gun-related cases.
</P>
<P>
   Liu said Clinton will also propose creation of gun-law
enforcement teams in 20 high gun-crime areas. These teams would
consist of federal prosecutors, crime analysts and an attorney to
work on a coordinated community approach, which the White House
aide called an attempt ``to replicate what Boston has been able to
accomplish through Operation Ceasefire... to provide a coordinated
community-wide approach that engages law enforcement at every level
in an effort fight gun crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Other elements of Clinton's initiative are creation of a
national system for ballistic testing, funding of research on
technology that would make guns fireable only by their owners, and
funding for local anti-gun media campaigns,
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino said Monday that Orchard Gardens was
chosen for the afternoon event because of the renaissance that the
housing project and the neighborhood around it are undergoing.
Until the current, massive overhaul was undertaken, the project --
previously known as Orchard Park -- was a hotbed of crime and
violence, and was one of the least desireable low-income housing
complexes in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now people want to live there,'' Menino said. ``Everything the
president and vice president have been talking about for the last
seven years'' in the area of urban reconstruction ``is there at
Orchard Gardens -- economic opportunity, better education, a safe
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Major assistance for the renovation of Orchard Gardens has come
through the federal government, which has committed about $50
million to assist the redevelopment of the development into units
for rental and for home ownership.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the housing funds, because the Orchard Gardens
area is part of the city's empowerment zone, federally assisted
low-income loans and grants for economic development and human
services also are available there.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, the president is to meet and talk with
Boston's street workers, who have been the city's front-line in its
widely recognized efforts to reduce youth gang activity and related
crime and violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The street workers are one of the most important groups we
have,'' Menino said. ``The kids trust them. They can talk with
them. He wants to see how it works.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said particular attention may be paid to Boston's
programs for girls, as the need for such programs nationwide has
not been recognized for as long as programs targeting boys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
