<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8423 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GIRL-PLACE-ART-NYT &LR;      01-17 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIRL-PLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLACE FOR LITTLE GIRLS AND PROFITABLE DOLLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Conn., Wis.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ELLEN ALMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ One employee remembers the time a young girl walked
through the door and promptly burst into tears, not because she was
feeling cranky, her parents told the distressed saleswomen, but
because she suddenly realized she had just entered American Girl
Place.
</P>
<P>
   This 35,000-square-foot building, in the ``Magnificent Mile,''
Chicago's most expensive shopping district, houses not only the
wildly popular American Girl dolls and their extravagant
accessories, but enough distractions to occupy the average girl for
a day or two.
</P>
<P>
   There's the 150-seat theater, where a few nights a week a
five-piece orchestra and a cast of teen-age girls put on a
$25-a-ticket show written for, by and about girls; there's the
pink-and-black polka-dotted cafe, where waiters roll out trays of
petits fours and ice cream sundaes for girls and their mothers and
grandmothers; and a doll hospital where a white-coated woman named
Dr. Sandra earnestly consults with girls about how to fix the
crayon marks inflicted by a little brother (usually a whole new
head is ordered).
</P>
<P>
   Since this store opened in November 1998, American Girl Place
has lured 750,000 girls and women (and a few men) from around the
world, and in its first year in business has made $25 million, more
than twice the original projection, for its parent, the Pleasant
Co., of Middleton, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The store, an outgrowth of the company's 12-year-old catalog,
offers an experience uncommon in a season marked by the convenience
of mouse-click shopping. Despite the popularity of Web sites like
eToys, where 100,000 toys can be had with a few clicks, devotees of
American Girl products seem more than willing to take planes,
trains and cabs to visit a store dedicated to dolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Internet, you don't even have to go to the store
anymore,'' said Mary Ann McGrath, a professor of marketing at
Loyola University of Chicago. ``Stores don't have a whole lot to
offer other than a unique experience. American Girl has taken it to
a new level. They obviously have products to sell, but they've
melded it into this new idea of a museum combined with a store.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, it is a one-store idea. The company is looking into
opening a second store within a couple of years, said Anne Maddox,
a company vice president and general manager of American Girl
Place, but has no plans for planting multiple stores around the
country anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Burt Flickinger III, managing director of Reach Marketing,
retail consultants in Westport, Conn., said American Girl Place was
making the right move by ``creating buzz with an on-land store,''
as opposed to just jumping online.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a very strong format, they've got a great business
concept and a loyal consumer _ there's tremendous room for them to
grow now, either online or on land,'' said Flickinger, who compared
American Girl Place with Niketown, a store that created excitement
in the early '90s by initially opening just one store in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGrath, who has studied the different ways men and women
shop, said, ``You know when you walk in there, you're going to
leave with something.''
</P>
<P>
   That something might be a doll from the American Girl
Collection, historical dolls accompanied by books that tell their
``life stories.'' There are six in all, including Molly, a girl who
makes mischief at home while her father is serving in World War II,
and Addy, a former slave girl who has escaped the South with her
mother.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a ``Dress like your Doll'' section, where one can
find girl-sized versions of Molly's plaid skirt and sweater, or the
bonnet and dress worn by Felicity, the Colonial settler girl. Girls
are encouraged to bring their dolls, and to stay all day if they
want.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a group of women and girls flew in from Maryland to
spend the weekend at American Girl Place.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to laugh at my girlfriend, saying I'd never spend that
kind of money on a doll,'' said Kathi Picard, from the Chicago
suburb of Brookfield, who was fulfilling a three-month promise to
her three daughters by taking them to the store on a Friday the
week before Christmas. ``Now, I'm more nuts about it than my kids.
It's gotten kind of nuts with the clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter Lauren, 10, owns all six American Girl dolls and
was eyeing a band costume with accompanying flute. She and her
8-year-old sister, Julie, had each brought an American Girl doll
from home.
</P>
<P>
   The store also gets its share of male customers, many clutching
lists. Tim Tracy, from the Chicago suburb of Winnetka, estimates he
has spent more than $1,000 here on his two younger daughters since
the store opened.
</P>
<P>
   The store, though, is meant to appeal to women, Ms. McGrath
said. ``There's a very strong sense of texture, as opposed to a
real simple product display,'' she said. ``A uniquely male store is
something like the Sharper Image or Brookstone, which women find
very boring because there's just one of something, there's no
choice, and women like to feel that they're putting something
together _ an outfit, a story. And that's what this has really hit
upon. The woman who started this at least intuitively knew that.''
</P>
<P>
   That woman is Pleasant Rowland, a married but childless
entrepreneur who morphed from a school teacher to a newscaster
before founding the Pleasant Co. in 1986, offering dolls and books
by catalog. In 1998, the company was sold to Mattel for $700
million, and although Ms. Rowland was named a vice president,
Pleasant Co. remained a separate entity. In 1999, Pleasant Co.
earned $300 million, more than two-thirds of it through its
catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maddox dismissed criticism that the store, loaded with $84
dolls and accessories, like a tiny Macintosh computer that (sort
of) works, is an exclusive playground for rich girls and their
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can spend one dollar here and have a wonderful time,'' she
said. ``This is a place just for girls, and there is really nothing
else quite like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
