<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8429 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CANADA-INSIDER-TRADE-     01-17 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-INSIDER-TRADE-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN STOCK-TRADING CASES LIKELY TO GO TO COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Canada's top securities watchdog, the Ontario
Securities Commission, has added muscle and sharpened its teeth
over the past two years. It is currently pushing three high-profile
cases _ two involving insider trading _ into court, where
convictions would help reverse a belief that stock-market scandals
occur frequently in this country because there is little risk for
wrongdoers.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the commission and for Michael Cowpland, the
chairman and chief executive of Corel Corp., are currently arguing
over whether an insider-trading case will be tried in Toronto or
Ottawa. The charges, made in October, relate to Cowpland's sale of
$13 million worth of stock in mid-1997, just before the software
maker released an unexpectedly poor earnings report.
</P>
<P>
   Corel's head office is in Kanata, Ontario, near Ottawa, so
Cowpland wants the case tried there. The commission prefers a court
in Toronto, its home base. Either way, commission officials expect
the trial to begin in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   An action against John Felderhof, the former vice chairman and
chief geologist of defunct Bre-X Minerals Ltd., may get under way
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, the commission charged Felderhof with insider trading
_ reaping a $57 million gain _ and violations of other securities
laws. He is the only person charged so far in the Bre-X fraud, the
biggest in Canada's rich history of mining scams. The stock-market
value of the Calgary company hit $4 billion before its gold find in
Indonesia was found in 1997 to be worthless.
</P>
<P>
   It is significant that these allegations _ and others _ will be
tried in civil court rather than brought to a commission hearing,
because the court can levy a fine, while the usual penalty handed
down by the commission is a temporary suspension of the right to
trade stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The third case that could go to court this year involves the
officers and directors of YBM Magnex International Inc., which is
also out of business. The shares of YBM, which had links to the
Russian mob, were once part of the Toronto Stock Exchange's
prestigious 300 index. The U.S. Justice Department is investigating
the mob ties. Ten people and two underwriting firms have been
charged with numerous securities offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The legal process for YBM is certain to be a long one, so it is
on insider trading that the commission hopes to first establish
important precedents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insider trading is the worst offense that can be committed in
this industry,'' said Michael Watson, director of the commission's
enforcement branch in a recent interview. When ordinary investors
are so clearly disadvantaged, he said, ``It's very important that
we make it clear that we will undertake these cases.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission has not always been so aggressive, nor has it
claimed many victories on insider-trading actions in the past. Two
big cases have been fumbled in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly dropped in 1991 was an action against William Bennett, a
former premier of British Columbia, and his brother, who sold
shares in Doman Industries Ltd. just before a plan to sell the west
coast forest producer was aborted. Charges were also made against
Harbanse Doman, chairman and president of the company. The British
Columbia Securities Commission pursued the case, convicted the trio
in 1996 and, after having its position weakened on appeal,
negotiated a settlement last year.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, in 1996, David Fingold, a director of Cineplex
Odeon Corp., a motion-picture chain, was acquitted on charges of
selling $20 million worth of stock in advance of poor results. A
judge ruled the commission had filed its charges too late.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, who moved to the commission from the British Columbia
Securities Commission nine months ago, is determined to get better
results. ``We wouldn't have started these cases if we had a fear of
losing them,'' he said. ``We are taking a more firm stand, and
there is less incentive to settle, because we've now got the
resources to proceed through the process.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He might be less confident if the commission had not undergone a
restructuring over the past two years _ one that has greatly
increased its budget and manpower.
</P>
<P>
   After paying little heed to the agency for decades, the
provincial government realized it had to be strengthened to deal
with growing concerns about investor protection and the reputation
of Toronto as the country's financial center.
</P>
<P>
   It also became clear that a much-discussed federal body, like
the Securities and Exchange Commission in the United States, would
not become a reality, because securities regulation falls under the
jurisdiction of the individual provinces in Canada and the
provincial government of Quebec has refused to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two years the commission's budget has been bumped
by 86 percent to $28 million a year. Its staff count is well on the
way to being doubled to about 330, and more competitive salaries
should slow the revolving door that used to carry the best of them
to firms in Toronto's investment community. Watson's enforcement
arm will more than double in size to almost 80 people.
</P>
<P>
   With the buildup of in-house expertise, the commission now
rarely hires outside counsel to prosecute its cases. Watson said
his aim is to have, within the commission, ``the best
securities-litigation firm in the province.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1915EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
