<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ABOUT THE NEWS MEDIA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Repeating from yesterday's wire for all needing)   (ms) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REALITY OF `HURRICANE' IS STILL STORMY
</P>
<P>
   The unhappy reality about happy movie endings is that often the
actors in the true-life drama do not go off blithely into the
sunset holding hands _ or talking for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   Such a chill is apparent in the promotional appearances
surrounding the books and ``Hurricane,'' the new film exploring the
life of Rubin (Hurricane) Carter, the boxer who was jailed for
nearly 20 years for a triple murder he did not commit.
</P>
<P>
   The film was adopted from two books, including Carter's 1974
autobiography, ``The 16th Round,'' and Sam Chaiton and Terry
Swinton's updated 1991 book, ``Lazarus and the Hurricane.'' Chaiton
and Swinton are part of a group of Canadians who befriended Carter
and ultimately moved to New Jersey to aid in the efforts to free
him. Later they took him into their commune house in Canada for
almost nine years, but they have not talked in more than two years
despite a movie guaranteed to make eyes mist over warm friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's divorce-like,'' Swinton said, ``in the sense that there
was a lengthy and very close relationship and the people drifted
apart from the stresses that you encounter.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carter and his former friends made an appearance in Toronto
in January for the screening of the film they did not speak.
``Rubin is into a different thing right now,'' Swinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Carter and Denzel Washington came to New York for a
screening of the film. Swinton and Chaiton were in New York, but
were not invited to attend until about three hours before,
according to their publicist at St. Martin's Press, Joseph Rinaldi.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Sakson, a senior vice president for national publicity
for Universal Pictures, insisted that the authors or their
representatives had been told about the event.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded, though, that managing the promotion for the movie
has been ``challenging.'' For example, the movie executives were
not aware until recently that Carter would criticize his Canadian
supporters in a new authorized biography by a former reporter for
The Wall Street Journal, James S. Hirsch. In it, Carter complains
that the Toronto commune became ``another prison'' and he was
treated like ``a trophy horse to fill the coffers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sakson notes that the current bitterness does not ``negate where
they were before. People are capable of doing very selfless acts of
kindness.''
</P>
<P>
   _DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
<P>
   ISUZU AND CONSUMERS UNION BRACE FOR TRIAL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a high-stakes defamation case set to begin here soon, Isuzu
Motors is saying that Consumers Union, the publisher of Consumer
Reports, rigged a test to ensure that two Trooper models and a twin
model manufactured for Acura would tip up on two wheels.
</P>
<P>
   A similar case involving testing of the Suzuki Motor Corp.'s
Samurai is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Isuzu asserts the publisher rigged the test to increase
circulation and fund-raising for its magazine, which accepts no
advertising, and to advance its cause of getting the National
Highway Transportation Safety Administration to establish rollover
standards for sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union said it had no motive to make the Trooper look
bad and that the test had been equally applied to all the vehicles
it has examined. The publisher says the lawsuit is an attempt to
silence independent criticism.
</P>
<P>
   As the case heads to trial, several newspapers and television
news shows _ including The Los Angeles Times, The Washington Post
and 60 Minutes II _ have raised concern about the case's
implications for the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Federal District Judge Richard A. Paez, who is presiding over
the case, has ruled that Isuzu must show that Consumers Union acted
with actual malice.
</P>
<P>
   But he also rejected the publisher's request to dismiss the
case, saying Isuzu found evidence worthy of a jury's consideration
regarding the quality of the vehicle test.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to evidence that the magazine knew its test was
subject to driver influence, that its methodology is not accepted
by the NHTSA, and that Consumer Reports failed to include
statistics it had collected showing that the Trooper's rollover
rate was not out of line with other vehicles of its type.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union has been sued 12 times since 1960 and has
prevailed in every case adjudicated so far. But even if it wins
again, it would come at a big cost: the magazine spent at least $10
million defending itself.
</P>
<P>
   _CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN
</P>
<P>
   ABRUPT DEPARTURE AT THE DAILY OKLAHOMAN
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Oklahoman and its billionaire owner, Edward L.
Gaylord, have long been monuments to conservative certainties and
frequent targets of journalism critics. Just a year ago, The
Columbia Journalism Review critiqued the paper in an article titled
``The Worst Newspaper in America,'' documenting its reportorial
attacks on Democrats, rosy view of industry and editorial savaging
of homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gaylord's son, E.K. Gaylord II, president of the Oklahoma
Publishing Co. of Oklahoma City, hired Stan Tiner to be executive
editor. An ex-marine known for reinvigorating The Mobile Register
in Alabama, Tiner arrived in April, saying he would change The
Oklahoman. And he accomplished so much in eight months that the
journalism review was preparing a follow-up filled with praise.
</P>
<P>
   But before that follow-up could be published, Tiner was gone.
The Oklahoman ran a short article last Tuesday saying that Sue
Hale, a longtime staff member, had been named executive editor. It
said simply that she would replace Tiner.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   No one directly involved returned telephone calls. Not Tiner;
not Gaylord or his father, Edward L. Gaylord; not Ms. Hale; and not
the newspaper's general manager, Edmund O. Martin.
</P>
<P>
   So curious onlookers sought clues in the articles Tiner had
published in The Oklahoman, a newspaper that is proud of being the
first to call on President Clinton to resign.
</P>
<P>
   They remembered the front-page feature about atheists in the
state, praised by atheists as ``fair, open and nonbiased'' and
condemned by some Christians, one of whom wrote, ``Before June 16,
I would have never imagined such a thing in The Oklahoman.'' The
newspaper still publishes a ``prayer for the day'' on its front
page.
</P>
<P>
   They remembered the complete face lift that turned the gray,
conservative newspaper into a showcase for feature work.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, they remembered the Dec. 16 publication of the
first article in a three-part retrospective on the 25th anniversary
of Karen Silkwood's death. The nuclear-plant worker had been
gathering evidence of safety and security violations by her
employer, the Kerr-McGee Corp., when she was killed in a car crash
on her way to meet with a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the three-part series was a straight-ahead
reminiscence of the federal trial against Kerr-McGee, noting that
the company, another Oklahoma institution, had been held liable _
for $1.38 million _ for allowing its plutonium to contaminate Ms.
Silkwood.
</P>
<P>
   The second and third parts never appeared. Ten days later, an
Oklahoman editorial lauded Kerr-McGee as ``one of the best
corporate citizens in Oklahoma.'' A spokeswoman for Kerr-McGee said
last Friday that ``Nobody in the company called to complain'' about
the coverage. But Tiner outlasted its publication by just three
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _FELICITY BARRINGER
</P>
</TEXT>
