<HEADLINE>
BOMB EXPLODES IN ISRAEL; POLICE SUSPECT TERRORISTS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ An unsophisticated bomb exploded in a garbage can in
the northern Israeli town of Hadera on Monday, and the Israeli
police suspect that it was aimed at disrupting peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli police said they would move on Tuesday into a high
alert in all major cities.
</P>
<P>
   After the bomb exploded at 11 a.m. near an open-air market in
the center of Hadera, some 20 bystanders sought medical attention,
mostly for shock. Several of the injured were retirees sunning
themselves on a park bench.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak said that such attacks were to be
expected ``inside Israel, such as we have seen today, in Lebanon
and even abroad.'' He had just finished briefing his cabinet on the
possibility of renewed terrorism when he received the news, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will act to crush terror,'' he said. ``Sooner or later we
will put a heavy and painful hand on the perpetrators of this
attack. These weeks are critical, and adversaries, whether they be
the Hezbollah in Lebanon, terror organizations operating in
Damascus or the long arm of Iran in Judea, Samaria and Gaza, will
attempt attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are prepared,'' Barak continued. ``There is no 100 percent.
But we are a strong people, very tough, who understand exactly the
tasks before us and no type of terror will break our spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli police suspect that Palestinian militant members of
the Islamic Holy War group carried out the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Ephraim Sneeh, the deputy defense minister, said the attack was
similar to one in Netanya last November that preceded
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, the Israelis, suspecting that an attack was in the
planning, swept through Palestinian homes in the West Bank and
arrested more than a dozen Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials pledged their cooperation against
terrorist attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
