<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THELANDGRAB.COM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Double parentheses should be set as brackets.) 
(lb) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just beyond the headlines about AOL merging with Time Warner and
the Internet retailers having a blowout Christmas, there is
another, more important land grab under way in cyberspace, which by
the time it's over could have an interesting impact on the global
balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   Let me put it to you this way: If you think the French and other
Europeans are annoyed with U.S. economic dominance today, wait
until they wake up and see the high ground that some key U.S.
companies are seizing in the business-to-business area of
cybercommerce. These companies are creating the global exchanges
that are going to mediate a huge amount of industrial e-commerce in
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The closest thing to these exchanges the consumer would see is
eBay _ the auction site, where individuals can buy or sell anything
from their basements. But imagine eBays for a whole set of
industries, where goods and services related to any aspect of that
industry can be exchanged between buyers and sellers.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, you already have Metalsite.com and E-Steel.com,
where construction companies from anywhere in the world can put out
their steel needs to the lowest bidder. There is already
e-Chemicals.com and Chemdex.com for chemicals and life science
products. And soon, no doubt, e-rubber, e-plastics and e-cement.
</P>
<P>
   In a world without walls, these global exchanges will be the
shapers of the rules, standards and technology by which a whole
host of goods and services will be bought, sold, auctioned and
bartered.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of companies are already throwing away their catalogs
and traditional supplier relationships and plugging into these
mega-exchanges, where they will buy everything from paper to
plastics. Because of America's lead in this cyberspace land grab,
these exchanges are being created largely in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of this is still happening just below the horizon, and
the numbers are still relatively small, so people don't see it
yet,'' said Joel Cawley, Director of Corporate Strategy for IBM.
``But estimates are that these big exchanges will mediate between
30 and 40 percent of industrial e-commerce by 2004. Once they get
on everyone's radar screen, it will be too late. The winners will
be established, and the cost of switching from a key site, or
starting up a new one, will be very high.''
</P>
<P>
   These online exchanges usually start out as spot markets, where
excess inventories are sold. But because of their efficiency, and
potential to be globalized, they are quickly evolving into
worldwide market-makers.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Enron. It has set up an online marketplace through which
companies all over the world are now able to buy and sell natural
gas, electricity, coal, plastics, pulp, paper and oil _ and, coming
soon, bandwidth. Bandwidth is the basic electronic pipe down which
companies send their Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Through Enron's Pooling Point Operators _ where ties between
bandwidth buyers and sellers will be established and monitored _ a
school with excess bandwidth capacity during the summer will be
able to sell its surplus to a company with rising bandwidth demand.
Bandwidth deals that used to take months to close will take
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first to do this sort of thing for trading natural
gas and electricity,'' says Enron's CEO, Kenneth Lay, ``but we
think the bandwidth market will be the biggest of all. It is now a
$30 billion market and in three years or so it should be $90 to
$100 billion. And it will be global. We are already operating in
the U.S., and will soon be in Europe and Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet economy runs on bandwidth, so if Enron's exchange
works, it could be the equivalent of discovering cyberoil _ for
Enron and for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are strong advantages to being the first mover in these
sorts of global markets,'' said Lay. ``When you are first, you get
scale very quickly, and with that comes economies that lower your
transaction costs, and that gives you more liquidity and the
ability to do more complicated transactions than others. We will
have competitors, I'm sure. But it's pretty much a winner-take-all
environment. The early entrants into these markets will in large
part determine how they are shaped. ((And)) once an entity
establishes a strong market position in this kind of global market,
it is awfully tough to overtake it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1923EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8435 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-17 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT LOANS CAN PAY OFF IN LONG RUN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (EDITORS: Note (at) in e-mail address in the tagline.) 
 
By SHANNON BUGGS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Class of '99, your grace period is up. Many of you who
got interest-deferred student loans will begin repaying those loans
next month.
</P>
<P>
   You are not alone.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of American students need financial aid packages of
grants and loans to go to college, graduate and professional
school.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government provides financial aid to more than 70
percent of all post-secondary students in this country. But nearly
60 percent of that aid is in the form of loans.
</P>
<P>
   That means money should not be an excuse for dropping out of
school, because private lenders are eager to make loans backed by
the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   But it also means that graduates often leave school owing more
than they will make in a year working full-time.
</P>
<P>
   Graduates, don't get overwhelmed by your debt. You can pay back
your loans and save money to buy a house, get married, plan for
retirement or any other financial goal you have.
</P>
<P>
   Defaulting ruins credit
</P>
<P>
   A student loan is good debt because it enhances your biggest
asset: your mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential to earn money is probably a young person's most
valuable resource,'' says Sheryl Garrett, president of Garrett
Financial Planning in Overland Park, Kan. ``A good education
increases your ability to make money.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can wreck that asset by not paying back your student
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Once you default on a student loan, you lose your eligibility
for future federal student aid. So, if you're planning to get a
Ph.D. and don't have the cash to put yourself through six years of
school, then you must have a good track record with student loans.
</P>
<P>
   Those of you who graduated and have no plans to pursue another
degree shouldn't think you can get away with not paying.
</P>
<P>
   Education loan defaults are reported to credit bureaus and will
appear on your credit report for seven years. Whenever you apply
for a credit card, home mortgage or car loan, the lender will see
that you didn't repay your loan.
</P>
<P>
   Many employers pull credit reports on potential hires and they,
too, will see the default.
</P>
<P>
   And if that doesn't scare you, maybe this will _ a new law
allows the U.S. Department of Education to chase down delinquent
loans dating back to the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   If the government sues you for payment and gets a judgment
against you, it can seize your bank accounts, garnish your wages,
impound your car and snatch your tax refunds to pay off the loan
and legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   Work with loan holder
</P>
<P>
   Since skipping out on the student loan is not an option, make
sure your monthly payment suits your paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't manage the payment, call the lender and ask for an
adjustment in the monthly amount. There are four repayment plans
for federal loans. Learn more about them at
www.ed.gov/DirectLoan/pubs/repabook.
</P>
<P>
   You also may want to consolidate several federal loans into one
loan payment. This may or may not lower your monthly payment, but
it will certainly help you keep track of what you have to pay and
when. Check out www.ed.gov/DirectLoan/consolid.html.
</P>
<P>
   But if you can't pay anything because of a financial crisis, ask
for a deferment. Lenders often allow people to put off repayment
until after completing graduate school, finding a job, getting
married or any other approved reason.
</P>
<P>
   Interest on the loan accumulates during the deferment, so you
will pay more in interest and take longer to retire the loan, but
that's better than defaulting.
</P>
<P>
   And, unlike credit card balances, student loans don't have to be
eliminated immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Student loans have interest rates between 8 percent and 12
percent and low monthly payments. Plus, the IRS lets qualified
workers deduct interest paid on student loans during the first 60
months of repayment.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than pay down student loans quickly, take that extra
money and pay off credit cards, which can have interest rates as
high as 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those of you without credit debt should invest the extra money
in your company's 401(k) retirement plan or an IRA, if you're not
eligible to participate in the 401(k).
</P>
<P>
   Because, even though age 59 1/2 seems far off in the future and
you're just getting used to your first ``real'' job, dreams of
retiring will sneak up on you before you know it, and you'll want
to have the money to make them come true.
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Buggs invites comments and column ideas, but cannot
offer specific financial advice about individual situations. E-mail
her at shannon.buggs(at)chron.com or call 713-220-2000, access code
1003.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
