<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8445 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-WIZARDS-B     01-17 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-WIZARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS SQUEAK ONE OUT OVER THE WIZARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the rarefied air of the NBA, where real playoff
teams dwell, back-to-back road wins over the Nets and Wizards
qualify as simply taking care of business.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, where the air is anything but rarefied, the wins
qualify as milestones.
</P>
<P>
   It took the Celtics 2 1/2 months to do it, but they finally won
consecutive road games, taking a tight, 105-101 decision from the
beleaguered Wizards Monday at MCI Center. The victory, coupled with
a similarly taut win at the Meadowlands Saturday, doubled the
team's road take for the season and kept it within eyesight of the
No. 8 playoff spot as the season approaches the halfway point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, two road wins is two road wins,'' said Kenny Anderson,
using indisputable math. ``Regardless of where it is, it's still a
win.''
</P>
<P>
   As was the case Saturday, the Celtics persevered and were the
poised ones when things threatened to become unglued. While Antoine
Walker was the glue Saturday, that role went to Paul Pierce Monday.
In easily his strongest outing of the season, Pierce poured in 34
points, a career high, which included 12-of-16 shooting from the
field, 10-of-10 from the line, and a macho 18 points and 3 steals
in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was time for Paul to step up,'' coach Rick Pitino said.
``He stepped up.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce was the beneficiary Sunday of a chat with No. 2 man Jim
O'Brien, who subtly reminded Pierce that the team needed more than
he was giving. O'Brien said he was delighted to see Pierce's
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You're right,' '' O'Brien said. ``It was simply a
matter of getting him to focus more. He does lose focus. It's very
typical of young players. Not many understand the nuances of
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pierce, ``I knew I wasn't playing my best basketball. I
took what he said to heart. For us to win, a lot of responsibility
is going to be on me and Antoine.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierce made five shots in the fourth, none bigger than an
up-and-under with 13.4 seconds to play. At that point, the Celtics
were nursing a 102-101 lead, and the shot clock was winding down.
But, as he put it, ``I've been working on that one since the
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   But the euphoria almost was short-lived. Pierce jumped at the
wrong time trying to contain Richard Hamilton. The rook managed to
squeeze off a decent trey attempt, which went in and out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was saying to myself, `Please don't go in,' '' Pierce said.
``Thank God it didn't. Coach would have been all over me if it had
gone in.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't, of course. Hamilton, playing for the injured Mitch
Richmond (ribs), was 3 of 10 for the game. Anderson was fouled,
made one clincher with 3.4 seconds left, and the Celtics had
themselves the W.
</P>
<P>
   The game was played against the backdrop of the most intriguing
basketball story here since Rod Strickland punched out Tracy Murray
over a girlfriend thing. Michael Jordan's presumed ascension to
exalted hoop overseer of the franchise (and, presumably,
part-owner) has dominated the hoop headlines. Monday, a fan carried
a sign that said, ``Jordan and the Wizards: It has a nice ring.''
There was a picture of Jordan showing off one of his six
championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards players have openly greeted the less-than-hostile
takeover, although Juwan Howard, who had a season-high 31 Monday,
did say that the issue has become a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   If he does deign to take over, Jordan will have his hands full.
Monday's announced crowd was 14,411; the Wizards must use the same
counting system as the Celtics. Washington shot 51 percent from the
field but was undone by 20 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Washington had a 14-point lead in the second quarter. The
Celtics had a 10-point lead in the third. Walker had 31 points, 29
over the first three quarters. Strickland had 24. Both teams made
their free throws. The fourth quarter alone featured six lead
changes, the final coming when Pierce hit two free throws with 6:07
left.
</P>
<P>
   Those were the first of 6 straight Boston points, which gave the
Celtics a 94-89 lead. Howard (14 in the fourth) kept the Wizards
close and a Strickland 3-point play with 36.4 seconds left made it
102-101.
</P>
<P>
   But Pierce made sure it got no closer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
