<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-FUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$500 MILLION WEB INVESTMENT FUND FULLY SUBSCRIBED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With investors elbowing each other aside to get into
the dot-com world, Highland Capital Partners announced Monday that
it has closed a new $500 million venture capital fund that will
invest in Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   The new fund is nearly twice the size of Highland's previous
investment vehicle and brings the total amount of money under the
company's management to over $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Highland officials said interest in the Boston firm's fifth
venture fund was so intense that dozens of institutional and
individual investors were turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were substantially oversubscribed,'''said Bob Higgins,
Highland's managing general partner.
</P>
<P>
   Over 25 investors, or limited partners, put up the $500 million,
including some of the world's leading endowments and pension funds
company officials said. Among those participating are Harvard,
Yale, MIT, Stanford, the Ford Foundation, Hewlett Packard and the
Mayo Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The individuals tapped to invest in the fund were also expected
to become part of a network of entrepreneurs, high-tech executives,
and other industry leaders that Highland has assembled to advise
the startups and assist them in developing strategic alliances and
management teams.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's Web-based investments will focus on companies
specializing on business-to-consumer and business-to-business
enterprises, as well as ``infrastructure opporturnities'' on the
Internet, Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers liken the current Internet investment environment
to a ``land grab'' or ``gold rush'' and say no signs of a slowdown
are in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Internet startups are mushrooming and over the past couple of
years, they have driven venture capitalists into a frenzy.
Dominating the intitial public offering market, web-based
investments were up more than 90 percent over last year, according
to recent published reports.
</P>
<P>
   Wary of a boom-bust cycle, some analysts worry that the hefty
bets in small Internet companies that are often years from
profitability could backfire, especially if Wall Street sours on
Internet stocks. .
</P>
<P>
   But Highland officials expressed confidence in prospects for
their own fund. ``The entrepreneurs we are backing have solid
business models and are focused on profitability,'' Higgins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
