<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-PRESIDENT-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILE'S PRESIDENT-ELECT: SOCIALIST BY PARTY, MODERATE BY NATURE 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile _ As President-elect Ricardo Lagos Escobar
mounted the stage on Sunday night to celebrate his victory with a
throng of his supporters, Socialists in the crowd chanted a leftist
slogan that was a favorite when Salvador Allende wore the
presidential sash back in the early 1970s: ``The people united will
never be defeated.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point in the festivities, the crowd called on Lagos
to bring Gen. Augusto Pinochet to justice after his expected return
to Chile from Britain, where he has been under house arrest on
human rights charges for 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   But after Lagos, a 61-year-old economist and lawyer,
acknowledged the presence of Allende's widow, he delivered a
carefully crafted message that struck more moderate chords than at
least some in the crowd had come to hear. It was the speech of a
veteran politician whose politics have long been more moderate than
those of his fellow Chilean Socialists.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of the former dictator, Lagos interrupted the
crowd's chants by promising to let any future prosecution of
Pinochet run its course in the courts without his interference. He
warmly complimented his adversary, Joaquin Lavin, a former aide to
Pinochet. And he promised to forge a government that is tolerant
and respects the human rights of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a defeat for anyone,'' Lagos said. ``I will be the
president of all Chileans. I want to resolve the pains that still
remain from the century that just ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Lagos will be inaugurated in March as the first Socialist
president of Chile since Allende was overthrown in the violent coup
in 1973 led by Pinochet and backed by the United States. Lagos'
presidency will almost certainly be very different from Allende's.
</P>
<P>
   In part, that is because he will be governing in a coalition
with the more conservative Christian Democratic Party. But Lagos
has long been a Western European-style social democrat, even
through the 1970s and 1980s when other leaders of his party
embraced Marxism and the Cuban revolution.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent his moderation is grounded in the Keynesian
lessons he learned while earning a doctorate in economics from Duke
University in the 1960s. But it is also seems to be a product of
his sober personality and what his friends characterize as a
distaste for impulsiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos was born to a middle-class family on March 2, 1938. His
father, a small landowner, died when Lagos was 8. His mother, Emma
Escobar y Froilan Lagos, a retired teacher, cast a vote for her son
on Sunday _ at the age of 103.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before traveling to the United States for graduate studies in
economics, he earned a law degree at the University of Chile. He is
a weekend gardener, an avid reader of histories and loves Brahms
and Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike so many Chileans, he does not smoke. But he does like to
take a siesta whenever possible.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1971 he has been married to Luisa Duran de la Fuente, with
whom he has a daughter. He also has two children from an earlier
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   He plays tennis and does light rock-climbing for exercise, but
his ample waistline suggests he is not a fanatic about either. And
when he talks of politics, compromise and consensus appear to be
uppermost on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is our goal now?'' Lagos asked rhetorically during an
interview on the campaign trail last year. ``Without affecting
investment, savings and growth, we need to produce a society a
little more just with less of a gap in the inequality of
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   During the Allende years, Lagos served as secretary-general of
the University of Chile and had been Allende's choice to be
ambassador to Moscow at the time of the coup. But after the coup,
when many top Chilean Socialist leaders went to East Germany, he
chose exile in the United States and was a visiting professor at
the University of North Carolina in 1973-75.
</P>
<P>
   He said he enjoyed his time in Chapel Hill, although he added
with a smile: ``I had real problems when North Carolina played
basketball with Duke.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1976-84, he worked as an economist for various United
Nations agencies, but then devoted himself increasingly to
opposition politics.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos spent only 20 days in Pinochet's jails, in 1986 during a
general crackdown following an assassination attempt, but he played
a key role in the 1988 plebiscite campaign that led to Pinochet's
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview that year, Lagos had the gumption to
point his finger at the camera _ as if to point directly at the
dictator _ and told him the country had had enough of his
repression, torture and executions.
</P>
<P>
   It was that brave moment of defiance that made him the leader of
Chile's Socialists and its future presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, the Christian Democratic-Socialist coalition took
power, and over the next eight years Lagos served as minister of
education and then minister of public works _ positions in which he
sought to help the disadvantaged but also improve his relations
with the business community and military.
</P>
<P>
   He expanded the influence of military academies by allowing them
to grant master's degrees to civilians. And he made sure to
complete Pinochet's pet public works project _ a highway connecting
Tierra del Fuego and the lake-dotted Patagonia region.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   During the recent presidential campaign, he and Lavin studiously
avoided mention of either Allende or Pinochet, as both focused on
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos promised to create 300,000 jobs and bring modern health
care to the poor, but he also made a concerted effort to calm the
concerns of domestic and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   In November, he told a conference of local businessmen that he
would work hard to keep the budget deficit in check and interest
rates and inflation low. ``I know the limits of the possible,'' he
said, ``and I know my responsibility to be a leader who orients the
public responsibly.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech was meant to reassure the private sector that he
would continue the current government's economic policies and not
encourage workers to strike, as Allende's government had done.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos' moderation through the campaign frustrated leftists in
his own party, and particularly angered Communist Party leaders who
had been allies of the Socialists during the Allende era.
</P>
<P>
   But his moderation was mirrored by Lavin, who called for cuts in
military spending and said he would not stand in the way of a
future trial of Pinochet should he not be extradited to Spain to
stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lagos is close to the third way of Blair and Clinton,'' said
Ricardo Israel, a University of Chile political scientist. ``As
president, you'll hear a lot about an ethical foreign policy but
you'll probably see more privatizations than you did under the two
Christian Democratic presidents. And he'll be very careful with the
army.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
