<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-FLEET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTOR BUYS THREE CONNECTICUT BRANCHES OF FLEET-BANKBOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A New York financier said Monday that he would acquire
three Fleet and BankBoston branches in Connecticut and transform
them into that state's only minority-run financial services
institution.
</P>
<P>
   The financier, Peter F. Hurst, said he plans to form a
minority-led investor group to serve as a holding company for the
branches. Hurst said he had signed a definitive agreement with
FleetBoston Financial, the branches' owner.
</P>
<P>
   Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The three offices are being sold by Fleet and BankBoston, which
have merged, as part of a group of 300 outlets they must divest
themselves of to satisfy antitrust requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Hurst, 44, declined to name the group's members, saying that his
plan was still subject to approval by state and federal regulators
and by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. But the participants
include private equity funds and prominent financial services
companies, he said, as well as individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   The group, to be known as Urban Financial Group Inc., would be
led and managed by minority executives, said Hurst, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   The branches in question, in Bloomfield, Bridgeport, and
Hartford, have $88 million in deposits and $8 million in loans.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction would fulfill FleetBoston's previously stated
goal of selling at least some of its branches to a minority-owned
company as a condition of undertaking New England's largest bank
merger ever.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the 300 outlets was the largest bank divestiture in
US history. Most of the branches were acquired by Sovereign
Bancorp, a thrift in Eastern Pennsylvania. As part of the
divestiture, the combined Fleet-BankBoston put aside more than a
dozen branches for smaller community and minority-owned
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had made a commitment to the Connecticut attorney general
and state treasurer and community leaders to selling two
Connecticut branches to a minority owner,'' said Fleet spokesman
James Mahoney. ``In this case, we ended up selling three.''
</P>
<P>
   FleetBoston's previous attempts to sell to minority-led
companies foundered because of price disagreements. Boston Bank of
Commerce, a leading minority-owned bank, was reportedly unwilling
to pay the 12 percent premium that Fleet was asking for the assets.
Other set-aside branches were snapped up by the holding company for
Rockland Trust Co., a Massachusetts community bank.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Hurst said that Urban Financial would create a
local bank, to be known as The Community's Bank, with diversified
financial services for individuals, small businesses, and nonprofit
organizations in the region. Products and services would include
mezzanine and equity capital, investment and insurance, and
financial and strategic advice. The bank also plans to launch
Web-based services.
</P>
<P>
   Hurst, an investment banker and Harvard-trained lawyer, runs
Hurst Capital Partners Inc., a New York financial advisory and
investment banking firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people of color have missed out on the bull market,''
he said Monday. ``We think it's important to provide both financial
and intellectual capital.''
</P>
<P>
   He might seek to expand his Connecticut franchise into New York,
he said, but would probably not enter the Massachusetts market.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Savings &AMP; Loan Association, in Hartford, was the
last minority-owned bank with a formal charter in Connecticut. It
was among nearly two dozen state banks that failed in 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
