<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: POLITICS OF REAL PORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GAIL COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ An urban person who listens to the
presidential candidates in Iowa can get to feeling sort of
inferior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose the family farm and we lose the nursery of America's
moral character,'' howled Alan Keyes in one of the presidential
debates. ``Where did we get the young men and women who were
willing to sacrifice themselves in battle?''
</P>
<P>
   Keyes tends to get carried away. (At one point he said American
farmers ``have the courage that used to be supposedly restricted
only to aristocrats.'') But this time he was only overstating
conventional political wisdom. We subsidize agriculture to save the
family farmers. We save the family farmers because they are good
people, who work incredibly hard and play by the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Hang around here long enough, and your hackles tend to rise. My
own home, New York City, is not generally described as a nursery of
moral character. But it's crammed with people who work 14-hour days
at the family dry cleaning store or corner bodega. If they founder
and lose their life savings, the government may deign to give them
a free night-school computer training course.
</P>
<P>
   This year the farmers are getting $22 billion in direct
government payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should the family farm ... be any more protected than the
corner drugstore or the mom-and-pop shoe store or the little
grocery store?'' Tom Brokaw asked at one of the debates. George W.
Bush looked at him as if he had asked why churches are tax-exempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ask the family farmer in Iowa, they don't feel
protected,'' Bush said rather frostily. ``People are hurting in
this state. Family farmers all across the state are wondering how
come we don't open more markets. ...'' He went on for a while,
concluding with a paean to ethanol subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   The family farmers do seem to be hurting _ if the character of
the nation depends on them, we're in very serious trouble, since
there are only a few million left.
</P>
<P>
   One of their big problems is competing with agribusinesses. But
when Congress extends a helping hand to the little guys, the
agribusinesses, who own the lobbyists and give the campaign
contributions, generally manage to land in the safety net. ``We've
increased the payment limit to $460,000 a farm,'' says Chuck
Hassebrook of the Center for Rural Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The great law of special-interest politics is that a group with
moral clout and little more can get Congress to spend money on its
behalf, but it cannot get Congress to do anything that hurts the
guys with the cash.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the hogs. Iowa farmers grow lots of pigs. ``We want
something to do when we're not in the fields in the spring,'' says
Linus Stolberg, who farms in Palo Alto County. He was telling me a
story about sitting up all night with expectant sows that made me
somewhat more sympathetic to the argument that we should all be
paying people to do this stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Stolberg, who's currently supporting Bill Bradley, says the
Clinton administration and George Bush's friends in the Republican
establishment are both afraid to take on Big Pork. Corporate hog
farming has gotten very popular lately, despite the fact that
monster pig herds create an unfortunate byproduct known as ``waste
lagoons.''
</P>
<P>
   Like so very, very many things in this nation, the lagoons are
no problem at all if they're run properly. However, when things
don't work out you get situations like North Carolina after
Hurricane Floyd, where a good part of the state wound up awash in
both floodwaters and pig manure.
</P>
<P>
   Increased pork production helped drive prices into the ground
last year, ruining a lot of smaller farmers. I think I speak for us
all when I say that all things being equal, I would prefer to keep
Stolberg in the pig business and skip the waste lagoons.
</P>
<P>
   Many people think the smaller farmers could compete pretty well
if the federal government enforced antitrust laws and kept the meat
packers from entering into preferential contracts with the pork
factories, some of whom happen to be the packers themselves in
different corporate guises. ``These people are so inefficient it's
unbelievable,'' says Stolberg. ``Who's going to sit up all night
with the corporate hog? Nobody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1937EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
