<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8450 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-VOTING-RATES-NYT     01-17 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTING-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE AND ALEXANDER BLAME FALLING VOTING RATES ON $1,000
CONTRIBUTION LIMIT
</HEADLINE>
  (Report: Testing Politics) 
(nk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Their wistfulness is probably forgivable.
</P>
<P>
   Each held important national office. Each won tough statewide
elections. Each had a set of proposals and ideas about what the
first president of the next century should do and stand for. Yet as
voters in Iowa prepare for the first real event of the presidential
season, the caucuses on Monday, Lamar Alexander and Dan Quayle sit
on the sidelines and consider why they are not campaigning here.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the answer is obviously the fund-raising juggernaut of
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, which at last count had amassed $63
million.
</P>
<P>
   But to Alexander and Quayle, the more serious obstacle was the
$1,000 limit on presidential campaign contributions, enacted in
1974.
</P>
<P>
   In separate interviews, they contended that the $1,000 limit now
serves primarily to clear the field before anyone gets to vote.
</P>
<P>
   They said the limit, combined with the scramble by states to
hold early primaries, was a major factor in declining voting rates
that saw just 49 percent of adults going to the polls in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the system we have got,'' said Alexander, the former
governor of Tennessee and secretary of education, ``the media picks
a winner, the fund-raisers place their bets, the thousand-dollar
limit runs everybody else out of the race, and it is all decided
before Thanksgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, said Quayle, the former vice president and senator
from Indiana, voters say: ``Okay, we're going to have these
candidates. I didn't have anything to say about that. I didn't
choose this situation. It's basically handed to me. There is this
sort of anointment going on, so I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither argued that a higher limit, or no limit at all, would
have enabled him to outdo Bush, whose take would also have been
greater. But without the $1,000 limit, Alexander said: ``I would
have raised enough. The problem is not that Bush has raised too
much, it's that nobody else can raise enough to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that except for a front-runner and an occasional
``media-certified challenger'' (a position Alexander conceded he
held in 1996), candidates find that they cannot raise the money to
compete. If the limit was removed, Quayle said, most of his $1,000
donors would have given $5,000, ``and I'd be out there debating.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Alexander nor Quayle sounded bitter. Each said it is
important to be a good sport. They discussed the system only after
they were asked. Quayle was interviewed on Friday in Phoenix and
Alexander a few days earlier in Nashville. Elizabeth Dole, the
other prominent Republican to pull out of the presidential race,
has also blamed money and the calendar. She declined to be
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the limit has been a frequent proposal from Republicans
in Congress. They have argued that while everything in politics
costs more than in 1974, and the spending limit for presidential
candidates who accept federal funds has grown to $33.5 million from
$10 million, the $1,000 figure was an anachronism.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats and outsiders have been unwilling to give ground
on the issue without getting something in return, and the proposal
has gone nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander and Quayle argued that getting rid of the limit would
not be enough to restore the public's sense of participation. They
argued that it was also necessary to spread the primaries and
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Alexander said, the emphasis on Iowa and New
Hampshire is the equivalent of the National Football League letting
sportswriters pick the Super Bowl teams and playing the game at the
beginning of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love to pick winners,'' Alexander said. ``But we don't
usually stop there. We play the season or run the race. In
presidential politics we say, `Okay, we'll pick a winner. We'll bet
on him. That's it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said that as a senator, he had introduced legislation
calling for four regional primaries to be held a month apart. That
would be better than the current system, he said, where ``there is
no time for reflection. There is no time for discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   He said another advantage of regional, ordered primaries would
be that candidates ``would have to get to know the whole country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a thing called America,'' Quayle said. ``It's not
just Iowa and New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who favors slightly more regions voting three weeks
apart, said, ``That would give the candidates a chance to compete,
debate, go home, rest, brush their teeth, and raise some more money
based on their most recent successes.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not object to Iowa and New Hampshire coming
first, if the media would treat them as ``Off Broadway rather than
the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle said he thought any change would require strong
presidential support. That would be difficult, he said, because
after being elected, presidents feel that ``it's a pretty good
system. I made it through. I'm on top of the hill right now, so why
change it?''
</P>
<P>
   If regional primaries could be arranged, Alexander said, ``then
the people in every part of the country would have a chance to
evaluate the candidates, and the issues, and, more importantly, to
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle identified two other factors that he said encouraged
apathy and discouraged voting. He said excessive media coverage of
campaign fund-raising ``reinforces the stereotypes that a lot of
people have, that this is all a grubby game, people are on the
take, and if you have a lot of money you can buy access.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it was reasonable for the media to report on
fund-raising, not only because occasionally the reporting turned up
corruption, but ``because you know how much time we have to spend
raising money. It's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   And he said the partisan atmosphere in Washington not only
discouraged voting but running for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no trust, and people see this,'' Quayle said. As a
result, ``you are going to have people look and they go `Gosh, that
is a congressman!' They roll their eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   But both former candidates focused on the $1,000 limit, and each
cited the million dollars that Stewart Mott, the General Motors
heir, had given Sen. Eugene J. McCarthy for his antiwar run in
1968. ``He changed history,'' Quayle said of McCarthy. ``Does that
make him a corrupt person because he took a lot of money?''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said the limit ``has made campaigns longer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has restricted the candidates' ability to get out their
views,'' he said. ``It has turned Washington into a city of
panhandlers, who accost each other begging for thousand-dollar
contributions as their principal occupation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has turned over more power to the rich and famous. Pretty
soon the only people able to run will be Warren Beatty, Donald
Trump and the latest Powerball winner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 1939EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
