<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8451 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-WB-LADN-CORRECTION     01-17 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WB-LADN-CORRECTION </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WB FUTURE BRIGHT IN SPITE OF LOWER RATINGS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fixes name Turell throughout) 
 
 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Executives at the WB faced television reporters Monday in the
awkward position of explaining an unprecedented decline in its
ratings even while its schedule includes some of prime time's most
talked-about shows.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-oriented network that brings us ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer,'' ``Felicity'' and ``Dawson's Creek'' is taking steps
toward broadening its base, announcing it will get the next drama
series from one of the creators of ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Turell, WB's top spokesman, explained to the Television
Critics' Association in Pasadena the chief cause for the first
ratings loss in the network's five-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Year to year, our ratings are down, and although we certainly
don't like it, there are some obvious reasons why,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most importantly, we dropped (Chicago superstation) WGN from
our national coverage,'' he said. The WB last year cut ties with
WGN because, in most markets, the network was carried on two
stations, one cable and one over-the-air. The net loss was 10
million homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence in this season we took a necessary but difficult
step back in order to localize our affiliate base across the
country,'' Turell said.
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed to ABC's phenomenal game show ``Who Wants to Be
a Millionaire'' and the impact it has had on all the competition.
In fact, ``Millionaire'' seems to be the program getting the most
mention by networks not airing it during the two-week TCA publicity
tour.
</P>
<P>
   Susanne Daniels, entertainment president, announced the network
has closed a deal with John Wells, co-creator of ``ER,'' ``West
Wing'' and ``Third Watch'' on NBC,'' to air his next prime-time
series. No concept was announced for the show, which could be ready
as early as one year from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of his success at NBC this season, John was not able
to produce another pilot for this spring,'' Daniels said. ``But he
and (Warner Bros. Television president) Peter Roth have promised us
his next show, and that's all I need to know to sleep a little
better at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels and WB chief executive officer Jamie Kellner both talked
of broadening the network's base to some extent, but Kellner said
the WB is not looking to reinvent itself as another ABC, CBS or
NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a strategy that aggregates a very valuable audience
that advertisers are willing to step up and pay a premium for,
which is what we have, is driving us close to the break-even
point,'' Kellner said. ``I think that, in fact, it will be a
disadvantage one day to be broad because then you become special to
no one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be narrow and have a unique special relationship
with an important demographic than be a broad network that doesn't
have any group that feels passionately about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
