<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UGA-TENN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia women rock Tennessee in 78-51 upset
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ For the last four years, all Georgia coach Andy
Landers could do as Chamique Holdsclaw routinely tore apart his
team was respectfully dub her ``the Great Denominator.'' On Monday,
the Lady Bulldogs may have unveiled her successor in their bitter
SEC rivalry with Tennessee in the high-flying form of Deana Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot junior forward, nicknamed ``Tweety'' for her athletic
ability, equalled her career high with 25 points and played a major
role in Georgia's superb defensive effort as the seventh-ranked
Lady Dogs easily carved up No. 2 Tennessee 78-51.
</P>
<P>
   In snapping a five-game losing streak to the Lady Volunteers,
Georgia (17-2, 3-1 SEC) also inflicted the worst SEC loss ever
suffered by Tennessee. The 51 points for the Lady Vols (13-3, 3-1)
also ties the second-lowest total in their illustrious history.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan, whom Landers has been imploring all season to become more
consistent, scored from everywhere _ on drives to the basket, back
door plays, perimeter jumpers as well as making six of 10 free
throw attempts _ as Georgia humiliated a Tennessee team clearly in
disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Before a Stegeman Coliseum capacity crowd of 10,523 and a
national television audience, Nolan also put the manacles on
Tennessee All-American guard Semeka Randall, who averages nearly 15
points a game but finished with only five.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Dogs outscored Tennessee 47-21 in the second half and
forced the Lady Vols into 32 percent shooting and 29 turnovers that
resulted in 31 Georgia points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a beautiful job defensively,'' Landers said. ``There
was never any pressure on our offense because we were able to stop
them over and over again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Dogs took the lead for good at 26-24 in the first half
on a fastbreak bucket by Coco Miller. Georgia dashed out to a 15-3
run over the first 5:29 of the second half and Tennessee got no
closer than nine. Coco Miller had 14 points and Tawana McDonald had
13 and 10 rebounds for Georgia, while Tennessee was led by Tamika
Catchings' 13 points and 12 from Gwen Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't compete,'' Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said.
``Give Georgia credit, they played so hard. We didn't match their
intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, which plays Georgia Tech Thursday, isn't ready to
proclaim this victory anything more than a big SEC win, especially
since another key conference game looms Sunday at No. 10 Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a real big game for us,'' Nolan said. ``We don't want
to celebrate too much, but we're real happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Parker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
