<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8460 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-NFCFEATURE-COX     01-17 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCFEATURE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rams to give Martz job when Vermeil retires
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Having made history a day earlier, the Rams looked
to their future Monday, well beyond this Sunday's NFC Championship
Game. Whatever happens against Tampa Bay, whenever Dick Vermeil
retires, offensive coordinator Mike Martz will become the Rams'
next head coach.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, the Rams have agreed to offer Martz the head
coaching job when Vermeil retires _ likely when the 63-year-old's
contract expires in two years. No doubt Martz will accept, with
Vermeil's blessing. The first-year coordinator of the Rams'
record-setting offense, which torched Minnesota 49-37 Sunday, said
Monday he's not considering any of the five head coaching vacancies
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe my future as a head coach in the NFL will be with
the St. Louis Rams,'' said Martz. ''I am therefore announcing that
I am not a candidate for any other head coaching positions in the
NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Already this year's most coveted coordinator candidate, Martz
was, according to media reports, under consideration by Dallas, New
England, New Orleans and Green Bay. While he was hoping to minimize
distractions with St. Louis a 14-point favorite to win Sunday and
reach Super Bowl XXXIV in Atlanta, the Rams also wanted to insure
their future.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't want to lose the best offensive coordinator in
football,'' said Jay Zygmunt, the Rams' executive vice-president
who helped negotiate a new two-year contract for Martz. ''We
promise to offer Mike the head coaching job when Dick is no longer
coaching here.''
</P>
<P>
   ''No one wanted to lose Mike as an offensive coordinator,'' said
Rams president John Shaw, who admitted the glut of coaching
vacancies and interest Martz attracted influenced the Rams'
decision. ''I would say that was a serious factor. We have a
commitment that he's not going to consider any jobs at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a natural fit,'' said Shaw. ''This is what Dick
wanted to do. He wanted to keep the staff in place.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel great about it,'' said Vermeil. ''Mike and I are here
for one thing _ to win football games. And we're doing a pretty
good job now. He's a very, very talented guy. I don't want to work
my tail off and get this thing up here and turn it over to a guy
who doesn't take it even higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Vermeil first discussed the plan with Martz a couple of weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was his intention that this opportunity was going to be
there for me. I think it's going to work out,'' Martz said. But it
was Shaw who first proposed this scenario to Vermeil, who endorsed
it.
</P>
<P>
   The move was made now to also allow Martz and the Rams to
concentrate on preparing for Tampa Bay _ and, they hope, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's been a real distraction,'' Martz said of
questions about other jobs. ''It's very flattering but my
intentions have always been to stay here. And my family's.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Martz's second tenure with the Rams. The team's
receivers coach from 1992-96, Martz was Washington's quarterbacks
coach the last two seasons. Here, Martz's offensive creativity _
along with quarterback Kurt Warner's accuracy and the speed and
big-play ability of the Rams' receivers _ helped St. Louis score
526 points (third-highest in NFL history) and become the league's
top-ranked offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams want all that to continue, through Sunday and beyond.
Martz does, too. ''This is where I want to be,'' he said. ''I do
not want to be a coach at this point at any other place than St.
Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
