<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Championship challenges: Can Titans, Bucs stop steamroller
offenses?
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Something will have to give in Sunday's NFL conference
championship games.
</P>
<P>
   The favorites _ the Jacksonville Jaguars in the AFC and St.
Louis Rams in the NFC _ feature two of the league's most prolific
offenses. Their opponents have two of the NFL's more stingier
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Titans and Buccaneers score enough points to upset the
Jags and Rams? Can the underdogs slow down the NFL' reigning
offensive juggernauts? Can anyone?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen a defense that has done it yet,'' Rams
quarterback Kurt Warner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, who host Tampa Bay in the NFC championship game, might
be the greatest team on turf. St. Louis scored a league-high 526
points this season, the third-highest total in NFL history, and
averaged more than 400 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   Warner was voted the league's MVP after throwing 41 touchdowns
in his first season as an NFL starter. Running back Marshall Faulk,
who had more than 2,000 yards from scrimmage, and receiver Isaac
Bruce also are headed to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis was held to 27 points or fewer only once this season _
a 24-21 loss at Tennessee _ and has won 10 games in a row at home.
The Rams averaged 36 points per game on the artificial turf of St.
Louis' Trans World Dome.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rams hadn't beaten a team with a winning record until
defeating Minnesota 49-37 on Sunday. And St. Louis probably hasn't
faced a defense as formidable as Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers held opponents to 17 points or fewer in 13 games,
including a 14-13 victory over the Redskins on Sunday. Washington,
which had the NFC's No. 2-ranked offense, was held to 157 total
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played against some explosive teams and I think our guys
are used to that,'' Buccaneers coach Tony Dungy said. ``It won't be
anything different. We won't be awed by their personnel. They're
certainly no more explosive than Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were better than the Vikings in the second round. St.
Louis scored five touchdowns in the first 21 1/2 minutes of the
second half; Tampa Bay hasn't allowed an offensive touchdown in 10
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to win, we're going to have to slow them down,'' Dungy
said. ``I don't think we'll be able to win an 80-point game like
they had (Sunday). No question, we're going to have to play our
best defensive game of the year because this is an explosive
offense, a unit that's used to scoring points. But we've played
teams like this all year.''
</P>
<P>
   So have the Titans, who will face the Jags in the AFC
championship game at Jacksonville's Alltel Stadium. The Jaguars
crushed the Dolphins 62-7 on Saturday, scoring the second-highest
total in playoff history. Jacksonville's eruption was eclipsed only
by the 1940 Chicago Bears, who beat the Redskins 73-0 in the NFL
title game.
</P>
<P>
   But Tennessee corralled Indianapolis' high-octane offense in a
19-16 victory on Sunday. The Titans held Colts running back
Edgerrin James to only 56 rushing yards, and took away quarterback
Peyton Manning's play-action passing.
</P>
<P>
   But doing it on the road might be a different animal for
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough because they know everything that we
throw at them, and we know everything they can throw at us,''
Titans defensive end
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Holmes said. ``I don't think it's going to be a
Miami-Jacksonville type score.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
