<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8466 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      01-17 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IT WON'T BE ELIZABETH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Elizabeth Dole's endorsement of Gov. George W. Bush
the other day set off speculation that she is angling to become his
running mate, which she coyly did nothing to deny.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has already virtually ruled out that possibility by
noting he means to pick as veep ``someone who likes me'' and shares
a confidential and ideological rapport. Despite the nice polite
things Dole and Bush said about each other when she embraced his
presidential candidacy, their relationship is inherently awkward.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the fact she would bring little to the ticket
except her gender, which is of dubious value, there are two
deep-rooted emotional reasons why she won't get the nod: her
husband Bob and his father, the former president.
</P>
<P>
   For three decades, those two Republicans rose simultaneously up
the party ladder - one in the executive branch, the other in the
legislative - clawing at each other, stepping on each other's toes,
elbowing each other aside when possible and distrusting each other
all the way.
</P>
<P>
   Their mutual hostility was usually carefully masked from the
public in the cause of party unity. But it surfaced in 1988 when
both were seeking the Republican presidential nomination. In the
New Hampshire primary, when then-Vice President Bush bested Dole,
Dole's response was furious.
</P>
<P>
   Bush should ''stop lying about my campaign,'' Dole snarled, a
remark that was not just the outburst of a sore loser but the
culmination of decades of mutual tension.
</P>
<P>
   The wife and son were technically non-combatants during this
running confrontation, but their loyalty and sympathy are naturally
with their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   To recap, briefly:
</P>
<P>
   In December 1972, Bush shoved Dole out as chairman of the
Republican National Committee; Dole did not want to leave, but Bush
lobbied President Nixon for the job. Both men competed to become
President Ford's vice president. That time, Dole won. When Ford
lost his re-election bid in 1976, Bush supporters blamed Dole's
sardonic performance for the ticket's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, in 1980, both were presidential candidates but
were flattened by the Ronald Reagan bandwagon. When Dole's campaign
collapsed before Bush's did, Elizabeth went to work for Reagan, not
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1980 convention, Dole was among the insiders pressing
Reagan not to give the second spot to Bush, the campaign runner-up,
but to turn instead to ex-President Ford. Reagan ended up selecting
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Dole was stuck in his Senate role so long as Bush remained vice
president, with no real shot at the 1988 GOP nomination against
Reagan's heir--apparent. In 1996, when it was finally Dole's turn
to run for the White House, both Bushes backed fellow Texan Sen.
Phil Gramm for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after the collapse of Gramm's campaign and Pat
Buchanan emergence as the only GOP alternative to Dole that the
Bushes finally endorsed Dole.
</P>
<P>
   During Elizabeth's campaign, her husband sounded as though he
really supported Sen. John McCain, his close friend. Was her
presidential effort rooted in a dual desire to block a second Bush,
one way or the other?
</P>
<P>
   It is premature this early in 2000 to be discussing a Bush vice
president. After all, Bush has yet to win the Republican
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Politics being politics, however, we can't help ourselves. Who
for veep? It's the next puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has given us some guidelines. He does not intend to pick a
running mate who can act as a bridge to views contrary to his own,
nor one who will merely be useful in one large state, nor one who
represents the defeated faction in his party. He wants a soul mate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain says he doesn't want the job. Note: this is also what
Sen. Lyndon Johnson said, right up to the moment Sen. John F.
Kennedy tapped him for a ticket that would not have won the
November election without Johnson's power to carry Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Bush is reacting to his father's unhappy experience as
vice president. Reagan never once in eight years invited the Bush
family into the White House private quarters. The two men had
little in common and no history of confidential communication.
Nancy Reagan was freely quoted expressing her utter scorn for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But father Bush's relationship with his own vice president
teaches a different lesson. It won't do to pick a blank slate and
hope to write upon it, either. Bush selected a young senator, Dan
Quayle, with whom he had become friends, in the hope that Quayle
would prove a pliable protigi. Qualye proved to be a political
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Bush may be merely following the Clinton script. President
Clinton tossed aside the old rules about geographical and
ideological balance to select fellow baby boomer Sen. Al Gore from
a neighboring state, with whom he felt mentally compatible. It
worked out very well for them both.
</P>
<P>
   So who's left that fits the limited Bush criteria?
</P>
<P>
   Some big state governors, with whom Bush has become friendly in
his years in the Texas statehouse. Some family advisors with
reputations in policy arenas, perhaps in Bush's weakest area of
foreign policy. Some member of Congress who could add the federal
gravitas Bush lacks.
</P>
<P>
   Some Reagan clone, still undiscovered. Somebody from outer
space?
</P>
<P>
   Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2001EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8468 &Cx1f; tth-z
r v BC-BUDGET-SPI &LR;      01-17 0134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Tuesday, January 18 and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Larry Johnson on the national-foreign desk at (206)
448-8035.
</P>
<P>
   LIBBY _ EPA investigators, already probing the health effects of
the closed vermiculite mine near Libby, Mont., are asking the
agency's regional offices to check the effects from the
asbestos-tainted ore at 60 places around the country where the ore
was processed.
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Schneider. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SONICS _ Sonics play Lakers at Los Angeles. Developing from
12:30 p.m. tipoff in Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
