A8469 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CITRUS-INSPECTIONS-NY     01-17 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITRUS-INSPECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSPECTING CITRUS FRUIT FROM AFAR WITH A DIGITAL CAMERA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas, Calif., Ind.)   By DENNIS BLANK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Growers in Florida are using digital cameras and
the Internet to market their fruit far from the citrus groves and
to resolve disputes when shipments arrive damaged.
</P>
<P>
   The images are often used to augment on-site inspections.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Martin, the assistant sales manager at the Haines City
Citrus Growers Association, said a distributor who was a new
customer recently contacted the cooperative of 200 growers located
just south of Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to see how the fruit looked in a particular bag,''
Martin said. ``We took the picture, e-mailed it to the warehouse
manager, and we got in an order for a truckload.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin called the digital images a valuable new tool, but added
that they cannot replace a physical inspection of the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Cane, president of Voita Citrus in Indianapolis, said his
field buyers in Florida, Texas and California all have digital
cameras. While he said he believed the images were an asset, they
would never be able to replace actually tasting the fruit at the
packing house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it our daily beauty contest,'' Cane said of the
photos. ``It's impossible to describe certain conditions over the
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Each load that is photographed is tagged to insure that it is
the same citrus when it arrives at a distributor, Cane said.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the supply chain, digital pictures can help
resolve disputes over damaged fruit. Both buyers and wholesalers
say the digital camera is a good way to help verify what happened
when fruit arrives scarred or rotten.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pictures are the records,'' Martin said. ``We may get
someone wanting to know why the load was rejected and they only got
$2 a case instead of $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the pictures, we may be able to show them what went
wrong,'' Martin said. ``A piece of metal may be cutting the fruit
or it may have happened during production.''
</P>
<P>
   Billy Heller, general manager of the Heller Brothers Packing
Corp. in Winter Garden, Fla., said the new technology was ``like a
fax machine was in the beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be recommending something, and the buyer may be
reluctant or vice versa,'' he said. ``So we shoot and e-mail it to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture has also adopted the new
technology, and inspectors at 12 major produce shipping terminals
around the country are now using digital cameras for marketing and
dispute resolution _ for which it charges $43 an hour _ as well as
for quality inspections.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, Martin and others expect growers to show
real-time images from packing houses on their Web sites as an
antidote to static images of fruit. ``So many sites are real
interesting the first time you see them,'' Martin said, ``but
there's nothing new the next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Les Crocker, citrus sales manager for A. Duda &AMP; Sons Inc. in
Vero Beach, Fla., said there was a downside to using the digital
camera. ``A picture, for some reason, always looks better than the
real fruit,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2009EST &QL; 
