<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GLAXO-SMITHKLINE-ART-     01-17 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLAXO-SMITHKLINE-ART-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAXO AND SMITHKLINE AGREE TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., N.C.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The summer of 1997 was unusually dreary for Glaxo
Wellcome PLC despite an unusually warm and sunny season.
</P>
<P>
   Glaxo's patent for its prize drug, Zantac, an anti-ulcer
medication that was the best-selling drug in the United States in
1996 expired that summer. Without another patent-protected
blockbuster drug in its arsenal to immediately replace Zantac, the
British pharmaceutical company began looking for a merger partner
with some probable hit drugs in the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   While copycat drug makers began marketing a generic version of
Zantac, Glaxo began talking late that year in earnest about merging
with SmithKline Beecham PLC, another British drug maker that had
the the pipeline Glaxo wanted. In it was a drug called Avandia, a
diabetes treatment with smash hit written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   The companies had qualities that complemented each other. Glaxo
had marketing resources and money to burn on research, and
SmithKline had a significant drug pipeline _ but neither company
had the size and scale to achieve the kind of success the two
companies could achieve together.
</P>
<P>
   Only one problem stood between the two drug makers: the egos of
the companies' top brass. Glaxo's chairman, Sir Richard Sykes and
SmithKline's chief executive, Jan Leschly, refused to merge,
because neither executive wanted to give up control of his drug
fiefdom.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, as Glaxo announced that it would acquire SmithKline
for about $76 billion in stock, both executives gave up the control
they so valued to a third man, Jean-Pierre Garnier. Garnier, the
chief operating officer of SmithKline will take the reins of the
newly anointed largest drug maker in the world, Glaxo SmithKline,
stepping into the role of chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Richard, 57, will become the nonexecutive chairman of the
combined company and may retire in 2002 when he turns 60, while
Leschly will leave the combined company entirely when he retires in
April.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Glaxo SmithKline did everything they could Monday
to quash the discussion about the bitter battle of egos that
prevented the companies from merging two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is today,'' Leschly said. ``What happened in the past is,
in reality, irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   While the previously collapsed merger talks may be irrelevant,
the summer of 1997, and Zantac's patent expiration, is clearly not.
It signaled the beginning of rampant consolidation within the
pharmaceutical industry as drug makers desperately sought _ and
continue to seek _ scale and size in an industry that is
fundamentally fractured. As the largest drug maker in the world,
Glaxo SmithKline will still control only 7.3 percent of the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   A major supporter of consolidation, Garnier, a Frenchman who is
a naturalized U.S. citizen, has been sitting in the shadow of
Leschly for more than five years waiting for this moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jean-Pierre always wanted control and he's been waiting
patiently,'' said James Culverwell, an analyst at Merrill Lynch in
London. ``He's an outstanding leader. Very impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Garnier has a challenging task ahead of him. The company pledged
Monday to achieve cost savings of $1.63 billion annually by the
third year of operation. More than costs, Garnier will have to
manage a trans-Atlantic work force of more than 100,000 people. And
most important, he needs to spend his $3.6 billion research and
development budget on discovering the dazzling drug before his
current roster of drugs have to compete with generic versions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Garnier will be stationed in the United States in a new
operational headquarters that the company plans to build somewhere
near New York, though the company has yet to settle on an exact
location. The company's corporate headquarters will remain in
London. Garnier said the drug maker would keep a second
headquarters in the United States because that is the company's
largest market.
</P>
<P>
   Garnier currently lives in a suburb of Philadelphia, near
SmithKline's U.S. headquarters. Glaxo's U.S. headquarters currently
is in Research Triangle Park, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Richard expressed his confidence in Garnier and his newly
appointed executive team, deflecting attention from himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is a company with unbelievable financial
power,'' Sir Richard said. ``If there are opportunities to build
and drive on the business, we will look at those opportunities and
take advantage of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the right leadership team to move the business
forward,'' he said. ``We all believe this was the right thing to do
at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the executives did not acknowledge it, analysts said a
major incentive to merge was the announcement on Thursday by
Warner-Lambert that it was in talks with Pfizer over a possible
merger, upsetting an earlier agreement between Warner-Lambert and
American Home Products. If they do combine, Pfizer and
Warner-Lambert would rank second in the world behind a combined
Glaxo SmithKline.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last year we've seen so much consolidation. There is a
real pressure on drug companies to merge,'' Culverwell said.
``Glaxo and SmithKline are biting the bullet.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all investors were thrilled that Glaxo and SmithKline had
decided to tie the knot. With the market expecting more cost
savings than the combined company pledged, shares of Glaxo dropped
4.7 percent, or 86 pence, to 1,732 pounds, and SmithKline fell 6.9
percent, or 58.5 pence, to 788.5 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Glaxo shareholders will get 58.75 percent
of the new company, while SmithKline shareholders will control
41.25 percent. SmithKline shareholders will get 0.4552 shares of
Glaxo SmithKline in exchange for each share of SmithKline that they
own. Glaxo shares will be exchanged on a one-for-one basis.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. stock markets were closed for the Martin Luther King
holiday. Glaxo's American depository receipts closed Friday at $60
and those of SmithKline were at $70.
</P>
<P>
   With combined annual revenue estimated at $25 billion, the new
company will surpass Aventis SA of Frankfurt, Germany, which was
created last year when Hoechst AG and Rhone-Poulenc SA merged, as
the world's No. 1 drug seller.
</P>
<P>
   Some jobs are likely to be cut from the combined company's
107,000 employees, though few of the nearly 22,000 jobs in the
United States are at risk, the companies said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
