<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFESTYLE-MEDICINE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS TURN TO COSMETIC MEDICINE TO MAINTAIN THEIR INCOMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 20 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the waiting room of Dr. Mark Fromer's office in
Trump Tower _ not so long ago filled with elderly patients seeking
treatment for cataract disease _ young professionals with expensive
haircuts whisper into cell phones as they wait for their 15-minute
laser eye surgery appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Patients at the SoHo Integrative Health Center in Manhattan can
see Dr. Laurie Polis, the center's dermatologist, for a routine
skin cancer check, then get the wrinkles in their forehead zapped.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Irwin Smigel, a prominent Manhattan dentist, passes people
needing routine fillings on to his associates; he is far too busy
applying the latest tooth-whitening concoction on his patients.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, doctors who specialized in so-called lifestyle
medicine _ elective and largely cosmetic procedures _ were limited
to rarefied corners of the medical profession. But facing declining
revenues because of reimbursement cuts by managed-care companies,
thousands of doctors in New York and across the country are turning
to cosmetic medicine to keep their practices lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is simple: Because nearly every elective procedure
intended to improve the appearance of a patient is not paid for by
insurance companies, patients must pay up front, often staggering
sums. Laser eye surgery, for instance, costs about $5,000. For
doctors, that means no rejected bills, no paperwork and no reduced
payments by managed-care companies.
</P>
<P>
   In some practices, cosmetic procedures are supplementing basic
care; in others, they are nearly replacing it.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 10 years, fees for many medical procedures dropped
significantly because of third-party payers, said Timothy J.
Murphy, chief executive of QVS Technology Group, a health care
consulting firm in Des Plaines, Ill., that helps doctors set up
alternatives to their usual business. ``And when doctors lost
that,'' he said, ``like any red-blooded American, they thought to
themselves, `What am I going to do here?'''
</P>
<P>
   And with a strong economy, there seems to be no shortage of
deep-pocketed consumers who feel their lives will be enhanced by
having fewer wrinkles, perpetually hairless legs and a face free of
cumbersome eyeglasses. In turn, explosions in technology have made
many of these aesthetic procedures more exacting and easier to
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Elective procedures make up nearly 25 percent of many medical
practices like plastic surgery and dermatology in urban areas,
experts in the field said, up from 10 percent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is led by laser eye surgery, which in just a few years
has transformed ophthalmology; in the last two years alone, the
number of Americans who underwent laser eye surgery to correct
their vision problems increased more than 500 percent, and doctors
who do the procedure are spending hundreds of thousands of dollars
marketing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors in a host of other medical specialties are also joining
aesthetics with medicine: Dermatologists, especially in major
cities, are prescribing more Botox injections for wrinkles than
they are acne medicines, and many are selling anti-aging creams and
other beauty products in their offices. Dentists are using the
latest in super-whitening techniques. And even
obstetrician-gynecologists are offering laser hair removal to their
patients.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction of cosmetic medicine, with its fee-for-service
payment structure and high demand, may mean that many doctors will
now shun more basic but less lucrative procedures like general eye
care and reconstructive surgery for accident victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you will find is that the supply of the low-profit
services will decline,'' said Dr. David Friend, a health care
management consultant with Watson Wyatt Worldwide in Boston. ``The
result is a tiering effect, where the best doctors are doing the
private stuff and doctors unable to succeed in those things will
provide the public service care. We have created an incentive for
everyone who can to get out of low-margin businesses, and that
could have enormous policy implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alan R. Kling, who has a dermatologic and cosmetic surgery
practice on Park Avenue, said that he is one such doctor. ``There
are certain cases that I am not doing anymore,'' Kling said, citing
complicated cancer surgeries for which he said insurance companies
reimburse him only $100, much less than the cost to him.
</P>
<P>
   Kling, whose hold music on his telephone is a running ad for
liposuction and skin injections, said that in 1996, things like
liposuction and Botox accounted for only 5 percent of his business.
Now, they are closer to 25 percent. ``It used to be when people who
came out of school wanted to do cosmetics, they were looked down
on,'' he said. ``At Harvard, they called it `throwing the pearls to
the swine.' Now, in terms of survival, it is what you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Fromer, the ophthalmologist, said that five years ago, the core
of his business was retina surgery and general ophthalmology. Now,
90 percent is laser eye surgery. He also points to economics. In
the early 1990s, he said, Medicare would pay him $3,000 to $3,500
for cataract surgery, but now he receives $750 to $2,000 per case.
``I would describe laser as the thing that allows me to offer
general care to my patients,'' Fromer said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, deciding to offer procedures that cater to
vain, stressed- out or just very wealthy patients is not a simple
matter of buying new equipment and adding another line to a Yellow
Pages ad. Doctors find that they have to overhaul their entire
practices, from the way their receptionists answer the phone to the
couches patients sit on to the length of time they make them wait
for an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And they often spend thousands of dollars on advertising: Listen
to AM radio for an hour and you might think the only things for
sale in America are laser eye surgery and auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``The demographics for these procedures is much younger, maybe
30 to 55 years old,'' said Murphy of QVS Technology Group. ``You
have to treat them differently than a 70-year-old patient trying to
get an appointment because they can't see.''
</P>
<P>
   ```I'll see if we can fit you in in three weeks' won't work with
the McDonald's society who wants it hot, wants in now and wants it
cheap,'' he said. ``The staff has to give high-class treatment. We
compare it to the airline industry: There is a difference between
the first-class cabin and the back of the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   Fromer said that he gave his office one such face lift. The
furniture and waiting room are turned out in subtle, tasteful
tones. The equipment is sleek and spotless, as though it just fell
off a space ship. Patients recovering from their surgery rest in
reclining chairs, covered in soft cotton blankets. His office
employees look as though they would fit in quite well behind the
counter of an upscale gym.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``When a patient walks through the door,'' he said, ``they have
to see that the doctor has done this before, that the equipment is
top-notch and the office has to be extremely friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the SoHo Integrative Health Center, atmosphere is taken to
the highest level. Patients see an array of specialists on one
floor, including an obstetrician-gynecologist, ophthalmologist and
internist, and can get their facials, massages, nutritional therapy
and Eastern medicine by climbing a winding staircase, past the
slate waterfall. (Dr. Polis, who runs the center, sent back the
slate once when it was not to her satisfaction.)
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes coming to the doctor feel more like self care,'' Dr.
Polis said. ``So if you include a massage, well, that is self care,
too. There is no need to compare the importance of a Pap smear with
a facial.''
</P>
<P>
   This medical mall of sorts _ where the plain vanilla medical
needs can be matched with aesthetic desires all under the same
elegant fabric-covered roof _ is driven by consumer demand, she
said. ``Those doctors who resist the trends in the way they deliver
medicine are not in tune to their patients' needs.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When money cannot be made in procedures alone, there are
products that can be sold. Dozens of businesses have opened across
the country in recent years to provide dermatologists with skin
care products. Often, the preparations they sell are similar to
those sold in department stores, only at a higher strength.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven J. Pearlman, the director of the Division of Facial
Plastic and Reconstructive Surgery at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital
Center in New York, sells alpha-hydroxy creams to prevent skin
aging, and bleaching creams for brown spots. ``They make up for
overhead,'' he said, declining to specify his exact profit margin.
</P>
<P>
   Offering skin care products and substituting a lot of the ear,
nose, throat and cancer-related surgeries he used to do with
cosmetic procedures has given his practice a whole new lease on
life, Pearlman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With medical things, first you have to fulfill numerous
requirements, like getting precertified,'' he said. ``You get paid
way later and have generated a load of paperwork. With cosmetic
things, it is, `Nice to meet you, here is the procedure, let's do
it or not do it.' It is how medicine used to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
