<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORBES-CAMPAIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISMISSING POLLS AND THE MEDIA, A CONFIDENT FORBES PLOWS AHEAD IN
IOWA
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo  NYT33 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Even though Steve Forbes has been dismissed
as a realistic presidential contender by most political pundits,
the Forbes campaign continues its seemingly never-ending swing
through Iowa, filled with the enthusiastic belief that one day, if
the breaks just fall its way, Forbes might actually occupy the Oval
Office.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes himself peppers his standard stump speech, which has not
varied in months, with phrases like ``as your commander-in-chief''
and ``when I am president,'' and his hard-core followers reward him
with standing ovations and murmured amens.
</P>
<P>
   From now until the Jan. 24 caucuses, Forbes is leading a highly
visible and heavily orchestrated bus tour of Iowa, drumming up
support in the one state where he has a shot at a fairly
respectable showing. That, of course, is because Sen. John McCain
of Arizona has decided not to compete here, making Forbes a virtual
shoo-in for the No. 2 spot behind the Republican front-runner, Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes needs a strong showing in Iowa to propel him into New
Hampshire. And to that end, his legendary organizational prowess
and lavish spending are on display as his two-bus cavalcade,
blaring Willie Nelson tunes, pulls into small towns. Forbes, a
gawky but effective speaker, and his entourage put on a spectacle
filled with power-point presentations, a plea for followers to
create a ``family and friends'' network of additional supporters,
and plenty of free food and gifts.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   No one goes away empty-handed or unfed. Gifts include a copy of
Forbes' book, a 15-minute biographical video, a bright orange
long-sleeved T-shirt with the campaign logo to wear on caucus
night, a blue computer mouse pad emblazoned with his name, campaign
buttons, campaign literature and a list of caucus sites in every
Iowa neighborhood. And wherever Forbes goes, the crowd is typically
already seated at tables where chili and potato soup, turkey
sandwiches and vegetable soup, individual crocks of cheese soup or,
in one case, a pork dinner, have been served.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is so organized that at each stop two young men
rush out of the bus before Forbes, carrying American and Iowa flags
to set up on the podium, where a huge Forbes sign already hangs.
Those who attend have either been called directly by the Forbes
campaign or drawn by an advertisement in the local newspaper or on
local radio. When they sit down, a packet of Forbes information
identifying their caucus site is already at their seat.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of 100 to 300 greeted Forbes at each stop on a recent
two-day Iowa swing, many saying they were little concerned that
Forbes' chances of winning are slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is a sure thing in Iowa to my way of thinking,'' said
Don Hahn, a retired farmer in Keota.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Stockland, an assistant manager of a grocery store in
Washington, Iowa, said: ``I like what he says about the family and
the flat tax, and I don't care what anyone else thinks. You are
supposed to vote for who you think is the best, no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Lorna Shepherd, an Ainsworth farmer: ``I don't vote to be
part of a bandwagon, I got to like what I hear. That's why we have
the caucuses.''
</P>
<P>
   What is particularly surprising about Forbes is how little his
basic stump speech has changed in months of campaigning, and how
highly programmed his presentations are. Even his jokes do not
vary. His reference to ``the Infernal, oops, I mean Internal
Revenue Service'' is a consistent laugh-getter.
</P>
<P>
   This consistency and these traditional themes are what his
followers have come to hear: a presentation against abortion, in
favor of a flat income tax and in favor of more choices in
education, health care and Social Security investments. He
continues to play the role of Washington outsider _ ``Washington
special interests have no hooks in me'' _ and he puts down the tax
plans of Bush and McCain, whom he refers to as the ``timid twins on
taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   For his campaigns, Forbes has spent $62 million from his own
fortune of over $400 million: $25 million in 1999 and $37 million
in his 1996 bid. In Iowa, that money has been used to set up a
powerful organization for a caucus competition, one in which a
strong organization often matters more than a winning message.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has 4,000 caucus captains in the state's 99 precincts and
has identified 88,000 ``Forbes-friendly'' households. Those
captains, along with everyone else who attends Forbes' appearances,
are being asked to bring five people each on caucus night and are
given cards to identify them to the Forbes campaign. Around 100,000
of the state's 500,000 Republicans typically attend the caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is for Forbes to do better than he did in the Iowa
straw poll last August, when he received 20 percent of the vote to
Bush's 31 percent. (The rest was scattered over 10 other
candidates, with Elizabeth Dole, who has since dropped out,
finishing third, with 14 percent of the vote.)
</P>
<P>
   The core of Forbes' support is made up of social and economic
conservatives: the Christian right of the party and those who want
less government and lower taxes. But to succeed, Forbes has to go
beyond that and gain a share of Iowa's undecided vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of undecided,'' said Steve Grubbs, former
chairman of the Iowa Republican Party and head of the Forbes Iowa
campaign, ``and we've got to have those undecided break our way on
caucus night.''
</P>
<P>
   The view from the Forbes campaign is that Forbes needs a strong
showing in Iowa to give him momentum for the New Hampshire primary
just eight days later. ``We don't have to win,'' Grubbs said. ``Our
job in Iowa is to get Steve Forbes to New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how much of the Iowa vote Forbes needed, Grubbs said,
``South of 20 percent, he goes wounded. We need to be north of 20
percent, there's no doubt about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most local polls show Forbes taking around 20 percent of the
Iowa vote.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for all the campaign ebullience, there is a defensiveness
over Forbes' low standing in polls and his dismissal by the
political establishment. One piece of campaign literature
distributed at all Forbes events says: ``With George W. Bush
weakening in the early states _ and John McCain unprepared to run a
full 50-state presidential campaign _ Steve Forbes is now in a
position to surprise everyone and win the GOP. nomination. That's
what the media isn't telling you.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the Forbes rhetoric about bold ideas, it often seems
that he is not so much running for president as he is running to
stop Bush, whom Forbes portrays as a latecomer to his anti-tax
crusade, though in a weaker form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that Bush is the front-runner, he's trying to portray
himself as a tax cutter,'' Forbes said, seated in his campaign bus
one dark Iowa night. ``I'm delighted that others are beginning to
evolve to where I am. Bush will have a fight on his hands and it
will be a long one. He tried to shut us down at the straw poll and
it did not work. I'm in for the duration. The Republican Party
wants to anoint Bush, but I don't think they will be able to pull
off their coronation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2027EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
