<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-BRITAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPANISH JUDGE SEEKS 2ND EXAM FOR PINOCHET 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ After a weekend of suspense, the Spanish
government Monday sent to the British government a judge's petition
that seeks a second medical examination of Gen. Augusto Pinochet to
determine if earlier tests wrongly declared him unfit to stand
trial for human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Baltasar Garzon, who is leading the effort to have the
former Chilean dictator extradited for trial in Spain, submitted
the document to the government Friday, but received no assurance
that it would be sent to London by Tuesday, the deadline set by the
British government for comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's detention in Britain for the last 15 months has
strained relations between Spain and Chile, and the Spanish
government had said it would send on Garzon's document only if it
added something new to the case. Over the weekend, the government
found a diplomatic way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Spanish government, there is nothing new in the
case,'' said Jose Luis Solano, a Foreign Ministry spokesman. ``But
Judge Garzon says there are new elements.''
</P>
<P>
   The government reiterated that it would not appeal any decision
by British Home Secretary Jack Straw, who said last week that he
was inclined to end the extradition proceedings and release General
Pinochet because a medical examination in Britain on Jan. 5 found
him unfit to stand trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
