u f BC-CYBER-MERGERS-BOS &LR;      01-17 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-MERGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SMALL HIGH-TECH FIRMS IN ACQUISITION DEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The maker of one of the world's top-selling electronic-commerce
security software systems, CyberTrust, is being sold by its
founder, GTE Corp., to a British rival, Baltimore Technologies PLC,
for $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, ScanSoft Inc., which develops software for
transferring digital images from scanners onto the Internet, said
it is buying out a competitor, Caere Corp., of Los Gatos, Calif.,
for about $143 million in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   Although unrelated, the two transactions underscore both the
continuing, robust growth and the volatility of the young
high-technology companies that are a Massachusetts economic
mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Technologies's chief executive, Fran Rooney, said
about 60 CyberTrust employees, most of whom work in Needham, Mass.,
will be laid off as part of the sale. Most of these veterans,
however, are expected to be offered jobs in other GTE divisions, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney also plans to retire the CyberTrust brand name, at least
temporarily, ``because it is so closely associated with GTE.'' He
said some CyberTrust features may be incorporated in Baltimore
Technologies's flagship security software, UniCert.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its all-stock deal, Baltimore Technologies is also
getting CyberTrust's 70,000-square-foot building in Needham and
plans to move its US headquarters there from Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ScanSoft, which was a Xerox Corp. subsidiary until a complex
spinoff last year, offered no details about how personnel will be
deployed after its takeover of Caere Corp. is completed this
spring. But it indicated layoffs are in store.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, chief executive Mark Tivnan said
ScanSoft hopes to reduce combined operating costs by $10 million a
year or more.
</P>
<P>
   ScanSoft has about 60 employees in Peabody, Mass. and sales
offices in the United States and Britain. Caere Corp., with strong
sales activity in France, Germany, the Netherlands, and Eastern
Europe, has about 300 employees altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Glamorous on their face because of the cutting-edge products
involved, both mergers in fact involve relatively small firms that
are jockeying with many others for position in their markets.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Technologies, which Gartner Group listed last year as
``a sleeping giant,'' tied for third place in market share with
CyberTrust, behind Entrust Technologies and VeriSign. Baltimore
Technologies posted a nine-month loss Sept. 30 of $39.5 million on
sales of $26.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   At GTE, which itself is about to merge with Bell Atlantic Corp.,
CyberTrust is seen as only a blip on corporate ledgers. A
spokeswoman said GTE doesn't report financial results for its
operating units, but Baltimore Technologies said that in 1998,
CyberTrust lost $33 million on sales of $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   CyberTrust was born out of GTE's early work for the US
government on security for financial and defense secrets
transmitted over the Internet. It became a separate division,
CyberTrust Solutions, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore Technologies got its start in Dublin, Ireland, in
1976, moving to London last year after a merger with another
competitor, Zergo Holdings PLC.
</P>
<P>
   It made its first overtures for CyberTrust over a year ago,
Rooney said, but added that GTE's decision to sell may have been
linked to preparations for the merger with Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, Baltimore Technologies gets a specialized
computer-software hosting service that GTE operates for CyberTrust
users. Along with current CyberTrust clients such as American
Express Corp. and MasterCharge International, Rooney said, this
infrastructure provides his firm with a solid US foothold for
selling full-service e-commerce packages.
</P>
<P>
   ScanSoft and Caere are leaders in their field of software that
converts desk-scanner and digital camera images for storage or
network transmission. ScanSoft alone claims 2.9 million registered
users of its products.
</P>
<P>
   For the first nine months of 1999, the two firms posted $70
million in combined sales _ $22.99 million for ScanSoft and $47
million for Caere. ScanSoft had $2.5 million in earnings; Caere,
$5.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Stock markets in the United States were closed Monday in
observance of the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday, but the news sent
Baltimore Technologies shares up 23 percent on the London Stock
Exchange, where they closed at 6,752.5 pence.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's Nasdaq trading, Baltimore Technologies's American
depositary receipts closed at 89 1/16, up 5 13/16. Also on Nasdaq,
ScanSoft closed Friday at 5 3/8, and Caere at 7 7/16, both
unchanged for the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
