<SLUG> BC-GORE-CAMPAIGN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING BIRTHDAY PROVIDES ELECTION-YEAR BONUS FOR GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the dais of Ebenezer Baptist Church, what he called
``the high ground'' of the civil rights movement, Vice President Al
Gore clasped hands Monday with Coretta Scott King and swayed as the
choir hummed ``We Shall Overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an election-year bonus, this observance of the birthday
of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., an ``official'' tableau
provided to Gore by dint of his position as vice president and one
he used to advance his platform in the race for the Democratic
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He extolled the record of the Clinton administration in
furthering the prosperity of African-Americans and their
appointments to federal positions. He called for affirmative
action, recalled his tie-breaking vote in the Senate in favor of
gun control, and lamented the Republicans' failure to confirm Bill
Lann Lee as chief of the Justice Department's civil rights
division.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating King's summons to build ``a greater economic base,''
Gore echoed phrases from his stump speech: ``We must keep our
prosperity going, not for the primary benefit of those who already
have the most, but to profit at last those who as yet have so
little. Like Dr. King, we do not seek to comfort the comfortable;
we do not seek to give away our hard-won surplus to the powerful
few, but to use it to establish justice and opportunity for the
many.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also announced that private donors had contributed half a
million dollars to help restore the Ebenezer church, where King
preached, and that the Clinton administration would seek $1.5
million in next year's budget to preserve and maintain King's
birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. King, whose husband would have been 71 on Saturday, hailed
Gore as ``a compelling advocate for racial justice.'' She praised
him for denouncing the Confederate battle flag, which flies over
the capitol of neighboring South Carolina, and recalled that his
father, the late Al Gore Sr., a longtime senator from Tennessee,
opposed the poll tax and the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour service featured two of King's children, Dexter
Scott King and the Rev. Bernice Albertine King, who offered a
fierce and passionate tribute to her mother. (``Thank you,
Bernice,'' Mrs. King said upon taking the pulpit, ``but I can take
care of myself.'')
</P>
<P>
   The audience of a few hundred people included Alexis Herman, the
labor secretary, as well as John Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO,
which has endorsed Gore, and James P. Hoffa, president of the
Teamsters union, which has made no endorsement. Both served as
grand marshals in a King parade here.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers have said that the votes of African-Americans are
crucial to his campaign, especially in the South, and Gore has made
frequent appearances here to rally blacks on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has referred to the assassination of King as an important
event in his young adulthood. He was driving from Boston to
Washington on spring break in 1968 when he heard the news on the
car radio. He said he drove to downtown Washington to pick up his
mother at a store, where protesters were smashing the windows.
</P>
<P>
   Gore described the assassination as one of the factors
contributing to his disillusionment with politics. He has said he
became more optimistic about the system after he worked as a
reporter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
