<SLUG> BC-MA-CISCO-EXPAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO BUYING 580 ACRES NEAR BOSTON FOR EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes acquisitions text table.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Cisco Systems Inc., the big California
comptuer networking firm which has been expanding in Massachusetts,
plans to acquire 580 acres of land northwest of Boston to
accommodate up to 1.8 million square feet of new office space.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco, a maker of equipment used in constructing the backbone
for the Internet, said it plans to spend $240 million over the next
few years developing the land, in three parcels in Boxborough,
Harvard, and Littleton. The Boxborough site already has a
277,000-square-foot structure.
</P>
<P>
   The real estate purchase, being made for an undisclosed sum, is
part of Cisco's bid to aggressively expand in New England through
internal growth and possible future acquisitions, said Ellen E.
Jamason, director of worldwide real estate for Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   The company has made a string of acquisitions and investments in
Massachusetts totaling more than $3 billion over the past five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New England area is attractive to us in part because of
the startup and technology-related venture capital activity'' in
the region, said Jamason. ``We're also particularly attracted to
the education centers (in greater Boston). These factors make it
one of the highly fruitful areas for acquisition and talent for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Of 47 acquisitions worldwide that Cisco has made, eight have
been New England companies. Cisco has also made a number of
investments in Massachusetts companies, including Akamai
Technologies Inc. in Cambridge. Cisco invested $49 million in
Akamai before the company went public last year, a stake that is
now worth more than $1 billion, based on Akamai's market current
capitalization.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is also hiring at a rapid pace in the Bay State and has
plans to grow its current employee base there from 1,500 to about
5,000 over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This announcement demonstrates our commitment to the growth of
high technology in New England,'' said Don Listwin, executive vice
president of Cisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a clear indicator not only of the strength of our
economy, but also of Cisco's recognition that Massachusetts is an
excellent source of high technology talent,'' said Gov. Paul
Cellucci, who met with Cisco executives in November regarding the
company's plans to expand in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cisco has been in Massachusetts for five years, it was
only in recent years that the company decided to set up a
substantial presence in the area. In the last two years, Cisco
spent $2.6 billion of the $3 billion used to purchase five of its
eight New England companies, which included GeoTel Communications
Corp. and WebLine Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is not the only large technology company to have
discovered the Bay State as fertile ground for technology
development. Sun Microsystems Inc., based in Palo Alto, last year
opened a $124 million, 158-acre campus in Burlington, Mass. for its
1,800 employees. Sun, which makes network servers and computer
workstations, plans to ramp up to 4,000 employees in Burlington
over several years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Oracle Corp. of Redwood Shores, Calif., and Lucent
Technologies Inc. of Murray Hill, N.J., are among several large
technology companies that have recently beefed up their presence in
the Bay State.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco already occupies about 800,000 square feet of office space
at five sites in Chelmsford, Lowell, Burlington, Lexington, and
Manchester, N.H. The company has not decided whether it will
relocate its existing offices to the three new sites or maintain
its current leases.
</P>
<P>
   Although the land being purchased is spread among three
locations, Cisco considers them part of one main campus to be
called the New England Development Center.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is purchasing the first site, a 140-acre parcel in
Boxborough, from Japanese computer maker NEC Technology. The site's
existing vacant building will be retrofitted by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Cisco plans to build 900,000 square feet of office
space in seven buildings on the second site, a 350-acre parcel that
straddles Boxborough and Harvard and was purchased from Towermarc
Business Park in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The third site, consisting of 90 acres of undeveloped land in
Littleton, was purchased from Hines Interests Limited Partnerships
in Houston, Texas. That parcel will have 640,000 square feet of
space in five buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the new campus, once under way, is expected to
take about 18 months, Jamason said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is also contemplating building a manufacturing plant on
one of the three sites. The plant, if built, would be Cisco's first
major plant outside of California, according to Carl Redfield,
senior vice president for manufacturing and logistics. Redfield
said Cisco is currently negotiating the zoning and permitting
process with local government officials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
