<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-JOKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H-E-R-E'-S JOHNNY: MCCAIN LEAVES 'EM LAUGHING ON THE CAMPAIGN
TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMILTON, N.H. _ Heard the one about the trees chasing the dogs?
If you were at Sen. John McCain's recent town hall meeting in
Merrimack, you would have. Twice.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little weather joke McCain likes to tell. So little water
in Arizona, the trees chase the dogs. Ba-dum-bum.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty amusing the first time, and it typically gets a chuckle
when the Republican presidential candidate uses it in his opening
remarks on the campaign trail, taking credit for bringing an
unseasonably warm day to New Hampshire from the desert. But even
his staff was silent when McCain recently offered the line a second
time to the same audience. Oops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed that as soon as I said it,'' a sheepish McCain said
later. ``They didn't laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Most candidates have a stump speech. McCain, who favors endless
question-and-answer sessions with both the public and the press,
has more of a stand-up routine. His mix of dry sarcasm, terrific
timing and a sweet rasp of a voice is reminiscent of Johnny Carson
(they also have similar hair). He can be funny off the cuff, but
the cuffs are becoming a little worn during long days riding around
New Hampshire in a campaign bus. So he relies on some old standbys:
</P>
<P>
   On who will play him in the movie version of his book, ``Faith
of My Fathers,'' a memoir of three generations of McCain military
men: ``I want Tom Cruise; my kids want Danny DeVito.''
</P>
<P>
   On the book, which many voters bring for him to autograph: ``I'm
not here to hype my book. I would never do that. $24.95, Random
House. It's been four months on the best-seller list, available on
Amazon.com. But I wouldn't hype it.''
</P>
<P>
   On campaign-finance abuses in the 1996 campaign: ``They were
renting out the Lincoln bedroom as though it were a Motel 6. Bill
Clinton was the bellhop.''
</P>
<P>
   On politicians taking credit for things they did not do: ``The
vice president invented the Internet. I invented television.''
</P>
<P>
   On young voters' cynicism about government: ``There's a study
out that says more young people believe Elvis is alive than believe
they'll ever get a Social Security check.''
</P>
<P>
   On early polls in New Hampshire: ``We were at 3 percent. The
margin of error was 5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the story of 101-year-old Neil Tillotson of
Dixville Notch, who came up with the idea of having his northern
hamlet be the first to count its ballots in this ``first in the
nation'' primary, making the burg a must-stop on every presidential
candidate's tour.
</P>
<P>
   Seems McCain, in his self-described desperation for votes _
including all 29 in Dixville Notch _ has visited with Tillotson not
once but twice this campaign season. Asked who his favorite
Republican was, out of all the candidates he had met, the old man
replied, ``Theodore Roosevelt.'' Ba-dum-bum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think humor is really important,'' McCain said. ``I've
thought it was important all my life. I think it's important in
these kind of, what sometimes get to be high-pressure situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Like when he was a prisoner of war in North Vietnam, tapping out
jokes about Hanoi Hannah, a piece of radio propaganda, in code
through the cell walls. And now in the heat of the presidential
race, where he tells audiences _ over and over and over again _
that his only problem with a television advertisement that shows
Bill Clinton's face morphing into his own is ``that it's the
ugliest picture of me I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   There are self-deprecating lines about how, with white hair at
63, people think he is his school-age children's grandfather. He
makes jabs at the press (``they go from liberal to communist'') and
his staff (``most of them are on work-release programs''), and he
offers a riff on Harry Truman's quest for a one-armed economist
``because economists always say, `On the one hand, on the other
hand.'''
</P>
<P>
   His audience eats it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them just talk serious and serious, but he's with the
people,'' said Caroline Jowders, 78, who has heard the senator's
routine at four campaign events since summer. ``He always has a
sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   In Keene the other night, the crowd was cracking up as if it
were a comedy club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very entertaining,'' Barbara Hecker said afterward.
``There aren't too many politicians that I think are funny.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also does a mean Bob Dole impression (though he refused
to offer a rendition of the Viagra commercial), and freely admits
that most of his humor is borrowed. (``The trees chase the dogs''
is a Barry Goldwater original, and many others are borrowed from
Morris K. Udall, the late Democratic congressman from Arizona.)
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to one of the candidate's favorite closing
lines. Something about how Goldwater, Udall, and Bruce Babbitt, all
Arizonans, all trod this path before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona may be the only state where mothers don't tell their
children they can grow up to be president,'' McCain cracks. ``I
want to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ba-dum-bum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BRAZIL-ECONOMY-ART-51     01-17 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECONOMY-ART-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S ECONOMY IS BETTER, BUT IS THE RECOVERY LASTING? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ A year after Brazil's currency crisis took
damaging hold, Belarmino Iglesias is toasting his good fortune.
Business has rarely been better at his steakhouse, Baby Beef
Rubaiyat, an old establishment here where businessmen put together
deals over Argentine sirloin and French wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the business lunch proved immune to the crisis,''
Iglesias said in a room of crowded tables peppered with
conversations in half a dozen languages. ``Twelve months ago I was
fearful, but hyperinflation didn't materialize and our clientele
even expanded.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just good food that weathered the 32 percent
devaluation of the Brazilian real. Buoyed by a record $28 billion
in foreign direct investment in 1999 and a 12-month stock market
rally of 164 percent in local-currency terms, the Brazilian economy
is a different beast than it was a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Growth this year is forecast at 3.5 percent, compared with a
rise of perhaps 1 percent in 1999. A handful of other indicators,
like unemployment, inflation and car production, also show signs of
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   And with concern over the Year 2000 computer problem washed
away, there has even been some calm in the currency markets, with
the Brazilian real strengthening 10 percent in recent weeks to
settle in the region of 1.79 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while almost no one expected Brazil to bounce back so
quickly, people here are beginning to look ahead in an effort to
gauge whether there is still the risk of a return to the
uncertainty, even panic, that gripped the country a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from some of the challenges ahead, the kind of lasting
stability enjoyed by rich industrial nations still seems somewhat
elusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Brazilians tend to have a short memory, but it's not that
short,'' said Oswaldo Castro Jr., sales director of Expresso
Aracatuba, one of the nation's largest trucking companies. ``You'd
think it's about time we reach the point where we can stop managing
our business from one crisis to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   One big doubt about a departure from crisis mode has to do with
the country's banks and their willingness to increase borrowing in
a credit-starved economy. After the real was floated a year ago and
doomsday predictions about a debt default were common, Brazilian
banks held firm and continued to buy government bonds. And although
the prescience of this strategy proved a windfall for these
institutions, with high-yield debt portfolios fattening profits,
banks made few moves to increase lending to individuals or
companies. Even with interest rates more than halved by the end of
1999, to 19 percent, loans remained rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the recovery to be consolidated, interest rates must come
down and consumer credit expanded,'' said Walter Molano, Latin
America economist at BCP Securities in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Yet because of possible interest rate increases in the United
States and the European Union, there may not be much room for the
central bank to lower rates. Economists see key rates declining to
perhaps 14 percent or 15 percent, but not much further.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, that might be enough to kick-start Brazilian companies
into again seeking domestic financing, said Carlos Novis Guimaraes,
head of Latin American investment banking at Lehman Brothers.
``Once you start lowering rates, that creates advantages for local
companies to finance acquisitions and other expansion,'' Guimaraes
said. ``This means there will be more advisory work. The outlook
for investment banks has certainly improved.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, interest rate cuts will largely hinge on
government efforts to contain spending. Improvements in
corporate-tax collection and belt-tightening steps have started to
pay off, with Brazil surpassing most budget goals agreed to with
the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   According to Raul Velloso, a Brasilia-based specialist on public
spending, the government's surplus before paying interest on its
debt rose to an estimated $13.2 billion in 1999, compared with
$2.74 billion a year earlier. He said this measure of surplus could
further improve this year.
</P>
<P>
   After interest payments are taken into account, however, the
numbers look a lot worse, with a deficit in 1999 of roughly 11
percent of the gross domestic product, one of the highest in the
world for an economy the size of Brazil's. The government could
succeed in lowering that to the equivalent of 3.8 percent of
output, according to Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   While efforts to reduce spending continue, it is widely believed
that medium- or even long-term economic stability is unreachable
without increasing exports.
</P>
<P>
   Partly because its domestic market is so large, Brazil still has
one of the world's lowest ratios of exports to its output _ at 7
percent, according to Jeffrey Sachs of Harvard University. While
this puts Brazil ahead of the weakest economies, it is far behind
the largest emerging-market economy _ China, with an export-to-GDP
ratio around 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that exports are finally starting to surge a
year after the devaluation made Brazilian products less expensive
abroad. In December, a month in which imports traditionally
generate trade deficits, Brazil had a trade surplus of $249
million. And during the first two weeks of January, exports rose an
estimated 30 percent compared with the similar period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the improvement has to do with more vibrant markets for
Brazilian goods in Asia and Europe. But while a healthier global
economy holds promise for Brazilian companies, perhaps the greatest
risk for recovery also comes from abroad. ``We are in a rising
global interest rate environment,'' said Geoffrey Dennis, Latin
America equity strategist for Salomon Smith Barney. ``How Brazil
will weather an increase in American or European rates, no one
knows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
