<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: PAKISTANI VISITS
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Pervez Musharraf, Pakistan's military ruler, arrived in
China for his first visit outside the Islamic world since seizing
power on Oct. 12. He met with Prime Minister Zhu Rongji. China has
helped Pakistan's nuclear weapons program, and the general
applauded China as Pakistan's ``most reliable and trusted friend.''
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: SHARIF TRIAL REOPENS
</P>
<P>
   The treason and hijacking case against the ousted prime
minister, Nawaz Sharif, began again after a judge quit the
proceedings last week. Judge Rehmat Hussain Jaffri has taken up his
predecessor's efforts to force prosecutors to share evidence with
defense lawyers, a difficulty that has delayed the trial's start
for over a month.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: U.N. ENVOY PICKED
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan appointed a special envoy to
Afghanistan, where a variety of U.N. programs operate under extreme
difficulty. The new envoy, Assistant Secretary-General Francesc
Vendrell, who had a key role in relations with Cambodia and in
negotiating East Timor's steps to independence, faces a political
stalemate that is prolonging war between the ruling Taliban and an
armed opposition.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY: IRANIAN HOLDS TALKS
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi of Iran arrived in Ankara for
talks. ``We are two good neighbors with common problems and of
course certain difficulties,'' Kharrazi said. Iran is an Islamic
republic that has not recognized Israel's right to exist, while
Turkey, a strongly secular state, is a close partner of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ANGERING CATHOLICS
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox Quesada, a presidential candidate, surprised and
antagonized Catholics with a campaign speech to Protestant groups
in which he compared Mexico's Catholic clergy to the political
party that has controlled the country for seven decades. Supporters
of Fox's party are overwhelmingly Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: ARMS DEMAND
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Ireland Assembly backed demands for an immediate
start in the destruction of paramilitary arms and said the future
of the legislature itself was at stake. First Minister David
Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionists, has set a party vote for
Feb. 12 on whether to remain in government with Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: TORIES' LONDON CHOICE
</P>
<P>
   Steven Norris, 54, a former transportation minister, was chosen
to be the Conservative candidate for the first elected mayor of
London, replacing the millionaire author Jeffrey Archer, 59, who
had to quit the race in a scandal over payments to a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: CARLOS AIDE IMPRISONED
</P>
<P>
   Johannes Weinrich, 52, a German leftist believed to be close to
the terrorist known as Carlos, was sentenced to life imprisonment
for the bombing of a French cultural center in Berlin in 1983. The
attack, in which a man died, was part of a campaign by associates
of Carlos to gain the release of two comrades in France. Carlos, a
Venezuelan whose real name is Illich Ramirez Sanchez, is in prison
in Paris for murder.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: MARCH 12 VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Ending months of speculation, Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar
set general elections for March 12. Aznar, 46, seeks a second
four-year term for his center-right Popular Party, which leads in
polls over the Socialist Party.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: POLICE COMPLAINT
</P>
<P>
   The national police chief, the first black in the post, has been
criticized for reportedly referring to an officer as a chimpanzee.
Commissioner Jackie Selebi was apparently angry at how he was
treated by the officer, a black woman, when he visited a Pretoria
police station. The officer has filed a complaint.
</P>
</TEXT>
