<SLUG> BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAN, NOT EVEN YOU HAVE MAGIC TO PULL OFF THIS COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dan,
</P>
<P>
   It is time to go. It is time to walk away while you can still
limp. It is time to give up on that Super Bowl ring while you still
have your dignity. Time's up.
</P>
<P>
   You've had 37 career comebacks, but you should not even attempt
this one. The clock has run out on your brilliant 17-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Please, don't consider Jimmy Johnson's retirement announcement
an invitation to return for one more season. Follow his lead.
</P>
<P>
   You will be 39 next season. You have been sacked 291 times in
your career. You have had eight operations.
</P>
<P>
   You wear a special brace on your right foot to protect the
Achilles' tendon that ruptured and ended your 1993 season after
five games. You have a special shoe that supports the right ankle
that was fractured in 1996. You have a bulky brace that holds
together a left knee that has been operated on five times. You have
a corset-like brace that protects the hip that was so badly bruised
in 1995 that blood and fluid had to be drained from it for 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Your body is battered. Your career is bruised.
</P>
<P>
   What makes you think next season will be any better?
</P>
<P>
   Your quarterback rating this season was a career-low 67.4. Trent
Dilfer, Jeff Garcia, Tim Couch and Gus Frerotte were better than
that.
</P>
<P>
   You were 5-7 as a starter this season. Your backup, Damon Huard,
was 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   We should be honoring your legend. We should be celebrating your
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   You are the greatest quarterback ever to play the game. You own
25 NFL records and share five others. There is a Hall of Fame bust
on hold for you in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, this is how we remember you: On your hands and knees
earlier this season as the New York Jets returned an interception
for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   This picture of you is not flattering, Dan.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still was Saturday's 62-7 loss to the Jacksonville
Jaguars.
</P>
<P>
   We wonder what in the world you were thinking when you hit
Jacksonville cornerback Aaron Beasley right in the hands with your
first pass.
</P>
<P>
   We hear you begging Johnson at halftime to return to the lineup
despite trailing 41-7.
</P>
<P>
   We see you standing on the sideline in a baseball cap after
throwing two interceptions and losing a fumble that was returned
for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   We smell blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for him,'' Jaguars right tackle Leon Searcy said
of you. ``He was one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the past tense now, Dan.
</P>
<P>
   We know you dream of going out like Michael Jordan and John
Elway.
</P>
<P>
   There should be a poster made of you hoisting the Vince Lombardi
Trophy high above your head like Elway or striking a pose with your
right wrist in place after scoring the championship game-winner
like Jordan. You don't deserve a 62-7 loss in your last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what Dan is going to do, but this is no way for
it to end,'' your teammate, defensive end Trace Armstrong, said
after Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   But you are not the only great player never to win a
championship. That honor roll includes Charles Barkley, Gale
Sayers, Willie McCovey, Ernie Banks, O.J. Simpson and Barry
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   If your career were meant to have a happy ending, Dan, it would
have happened by now.
</P>
<P>
   You will make $7.5 million next season. Memories are not worth
that much.
</P>
<P>
   New Dolphins coach Dave Wannstedt did not exactly give you a
vote of confidence in his introductory news conference Sunday. He
referred to your future as ``the Dan thing,'' and said, ``It's a
very sensitive issue. We're going to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   You need to do the right thing, Dan. You need to make it easy on
the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   You have overstayed your welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Don't end up like Simpson in a San Francisco 49ers uniform. Or
Joe Namath in a Los Angeles Rams uniform. Or Willie Mays in a New
York Mets uniform.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have a championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   But you have wealth. You have your health. You have your family.
You have your place in history. You have your memories. You have
plenty of opportunities for a second career. That should be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, Dan. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
