u p BC-DEMOCRATS-DEBATE-HNS &LR;      01-17 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     BRADLEY, GORE SPAR ON CIVIL RIGHTS IN FINAL IOWA DEBATE   (For
use by New York Times News Service clients.)   By DAN
FREEDMAN   c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  DES MOINES, Iowa _ Before a
<TEXT>
mostly-minority audience on the Martin Luther King Jr. national
holiday, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley
attempted Monday to one-up each other on who is best qualified to
carry on the slain civil rights leader's legacy.
<P>
   The two Democratic candidates used their last face-to-face
meeting before the Jan. 24 Iowa caucuses to argue over Medicaid and
racial profiling in a debate otherwise marked by general agreement
that civil rights law enforcement and educational opportunity must
be expanded, and affirmative action protected.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks make up just 1.7 percent and Hispanics 1.1 percent of
Iowa's 2.8 million people. But minorities are an important part of
the Democratic base of support and the debate itself, broadcast on
MSNBC, could resonate among minority voters well beyond Iowa's
borders.Gore is comfortably ahead of Bradley in most polls, leading
the former New Jersey senator and New York Knicks basketball star
54 percent to 33 percent in the latest Des Moines Register Poll.
And polls have shown that blacks favor Gore over Bradley by a
2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   On a question about racial profiling, a criminal identification
technique used by law enforcement agencies that has been decried by
minorities, Bradley and Gore both said that as president they would
issue executive orders banning racial profiling.Bradley challenged
Gore to walk into President Clinton's office and tell him to ``sign
this executive order today.''After cheers from the audience, Gore
shot back: ``I don't think President Bill Clinton needs Bill
Bradley to tell him how to stand up and fight for
African-Americans.''Gore then said that Sharpe James, the long-time
mayor of Newark, N.J. _ the largest city of the state Bradley
represented 18 years in the Senate _ was a Gore supporters
``because President Clinton and I have helped him on racial
profiling.''Gore attacked Bradley on his health care plan, which
among other things would eliminate Medicaid, which subsidizes
health care for poor people. Under Bradley's plan, Medicaid would
be replaced by a income-based subsidy for health care and the
health insurance program for federal workers would be expanded to
cover non-employees.Gore introduced black and Hispanic families in
the audience he said would receive a $150 ``voucher'' under the
Bradley health plan if they lost Medicaid.Bradley defended his
plan, saying that ``only politicians in Washington think Medicaid
is a great system,'' a jibe at Gore's background growing up in
Washington and spending virtually a lifetime in elective office.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the nation's doctors do not accept Medicaid
patients, Bradley said. ``Two dentists in Des Moines accept
Medicaid,'' he said. ``That's not good enough.''He denied that his
plan would replace Medicaid with a voucher, explaining that it
relies on a ``weighted average'' that would ideally subsidize
health care for the poor according to income. Gore compared
Bradley's ``weighted average'' to ``the guy who's got his feet on a
block of ice and his head in the oven and according to the
'weighted average' he was comfortable.''The forum, sponsored by the
Black-Brown Coalition, an organization of blacks and Hispanics, is
the final forum for the two Democratic candidates before next
Monday's caucuses in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The debate's only unscripted dramatic highlight was the removal
of a woman environmental activist who interrupted the debate with a
denunciation of global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates said they would appoint Supreme Court justices
who support affirmative action. And both supported the idea of
appointing a first-ever Hispanic to the Supreme Court, though they
stopped short of an iron-clad commitment.
</P>
<P>
   In other areas of agreement, both said the Confederate battle
flag was a symbol of racial insensitivity and exclusion and should
be removed from atop the South Carolina Capitol, as well as any
other government building.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the leading Republican candidates for president,
Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Arizona Sen. John McCain, have
described it as a state matter.Gore accused the Republicans of
backing away from the issue because they are ``scared of the right
wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of the Democratic candidates go back on the road in Iowa
Tuesday in a final sprint to win support in the symbolically
important Iowa caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is scheduled to visit four locations southeast of Des
Moines while Bradley is scheduled to go to Iowa City, home of the
University of Iowa, and then fly to New Hampshire for a day of
campaigning in that state, which holds its primary on Feb. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
