<SLUG> BC-ELEPHANTS-BRITE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEIGHBOR FED UP WITH VISITS FROM ELEPHANTS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARVEY RICE 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUT AND SHOOT, Texas _ A warning from his grandson caused Robin
Walker to look up from his living room couch.
</P>
<P>
   Walker was startled to see an elephant pressing its head against
the sliding glass door that led to his back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa, I think we got a problem,'' 5-year-old Zachary Mitchell
told his grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, a 42-year-old machinist, said he feared that the beast
looming in his doorway would burst into living room.
</P>
<P>
   Believing the elephant was drawn by the family's presence,
Walker said he took his wife, Debbie, 49, and Zachary into the back
of the house. The elephant stopped pressing against the door soon
after they left the room, Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 5 close encounter with an elephant was not the first
Walker has had since he moved into his house about 50 miles north
of Houston 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said Monday that an elephant has escaped from his
neighbor's property at least once previously. But this was the
first time one had ever tried to come into his house.
</P>
<P>
   A furious Walker climbed onto a bench in his backyard and yelled
over the fence for his neighbor to come get his elephant. About
that time, some of the elephants that had not escaped began
trumpeting, and, as if in response to a signal, the loose elephant
crashed through a 6-foot wooden fence that separates the properties
and returned to the herd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went right through it like it was matchsticks,'' Walker
said.
</P>
<P>
   The elephant is the property of Walker's neighbor, Bill Swain, a
51-year-old animal trainer who has kept up to six elephants on his
seven-acre property since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Swain, owner of Trunks and Humps Inc., said he is making every
effort to be a good neighbor and is taking steps to ensure that his
elephants stay off Walker's property.
</P>
<P>
   Swain and his trapeze-artist wife Mayola, 49, come from two
generations of circus performers. Swain said his four elephants,
three camels and two llamas are booked at performances throughout
the country.
</P>
<P>
   The elephants appeared in the movies ``The Little Princess'' and
``Jungle Book'', he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker took his complaint to the Cut and Shoot City Council last
week, and the two neighbors presented their cases.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Lang Thompson said Swain was issued a permit in 1984
giving him permission to keep two elephants on his property. Walker
is asking the city to force Swain to adhere to his permit.
</P>
<P>
   Swain is putting up a wire fence around his property, building
larger pens and has carted away a pile of elephant manure that the
Walkers have complained about. He has contracted to have the manure
removed regularly, but that's as far as he is willing to go, he
said. The four elephants will stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of like the Syrians and the Hebrews having a
conversation,'' Swain said about Walker's demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived her for 20 years,'' Swain said. ``I've built this
business up to where me and my family can make a decent living. I'm
willing to compromise to a reasonable point.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker is not convinced that a new fence will make any
difference, although he and his wife are grateful that the manure
has been removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A chain-link fence like that, he'll rip that wire like tissue
paper,'' he said about the elephants. ``I can't be assured that,
under the present circumstances, one won't wake up in the bed with
me,'' he Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Swain said the elephant that pressed its head against Walker's
glass door escaped from a temporary pen formed by an electric wire,
known as a hot pen.
</P>
<P>
   A pine branch fell on the wire, allowing the elephant to wander
onto Walker's property, Swain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason, this really ignited the situation,'' Swain
said. ``Perhaps I was neglectful in some ways, but it wasn't
intentional.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
