<HEADLINE>
N.Y. GOP TO CHALLENGE MCCAIN PETITIONS IN HALF OF STATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Republican State Committee, which is supporting
Gov. George W. Bush in the presidential race, said Monday that it
would seek to disqualify Sen. John McCain from the primary ballot
in roughly half the state. State party officials said the McCain
campaign had in many instances failed to meet the arduous petition
requirements, which the officials themselves devised.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of threatening to wield the election law to beat
back McCain, the officials said they would file papers by a
deadline Tuesday, formally challenging the McCain nominating
petitions in 15 to 17 of the state's 31 congressional districts.
They declined to identify the districts.
</P>
<P>
   The move opens what is expected to become a costly legal
skirmish that will once again highlight how the rules for gaining a
ballot spot in New York's Republican presidential primary are
unusually forbidding to all but the party favorite. In many states,
the party leadership does not choose sides in presidential
primaries and widely recognized candidates like McCain are assured
a place on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican establishment in New York has thrown its muscle
behind Bush and made it clear that the faithful should shun other
candidates. The McCain campaign says it was unable even to hire a
prominent Republican election lawyer, and instead had to retain a
Democrat, Henry Berger, who represented the Clinton-Gore campaign
in the state in 1996 and had never before worked for a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who has sued in federal court to overturn the New York
system, suggested that the state party was trying to rig the March
7 primary for Bush, who with the party's assistance has easily
gained a ballot spot across the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' McCain said while campaigning in New
Hampshire. ``Everybody knows that I'm a qualified candidate and I'm
sorry they're going to do that. I don't see the point; if you've
got $74 million and you've got all the organization, you've got
everything, why do you want to challenge somebody off the ballot?''
</P>
<P>
   With little money and few ties to party officials, the McCain
campaign had struggled to gather the required signatures, failing
to reach the threshold in six of the state's 31 congressional
districts. The party is expected to file challenges in five of
those districts, as well as 10 to 12 others, to insure that McCain
is not allowed on the ballot in those districts, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the McCain campaign filed its nominating petitions
earlier this month, the Republican party has dispatched a squad of
workers to ferret out possible errors in paperwork. Monday, the
party's chief counsel, Jeffrey T. Buley, said he had identified
many signatures of people who were not registered to vote, were not
Republicans or did not live in the districts _ three of the
criteria for valid petitions.
</P>
<P>
   Buley defended the requirements, saying they are intended to
ensure that candidates who appear on the ballot are committed to
getting to know the state by establishing an organization. ``It's
all part of developing grass roots support,'' Buley said.
``Obviously, Gov. Bush has worked long and hard at gaining the
support of the New York GOP.''
</P>
<P>
   Buley also said that the party decided not to challenge McCain's
petitions on more arcane points, like trying to knock off
signatures on pages that list the wrong date.
</P>
<P>
   The petition fight raises the prospect that, if McCain wins the
primary on Feb. 1 in New Hampshire, where he is locked in a tight
race with Bush, he would then be forced to virtually forfeit the
New York contest because many Republicans would not be able to vote
for him. (There are several other primaries on the same day,
including one in California, where well-known candidates
automatically garner a spot.)
</P>
<P>
   Three other Republicans who will appear on the ballots in most
other states _ Gary Bauer, Sen. Orrin Hatch and Alan Keyes _ have
withdrawn from New York, all citing the difficulty of complying
with the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the millionaire publisher, who successfully took
his case to federal court in 1996 over similar issues and was
placed on the ballot across the state, this year spent $750,000
hiring lawyers and petition gatherers, and is expected to gain a
spot in all districts. State Republicans this year say they will
not dispute the petitions of Forbes, who is considered less of a
threat to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic primary rules also require petitions, but they
are somewhat less complicated. The major contenders, Vice President
Al Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley, will both be on the ballot
across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Almost daily in the last week, McCain has demanded that Bush and
Gov. George Pataki, Bush's most prominent supporter in the state,
forswear petition challenges. Bush and his aides have tried to
distance him from the dispute. ``It's a decision for the state
party to make,'' a spokeswoman for the Bush campaign, Mindy Tucker,
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, the party leader, has said anyone with grass-roots
support should be able to comply with the rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
