<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PLAYOFF-CONTENDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: A STRANGE BUT EXCITING WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There were many exhilarating and bizarre moments from the
National Football League division playoff weekend, and one happened
somewhere past midfield at the RCA Dome in Indianapolis, when
running back Eddie George was breaking his breathtaking 68-yard
touchdown run and, in turn, breaking the spirit of the Indianapolis
Colts.
</P>
<P>
   As George rumbled toward the end zone, he glanced up at the
giant replay screen to watch himself. A tiny smile broke across his
face, as in, ``Wow, I look pretty good.'' And he did, outrunning
three defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the TV cameras caught me checking out the replay
screen to see if anyone was catching up to me from behind,'' a
modest George said. ``I know I shouldn't have done that. I tried to
focus on just pumping my legs and not letting the turf monster trip
me up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the more fascinating sights of the playoffs: a
broad-shouldered, 6-foot-3-inch, 240-pound runner, built like a
superhero but fast enough to set off a radar gun, outrunning
supposedly speedier Colts defensive backs, en route to one of the
biggest touchdowns in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie was worried someone was going to catch him, because if
he was caught, he would have never heard the end of it from us,''
said Tennessee receiver Yancey Thigpen. ``People don't realize it,
but once he gets going, he gets on a roll. When you see those
defensive backs chasing him for 60 yards and he outruns them that
says it all.''
</P>
<P>
   What a run. What a weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, a coach quits. In New York, a coach just says no. In
St. Louis, there was a track meet, while in Tampa Bay, it was a
game from the 1950s. Peyton Manning struggled, Steve McNair
excelled, Kurt Warner tossed five touchdowns and somebody named
Shaun King became the first rookie quarterback in 23 years to win a
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   The weird, the spectacular, the ugly. It was all there.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans, the current incarnation of the old Houston Oilers,
won the franchise's first division playoff game since 1979. That's
good. Television cameras caught Minnesota wide receiver Randy Moss
squirting liquid from a container at an official who had made a
call Moss did not like. That's bad. Look for the star player to
receive a hefty fine from the league, and maybe an endorsement from
a bottled water company.
</P>
<P>
   And by the way, instant replay worked. Beautifully. It correctly
reversed a punt return for a touchdown by the Colts' Terrence
Wilkins, who had clearly stepped out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very, very strange weekend,'' Thigpen said. ``You
watch some of the games and just sit back in disbelief.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Williams, the defensive coordinator for the Titans, said:
``I saw great plays. I saw wild games. I saw it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The strangeness led to two intriguing conference championship
games for Sunday. Tampa Bay may be the only team that can slow the
offensive juggernaut of the Rams. The Buccaneers have the speed and
depth on defense, especially when St. Louis goes to three and four
wide receivers. And defensive lineman Warren Sapp will surely be in
the face of Warner all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know people may think that St. Louis will beat them
handily,'' said Tennessee coach Jeff Fisher. ``But with Tampa Bay's
defense, don't count on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville has lost only twice this season, both times to the
Titans. Perhaps the Jaguars see the Tennessee players in their
nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson who endured a living
nightmare against the Jaguars on Saturday. Johnson was leaning
toward retiring from professional football anyway, but the
humiliating 62-7 loss to Jacksonville was a not-so-gentle shove. In
the end, Johnson's four-year tenure can only be viewed as
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   As a television analyst, it was Johnson who criticized Don
Shula, the former Dolphins coach, saying that Shula was failing to
take advantage of a Super Bowl-caliber team and organization.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson and Shula's records were almost identical. In
Shula's last four seasons, from 1992 to 1995, he was 39-25 with a
2-3 playoff record. Johnson, from 1996 to 1999, was 36-28, and also
had a 2-3 record in postseason play. But Shula never had an
embarrassing playoff loss like Johnson did Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances of Johnson's departure provide a stark
contrast to the status of St. Louis coach Dick Vermeil. While
Johnson leaves the game in embarrassing fashion, Vermeil, who last
season was on the verge of being fired, is so confident that he
says his team has no weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the RCA Dome. In one corner Colts running back Edgerrin
James, with a long face, tried to explain how he was held to only
2.8 yards a carry.
</P>
<P>
   A short walk down the hall, George was all smiles. He began to
daydream about the old days four years ago, when the Titans were
the Houston Oilers, and his rookie year, after the team returned
from a road game, there were two measly fans in the airport singing
the fight song.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `We have a long way to go,''' George said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Titans arrived at Nashville International Airport late
Saturday night, there were 8,000 fans cheering George and his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference. What a weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
