<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-DEMOCRATS-0118 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DEMOCRATS DEBATE RACIAL PROFILING
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ In the last debate before Iowa's Democratic
presidential caucus, Bill Bradley Monday challenged Vice President
Al Gore to demand that President Clinton immediately issue an order
ending racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   , Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley challenge sparked a heated defense of Clinton from Gore,
who had earlier promised that one of his first acts as president
would be to sign an executive order ending the practice by which
some police offers target racial minority motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he had no doubt that Gore would fulfill that
promise. However, he told Gore: ``We have a president now. You
serve with him. I want you to walk into his office and say, 'Sign
this executive order today.'''
</P>
<P>
   As many in the audience cheered, Gore rushed to the defense of
Clinton, who has had an unusually close political and personal
relationship with minorities during his two terms in the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think President Bill Clinton needs a lecture from Bill
Bradley about how to stand up and fight for African Americans and
Latinos,'' Gore said, also to cheers.
</P>
<P>
   But a scattering of boos arose when Gore added, ``It's one thing
to talk the talk. It's another thing to walk the walk,'' a common
refrain among civil rights activists.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Sharpe James, the African American mayor of
Newark, N.J., had once sought help from Bradley to end racial
profiling during Bradley's tenure in the Senate, but that Bradley
had demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's supporting me because President Clinton and I helped him
with racial profiling,'' Gore said. James, following the debate,
confirmed Gore's account, but Bradley spokesman Eric Hauser
dismissed James's comments as ``politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that if elected he would immediately sign an
executive order to end the ``pernicious'' practice of racial
profiling and would ``sic'' the Justice Department on police
departments that did not comply.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ``Brown-Black'' Forum was staged on the national
holiday honoring the late Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and just one
week before the Iowa presidential caucuses, the first actual voting
of the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   The forum focused almost exclusively on issues of significance
to African Americans and Hispanics, including the Confederate
battle flag, affirmative action, immigration, health care, public
education, child poverty and the sweeping demographic changes the
United States is undergoing.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it occurred in Iowa, a state with a population that
is 97 percent white. But in the Southern states that dominate the
Democratic primaries in March, where the nomination is likely to be
decided, nearly one in three voters in Democratic primaries are
black.
</P>
<P>
   One exchange shifted away from issues and focused instead on two
controversial figures, Atlanta Braves pitcher John Rocker and the
Rev. Al Sharpton, a black activist in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates condemned the inflammatory remarks Rocker made
about minorities, gays and for in a Sports Illustrated
interview, but neither would rule out seeking the political support
of Sharpton, whose occasional anti-Semitic remarks have made him a
polarizing figure.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he had met earlier with Sharpton during a campaign
visit to Harlem, but said, ``I don't agree with Al Sharpton on
everything.'' Gore, who also has made a campaign trek to Sharpton's
church, said, ``We'll see how things go'' before making the trip
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know John Rocker and I don't want to know John
Rocker,'' said Bradley, a former pro basketball star whose racial
attitudes were formed largely by witnesses the discrimination to
which is black teammates were subjected in the 1960s and 1970s. ``I
wouldn't be disappointed if they fired him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore said Rocker could be ``on the road to receiving
forgiveness'' if he impresses more people like former Atlanta Mayor
Andrew Young and baseball homerun king Hank Aaron, both of whom
recently met in a counseling role with the Braves pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley largely agreed on most of the policy issues
that arose throughout the evening, although each defended his
health care plans as being more beneficial for minorities. A
proportion of minority Americans rely on government-subsidized
health programs.
</P>
<P>
   Both men also said the Confederate flag should be removed from
the state Capitol in South Carolina, but Gore said he would not
participate in an NAACP boycott of the state because ``I don't
think a president of the United States should ever boycott an
individual state.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, citing a poll showing a majority in South Carolina would
like the flag removed, added, ``It's only the Republican candidates
for president who are so scared of the extreme right wing, that
they will be tolerant of intolerance, less they offend the
offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said the flag ``offends our common humanity and it is
not the future of our country.''
</P>
<P>
   The leading GOP hopefuls, Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Arizona
Sen. John McCain, have said it is up to the residents of South
Carolina to decide whether the flag should fly atop their
statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley vowed to fill their administrations with
African Americans and Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore dodged a question about who among Latino leaders he
would consider for appointment to the Supreme Court. He said he
would make appointments that reflect ``the diversity of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said, ``I could never appoint someone who would turn the
clock back on civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men also said the father of Elian Gonzalez, a 6-year-old
Cuban boy at the center of an international dispute, should come to
the United States to press his claim for custody.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley sought to reassure African Americans about his proposal
to extend the 1964 Civil Rights Act to protect gays against
discrimination, an approach Gore opposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never do anything, anything that could possibly
undermine that act,'' Bradley said. ``But I don't think progress
for everyone means less progress for someone.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard can be reached at scotts (at) coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
