<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8529 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SC-FLAG-COX     01-17 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Demonstrators try to distinguish between heritage, hate in S.C.
flag flap
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ A civil rights army of 46,000 demonstrators
marched Monday on South Carolina's Statehouse _ hallowed ground for
the Confederate flag _ and demanded the divisive banner be removed
from atop the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring the peaceful Martin Luther King Jr. Day rally the
``greatest demonstration against the symbol of bigotry and hatred''
in 40 years, NAACP President Kweisi Mfume vowed further
demonstrations if South Carolina legislators refuse to furl the
Confederate flag.
</P>
<P>
   This month the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People launched a tourism boycott of South Carolina until
the flag comes down. Monday, amid the impassioned speeches, the
head of the state's black coaches association announced another
step intended to pressure legislators.
</P>
<P>
   C. Timothy Stoner, executive director, said the coaches group
had urged the National Collegiate Athletic Association to refrain
from scheduling tournaments in South Carolina until legislators
remove the flag and declare King's birthday a state holiday.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina is the only state that doesn't officially
recognize the national King holiday. State workers can take the day
off on the King holiday or another of their choice, including one
of several tied to Confederate anniversaries.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina is also the last state to fly the Confederate
flag atop its state capitol.
</P>
<P>
   That combination has turned South Carolina into an ideological
battleground, 139 years after Confederate soldiers fired on Fort
Sumter in Charleston's harbor and started the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, 6,000 flag supporters rallied in Columbia. Their
leaders vowed to pressure legislators to keep the rebel flag
flying, as it has since 1962 when legislators raised it as part of
a Civil War centennial.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Monday's protest in Columbia, David Robinson, 38, said
he couldn't ''believe they have nothing better to do than protest
the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The flag doesn't represent hate,'' said Robinson, from
Trenton, S.C. ''It is heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   But speaker after speaker denounced the Confederate flag as an
insulting relic that demands immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
   Some cited a recent remark by state Sen. Arthur Ravenel (R-Mount
Pleasant). During the flag supporters' rally, he referred to the
NAACP as the ''National Association for Retarded People.'' When
asked to apologize, he apologized to the mentally disabled, not to
the NAACP.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't wait because it symbolizes racism and shame,'' the
Rev. Lewis Graham, pastor of Zion Baptist Church in Columbia, said
Monday. ''We can't wait because the blood of Martin cries out in us
now that it ought to come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Evans, 55, drove from his home in Decatur, Ga., to
protest a symbol that he said ''belongs in the museum. It is the
new millennium, the year 2000, and that is old history.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans predicted ''once they take this one down, Georgia will
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta civil rights leader, in fact, has vowed to draw
Georgia into the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Beasley, the Southern regional director for the Rainbow/PUSH
Coalition, said he is bringing together civil rights groups in
Atlanta to call for a tourism boycott of Georgia until legislators
remove the Confederate emblem from the state flag.
</P>
<P>
   A rally announcing the boycott is planned for Jan. 30 during the
Super Bowl in Atlanta, Beasley said. He added the coalition's
president, the Rev. Jesse Jackson, has not endorsed the boycott,
but he expects Jackson to participate in the rally if he attends
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt to reach Jackson at the coalition's offices in
Chicago on Monday night wasn't successful.
</P>
<P>
   As South Carolina's flag fight has drawn in presidential
candidates, Beasley said Monday he plans to contact Vice President
Al Gore's campaign headquarters in Nashville, Tenn., and ask that
he speak out against the Georgia flag.
</P>
<P>
   In a weekend TV interview with Jackson, Gore said the
Confederate flag represents for ''many Americans a hurtful message
that recalls the pain of slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's turnout in Columbia exceeded the expectations of
organizers, including the NAACP, the Urban Leagues in Columbia and
Upstate South Carolina and several church groups. The long list of
speakers included Columbia Mayor Bob Coble and Charleston Mayor Joe
Riley, who said the flag should be removed and put in ''a place of
honor and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   As the speeches dragged on, some in the crowd grew restless. But
they snapped to attention when NAACP President Mfume stood at the
lectern, next to a statue of George Washington holding a broken
cane. It had been damaged by Gen. Sherman's invading Union troops
in 1865.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have come to the state of South Carolina to say that
bigotry, racism and racist symbols _ whether a Confederate flag or
burning crosses _ will not be allowed to go unchallenged,'' Mfume
told the cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The march and rally lasted more than five hours, during which
police reported one arrest for disorderly conduct: A man carrying a
large Confederate flag with a sign that said ``I love you''
exchanged words with people in the crowd and ignored police
requests to back off. There also were a small number of fainting
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the aroma of fish frying and ribs barbecuing, the packed
crowd spilled from the Statehouse grounds onto Main Street. Police
looked on from the ground and rooftops. Wooden barricades and
volunteer marshals with locked arms lined the parade route from
Zion Baptist Church to the capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Though predominantly black, the crowd drew some white people and
a large number of school children whose classes had been canceled
because of local observance of the King holiday.
</P>
<P>
   As people assembled around the red-brick church in the morning
chill, leaders inside exhorted the crowd in the sanctuary to ''fire
it up'' but to do it peacefully.
</P>
<P>
   Led by youngsters from Clover, S.C., the parade moved slowly,
stretching and collapsing like an accordion along a route that
passed the beauty parlors and vacant storefronts of Washington
Street. Turning on to Main, the crowd grew thicker. Leaders began
singing, ''I got a feeling the flag's coming down in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   People carried placards reading, ''Your heritage is my slavery''
and ''It's time to look ahead. The Confederacy is dead.'' Another
read, ''The days of Yes'um' are over. Take the flag down.''
</P>
<P>
   A gathering of 3,000 waiting at the Statehouse erupted into
cheers as the procession reached the tall monument to the
Confederate war dead. People clamored up and stood on the side of
the statue, unveiled in 1879 by South Carolina women.
</P>
<P>
   One man waved a flag of red, black and green _ the colors of
African liberation _ as he perched on the statue. Atop it, a stone
figure of a rebel soldier faced away from the impassioned speech
making.
</P>
<P>
   At day's end, the wind stretched out the Confederate flag in
full view, flying beneath the American flag and the South Carolina
state flag.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all still have the dream,'' said marcher Inese Bonapart,
47, of Swanson, S.C. ''I am hoping that we will make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
