<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8530 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MOTOROLA-MARKETPLACE-     01-17 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-MARKETPLACE-1STLD-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: MOTOROLA REPORTS BIG JUMP IN PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Rewrites 6th graf.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Motorola Inc. showed more evidence Monday that it is
in the middle of a remarkable turnaround by reporting a big jump in
fourth-quarter profits on growing demand for its cellular
telephones and semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which just a year ago was laying off thousands of
workers and trying to reorganize its operations after huge losses,
has become a Wall Street darling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This looks pretty solid,'' said Brian Modoff, an analyst at
Deutsche Bank Alex. Brown. ``There's clearly a trend toward higher
profits, because wireless is one of the fastest-growing markets out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock market was closed Monday, but shares of Motorola
soared $11.25 on Friday, to $151 a share, on expectations of a
strong showing Monday, and Motorola delivered just that, posting a
profit of 82 cents a share, excluding special items, a penny better
than Wall Street forecasts and up from about 26 cents a share in
the period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola had an operating profit of $514 million, or 82 cents a
share, compared with $159 million, or 26 cents a share in the
fourth quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which reported sales of $8.5 billion in the fourth
quarter, with $7.9 billion from continuing operations, is
benefiting from soaring worldwide demand for cellular telephones
and strong growth in the semiconductor market.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, investors who had dragged the stock down to about
$40 a share a year ago, have in the last year bid it up to an
all-time high in a frenzy of buying that has been largely built on
optimism that the company is reasserting itself as a leading
developer of cellular handsets.
</P>
<P>
   Investors are also optimistic about the company's effort to
recast itself by developing new hardware platforms and a broad
array of software applications that are expected to be critical
components in the convergence of the Internet and wireless
communications devices.
</P>
<P>
   The new Motorola _ as its chief executive, Christopher Galvin,
calls it _ is betting that an increasingly wired world is going to
be dependent on a growing array of wireless communications devices
and a growing number of microchips that link up and communicate
with one another. It is a development that one Motorola executive
calls the ``trillion device problem,'' one that Motorola aims to be
at the center of.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're focusing on access technology,'' Modoff said, ``the
ability for you to access information whether it's at home through
cable modems or through wireless devices, and the ability to
control all kinds of devices from remote locations.''
</P>
<P>
   To stake out its ground in the wired world, Motorola, which is
based in Schaumburg, Ill., has moved swiftly in the last year,
forging alliances with Cisco Systems Inc. and Sun Microsystems Inc.
to develop a new wireless infrastructure capable of delivering
high-speed Internet access, and acquiring, for more than $11
billion, General Instrument, a leading maker of cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola is also trying to expand its microchip franchise by
promoting semiconductors that power all kinds of devices, chips
that are planted in cars, in toasters, in high-definition
televisions, in lighting systems and more. The company even started
a multimillion-dollar advertising campaign touting its ``digital
DNA,'' which it calls the ``heart of smart'' technology.
</P>
<P>
   One of the clouds hanging over Motorola, however, has been
Iridium LLC, the $5 billion satellite telephone venture that filed
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection late last year. Motorola has
already taken huge charges because of its big investment in the
project, which it helped create, and on Monday the company
announced another $740 million write-off associated with Iridium.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola also remains in fierce competition with Nokia, the
Finnish cellular-telephone maker, which is the market leader. And
Motorola is trying to revive its cellular infrastructure unit,
which also fell behind a year ago by making a big bet on analog
technology when the world was turning to digital technology.
</P>
<P>
   The company's fortunes have now turned. Cellular telephones are
taking off because of soaring demand around the world. (Herschel
Shosteck &AMP; Associates projects sales of about 360 million handsets
this year.) Chips are recovering from a slowdown in parts of Asia,
and even Motorola's flagging cellular infrastructure division is
showing signs of recovery in the fourth-quarter report.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola executives have also moved to give the company a higher
profile, by introducing new consumer products, like two-way radios
for children and a watch pager developed with Timex. The company
has agreed to spend about $60 million over the next three years to
be the official wireless communications sponsor of the National
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   And Motorola is trying to bring new wireless technologies _
including Internet access _ to automobiles, and has already signed
pacts and released products in cars like the Mercedes-Benz.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After making a bad bet on analog technology over digital,
Motorola has tried to seize upon the Internet and has begun
developing devices, including cellular telephones, that deliver
Internet access. And the company has, in effect, tried to hedge its
bets by making more bets.
</P>
<P>
   The new Motorola has a new line of jazzy cellular telephones, to
compete with the stylish Nokia phones. It has pagers, microchips
and cable modems; it's under the dashboard, in your toaster, your
high-definition television sets; it's in the 3Com Palm Pilot and
Apple's MacIntosh computer. The company even built satellites for
Iridium.
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Teledesic LLC, the global satellite network
that aims to become a kind of ``Internet in the sky,'' with the
help of Motorola satellite technology.
</P>
<P>
   The message is that Motorola is highly diversified and prepared
for the Internet revolution. And so far, despite an array of nimble
and fierce competitors like Nokia, Lucent and even Microsoft, Wall
Street analysts and investors are buying it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
