<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOLLAR SLIPS AGAINST YEN
</P>
<P>
   Most major foreign stock markets ended higher while U.S. markets
were closed in observance of Martin Luther King's Birthday. The
dollar edged up against the euro but slipped against the Japanese
yen in overseas trading.
</P>
<P>
   The gains in European stocks were led by telecommunications
companies. In Frankfurt, Germany, the Dax index rose 85.68 points,
or 1.19 percent, to 7,258.90, its second consecutive record close.
And in Tokyo the Nikkei 225 stock average rose 480.68 points, or
2.5 percent, to 19,437.23, its highest close in two and a half
years. The French CAC-40 index and the Ibex 35 index in Spain
closed up nearly 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   BID MADE FOR JAPANESE DRUG MAKER
</P>
<P>
   Boehringer Ingelheim, a large German pharmaceuticals company,
started a tender offer for shares of SS Pharmaceuticals, a Japanese
drugmaker, in another sign of deregulation's ability to pry open
the Japanese economy and breathe new life into business.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL WARILY CELEBRATES RECOVERY
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian economy has recovered from its currency crisis of
a year ago with record inflows of $28 billion in foreign direct
investment in 1999; a 12-month stock-market rally of 164 percent in
local-currency terms, and growth forecast this year at 3.5 percent,
compared with a rise of perhaps 1 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   FIGHTING SECURITIES FRAUD IN CANADA
</P>
<P>
   The Ontario Securities Commission is pushing three high-profile
cases, two involving insider trading, into court, where convictions
would help reverse a belief that stock-market scandals occur often
in Canada because there is little risk for wrongdoers.
</P>
<P>
   REPORT CHALLENGES BERTELSMANN
</P>
<P>
   A year after Bertelsmann, the German media conglomerate,
appointed an independent group of scholars to examine its disputed
history during the Nazi era, the commission issued a preliminary
report that took issue with corporate lore that the Nazis closed
the publishing company because of its political opposition. The
four-member commission's tentative conclusion was that Bertelsmann
was closed simply because its product was not considered critically
important for the war effort.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN GIRL'S RETAIL PLAY
</P>
<P>
   American Girl Place, since opening in Chicago's most expensive
shopping district in 1998, has drawn 750,000 girls and women (and a
few men) from around the world, and in its first year in business
has made $25 million, more than twice the original projection, for
its parent, Pleasant Co. of Middleton, Wis. The store offers not
only the wildly popular American Girl dolls and their extravagant
accessories, but other distractions like a theater, a cafe and a
doll hospital.
</P>
<P>
   USING E-MAIL TO MARKET CITRUS
</P>
<P>
   Growers in Florida are using digital cameras and the Internet to
market their fruit far from the citrus groves and to resolve
disputes when shipments arrive damaged.
</P>
<P>
   PREPARING FOR THE `DOT-COM BOWL'
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen Internet companies are scheduled to make their
Super Bowl advertising debuts during football's championship game
on Jan. 30, compared with three in 1999 and one apiece in 1998 and
1997. The eagerness of dot-coms to parade themselves before what is
usually the largest viewing audience of the year helped drive ad
rates for Super Bowl XXXIV to a record average of more than $2
million for each 30-second spot during the game, at least 25
percent more than the 1999 rate. Some latecomers are paying up to
$3 million for their 30 seconds of fame.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. FINANCIAL MARKETS REOPEN
</P>
<P>
   U.S. financial markets will reopen Tuesday. They were closed
Monday in observance of Martin Luther King's Birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
