<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-CONNECTICUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABROSIMOVA LEADS UCONN TO 65-50 TRIUMPH OVER RUTGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ In the first minute of Monday's game, as
Rutgers began its surge to a surprising 9-point lead, Svetlana
Abrosimova of Connecticut took an elbow to the nose from Tammy
Sutton-Brown of Rutgers as they fought for a rebound. Abrosimova
blinked and looked quizzically at the big center of the Scarlet
Knights. With second-ranked Tennessee having been upset earlier in
the day, was this a hint that the second shoe was about to fall
with Rutgers toppling the top-ranked and undefeated Huskies?
</P>
<P>
   No way. After a brief rest, Abrosimova returned to the game and
to her forward position. Later in the half, starting with four
minutes to play and two of Rutgers' top players on the bench,
Abrosimova and her Connecticut teammates returned the surge with 17
unanswered points to take an 8-point halftime lead. In the second
half, the Huskies never let Rutgers get closer than 6 points as
they rolled to a 65-50 victory before 16,294 at the Hartford Civic
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Although several Huskies (15-0, 5-0 Big East) contributed, none
were as dominant as Abrosimova, a lanky junior from St. Petersburg,
Russia. She led all scorers with 20 points, shooting jumpers from
long range and slashing along the baseline. She grabbed five
rebounds and crashed to the floor many times in struggles for loose
balls against Rutgers (11-4, 4-2), which had fallen from 9th to
11th in the Associated Press poll after last week's loss to
Villanova.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has more competitiveness than she does,'' Huskies coach
Geno Auriemma said of Abrosimova. ``She understands at all times
when the game is being decided. She's always in the middle of a lot
of stuff that happens. You can't teach that. You can't coach that.
She has it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Abrosimova said she didn't understand why her coach rested her
so early. ``It wasn't because of that,'' she said, referring to the
elbow. ``When I came back, I tried to play the best I could.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her team was not rattled by Rutgers' early rally. ``We
still knew we were going to have our own run,'' Abrosimova said.
``We just waited for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her coach seemed slightly amused that Abrosimova reported no
problem from the elbow. ``She took a pretty good shot to the face,
it looked like it staggered her a little bit,'' he said. ``I said,
`Is something bothering you? Why did you go all the way down and
sit next to the trainer?' Mixed messages, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Bird had 13 points and 5 assists for the Huskies, and
Swintayla Cash added 11 points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   For Rutgers, Shawnetta Stewart had 13 points and 5 rebounds, and
Tasha Pointer, the other starting guard, had 13 rebounds and 9
points. Sutton-Brown, a dominating presence near the basket, had 7
points and 5 rebounds in the first half, but no points and just 2
rebounds in the second half. Rutgers Coach C.Vivian Stringer was
asked about resting Sutton-Brown, who had two fouls, and Stewart,
who had three, during the Connecticut comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have quality substitutions,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart added, ``I wanted to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Stringer and her players said they were not content to play well
on Connecticut's home court and go home with a respectable defeat.
Stringer said of the Huskies: ``They're the best, there's no
question about that. They've got great balance. They are extremely
bright. It's Connecticut and everybody else. I want to leave with a
smile sometime after a game like this. But I don't want to drop my
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Her players played with determination and aggression, outfouling
Connecticut, 21-10. ``I don't have anything to say about the
officials,'' Stringer said. ``Make sure you say that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The last of those fouls came with one second left. It was the
fifth against Linda Miles, who intentionally crashed Shea Ralph to
the floor. Ralph, who scored only 9 points and watched the
first-half rally from the bench, said Rutgers might have been
motivated by its loss to Villanova.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably, if anything, it made them angrier,'' Ralph said,
making the Scarlet Knights want to ``beat somebody up and make
somebody pay for it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
