</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-HOLOCAUST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERLIN MAYOR TO SKIP DEDICATION OF HOLOCAUST MEMORIAL, ANGERING
MANY 
</HEADLINE>
 (Subs 4th graf to add description of Elie Wiesel, `the author...') 
(nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Eberhard Diepgen, the mayor of Berlin, has decided not
to attend the dedication ceremony next week for a large Holocaust
memorial near the Brandenburg Gate, a project he has long opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Diepgen has said his agenda was too full to attend the ceremony
on Jan. 27, although he has declined to specify what his other
engagements are.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Naumann, Germany's senior cultural official, said:
``This is a significant ceremony demonstrating the fact that the
memorial will be built. I am very surprised that Diepgen is not
coming and hope he will change his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, to be attended by Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder,
President Johannes Rau and Elie Wiesel, the author and holocaust
historian, is intended to put to rest a decade of tumultuous debate
over a memorial that will combine a field of more than 2,000 stone
pillars and a ``documentation center'' whose exact form and
character remain murky.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has revealed deep differences over the place of
memory in a society now two generations removed from the Nazi era,
and over the image of the new city being built on land once
occupied by the Berlin Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Diepgen has argued that the memorial is too big and impossible
to protect. Officials close to him have suggested that it may be
unnecessary in a city that already has several smaller monuments
commemorating the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   By its position and size, the memorial, by the New York
architect Peter Eisenman, will be a dominant feature of the city.
It is to be built at a time when many Germans feel that the country
has done enough to commemorate, confront and pay compensation for
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Michael-Andreas Butz, the spokesman for the mayor, did not
return several telephone calls seeking comment. In statements to
the German press, he has said the mayor is far too busy, may not
have been invited, and will in any event be represented by another
senior Christian Democratic politician.
</P>
<P>
   Naumann said he was sure that the mayor had been invited and
that his absence from the ceremony would be unfortunate.
</P>
<P>
   American officials, already in a conflict with Diepgen over
security for a new American Embassy in Berlin, expressed irritation
at the mayor's decision. John Kornblum, the American ambassador, is
to attend the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Thierse, the speaker of Parliament, has described the
ceremony as the ``symbolic start of the memorial's construction.''
But building at the vast site is not expected to begin until next
year at the earliest because financing and some architectural
details have not been completed.
</P>
<P>
   It also emerged late last year that a small corner of the site
was still owned by a municipal housing company, and the status of
that piece of land has to be resolved. Because discussion over it
will involve the city government, and because Diepgen is not
enthusiastic, the talks could take some time.
</P>
<P>
   The city will also be largely responsible for construction of
the project. It remains unclear when the memorial, whose cost is
estimated at $26 million, will be completed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Because of those remaining difficulties with a project approved
last year by Parliament, officials have decided to refrain from a
groundbreaking ceremony. Rather, large signs in German and English
will be unveiled at the dedication showing what the memorial will
be and explaining its significance.
</P>
<P>
   As other buildings around the 4.9-acre empty lot have moved
toward completion in the last year, this large hole in the heart of
Berlin has become increasingly conspicuous, prompting occasional
exasperated suggestions that the best memorial would be simply to
leave the site vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Delays have also emerged at the city's new Jewish Museum, which
was to have opened later this year. Problems with the
air-conditioning system and other technical features of the
building by Daniel Libeskind, an American architect, have pushed
the opening back to 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
