<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GASOLINE-PIPELINE-ART     01-17 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-PIPELINE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE OVER PIPELINE ILLUSTRATES DECLINING STRENGTH OF OIL
INDUSTRY IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ROSS MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNSET VALLEY, Texas _ Sandwiched between the sparsely populated
Texas hill country and the sprawling city of Austin, this community
of 327 people sits on the line between new and old versions of the
Lone Star state. To the east rise the office buildings of an urban
high technology center; to the west, rolling ranch land stocked
with cattle, and beyond, the flat prairies of Big Oil.
</P>
<P>
   And just beneath the limestone soil of Sunset Valley's quiet
suburban neighborhoods runs another line, a 50-year-old,
700-mile-long oil pipeline that some say represents a grave
environmental threat and others contend holds environmental and
economic benefits just waiting to be tapped.
</P>
<P>
   The differing views say much about how Texas has changed since
the pipeline was built, and about the oil industry's declining
influence.
</P>
<P>
   For more than five years, Longhorn Partners Pipeline Co. has
been trying to convert the pipeline from its former function,
pumping crude oil from Houston to West Texas refineries, to a new
use, carrying cleaner-burning gasoline to El Paso, a city under
federal air quality sanctions. From there, the gasoline would go to
New Mexico and Arizona. The result, Longhorn says, would be cleaner
air for El Paso and reduced fuel costs for Southwest motorists who
have historically paid some of the nation's highest gasoline
prices.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline has been dormant since it was bought for $325
million in 1995 by Longhorn, a partnership of Exxon, Amoco and
other oil interests.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say moving gasoline rather than less-volatile crude
oil through the aged line poses risks of explosions and fires for
thousands of people living near it. They also say spills from the
pipeline could threaten lakes and the ecologically fragile Edwards
Aquifer, an underground network of spring-fed catacombs that
provides water to 45,000 Central Texas residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about pitting one area against another,'' said
Jeff Jacks, an Austin neighborhood leader. ``El Paso needs cleaner
gas for their air quality problems, and so we end up shipping
gasoline across our aquifer. None of it makes much sense.''
</P>
<P>
   J.J. Pickle, a Democrat who represented this area in Congress
for 31 years until 1994, says he cannot remember a similar
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty years ago things like this pipeline were just
automatic,'' Pickle said. ``People didn't think there was another
side to putting in pipelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Longhorn has agreed to a long list of protective measures as a
condition for reopening the line. But officials here have vowed to
fight the move, insisting that the line be re-routed around the
Edwards Aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message is very direct, put this pipeline somewhere else,''
Rep. Lloyd Doggett, a Democrat who replaced Pickle, said last week
at a meeting that drew 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Oil and Texas have been synonymous since the Old Spindletop
field was discovered in East Texas in 1901. The state has 250,000
miles of underground oil and gas pipelines, more than any other,
said Gene Acuna of the Texas Railroad Commission, which regulates
the network.
</P>
<P>
   Local sensitivities to pipeline safety were heightened by an
explosion on a pipeline in Bellingham, Wash., that killed three
people in June 1999. And on Thursday a $35 million settlement was
announced between the federal government and Koch Industries of
Wichita, Kan., arising from oil spills in rural areas. Texas will
receive $17.5 million of that settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't think much about them until there's an accident
or a controversy,'' Acuna said, ``but the state is literally
crisscrossed with pipelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1993 and 1996 there were 614 incidents involving
pipeline safety along the 150,000 miles of intrastate lines
regulated by his office, Acuna said, and three reported fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   With high technology now driving the Texas economy, oil is no
longer king. In the 1950s, when the Longhorn pipeline was built,
oil represented over a quarter of Texas' total economic output and
employed 233,000 Texans, more than 10 percent of the state's work
force.
</P>
<P>
   Oil and gas have slipped to 11.9 percent of the state's gross
product and 3 percent of the state's work force. By comparison, the
high-tech industry employs over 100,000 in Austin alone and more
than 500,000 statewide. The technology industry has surpassed oil's
role in the economy and now totals 12.5 percent of the state's
gross product, the state Comptroller's Office said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our real economic resource is not minerals, but our quality of
life,'' Doggett said. ``Our quality of life is what attracts the
talented people. And you cannot get those people if you are next to
a smelly oil well or a potentially exploding or leaking pipeline.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Martin, a spokesman for Longhorn, counters that it would
take 12,000 tanker trucks to move the volume of gasoline that would
be transported by the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you tell me which represents the greater environmental and
quality-of-life risk: an underground pipeline that no one ever sees
or 12,000 tanker trucks in the street?'' Martin asked.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute illustrates the declining influence of the oil
industry, Pickle said. But just as important, he said, is the
growth in agencies and laws to protect the environment. ``It's not
just that the oil industry has gotten weaker, but that the citizens
and the environmental groups have gotten so much stronger and
better organized,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NETS-76ERS-365&AMP;AD     01-17 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-76ERS-365&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER VAN HORN'S MISSTEPS, NETS FALL TO SIXERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The preferred play had broken down, and it was up
to Keith Van Horn to create another. With the New Jersey Nets
trailing by 3 points and victory or defeat hinging on his move, he
had two options _ get to the basket fast for a quick score or
drive, draw attention and find a teammate on the perimeter for a
3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   When Van Horn began penetrating the lane from the top of the
key, the options swirling in his head, the ball slipped from his
right hand and into the grasp of the Philadelphia 76ers' George
Lynch. A lead pass to the streaking Allen Iverson for a game-ending
dunk emphatically sealed the Philadelphia victory and Nets defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The final score was 101-96 Monday at the First Union Center. The
final vision was of Van Horn committing his eighth turnover of the
day with the game hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right when I got down to the point of making the decision I
became indecisive, and that's when the ball slipped out of my
hands,'' said Van Horn, who had 20 points and a game-high 14
rebounds. ``You can't be indecisive at that moment. You just have
to make the right play. I just tried to think a little too much
instead of just playing basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment that I went up to shoot, I saw George Lynch step in
and I went to pick it up to kick it out to Scott Burrell, and
that's when the ball came out. I take full responsibility for
losing the ballgame there.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn appeared to be going for a 2-point basket, which would
have left the Nets, who had no timeouts remaining, with little
chance to get the ball back and score again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad play,'' coach Don Casey said. ``I'll talk to him
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the second consecutive game in which the Nets foiled
themselves in the waning moments. In Saturday's 99-96 loss to
Boston, Kendall Gill threw away an inbounds pass with 18 seconds
remaining, thwarting the Nets' last opportunity. Monday, the Nets
failed to get a 3-point attempt when trailing by 99-96 with nine
seconds remaining. Neither Stephon Marbury, Kerry Kittles nor
Burrell could get open to receive a pass from Johnny Newman, which
put the ball in the hands of Van Horn, the last resort.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet after dropping to 15-22, the Nets were not hard on
themselves in the locker room. The felt they had played a tough,
solid game and done well to give themselves a chance to defeat the
surging 76ers (22-16) on their home floor. One of the league's
hottest teams, Philadelphia has won 5 of its last 6 games and 8 of
its last 10 since falling to the Nets at Continental Arena on Dec.
23.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nets, with their owners Lewis Katz and Finn Wentworth
watching from courtside seats, did plenty wrong. Casey elected to
play his rebounding fiend, Jamie Feick, only 23 minutes because he
thought Jim McIlvaine and Michael Cage were playing stronger post
defense, and the result was Philadelphia dominance on the
backboards.
</P>
<P>
   Just a mediocre rebounding club, Philadelphia outrebounded the
Nets by 51-36 and outscored them by 20-7 in second-chance points.
On top of that, the jump shot-loving Nets attempted 25 3-pointers
but hit only 7. Marbury led the Nets with 31 points and 9 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia, which was led by Iverson's 34 points, looked set
to cruise after building an 82-70 by the final minute of the third
period. But the Nets employed the surprising weapon of Lucious
Harris to get back in contention.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, a 6-foot-5-inch guard and former 76er, used his size
against the 6-foot Iverson to hit five straight baskets and score
10 of the Nets' first 11 points of the fourth quarter. His final
basket, an 18-footer, pulled the Nets within 88-87 with 6 minutes
41 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia went back ahead by 6 points, but the Nets moved
within 96-93 and had a chance to scoot closer when Kittles grabbed
a rebound and kicked it to Marbury streaking on a fast break.
Marbury, who penetrated successfully all day, drove again, but
Aaron McKie knocked the ball out of his hands with 54.4 seconds
remaining, and Eric Snow recovered. Caseythought Marbury deserved
a foul call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to the officials that somehow I feel if Iverson was
breaking away for a layup, there would have been a foul called,''
said Casey, questioning the officials publicly for the first time
this season. ``My guy doesn't get a foul call. That was a huge
play. Whether it was a foul or not, I just have a feeling that, to
Iverson's credit so to speak, he would have gotten the call. Our
little guy gets the stuff kicked out of him all the time and hardly
ever gets a call.''
</P>
<P>
   After Philadelphia's Theo Ratliff made one of two free throws,
Marbury gave the Nets a chance by sinking a 3-pointer that made it
97-96 with 10.6 seconds to play. McKie followed with two free
throws, and then, after a Nets timeout, the ball and the big
decision were left to Van Horn.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff, who blocked three shots and intimidated on numerous
others, said Van Horn, who had his season high for turnovers, was
thinking about more than his options on that final play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know he heard me coming,'' the 6-10 Ratliff said, joking
somewhat. ``He knows I'm going to challenge every shot. He knows
there ain't going to be any plain looks.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there was no look at all for the Nets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
