<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8539 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEMOCRATS-BAXTER-COX     01-17 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-BAXTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A meeting of minds on this King holiday
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ It was reported last week that Maytag Corp.
is considering moving its headquarters out of Iowa, in part because
the state doesn't have enough diversity. This relatively
homogeneous state might seem an odd place, then, to hold a debate
on racial issues.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, the added draw of next week's caucuses, which
assured at least that both Democratic candidates would show up at
the Brown-Black Forum, held at a high school in a racially mixed
area of this city.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is counting on minority votes to help him
win not only the nomination but the election, and former Sen. Bill
Bradley has made racial healing the cornerstone of his campaign. So
it was not surprising that the two had few real disagreements about
civil rights policy.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate did reveal substantial differences in the way the
two Democrats approach what moderator Tavis Smiley called ``the
all-important issue of race in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore cast himself at every turn as the pragmatist, and in this
forum, unlike some other, the vice president didn't hesitate to
hold up the record of the Clinton administration. Bradley, on the
other hand, presented himself as the candidate ost willing to
think outside the box, as a visionary for whom not even the record
of this administration, so popular with African-American voters, is
good enough.
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of racial profiling, for instance, Bradley said
Gore should march into the Oval Office and demand that Bill Clinton
sign an executive order banning the practice. Clinton, Gore
retorted, didn't need ``a lecture from Bill Bradley'' on how to
fight for minorities.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, there could hardly be a debate on race without a
John Rocker question.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he ``wouldn't be disappointed'' if the Braves fired
Rocker, and said the Atlanta squad should emulate his old team, the
Knicks. Gore repudiated Rocker's remarks, but related what he'd
heard earlier in the day in Atlanta from Andrew Young, whose
eloquence on this overworked subject is as yet unmatched.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think America is all about redemption,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   This debate was notable for being the first in memory in which a
candidate agreed with a heckler. When an environmental activist
interrupted the forum to shout something about global warming, Gore
remarked that while he didn't like her tactics, she had ``a pretty
good point.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also one nugget of news in this debate, at least for
those who have not paid attention to what the Democratic candidates
have had to say about the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   Given the chance, neither was willing to stand squarely behind
Attorney General Janet Reno's decision that the boy should be sent
back to his Cuban father. If anything, Gore was a little more vocal
in his waffling than Bradley, speculating that the father may be
intimidated by the demonstrations held outside his home by Cubans
demanding the boy's return.
</P>
<P>
   The very next question was whether the same philosophy should
apply to Chinese, or Haitian, or Mexican children _ which
illustrates just what a slippery slope the Gonzalez case rests on.
</P>
<P>
   The question also illustrates just how broad the subject of
civil rights has become. On this first King holiday to be
celebrated in all 50 states, many of the answers propounded by the
late civil rights leader have become an accepted part of the
national canon. But today, those answers are being connected with a
far wider variety of questions.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
