<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFCNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFC Notebook: Bucs expect loud crowd to be factor
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Buccaneers coach Tony Dungy was asked Monday if
crowd noise would be a problem for his team in the NFC
Championship. The game will be played at the Trans World Dome, home
of the St. Louis Rams and one of the loudest places in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Before Dungy could answer, a plane flew over the Tampa Bay
practice facilities, which are located less than a mile from Tampa
International Airport. After pausing a few seconds to allow the
noise to diminish, Dungy grinned and said, ``That is why we
practice here.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his players and coaches are accustomed to the din,
Dungy remains concerned about the St. Louis crowd on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noise is going to be a factor _ no doubt about it,'' he said.
``We could tell that by watching the TV (on Sunday). The crowd was
all hyped up and it will be loud in there again this weekend. The
best thing we can do is play well and hold down the score.''
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy football
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers' workouts Monday were extremely light Monday.
There was a short 30-minute walk-through, and the only players to
break a sweat all day were punter Mark Royals and kicker Martin
Gramatica, who both lifted light weights before the team took the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Several players didn't even suit up in complete practice
uniforms. Seven players were injured in Saturday's ultra-physical
contest against the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of guys that were banged up today,'' Dungy said.
``We anticipate everybody other than Al Singleton (broken ankle)
and Reidel Anthony (strained quadraceps muscles) to probably be
practicing on Wednesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Dungy has rewarded the players with a day off today, while the
coaches will report to work to study film and devise the game plan.
The staff will also have to make personnel decisions, such as
deciding whether or not to put Singleton on injured reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't decided that yet,'' Dungy said. ``(Singleton) told
me he will be ready to play next week (if we make it to the Super
Bowl Jan. 30), even though he has a broken leg. We're going to wait
and see. We may put him on the (injured reserve), but we really
don't need to. We've still got a couple of spots (on the 53-man
roster) available.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony is the third-leading receiver on the team, while
Singleton is a standout on special teams and a reserve linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   No security worries
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Falcons guarded NFC Championship practices last year
like a presidential visit. Tampa Bay has almost the opposite
approach to security, with most of it due to location. A tall
business building and four-level parking garage overlook the west
side of the team's practice field. Reporters walked through the
gates on the field without press credentials being checked.
</P>
<P>
   So does Dungy think St. Louis spies are all about?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Dungy said. ``I know Coach (Dick) Vermeil real well and
he does not cheat. So I don't have to worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like old friends
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Vikings coach Dennis Green and Dungy are close
friends. Green employed Dungy as Minnesota's defensive coordinator
from 1992-95. On Monday, Dungy called some of his old buddies on
the Vikings staff to ask for any tips or advice against the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to people there, and we got some things that
hopefully we can use,'' Dungy said. ``But we are going to have to
figure out how to beat St. Louis on our own. Not many people have
done that on their own. We'll see if we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Carvell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
