<HEADLINE>
PALLADIAN VILLAS  
 SAN GENNARO  
 TOKYO POLICE TOURS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is there a specific time each year when the villas designed
by Palladio in the Veneto are open to visitors? And do you need to
travel in a group to see them? _ Louise Wartik, State College, Pa. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. It depends on the villa. There are 18 surviving Palladian
villas in the area around Venice, and many welcome visitors.
Admission fees range from about $4.25 to $6.50, at 1,875 lire to
$1. Here is a sampling of the villas that are open to visitors,
with their dates and hours: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Villa Barbaro, in the village of Maser next to Asolo, was
built between 1549 and 1558; the chapel was built in 1579-80. The
central residence features 16th-century frescoes, principally by
Veronese. It is 35 miles from Venice and is open Tuesday, Saturday
and Sunday from 3 to 6 p.m. March to September and 2:30 to 5 p.m.
October to February. The chapel is open Tuesday upon request; call
(39-0423) 923-004. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Villa Cornaro, in the village of Piombino Dese about 20
miles from Venice, was built in 1552 to 1553. The two-story
projecting portico-loggia was a motif that influenced Western
architecture for centuries, turning up in Georgian and Colonial
American architecture. It was said to be the first model Jefferson
used for Monticello. The villa is a short walk from the Piombino
Dese train station. It is open May to September on Saturday 3:30 to
6 p.m. Call (39-049) 936-5017. &QL; 
   The Villa Emo, in Fanzolo di Vedelago (about 30 miles by car
from Venice), was built in 1559-65. The central residence has four
columns, and symmetrical wings of farm buildings extend from each
side, with dovecotes at the ends. The Capitol building in
Washington can trace its architectural roots to the villa. It is
open May through September, on Monday, Wednesday and Friday 2:30 to
6 p.m., Tuesday 3 to 6 p.m., Saturday 2:30 to 7 p.m. and Sunday 10
a.m. to 12:30 p.m. and 2:30 to 7 p.m. Call (39-0423) 476-414. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Villa Foscari, in Malcontenta di Mira on the banks of the
Brenta River, is near the Venice coastal lagoon. Completed around
1560, it has a sad-looking woman in one of its frescoes, which may
have been the source of its commonly used name: La Malcontenta. It
is open Tuesday and Saturday 9 a.m. to noon and by appointment;
call (39-041) 547-0012. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Villa Almerico, in Vicenza, was completed after Palladio's
death in 1580. The central dome, inspired by the Pantheon, gives
the villa its other name, La Rotonda. It is open March through
December. The villa and grounds are open Wednesday 10 a.m. to noon
and 3 to 6 p.m.; the grounds only are open the same hours all other
days except Monday; call (39-0444) 321-793.
</P>
<P>
   To learn more about Palladio's villas, call up
www.boglewood.com/palladio/home.html. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do Neapolitan-Americans in New York still celebrate the feast
day of San Gennaro? If so, when and where? _ Peter Barna, Hollywood
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. St. Januarius, who was the bishop of Benevento in southern
Italy during the Emperor Diocletian's persecutions, was martyred in
Naples in 305. He is considered the patron saint of Naples, where
his remains are enshrined and where he is known as San Gennaro.
</P>
<P>
   Many New Yorkers, though, probably think he is the patron saint
of sausage-and-pepper heroes _ along with zeppole and cannoli and
all the other delights sold each September on the streets of Little
Italy during the Festival of San Gennaro. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 74th festival will be Sept. 14 to 24, with most of the
attractions _ outdoor food stalls, music and games of chance _ on
Mulberry Street between Canal and Houston in Lower Manhattan. Hours
are usually 11:30 a.m. to 11:30 p.m. on weekdays and until midnight
on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of the festival include the two appearances of the
statue of San Gennaro, which is carried along Mulberry by a half
dozen men. The first appearance will be in the afternoon on Sept.
16, as part of a parade with floats. The second will be in the
evening on Sept. 19, the feast day, and will simply be the carrying
of the statue. Members of the San Gennaro Society will accept
donations as the statue is carried past.
</P>
<P>
   Musical performances ranging from rock to Italian folk music
will take place in the evenings on weekends and many weeknights.
For more information, contact the Most Precious Blood Church at
(212) 226-6427. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a New York City police officer and will be in Tokyo in
March. Whom can I contact to arrange a tour of a police facility in
Tokyo? _ G.C., Brooklyn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. There is a much easier way to see Tokyo police headquarters
than getting arrested. And as a police officer, you even have a
couple of choices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone may request a visit to the Tokyo Metropolitan Police
Department headquarters, where tours are conducted five times a day
on weekdays, as well as in other cities. In Tokyo, the tour
includes the Police Museum, the Communication Command Center and _
if you want to see people handling a really tough job _ the Traffic
Control Center. The tours are offered at 9 and 10:30 a.m. and
12:30, 2 and 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   You must send an advance request by fax to the Public Relations
Department with your name, the date and time of the tour you prefer
and the city where you wish to take the tour. Requests are accepted
any time from six months in advance to the day before. For tours in
Tokyo, fax it to Orito (no given name needed, per local business
etiquette) at (81-3) 3580-5091; the telephone number is (81-3)
3581-0141, extension 2623. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For tours outside Tokyo, you should fax this information to
Oshiki at the Public Relations Department of the National Police
Agency at (81-3) 3581-3924; telephone (81-3) 3581-4321, extension
32295 or 32296.
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the law-enforcement profession, however, you can
request a more detailed tour. Besides specifying a date, time and
location, your application must also include the following: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ A profile of your law-enforcement background. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ The reason you are requesting the visit, anything that you
specifically want to learn and what kind of police facilities
interest you. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ A recommendation letter from your direct superior. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ The name and telephone number of the hotel where you will be
staying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2133EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
