<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0336 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8546 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-CALIFORNIA-$AD     01-17 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CALIFORNIA-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAKEOVER IN ANAHEIM, FOR PARKS AND CITY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ There is no missing the big changes afoot in
Anaheim. For months, no motorist on Interstate 5, the overcrowded
freeway that snakes through this aging tourist town, could fail to
notice the outline of new ramps and overpasses and seemingly
endless construction that herald the biggest development effort
here in the 45 years since Walt Disney first built his Magic
Kingdom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half a century after it opened in a sleepy sea of orange
groves, Disneyland is as fresh and spotless as ever, and it remains
the single most popular tourist attraction in Southern California,
drawing some 13.7 million visitors in 1998, according to Amusement
Business, a trade journal.
</P>
<P>
   But the urban corridor of strip malls, fast-food outlets and
motels that has grown up around it was tired and long overdue for a
lift. It is getting one in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two years, Anaheim will see the fruits of a $4.2
billion public-private redevelopment in the works since 1996. It
will bring a whole new theme park called Disney's California
Adventure, plus a retail shopping complex, an expanded convention
center, and new hotels, roads and landscaping to 1,100 acres
surrounding the original park.
</P>
<P>
   Just 12 miles away in Buena Park, Knott's Berry Farm, Orange
County's second-most-popular attraction, with some 3.4 million
visitors, will open its Perilous Plunge this summer. That ride,
featuring a four-and-a-half-story chute down which boats will
plunge at a 75-degree angle, is billed as the longest, steepest
water ride in the world and is just one part of an overall upgrade
at Knott's that will also feature a separate new 13-acre water park
called Soak City, U.S.A., scheduled to open on Memorial Day with 21
water rides and attractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a different world every day now,'' said Elaine
Cali, the communications director for the Anaheim/Orange County
Visitor and Convention Bureau, whose office overlooks the changing
construction scene.
</P>
<P>
   Disney alone is investing $1.4 billion to expand its original
resort and build the new California-theme park _ celebrating beach
culture, the redwood forests and other features of the state _ on
the site of its former parking lot. It is bridging the two with
Downtown Disney, a 300,000-square-foot retail, dining and
entertainment complex, like the one at Walt Disney World in
Orlando, that will feature outlets of popular spots like House of
Blues and the La Brea Bakery, the Los Angeles-based emporium of
irresistible breads and pastries.
</P>
<P>
   These expanded attractions, including a 750-room luxury hotel,
the Grand Californian, built in the style of Frank Lloyd Wright,
are to open early in 2001. A 10,000-car enclosed parking garage is
going up adjacent to the parks, and the original Disneyland Hotel
is being remodeled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By December 2000, a $177 million expansion of the Anaheim
Convention Center, across the street from the park, is scheduled to
be finished, increasing total square footage by 40 percent, to 1.6
million square feet. A major redesign of the former Anaheim
Stadium, now known as Edison Field International and home of the
Disney-owned Anaheim Angels baseball team, has already been
completed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The town has not seen anything of this magnitude, certainly
since the original Disneyland was built,'' said Ms. Cali of the
convention bureau. ``This was truly an agricultural community then,
but today it's an urban destination and very built up, so to be
able to change the landscape is pretty remarkable.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Together, the new Disney-related attractions are expected to
increase the average stay in the resort corridor to four nights,
from three now, though some developers have held off building new
hotels until they are sure more visitors will come, leading to some
predictions of a shortage of rooms in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, when the California economy was in a deep
recession and the greater Los Angeles area was rocked by riot, fire
and earthquake, attendance at Disneyland and other parks fell
sharply. Although it has since bounced back, some hotel analysts
say lenders remain put off by Anaheim's low average room rate,
about $76, compared with an overall nationwide average of $81
through November, according to Smith Travel Research. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All the construction has been a challenge for local hotels,
which have struggled to fill rooms in the face of the congestion.
While the California Division of Tourism has projected an overall
increase of about 6 percent in travel within and to California in
1999, Orange County was expected to end the year with about 38.05
million visitors, up just 0.8 percent from 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, perhaps the most visible sign of the efforts in
Anaheim is the freeway construction, a $1.1 billion makeover aimed
at nearly doubling the lanes of a 9.5-mile section that has been
among the most congested in the region. Construction has had to
allow for the continuing crowds at Disneyland and has required
rerouting up to 36,000 vehicles a day. It is scheduled to be
finished late in 2000, just in time for the opening of the new
Disney park. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
