<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MEDIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAMP SAYS MEDIA PARTIAL TO MCCAIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and top aides
are doing a slow burn at what they _ as well as some unaligned
observers of the race for the Republican presidential nomination _
see as the news media's favorable treatment of Sen. John McCain of
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   While hesitant to make their discontent a front-burner issue in
the increasingly testy Bush-McCain face-off, it doesn't take a
jackhammer to unearth the Bush camp's resentment.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's side is bemused and blames any problem on what it sees
as a result of the naturally gregarious governor being kept from
the news media and ``overhandled'' by aides, while McCain is
perpetually available for interviews and schmoozing.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bush high command sees a media determination to attempt
to create a close Republican race and says reporters are reacting
unprofessionally to McCain's constant courting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the front-runner, and he's not held to the same
standard of scrutiny the front-runner is,'' Karen Hughes, Bush's
spokeswoman, said of McCain. ``I understand the media is human. The
media likes an underdog. ... But I do think, if you look at the
standards of scrutiny, they're a little different.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, a former TV reporter, insisted that she does not like
``to blame the media for things,'' but that was the clear thrust of
her remarks.
</P>
<P>
   When asked for specifics, Hughes cited examples of the news
media's handling of what she sees as both superficial (pop quizzes
for both candidates) and substantive (economic plans from both
campaigns) elements of the race.
</P>
<P>
   When McCain was asked in December to name the prime minister of
Ireland and the governor of Vermont, he came up with neither
without some prompting.
</P>
<P>
   ``One newspaper wrote about it,'' Hughes said of a brief article
in the New York Times. ``No other newspaper in America mentioned
it.'' When Bush earlier was asked to name the leaders of four
hot-spot nations, he at least got one right, she said, but ``every
newspaper, every broadcast outlet, every radio in America reported
it'' as a major shortcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I think it implies a little bit of a double standard,''
Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that McCain has gotten an easy ride from reporters
on his economic proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think that Governor Bush could have released a tax plan
and said he was going to pay for it with unspecified cuts in pork
barrel (projects)?'' Hughes said. ``I mean, the press would have
been all over him to identify them. ... That's an example in which
we feel we've been very conscientious in developing our policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush seemed tempted to let loose when asked about the media's
perceived tilt to McCain, but checked his impulse and, with a fixed
smile, offered a bit of mock high-mindedness: ``I'm confident the
esteemed members of the press corps will treat all of us fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Academics see the media's treatment of McCain as classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The emerging challenger story is just irresistible,'' said
Linda Fowler, government professor at Dartmouth College in Hanover,
N.H., pointing to political science studies of the phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The national news media has been, until recently, much more
critical of Bush,'' Fowler said. ``The minute that somebody attains
front-runner status, the press begins to examine them more
closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Schnur, the McCain campaign's director of communications,
said his candidate's success with the news media ``isn't rocket
science. A candidate or officer-holder who makes himself available
to reporters is more likely to be covered'' favorably. ``It's not
much more complicated than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Schnur said Bush's aides have kept him inaccessible to the media
and that it has been a disservice to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know George W. Bush is a great guy. I worked with him on his
father's campaign,'' Schnur said. ``A reporter traveling with him
may never get the opportunity to come to the same conclusion. ...
There are some candidates who you want to keep locked away, no
matter what, but that's not Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   And it certainly hasn't been McCain, who has a virtually nonstop
political tutorial with reporters aboard his not immodestly named
campaign bus, the ``Straight Talk Express.''
</P>
<P>
   Schnur said the almost constant access has paid off, and the
candidates' pop-quiz experience was ``a perfect example.''
</P>
<P>
   When McCain faced the questions about leaders of Ireland and
Vermont, ``he had just finished holding forth for 45 minutes on
foreign policy, history and public affairs,'' Schnur said. ``So by
the time of that particular question, reporters understood it was
an atypical lapse instead of an indication of some broader
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a guess,'' Schnur said, but if Bush had just spent
that much time talking with reporters about his relationship with
the president of Mexico, that TV interview (in which the pop quiz
occurred) wouldn't have gotten so much more attention than it
deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd let (Bush) sit in the back of the bus with the press
corps, I can't even imagine the kind of an impact it would have.''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL END
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Hughes said that, as a result of the claims
of Bush's inaccessibility to reporters, she had begun keeping a
list of the governor's media contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get sort of frustrated with all this `He's not answering the
questions,''' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of days, she said, she had noted 18 one-on-one
interviews with reporters and two ``press availabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a major reporter who's asked to talk to the
governor who hasn't been able to,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes does not blame reporters who have covered Bush on an
ongoing basis, but she recalled a national reporter who had not
been out with the governor much and then on a Sunday interview show
talked about Bush avoiding reporters. Next day, Hughes said, the
reporter called seeking an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to say, `you just said he's not accessible to the
media, so why bother to ask,''' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
