</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NOTREDAME-RUTGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE WHO GOT AWAY RETURNS TO NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time Kevin Bannon saw Troy Murphy, Murphy was just a
gangly freshman center at Delbarton High School in Morristown, N.J.
A bit awkward and unpolished, Murphy seemed like a player that
Bannon, who was then coaching at Rider College, might be able to
land.
</P>
<P>
   But as Bannon watched him play continually over the next few
years, he noticed that Murphy was not quite what he appeared to be
at first glance. The 6-foot-9-inch frame hid an athleticism that
would bring him far out of Rider's reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 10 times quicker than you think,'' Bannon said. ``He's
way more athletic than he looks. He's just got an incredible feel
for the game. It's effortless. It looks like he's going through the
motions, and then at the end of the game he's got 35 points and 15
rebounds. He looks like a guy who should be playing in a men's
league. He looks like he's not a sculpted athlete, but he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannon moved on from Rider to Rutgers at the time that Murphy
was entering his senior year of high school. Bannon hoped that the
early contact and attention would persuade Murphy to take a chance
on a team that won just 11 games the season before and had
dismissed its head coach. But the allure of Notre Dame and the
chance to follow a player he idolized, Pat Garrity, proved too
strong. When it came down to the decision between the schools,
Murphy left his home state in favor of the Golden Dome.
</P>
<P>
   He will return Tuesday night, to Piscataway, meeting Rutgers for
the first time after missing last year's game because of a sprained
ankle. It is one of two Big East games in New Jersey on Tuesday
night, with 12-2 St. John's, fresh off its upset of Connecticut,
taking on 11-3 Seton Hall at Continental Arena in East Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   While St. John's-Seton Hall may be the marquee game, Murphy may
be the Big East's marquee player. He filled out to 240 pounds and
won Big East honors as rookie of the year last season, shattering
Adrian Dantley's school record for freshman scoring and becoming
the first rookie to lead the conference in rebounding. This season,
he has been named the Big East player of the week five times,
including the last four weeks in a row, and has led the Fighting
Irish to an 11-6 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rutgers is a school I really liked in the recruiting process,
and I felt really comfortable with Kevin and his staff,'' Murphy
said. ``I remember I was the first one he went on a home visit with
as the new coach there. It was a hard decision. A lot of people
were saying the only way you can be a good player is if you stay
home. I just went with my heart. But I check on Rutgers in the
paper to see how they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannon said: ``When we were able to talk, we hit it off really
well. I thought that Troy and I had a lot in common. I knew he was
hungry to be great and I was hungry to build this program. We were
close to doing those two things together. But the pull of Notre
Dame, I think, was coming from people around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he in his heart he would have liked to come here. We
brought in Dahntay Jones, Rashod Kent and Eugene Dabney that year.
I've been looking at film of him this week and thinking that that
would have been a great first recruiting class.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Murphy was the main ingredient that Matt Doherty
inherited this season when he became head coach at Notre Dame.
Little has changed in Murphy's production with the coaching change
as he ranks second in Division I in scoring behind Sirvaliant Brown
of George Washington, averaging 24.9 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   On this trip home, Murphy said that he would not do any
visiting, trying to focus on the game and nothing else. But he
still relishes talking about his New Jersey roots. In the Notre
Dame media guide, each player's biography is accompanied by a
questionnaire. The final question asks each player for his picks
for this year's Final Four. Murphy listed three New Jersey
community colleges, along with Indiana University-South Bend.
``It's a salute to New Jersey,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy is as loose as a player can be on the floor, an attribute
he believes helps him overcome the constant attention he gets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not flaky,'' he said. ``I just mess around and try to have
a good time. I try to stay loose. It relaxes me, and I play better
when I'm loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannon said that he sees an amazing leap in Murphy's abilities
since those first few times he saw him. ``He wasn't anywhere near
the finished product back then,'' Bannon said. ``His game exploded,
and it's all hard work. What separates him from other kids is that
a lot of kids talk about wanting to be great. He doesn't talk about
it; he does it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
