<HEADLINE>
DEVRY INSTITUTE OPENS NEW CAMPUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES -- With an eye toward providing the region's
growing technology industry with a stream of skilled workers, DeVry
Institute officially opens its doors Tuesday in the West Hills
section of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The school, one of four DeVry campuses in California, has been
conducting classes since November.
</P>
<P>
   But today DeVry will celebrate its grand opening.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 students are enrolled at the campus, said Rose Marie
Dishman, president of Devry's Southern California campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Dishman said she plans an outreach program to attract students _
particularly women _ who are underrepresented in technology jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was growing up, there weren't very many women and then
Sputnik came along and women got interested in technology,'' Dish
Still, the technology industry is one that has lacked an equal
representation of women, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like the computer industry has become a man's
world,'' she said. ``We are trying to get into the grade schools to
stimulate interest.
</P>
<P>
   While DeVry is primarily a technology-oriented school, it offers
other programs as well, including accounting, Dishman said. DeVry
tends to draw its students from a 30-mile radius, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the (technology) industry that's developing in the San
Fernando Valley, we're really in the right place at the right
time,'' Dishman said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to hands-on training using the computers and
applications employed in the industry, DeVry tailors its programs
to meet the needs of specific companies, Dishman said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the senior projects required of graduates are designed
by local technology companies to fit within the requirements estab
``We try to go and find a company that's willing to spend their
time to design a project that a student can do in 15 weeks,'' she
really where you can focus the program on what the industry is.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
