<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMAN HOLIDAY? SAMPLE TOURS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking a trip to Rome during the Catholic Church's Jubilee Year
might seem intimidating, particularly to travelers who have never
been to Italy. But even for those not religiously motivated, this
year provides a good opportunity to see the city spruced up, with
many public facilities renovated and transit systems attuned to
tourists. The exchange rate is also advantageous, with the lira at
nearly 1,900 to $1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The easy way to do it is with a tour or package, because many
causes for anxiety, like getting to the hotel from the airport, are
dealt with by someone else, and old hands are ready to offer help. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Regular tour operators are not using the Jubilee Year as a
selling device, and thus have shunned the big price jumps that
upset many consumers about millennium tours and events. Travelers
to Rome are still able to look at the choices and seek out the
religious component, or bypass it, in selecting a tour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't focus on the Jubilee as an event,'' said Robert
Saccone, director of United States development for Italiatour, a
division of Alitalia. ``Our job is to promote travel by people of
all religions.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perillo Tours of Woodcliff Lake, N.J., has this to say in its
catalog for spring and summer: ``Scrub, scrub, scrub. It seems that
half of Rome's buildings have shed centuries of grime to happily
reveal their original beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Perillo, the president, said that his company does not
emphasize events like papal audiences, although of course tour
officials advise group members of each day's events. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Operators consulted early this month said that they had space on
Rome tours scheduled through the end of the year. That includes
TourCrafters of Libertyville, Ill., one of two United States
operators designated by the Vatican Central Committee as official
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The second, the Catholic Travel Center of Burbank, Calif., which
designs tours for clubs and churches, said that it had instituted
early deadlines and that most of its group capacity for spring and
summer was booked, although there were spaces for independent
travelers. J. Scott Scherer, the president, said that bookings
would be 65 percent above last year _ he anticipates 3,000 to 4,000
clients. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perillo, whose company calls itself the world's largest operator
of tours to Italy _ with clients numbering ``tens of thousands
yearly'' _ said he was sure that spring and summer would fill up
but that at the moment there is space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prices on Rome tours take a step up in March, when the weather
eases and average sunshine increases to six hours a day from the
January-February level of four. Lent begins March 8 and Easter is
April 23, and high-season prices are fully in effect by then. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until then, what would normally be viewed as short-stay winter
packages are available. Almost all use Alitalia, but some flights
are on British Airways and Sabena. Trans World Airlines dropped its
New York-Rome route on Jan. 10, although it still serves Milan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a sampling of tours headed for Rome this year: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until March 10, TourCrafters' economy trip of five nights costs
$599 in double occupancy, with air fare from New York, Boston,
Miami or Chicago. It uses the Brasile, a three-star hotel, and
includes breakfast, hotel service charges and taxes. Transfers are
not included; neither are airport taxes and other miscellany,
totaling about $75 a person. There may be a $25 extra charge for a
departure on Friday, Saturday or Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CIT Tours Corp. in New York also has a five-night Rome winter
special at $599 a person, with two in a room, through March 10. It
includes round-trip nonstop Alitalia air fare from New York,
Boston, Chicago or Miami, rail transportation to and from the
airport, and five nights at the three-star Donatello Hotel on the
Via di Porta Maggiore near the train station, with buffet
breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   British Airways through London is also offered, for $70
additional. Departure is available any day of the week. Airport
taxes are not included.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Italiatour offers Roman Jubilee, a four-night trip. Until March
12, including air fare from New York and Boston, and using the
three-star hotels Augustea, Center and Portamaggiore, it costs
$689; for the rest of March, it is $769. Three days of tours,
including the Christian Rome Tour, are offered. Continental
breakfasts, transfers between airport and hotel, and hotel service
charges and taxes are included.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perillo's prices are higher than those given above because the
company quotes the same cost for many different departure cities,
some as far from the Atlantic as Seattle and San Francisco. The
company also uses first-class hotels. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Through Feb. 26, Perillo's six-night packages begin at $1,199
for each of two people in a room in a four-star hotel. The tours
leave on Saturday and Thursday, returning the next Saturday or
Thursday. The price includes round-trip air fare, transfers from
the Rome airport and back, buffet breakfasts, hotel service
charges, taxes and tips.
</P>
<P>
   A half-day of sightseeing is scheduled, and Perillo provides a
host at the hotel at particular hours to give directions and help
with activities. A single room costs $329 more. In March, the tour
price goes to $1,299.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On April 17 the Perillo schedule shifts to Monday-Monday, and
the price rises to $1,799; from June 19 into October, it is $1,999.
The hotel for the high season is the new Hotel Empire Palace on the
Via Aureliana. Perillo is unusual in not accepting credit cards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A six-night package designed for the Jubilee Year by
TourCrafters is called ``Rome, Home of the Holy Father.'' It is
available until March 31 for $1,099 a person from New York or
Boston, with two in a room. The price increases thereafter. This
tour includes a Pilgrim's Card allowing entry on Rome's transit
system for three days, medical assistance and telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The tour is open to groups _ which depart on the day of their
choice and get price discounts at certain levels of participation _
and to independent travelers, who also may depart any day. The
hotel at the basic price is the three-star Centro, on Via Firenze,
or a similar place. Breakfasts and dinners are included, also
transfers from the airport, hotel service and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Two sightseeing expeditions are included, as well as attendance
at a papal audience on a Wednesday, a papal blessing on a Sunday
and a Jubilee event. Airport taxes are not included.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All these tours can be booked through travel agents. Here are
addresses and numbers for the operators mentioned. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Travel Center, 4444 Riverside Drive, Suite 201,
Burbank, Calif. 91505; (818) 848-9449. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CIT Tours Corp., 15 West 44th Street, New York, N.Y. 10036;
(800) 248-8687.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Italiatour, 666 Fifth Avenue, New York, N.Y. 10103; (800)
237-0517; www.italiatour.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perillo Tours, 577 Chestnut Ridge Road, Woodcliff Lake, N.J.,
07675; (800) 431-1515; www.perillotours.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TourCrafters, 28085 North Ashley Circle, Unit 202B,
Libertyville, Ill. 60048; www.tourcrafters.com; (800) 621-2259.
</P>
</TEXT>
