<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8560 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MLK-WRAP-COX     01-17 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLK-WRAP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlantans turn out to honor martyr
 &HT;    By Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Whether they were trained, ordained or just inspired,
it seemed that everyone who took the pulpit at Atlanta's Ebenezer
Baptist Church on Monday became a preacher, extolling the virtues
and vision, the legend and legacy of the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr., as part of the 15th annual King Day Celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to do something about all these unlicensed
preachers up here,'' quipped Rev. Joseph Roberts, who has been
pastor of Ebenezer more than 20 years. Following greetings from
U.S. Sen. Paul Coverdell, U.S. Rep. John Lewis, Gov. Roy Barnes and
Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell, Roberts said people have to move from
talking to walking and have to learn, as King urged, to judge each
other not by the color of their skin but by the content of their
character.
</P>
<P>
   The audience in the historic sanctuary _ and in nearby Freedom
Hall and in an auditorium of the new Ebenezer, from which the
commemorative 10 a.m. service was broadcast _ responded to the
speakers with shouts of ``amen,'' applause and standing ovations.
Among those cheering was Naphtalie Hatcher, a 20-year-old Georgia
Tech student from Augusta, who got up hours before normal and
waited in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two years, I've slept in, but this time I was
determined to come,'' said Hatcher, who planned to spend the
afternoon studying engineering. ``I wanted to learn more about Dr.
King, and I've learned a lot from the speakers, that a lack of
education holds everyone back, and with knowledge comes the
opportunity to serve. I'm really glad I came.''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic Bishop Eddie Long of fast-growing New Birth
Missionary Baptist Church in Decatur brought the audience to its
feet with a tribute that said King knew the difference between
purpose and destiny _ in fulfilling his destiny, he transcended
time and moved into eternity. Long urged his listeners to not
celebrate yesterday but move into tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   The keynote speaker was Rev. DeForest ``Buster'' Soaries Jr.,
pastor of the First Baptist Church of Lincoln Gardens, N.J., and
the New Jersey secretary of state. He likened King to David
battling the Goliath of discrimination, adding that there are
Goliath's children to fight. These modern-day Goliaths, he said,
fly Confederate battle flags over the South Carolina state Capitol,
drag black men to their deaths in Jasper, Texas, and come in all
shapes, colors, guises and economic packaging.
</P>
<P>
   Loving King today is easy, but that hasn't always been the case,
Soaries said _ people hear only the part of his message they want
to hear. ``We love Dr. King when he says, 'I have a dream'; we hate
Dr. King and his family when he says, 'I have a copyright,''' said
Soaries. Some people have criticized the King family for agreeing
to sell the papers of Martin Luther King Jr. to the Library of
Congress for $20 million. Hearings on the sale will be held when
Congress reconvenes.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the curb near a t-shirt vendor were Tina and Kevin
Underwood, of Jonesboro, Ga., and their two sons, Martin and Aaron.
They think so much of Martin Luther King, Jr., that they named
their older son in his honor.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Underwood, who teaches math at Jonesboro High, said she's
feeling a call to get more involved in community affairs, maybe by
working with young people. She said King Day ``is a time to
celebrate our differences. We can have a dialogue and learn to
celebrate all people.''
</P>
<P>
   As the marchers made their way along Auburn Avenue, Thomasville
native, Mack Clark, 32, watched various union groups, cheerleaders,
parent groups, Boy Scouts, step groups, Greek organizations, and
dance and drum troupes pass by, all races, all ages, sizes and
nationalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look back on what Dr. King did and realize he was
out for everybody,'' said Clark, who has lived in Decatur for seven
years. ``It feels good to see people sticking together. That's what
he would have wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
