<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8564 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-IOWA-DEBATE-2TAKES(TR     01-17 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-DEBATE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY AND GORE ENGAGE IN A SHARP EXCHANGE ON RACIAL PROFILING
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Hoping to stir doubts about the
administration's commitment to minorities, former Sen. Bill Bradley
on Monday night challenged Vice President Al Gore to press
President Clinton to issue an executive order banning racial
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Gore fired back with a forceful defense of the president in a
brief but sharp confrontation between the two Democratic
presidential candidates as they appeared in their sixth _ and final
_ debate before the first votes are cast in the Iowa caucuses next
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley seized the offensive at a debate at a high school here
sponsored by the Iowa Brown-Black Presidential Forum, a group that
promotes black and Latino issues, after Gore pledged to sign an
executive order banning profiling, the practice of singling out
blacks for police questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Al, I know that you would issue an order to end
racial profiling if you were president of the United States,''
Bradley said. ``But we have a president now. You serve with him. I
want you to walk down that hallway, walk into his office, and say,
`Sign this executive order today.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore jumped to the president's defense, asserting, ``I don't
think President Bill Clinton needs a lecture from Bill Bradley
about how to stand up and fight for African-Americans and Latinos
in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   His voice rising, Gore went on, ``It's one thing to talk the
talk. It's another thing to walk the walk, whether it's down the
hallway.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's comments elicited boos and jeers from the
audience of several hundred, which was stocked with supporters of
Bradley, who is lagging far behind Gore in the polls in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange over racial profiling made for the most tense
moments of the 60-minute televised forum. Most of the time, Bradley
and Gore put forth virtually identical positions. In fact, even
though minorities make up a tiny portion of the Iowa electorate,
they devoted themselves to trying to top one another in responding
to questions about who they would put on the Supreme Court, their
outrage at the Confederate flag that flies over the capitol of
South Carolina and their efforts to reach out to the Rev. Al
Sharpton, the New York civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, Gore reminded the audience that Monday was the
holiday honoring the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. And invoking
King's memory, he pointed out that he had spoken Monday at the
Ebenezer Baptist Church in Atlanta at the invitation of King's
widow, Coretta Scott King.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley sought to strike a chord with minorities by recalling
something he rarely discusses in public: his self-described role as
a conciliator between white and black players when he was a forward
for the New York Knicks. The subject came up when he was asked
about John Rocker, a pitcher for the Atlanta Braves who had made
disparaging remarks about blacks, immigrants and gays.
</P>
<P>
   He put it this way: ``When I was on the Knicks, one of my jobs
was when there was a white player that came on the team, who didn't
quite understand, used the wrong words, I took him over to the side
and said, `Look, that doesn't work on this team. If you want to be
on this team, you respect everybody.' If that had happened on the
Atlanta Braves, you wouldn't have had John Rocker.''
</P>
<P>
   In appealing to minorities, Bradley sought to close a gap in
what appears to be Gore's overwhelming edge in support from black
voters. Clinton is enormously popular with black voters, many of
whom are loyal to Gore because of his service in the Clinton White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Given Clinton's popularity among blacks, Bradley's scolding of
Clinton on Monday night was something of a risk. It was also
curious given that at forum honoring King at Drake University here
on Monday morning, Bradley praised the president's racial policies
in response to an audience question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're different people,'' he said of Clinton, ``but we have a
common commitment on race.''
</P>
<P>
   But among the broader electorate, Clinton is not as popular. By
invoking the Clinton-Gore connection, Bradley reminded voters of
what they may not like about the administration _ and implicitly
presented himself as a fresh face.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals Monday night were probably aimed as much at liberal
voters as at minorities. That is certainly the case here in Iowa,
which is 96.7 percent white and has among the lowest percentages of
minorities of any state. Blacks account for roughly 1.7 percent of
the population; Latinos make up 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley also reached out to minorities in response to a
question about the high percentage of blacks in prison. Both
candidates said they would consider reviewing the prohibition that
bars felons from voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principle that convicted felons do not have a right to
vote is an old one, it is well established,'' Gore said. ``I think
that the definition of what kind of crimes automatically fall in
the category that triggers that exclusion from the franchise could
well benefit from a fresh review.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley put it this way: ``If someone is on a nonviolent offense
and comes out and is able to go straight for two years, I think
that that person ought to be able to wipe his record clean and
start the day anew.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In a marked contrast to Republican candidates who were reluctant
to attack South Carolina residents for hoisting a Confederate flag,
Gore and Bradley said it was a hurtful symbol.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only the Republican candidates for president who are so
scared of the extreme right that they will be tolerant of
intolerance lest they offend the offensive,'' Gore declared. ``It
ought to come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said: ``I don't want this to be a symbol of America in
any way whatsoever. That's why it ought to come down.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For a few moments, the discourse veered from minority concerns
when Kimberly Defeo, a protester from Des Moines, interrupted the
forum by standing up and asking the candidates about their plans to
stop global warming. She was quickly hustled out of the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, who wrote a best-selling book on global warming,
seized the opportunity to remind the audience of his background.
``I actually think they've got a good point,'' he said of the
environmental groups. ``Going about it the wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the debate, the one-upmanship continued as both
contenders trotted out some of their best-known black and Hispanic
supporters to stand before reporters and tout their candidates'
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Gore brought along three minority cabinet members: Alexis
Herman, the labor secretary, and Rodney Slater, the transportation
secretary, who are both black, and Bill Richardson, the energy
secretary, who is Hispanic. During the debate, Gore also mentioned
two politicians from Bradley's home state of New Jersey who have
been sharply critical of Bradley: Mayor Sharpe James of Newark, who
is black, and Rep. Robert Menendez of Union City, who is of Cuban
descent.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, in turn, brought along Rep. Luis Guttierrez of Chicago
and state Rep. Maria Escutia from Los Angeles, both Hispanics. And
after the debate, Bradley also made an unannounced foray into the
press room with Bill Russell, the former Boston Celtic star, and
Cornell West, the Harvard professor who is his constant companion
at debates.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although the event Monday night marked the last time Gore and
Bradley will share a stage before the Iowa caucuses, both
contenders _ and their loyalists _ will be engaged in a frenzy of
stumping over the next six days. But it will be complicated by the
fact that the two are also spending time in New Hampshire, where
they are locked in a tighter race. The primary there is Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   With Gore well ahead in every poll of expected caucuses-goers,
the question among politicians in this state is not whether he will
win but by what margin. Polls show he is pulling more than 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the vice president still maintains his lead, Bill Bradley's
going to have a hard time breaking the 35 percent barrier,'' Rob
Tully, the chairman of the Iowa Democratic Party, said in an
interview. ``What the Bradley campaign has done over the last week
is to lower the expectations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
