<SLUG> BC-PATHMARK-FINANCES-570&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL WOES CLOUD PATHMARK'S FUTURE IN POOR AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the last decade, Pathmark has sought to expand
its established presence in low-income neighborhoods, where other
chains declined to venture. It has been a successful part of their
business, despite perilous predictions.
</P>
<P>
   But now the chain's future in poor urban areas has been cast in
doubt by mounting debt, a failed merger attempt and other financial
problems, according to market analysts and company officials.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they say, Pathmark's efforts to build additional
supermarkets, including one in Harlem that is considered a
centerpiece of the area's economic redevelopment, are in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would still like to work with the people of Harlem,''
Harvey Gutman, a senior vice president at the supermarket giant,
based in New Jersey, said when asked about the prospects of
building the Harlem market.
</P>
<P>
   The worries about Pathmark's financial health come a month after
a failed corporate marriage that promised to erase much of the
company's nearly $2.5 billion debt and to guarantee its presence in
low-income areas, where stores have generally been profitable for
Pathmark.
</P>
<P>
   The problems could force the company to retrench in many
neighborhoods, both rich and poor. But the concern among advocates
for the poor is that no other supermarket company will take the
risk to invest in low-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market niche they carved was borrowed from `Star Trek,'''
Paul Fetscher, a market analyst who is the president of Great
American Brokerage in Manhattan, said, referring to the show's
theme of boldly going where no one had gone before.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did an excellent job of going into minority areas and
developing excellent stores,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pathmark is sagging under the huge debt that it incurred when it
was taken private in 1987 by an investment group headed by Merrill
Lynch. Because heavy interest payments burned up much of its cash,
the company was unable to expand quickly enough, fiscal analysts
say.
</P>
<P>
   So, for two years Pathmark has been searching for a suitor that
could acquire the company and much of its accumulated debt. Last
March, Pathmark thought it had found one: Royal Ahold, an
aggressive Dutch food retailer, which offered to take on its debt
and buy the company for $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ahold officials said publicly many times that they admired
Pathmark's ability to do so well in poor communities and planned to
continue those efforts. But nine months later, the deal fell apart,
under objections from the Federal Trade Commission. Federal
officials, while not specifically barring the merger, expressed
strong reservations about allowing Royal Ahold, which already owned
Edwards supermarkets, to have such a hold on the New York market.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Pathmark officials have said they fear that their
financial troubles have placed them in a position with limited
options: being acquired by another company, a drastic refinancing
and reorganization, or bankruptcy. It is a position that is
supported by market analysts, like Fetscher.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really only have three choices,'' Fetscher said, adding
that the trade commission decision, ruling out competitors in the
New York market, made it tough to find a company to acquire
Pathmark.
</P>
<P>
   The best case, those officials said, would be for another
company to acquire Pathmark and take on its debt, but few larger
food retailers seem to be in a position to make such a purchase.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This year alone, Pathmark is scheduled to make a $116 million
debt payment, a position that places the company's plans for a
supermarket at 145th Street and Bradhurst Avenue in jeopardy,
company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other companies are bidding for the
30,000-square-foot project, but, given its track record, Pathmark
had been seen as the leading contender. The market is seen as
important to the neighborhood, because aside from Pathmark's East
Harlem store, the only other large market is a Fairway on 133rd
Street, which caters as much to Upper West Siders as to Harlem
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Fairclough, the director of the supermarket project for
the Community Food Resources Center, an advocacy group for the
poor, said, ``We've worked consistently to get larger supermarkets
into low-income neighborhoods, and it is a loss for New York City
if Pathmark stays in a holding pattern or has to retrench.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates are equally concerned that Pathmark stores may decline
in quality or that they could be taken over by a company with a
different set of corporate values. ``Pathmark is really th
supermarket chain that has made a commitment and taken the risk to
develop in low-income neighborhoods,'' Ms. Fairclough said.
</P>
<P>
   Pathmark's future has also become a concern for C. Virginia
Fields, the Manhattan borough president.
</P>
<P>
   As a city councilwoman, Ms. Fields helped the company overcome
objections from local retailers who did not want the
53,000-square-foot supermarket built five years ago on 125th Street
in East Harlem, and she considers the store one of her more
important accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Daglian, a spokeswoman for Ms. Fields, said the borough
president's office was still working with Pathmark and was
optimistic about the proposals for the 145th Street store.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took a lot of work to get Pathmark to the 125th Street
location, and they have shown a lot of tenacity in the face of a
lot of adversity there,'' Ms. Daglian said. ``We would hope
ultimately that if they are taken over by another corporation, the
values and the interest that Pathmark has shown in investing in
lower-income communities are still reflected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
