<HEADER>
A8583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-HILL-PISTONS-NYT &LR;      01-17 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-PISTONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GRANT HILL, TO STAY OR GO IS THE ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   (bl)  
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grant Hill was asked recently whether he would consider
returning close to his childhood home in Reston, Va., and playing
for the Washington Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I would want to be that close to my parents,''
Hill said, breaking up a room.
</P>
<P>
   The most accomplished all-around player in basketball today has
received many inquiries lately. Able to exercise an escape clause
in his contract this summer, the player the Detroit Pistons have
tethered their image to can up and leave if he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Loyalty is a plummeting commodity in sports, and if Hill signs a
long-term extension with the Pistons, it would be a sappy,
feel-good story for the National Basketball Association, a genuine
blow to the current culture of Leverage and Leave.
</P>
<P>
   But is that genuinely good for the league? What if Grant Hill,
27, whose off day at Madison Square Garden against the New York
Knicks on Monday barely detracted from his recent run of 40-point
nights, winds up 10 years from now in the same city, without a
title, wondering hard and long whether he should have left when had
a chance?
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing admitted recently he often thought about whether
he had remained in New York too long, holding onto a dying dream.
Dan Marino is at the end in Miami, his Dolphins much further from
the Super Bowl than they were with Marino in 1985. He, too,
probably asks himself if he stayed with same franchise beyond its
championship shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to way lean one way or the other,'' Hills begins when
asked if loyalty is important, ``but it definitely is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You respect guys either way. Some people leave, some people
stay. In both situations, people are successful. And in both
situations, people fail.
</P>
<P>
   `` Joe Dumars, I respect him a lot,'' he said of his former
Piston teammate, who played out his entire career in Detroit.
``Charles Barkley, I also respect him a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley only played for three teams in his career, but at the
end he was treating the NBA like a game of musical chairs, hoping
beyond hope he could sit down with a team on the cusp of a title.
When he saw slippage in Philadelphia and later Phoenix, Barkley
found a way to move on to Houston, to convince himself life would
be better in another city.
</P>
<P>
   Hill can earn nearly $20 million more by staying in Detroit one
more season and re-signing in 2001, based on experience. The
Pistons could pay him $103 million, while the most any other team
in the league could pay him is $86 million.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he needs the extra cash. Hill, the league's endorsement
king since Michael Jordan retired, is selling much more than the
NBA. Soft drinks. Designer watches. His smile is almost as golden
as his game. His wife, the Grammy-nominated singer Tamia
Washington, is 20-car-pileup beautiful. We should all have his
problems.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, like Jordan after five years, Hill has not won a
playoff series. The Pistons have built nicely around him, put a
cadre of spot-up shooters in place so when Hill is finished
breaking down a defense, he has someone to drop in shots for him.
But though they came into Monday's matinee having won 9 of their
last 10 games, they have yet acquire a true point guard or
dependable center.
</P>
<P>
   After all, you only go so far in this league with one All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   So Grant Hill will soon have to make a decision. Pull up from
the perimeter and take a comfortable jump shot? Or drive hard to
the rim, head down, uncertainty in the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the real legends of the modern era _ Michael,
Larry and Magic _ and they were with one team,'' said Jud Buechler,
Hill's teammate who also played with Jordan in Chicago. ``I think
that means something to Grant. Then again, there is another side to
it: Are you going to get to that next level?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that he may not figure out until we've shown
what we can do in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Either way, at least Hill will soon relate to what Jordan is
going through these days. Asked what he thought of Jordan deciding
whether to purchase a stake in the Wizards and take over their
basketball operations, he said, ``I just can't understand why he'd
want to do that. It just seems like it's beneath him. Not to be an
owner, but to be a GM.''
</P>
<P>
   You mean, all the scouting, the game film, the haggling over
contracts?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I just can't see him living in D.C.,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course. Too close to the parents. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
