<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JAN. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   High-Speed Train Takes Skiers to the Alps  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Through April 29 visitors in England can ride the high-speed
Eurostar Ski Train to the Savoy Alps in France on Friday night or
during the day on Saturday. The trains run from London and Ashford
through the Channel Tunnel to Bourg-St.-Maurice, taking 10 hours
from London overnight or 8 hours in the daytime.
</P>
<P>
   The one-way fare is $245 in first class and $172 in second
class, called standard class by British Rail, which operates
Eurostar trains jointly with the French and Belgian railroads.
</P>
<P>
   Included in the first-class fare on the overnight train is a
reclining seat for sleeping and dinner and breakfast. On the day
train, breakfast and lunch are served to first-class passengers.
Second-class passengers on both trains ride in coach seats, and no
meals are included in the fare. Information: Rail Europe, which
represents the European railroads in the United States, at (888)
382-7245 or www.raileurope.com.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Small Change Adds Up On Airline Taxes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sharp-eyed passengers will notice alterations in the tax boxes
on airline tickets purchased since New Year's. Some taxes went up,
some went down. The net results, though not huge, graphically
demonstrate that nickels and dimes certainly add up.
</P>
<P>
   The main change is on tickets for international trips. The
United States tax for arrival or departure rose to $12.40 from
$12.20, an increase of 40 cents for a round trip. In addition, the
Agriculture Department's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service
fee for arrival from overseas rose to $3 from $2.05, an increase of
95 cents. Combined, these two raise a round-trip overseas ticket by
$1.35.
</P>
<P>
   Trips to and from Alaska and Hawaii, or between the two states,
face an international facilities tax, which rose 10 cents, to $6.20
from $6.10.
</P>
<P>
   On domestic trips, flight segment taxes, which began life at $1
each in 1997 and are going to reach $3 on Jan. 1, 2002, took a
25-cent step up on Jan. 1, to $2.50 from $2.25. Each segment _ that
is, each flight you get on and off _ generates a tax. Offsetting
this, the domestic ticket tax, which was 10 percent before Oct. 1,
1997, dropped to 7.5 percent last Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Most airports levy a passenger-facility charge of $3, but no
passenger pays more than $12 a ticket, one way or round trip,
however many airports the trip involves.
</P>
<P>
   When there are not enough boxes on the ticket to list all the
taxes, some may be bundled under the code XT. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   London for Tourists Costs Less With a Card &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to London can save on transportation and entrance fees
with a new discount card. The London Pass, which offers unlimited
local travel, tours and entry to more than 40 museums, movie
theaters and art galleries, can be bought for one day ($29, at
$1.60 to the pound), three days ($67) or six days ($118). Children
pay $18, $35 and $61, respectively. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pass holders could save up to $320 on admission fees, if they
were to go to all the attractions, and can travel on subways,
trains and buses in London Transport zones 1 to 6. The pass comes
with a 100-page guidebook and map and $8 of phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sites accepting the pass are the Alexander Fleming
Laboratory Museum, in Paddington, where penicillin was discovered;
Downe House, the home of Charles Darwin in Bromley, Kent, about 10
miles from the center of London; the Guards Museum near Buckingham
Palace, which explores the history of the Guards regiments of the
British Army, and the Saatchi Gallery in Primrose Hill, London.
</P>
<P>
   Trips on Catamaran Cruises _ linking Embankment Pier, the Tower
of London, St. Katherine's and Greenwich on the Thames _ are
included, as are London Bicycle Tours, three different guided city
tours and a walking tour with Stepping Out Walks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pass may be bought by calling (44-208) 5808875 or at
www.londonpass.com and picked up at the Britain Visitor Center, 1
Lower Regent Street, London SW1. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Geometric Abstraction Adorns Paris Museum  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The zigzag of bright blue neon clinging to the facade of the
Musee Zadkine in Paris represents a tiny sliver of infinity for the
French artist Francois Morellet. By assigning geometrical degrees
to the open-ended procession of pi decimals, Morellet, born in
1926, fashions free-wheeling neon arcs that, theoretically, can
ramble forward to the end of time, thanks to the expansiveness of
pi and the indefatigability of modern computers.
</P>
<P>
   Pi, the ratio of the circumference of a circle to its diameter,
is approximately 3.14159265, but the sequence of numbers beyond the
decimal point is believed to be infinite.
</P>
<P>
   Through March 5, Morellet's prints and neon constructions,
including three small-scale allusions to his ``Geometree'' works
that incorporate branches and twigs into witty geometric forms,
mingle with the permanent collection of 20th century sculpture by
Ossip Zadkine (1890-1967) at the secluded garden museum, 100 bis
Rue d'Assas, which was established in the artist's former house and
studio in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   An emblematic figure of Geometric Abstraction, Morellet has
often used sequences of random numbers, notably from the telephone
book, to fuel his imagination. The off-kilter curves of the pi
series, which the artist compares to the pleats of a badly battered
accordion, took shape in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Fragments of the neon Rococo pi series illuminated the facades
of the train station in Tours and the Ecole des Beaux-Arts in
Bourges in 1999. Morellet intends to pursue this ``infinite
progression'' to new sites in Germany and America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Musee Zadkine houses a research library and displays over
100 works from Zadkine's primitive, cubist, classic and abstract
periods. Information: (33-1) 43.26.91.90. Open Tuesday to Sunday 10
a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Admission: $4.80 at 6.2 francs to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Corinne LaBalme &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guides That Help Trace Jewish Roots &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They're not what you'd tuck into your knapsack for picking out
the best restaurants in Warsaw or a place to lay your head in Kiev,
but Miriam Weiner's voluminous guides to archives in Eastern Europe
could be very helpful for anyone trying to trace Jewish family
roots to the vanished world of pre-Holocaust Poland, Ukraine and
Moldova (which incorporates the former Bessarabia).
</P>
<P>
   The encyclopedic volumes _ ``Jewish Roots in Ukraine and
Moldova,'' published last year, and ``Jewish Roots in Poland,''
which came out in 1998 _ offer town-by-town listings of archives,
from birth, death, marriage and divorce records to voter and tax
rolls, draft registrations and property listings, some going back
to the 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   The books, published by the Routes to Roots Foundation and the
Yivo Institute for Jewish Research, are lavishly illustrated with
maps, photos and period postcards, many eerily tranquil
(considering what was to come) and some just eerie. Whose idea was
it, for example, to print up postcards of actual pogrom scenes?
</P>
<P>
   While it is often assumed that records of Jewish life in Eastern
Europe were expunged by the Nazis, much information survives, says
Ms. Weiner, who has spent the better part of a decade in transit
unearthing and mapping the documents, with the help of archivists
and municipal officials in former Soviet republics and Poland.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the town of Priluki in the Chernigov district of
Ukraine, northeast of Kiev, where Ms. Weiner's forebears came from,
was found to be rich in police files, school records, occupation
lists and census forms dating back to 1788 in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in taking their research to the next stage
_ a trip to the localities and their archives _ Ms. Weiner's travel
agency, Routes to Roots in Secaucus, N.J., sets up genealogical
tours for individuals and families. The books cost $50 (Poland) and
$60 (Ukraine and Moldova), plus $8 shipping and handling. To order,
call (800) 742-5403 or visit www.rtrfoundation.org. For more
information about the book: (201) 866-4075.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Blumenthal &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
