<SLUG> BC-CYNET-NASDAQ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYNET TRADING TO BREAK THE COLOR BARRIER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (ART ADV: Photo of Cynet executives will be sent to NYTNS photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
 
By REBECCA MOWBRAY 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When shares of Cynet Inc. begin trading on the Nasdaq exchange
at noon Tuesday the first day of stock trading after Martin Luther
King Jr. Day, it is believed that the fax and Internet company will
become the first African-American-managed publicly traded company
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very, very exciting time. We're entering the new
millennium energized and with great expectations,'' said Chairman
and Chief Executive Vincent W. Beale Sr., who owns 57 percent of
Cynet's stock. ``I would like to see Cynet as the leader in the
Internet messaging arena.''
</P>
<P>
   While the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission does not track
racial data on publicly held companies, Houston Mayor Lee Brown's
office, the Houston Minority Business Council, state Sen. Rodney
Ellis, D-Houston, and others believe that Cynet is the first
African-American public company in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The company will trade under the symbols CYNE and CYNX. However,
Cynet's listing on the Nasdaq is not an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   It's a low-key trading debut that's the culmination of a rare
stock swap known as a recision offering. Vincent Beale and the rest
of his management team _ his brother Sam, a lawyer, and his brother
Bernard, a former investment banker who is chief operating officer
_ are relieved that they got Cynet to this day.
</P>
<P>
   When the Beale brothers took over the company in 1998 after
working there briefly as consultants, Cynet's finances were in
disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Its 1997 revenues were $4.96 million, but it had pretax net
losses of $7.76 million and cash-flow losses of $6.85 million,
according to its prospectus. Its fax transmission business was
losing its luster against the growth of the Internet, and making
matters worse, the company's founder, Ray C. Davis, had issued
approximately 26.8 million shares _ in violation of U.S. Securities
and Exchange Commission procedures _ to a tangle of 855
shareholders in 39 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We inherited them from the founder, who was a very good
promoter,'' Vincent Beale said.
</P>
<P>
   Without being in compliance with SEC regulations, the Beale
brothers couldn't take on institutional investors to raise the
money they needed to transform the business. They had no choice but
to make their shareholders legal through an obscure SEC stock
buyback procedure called a recision offering. Last fall, Cynet gave
the owners of $16.5 million worth of shares the option to cash out.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules of a recision offering, the Beale brothers
couldn't campaign to keep shareholders on board, so they held
shareholder information sessions around the country, including two
in Houston, to try to answer questions candidly and show that there
were three new trustworthy faces at the helm of the company.
</P>
<P>
   When the recision offering was completed Dec. 6, Cynet bought
back $5.5 million in shares and officially became a publicly held
company, Sam Beale said.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the year, the Beales knew that they would need money to
fund the recision offering, so they approached Enron Corp.'s
Houston Economic Opportunity Fund, which took a 6 percent ownership
stake in Cynet.
</P>
<P>
   Because no investment bank was interested in underwriting the
recision offering, Enron also became the underwriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in the business of underwriting securities. Instead
of just selling us equity, the company needed us to act as
underwriters,'' said Mark Lay, director of the Enron fund.
``Because of Vincent's focus on getting that done, they were able
to mitigate a very large risk issue that was overhanging the
company.''
</P>
<P>
   After a breather over the holidays, Tuesday's trading represents
Cynet's official entry into the open marketplace, not a
fund-raising effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's stock that's already in the hands of shareholders. We
did not raise any new money in this offering. Our goal is to raise
that new money in a second offering in 2000,'' Sam Beale said.
</P>
<P>
   Until Cynet can make that second offering, it will continue to
be bound &UR;  &LR; by the strings of the recision offering.
</P>
<P>
   While other companies hire an investment company as a ``market
maker'' to promote the stock to other brokers when the company
enters the market, under the SEC rules, market maker Harris Webb &AMP;
Garrison can't make a pitch for Cynet.
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   ``We are precluded from doing anything that is of a promotional
nature for this company. We are just a facilitator in this
instance,'' said compliance administrator Cary McDonald.
</P>
<P>
   It's the first time Harris Webb &AMP; Garrison has been a silent
market maker, McDonald added.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when Internet companies make such a splash on their
first day of trading, entering the stock market without a
traditional underwriter and without a market maker could put Cynet
at a disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be extremely unusual. Often it's a sign of a very
small company or one with a checkered background,'' said Sanders,
Morris Mundy Chairman George Ball, who was asked to comment on what
this general set of circumstances might mean. ``Lacking a
third-party sponsor, however, is a definite detriment in the
money-raising process.''
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   However, the Beales, who came to Cynet as advisers and ended up
buying the company when founder Ray C. Davis got sick, are unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   They say they hope to raise as much as $150 million in a public
offering later this year to fund Cynet's transition from fax
messaging to business-to-business Internet services, wireless
technology and database services, and that Cynet will gobble up
other companies to muscle its way into the Internet applications
arena.
</P>
<P>
   Cynet's main business always has been faxing. Customers ranging
from mom-and-pop companies to Fortune 500 clients use Cynet's fax
broadcasting network to keep costs down. They also use a messaging
software at Cynet that enables them to type fax numbers, e-mail
addresses and Telex numbers in the same line of a message to reach
clients at different levels of technology.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Cynet has begun selling its line of wireless
modems, which will begin appearing in Round Rock, Texas-based Dell
Computer's small &UR; - &LR; business catalog in February. It also has
launched Cynet Interactive, a division that builds Web sites to
allow companies to run business-application software directly from
the Internet, Bernard Beale said.
</P>
<P>
   And, in the hands of the Beales, Cynet's finances appear to be
turning the corner. Revenues nearly doubled to $8.95 million in
1998, while its operating losses were nearly cut in half to $4.23
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to see Cynet as a hypergrowth company in a hypergrowth
time,'' Vincent Beale said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
