<SLUG> BC-RIO-FERTILITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE IS EASIER IN BRAZIL AS FAMILY SIZE SHRINKS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENALIA MORENO 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Even by Brazilian standards, Musa
Cipriano comes from a big family.
</P>
<P>
   In her home state of Minas Gerais, her farmer father and mother,
a part-time cook, struggled to support Cipriano and her 10 brothers
and sisters. Cipriano's grandmother bore even more children _ 19.
</P>
<P>
   Cipriano moved to Rio de Janeiro seeking a better life. She did
two things to ensure she reached that goal: She found a job as a
hotel cook, and she made sure she had only one child.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at age 45, she says her life is 10 times better than that
of her parents. Cipriano made that optimistic pronouncement as she
watched her 11-year-old daughter, Ana Musa, graduate from the
fourth grade, the highest grade Cipriano reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Rio, everyone understands that if you have more kids,
then it's more difficult,'' said Cipriano, who earns the equivalent
of $330 a month. ``If you have more than one or two kids, then
they're going to be hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   That realization by millions of Brazilian matriarchs translated
into a decline of more than 50 percent in the nation's fertility
rate over the last three decades. A similar trend took more than a
century in developed countries, such as the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Until the 1970s, Brazilian women gave birth to an average of six
children. This year, demographers predict that Brazilian women will
bear an average of 2.2 children, nearly balancing the country's
birth and death rate.
</P>
<P>
   That sudden drop concerns Brazilian demographers, who fear that
Brazil's aging population will not be able to support the nation's
costly social security system.
</P>
<P>
   But, overall, a declining birth rate is good news for this Third
World nation seeking First World status.
</P>
<P>
   For Cipriano, a small family meant she could save money for Ana
Musa's college education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm living and saving so she can keep being educated,''
Cipriano said, beaming proudly. ``That's my function.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the ability to save money and own a few of life's
luxuries, such as a television and kitchen appliances, Cipriano can
only afford a home in the CantaGalo favela, one of more than 500
slums. She and her daughter live in one of the shacks that are
stacked like various sizes of shoe boxes, awkwardly perched on the
sides of mountains in Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   As in many favelas, in CantaGalo, streams of sewage drip down
the streets. Few homes have electricity. Brazil's once-exploding
population meant that the government could not keep up with
infrastructure demands. Today, 32 percent of homes do not have
telephone lines, and 21 percent do not have sewage service.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller families mean that the Brazilian government can invest
more in such basics as sewers and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you continue to have six children, you can't develop in
the face of that,'' said Carl Haub, a demographer for the
Population Reference Bureau in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller families also means a lower unemployment rate, now at
7.3 percent, and more government funds for health care and
education.
</P>
<P>
   For U.S. manufacturers, a lower fertility rate means that
Brazil's 164 million residents can afford to buy more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brazil is emerging as the most important market in Latin
America, even more so than Mexico,'' said Haub of the nonprofit
think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's birth rate began to decline in the 1970s as birth
control became more widespread, women began to enter the work force
with a fury, and more residents moved to the cities. Urban living
meant that families did not need as many children to help on farms.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the decline in fertility occurred with no
encouragement from the government. This is different from Mexico,
where a barrage of public service announcements urged couples to
take control of their own economic situation by having fewer
children. There, the fertility rate dropped from seven children per
woman in 1965 to an average of 2.4 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fertility declined without any kind of public policy on family
planning,'' said Esther Hamburger, a Sao Paulo anthropologist.
``There was not an organized effort; that's why it was a
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Government may have stayed out of Brazilian bedrooms, but
television did not.
</P>
<P>
   Every weeknight, most of this nation is glued to its TV sets,
watching the latest one-hour telenovela, a soap opera that's often
far more glamorous than any ``Dallas'' episode. If there's no
important soccer match on, most bars and restaurants set their
dials to the latest telenovela.
</P>
<P>
   In telenovelas, most young couples have no children. Older
couples have no more than three children, and often they live in
luxurious homes or ranches.
</P>
<P>
   Many Brazilians want to emulate the lifestyle they see in these
dramas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role that television plays in the Brazilian economy is
higher than the role that it plays in other countries,'' said
Hamburger, who studied the effects of telenovelas on family size.
``Television was very important in the development of the consumer
market.''
</P>
<P>
   The trend was encouraged during the 1970s, when retailers began
advertising payment plans for everything from TV sets to clothing.
That gave the poor the opportunity to become consumers. Desperate
to appear connected to current events and a part of a society, they
sacrificed other household goods to buy televisions and radios.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reflects the desire to be tuned,'' Hamburger said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 87 percent of households have a TV set while 32 percent
have a washing machine and 82 percent of homes have a refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Single mother Deborah dos Santos lives in a rundown mansion,
abandoned when the poor took over this neighborhood to create
CantaGalo. Her home, a room she shares with nearly a dozen family
members, is simply decorated and has a tiny stove and two single
beds. In the corner is an older TV set, carefully protected by a
dust cover.
</P>
<P>
   She has an 8-month-old son, Jefferson, whose father is a street
kid with no job and no home. She once lived with her boyfriend on
the streets, but since Jefferson was born, she's moved home with
her mother and found a job in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Dos Santos, who earns the equivalent of $50 a month as a
computer teacher, said more children means a tougher life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life isn't that great right now,'' said dos Santos, 16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
