<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT &LR;      01-17 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN HOUSE FOR NEW ZEALAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Russell Coutts and his crew were
invincible in the last America's Cup in 1995, and now they will
soon get the pleasure of defending the cup on home water. But they
can be beaten.
</P>
<P>
   It happened here on the Hauraki Gulf on Monday afternoon. With
Coutts at the helm and the gray-haired tactician Brad Butterworth
scheming by his side, the crew on NZL-57 was beaten convincingly to
the first mark and then outsailed in the light winds for the rest
of the race, trailing by nearly two minutes at the second windward
mark.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday's result won't be all that encouraging to the two
remaining challengers, America One and Prada, whose speedy spy
boats observed it all from the 200-meter legal distance. It won't
be encouraging because the boat that routed NZL-57 was NZL-60, the
newest of the two black yachts that Team New Zealand has built for
this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was only a practice day, like the day before it and so
many days, perhaps too many, before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit frustrating actually,'' said Grant Loretz, a crew
member. ``We're itching to get out there and have a go, but our
turn is obviously going to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Sport has no shortage of long waits: four years between
Olympics, four years between soccer World Cups. But it has been
nearly five years since the last America's Cup, and while the
challengers for sport's oldest major trophy have been dueling under
genuine pressure for genuine points since October, Team New Zealand
has been conducting dress rehearsals and attempting to avoid the
pitfall of learning its lines so well that it no longer takes much
pleasure in saying them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this phase is the hardest thing I've had to do,'' said
Butterworth, a 40-year-old Aucklander, who was also the tactician
for Black Magic in 1995. ``We understood two years ago that we were
going to have to be a lot better than last time if we wanted to
defend, and so we've tuned up, and we've been working our skills
for a long time now.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday was also a day for working on communication skills, which
explains why Butterworth made his comments while NZL-57 was still
under sail and still on the gulf. For the first time since the
challenger series began, a small group of foreign journalists had
been invited on board one of New Zealand's new yachts, and as
trimmers yanked at their sheets and Coutts leaned and occasionally
yawned on his helm, reporters from France, Japan, China, Australia
and the United States attempted to interject without interfering as
the boat headed back to the harbor after the one-sided ersatz race.
</P>
<P>
   It did not have to be this way, of course. There could have been
defender trials, just as there have been for every cup in recent
history. But the syndicate head, Peter Blake, and his advisers
decided that New Zealand, with its 3.5 million people, was too
small to support rival syndicates and that splitting up the limited
sponsorship dollars and limited know-how would only weaken the
cause. The price to pay for solid financing, however, is the wait,
made all the longer by the challengers' decision not to practice
with them. (The only exception was Nippon Challenge, which did so
once in December.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always going to be difficult being the single defender,
but we've known that since the beginning, so I can't say it's a
surprise,'' said Coutts, the skipper and former Olympic gold
medalist. ``We've had some great races out here among our two
boats. We had one last week with four lead changes.''
</P>
<P>
   This had been billed as a day on the water with Team New
Zealand, but in truth, it was more a day on the water. Journalists
were allowed on board as the boats were towed from the Viaduct
Basin to the racecourse in the late morning and then again after
the race had been decided. In between, they followed the progress
of NZL-57 and NZL-60 from a chase boat, although _ this being the
America's Cup _ not all of their progress was visible. Shortly
before the races began, Coutts, concerned about security leaks,
asked for the chase boat and its occupants to leave the area for
about an hour. The visitors/inquisitors were not invited back until
after the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some general things we wanted to do that we'd
rather keep to ourselves,'' Butterworth said. ``Putting them on the
front page would not help our cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the surveillance tools at their would-be rivals'
disposal, despite the close quarters along syndicate row in the
Viaduct Basin, there are still secrets to be kept and technological
edges to be maintained. In 1995, when New Zealand swept Dennis
Conner and his American crew to win the cup by 5-0, its boat was
undeniably superior, partly because of an innovative rig.
</P>
<P>
   New Zealand has continued innovating in that area: the mast used
on NZL-57 Monday has holes built into it that allow some of the
diagonal supporting cables to pass through it. It allows the Kiwis
to use three spreaders instead of four, presumably reducing wind
drag and pressure on the mast. But that is no longer a secret. Nor
is the fact that both new boats are significantly faster than their
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be lucky to win a race in the old boat against these,''
Coutts said. ``Very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Coutts and Blake maintain that they have yet to decide which
yacht will be used in the cup match. They will declare both on
Thursday, the same day America One and Prada must declare which
boats they will use in the challenger finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually haven't decided on all the bits,'' Butterworth
said. ``This boat has a few bits that are pretty nice. So does the
other one. We'll have to swap them around, and get all the good
bits on one boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Coutts said the final decision won't be made until early
February. The cup is scheduled to begin Feb. 19. That is a
Saturday, and the spectator fleet is expected to number about
4,000, which should make for a much livelier scene than Monday's,
as only a handful of motorboats were in the immediate vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   The sailors, most of whom have known each other since they were
teen-agers, have been waiting for months. Their public has, too,
and the summer days when a black boat is guaranteed of victory on
the gulf are definitely, thankfully numbered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
