<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER ISSUES IMPEDE MIDEAST PEACE EFFORTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Israeli and Syrian leaders on Monday indefinitely
postponed their next round of talks, marking a setback to President
Clinton's efforts to broker a peace deal between the Middle Eastern
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Barak announced the delay in Jerusalem, two days before he was
planning to meet Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa for a
second set of negotiations in Shepherdstown, W.Va., this month.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came amid renewed terrorism in Israel and
opposition to ceding any of the Golan Heights, the strategic
plateau that Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Middle East
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it isn't comfortable for the Syrians to come now, and they
need some time, they should take the time,'' Barak said. ``We will
come when there are discussions, and the delay, if in fact it is
agreed on, does not bother us.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. diplomats reportedly telephoned Barak and al-Sharaa in an
effort to persuade them to keep the talks on track. The Israeli and
the Syrian agreed to send subordinates to Washington to discuss
relatively minor issues.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, before the postponement was announced,
Clinton expressed cautious optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is, I'm convinced they both still want to do
it,'' Clinton said of Barak and al-Sharaa. ``And they're not as far
apart as they might be, not as far apart as they have been. So
that's the good news.''
</P>
<P>
   Their major sticking point seemed to be the disposition of the
Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Israeli press published a U.S.-prepared ``working
document'' expressing Israel's and Syria's negotiating positions.
It states that Israel wants security guarantees from Syria before
beginning any discussion of a withdrawal from the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, the document says, wants Israel to agree to return the
land all the way to the Sea of Galilee, a source of water for
Israel, before the talks progress to other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The document also reportedly includes Syrian concessions to
discuss security and political ties, but it does not include an
Israeli commitment to discuss Syria's border demands, causing the
Syrian negotiators considerable embarrassment at home.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in Israel said they suspect that the Syrians have been
fuming since the document's publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Syrians are saying, `We gave in during the previous round
of negotiations. Now we want to get back to the issue of borders,'
'' said Reuven Hazan, a political analyst at Jerusalem's Hebrew
University.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls in Israel suggest that a majority believe that
peace with Syria will mean giving up the Golan Heights. Barak,
however, has refused to say whether, or how much, of the territory
he is willing to relinquish.
</P>
<P>
   The ``working document'' included demands by the Israeli side
that the Golan settlers remain there after a peace deal is reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak won't give it to them, and it actually looks good for
him,'' said Hazan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody on the left-wing saying, `Oh just give the
Syrians what they want,' '' he said. ``Because Barak is acting
powerfully, those on the right aren't able to criticize him.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's chief rabbis indirectly challenged Barak on Monday when
they proclaimed that the Golan Heights is part of the biblical land
of Israel. The influential Chief Rabbinical Council, however, did
not say that Jewish law prohibits Israel from returning the land
for peace.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling could make it more difficult for Barak to sell any
peace agreement with Syria that includes giving up the Golan
Heights. The rabbis' position could convince many of the country's
politically powerful, conservative Orthodox Jews, who make up 25
percent the population, to oppose any surrender of the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   In the Israeli coastal town of Hadera, a small bomb hidden in a
garbage can exploded, injuring 21 people. Israeli police said they
suspected Islamic extremists carried out the attack to derail the
peace process. But Hamas, a Palestinian organization responsible
for past bombings, denied involvement in the blast. Instead, a
small group in Lebanon called Omar Mukhtar claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said that Israel was ``determined to act with all its
might to crush terrorism,'' but he did not threaten to halt the
peace talks with the Syrians or the separate track with the
Palestinians. A similar bombing occurred in the nearby town of
Netanya in November, wounding 33 people.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Horan contributed to this story from Amman, Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
