<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-LOBBYING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GIFT GAMES IN ALBANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Jan. 18:
</P>
<P>
   Curiously missing from Gov. George Pataki's recent State of the
State Message were any proposals to elevate New York's dismal
standards of government ethics. The governor may be under the
impression that he fulfilled his duty on ethics when he consummated
a deal with the state Legislature late last month to renew the
state's expiring lobbying law.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that deal, concocted behind closed doors as New Yorkers were
distracted by the holidays, was an act of bipartisan cynicism. Its
purpose was to leave undisturbed the discredited system of
legalized bribery that permits lawmakers to accept fancy meals,
choice sports tickets and other personal financial favors from
lobbyists seeking to gain influence over public policy.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is not alone to blame for this travesty. The Assembly
speaker, Sheldon Silver, a Democrat, has also been unmoved and
unchastened by the current lobbying scandal involving widespread
legislative gift-giving by Philip Morris, the tobacco giant. Over
the objection of a small group of reformers led by Assemblyman
Alexander Grannis of Manhattan, Silver refused to go along with a
gift ban after the Senate majority leader, Joseph Bruno, a
Republican, had boldly persuaded his chamber to pass a bill that
included several useful restrictions on gifts. Silver wanted to
keep the Knicks and Rangers tickets flowing, so Pataki dropped his
support for gift reform in exchange for Silver's agreement to drop
another reform that Pataki did not like. The net result was a
halfhearted ethics overhaul that strengthened and expanded the
reach of the state's disclosure rules but did not fundamentally
threaten Albany's pervasive culture of influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's recent decision to decline most gifts from
lobbyists voluntarily is praiseworthy, but no substitute for
mandatory curbs. Meanwhile, Silver has sought to divert attention
from his role in this mess by reviving some old if worthy proposals
for campaign finance reform. It will not work. Gift-giving in the
Legislature is a festering scandal that Silver, the governor and
members of the Legislature must promptly address.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
