<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-SAMSONITE-MAKEOVER-AR     01-17 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMSONITE-MAKEOVER-ART-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GADGETY TRAVEL WEAR THAT 007 WOULD LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By GINIA BELLAFANTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In March, when six Libyan officials were tried in Paris for
ordering the bombing of a French plane a decade earlier, the
evidence against them included a Samsonite suitcase armed with
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, a deposition sworn in Mexico described a scene
in which cocaine traffickers transported $60 million in bribe money
in Samsonite luggage.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few months ago, Samsonite _ the favorite suitcase for
much of the world _ was more likely to be named in court documents
about international miscreants than in the pages of international
fashion magazines.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrival of the British designer Neil Barrett, 34, at the
company about a year ago has done much to refurbish Samsonite's
image as something other than a maker of drab luggage for
Floridians over 63, along with the occasional felon.
</P>
<P>
   The suitcase purveyor has gained such cachet that last week
Francois Pinault, the French financier bent on assembling a
luxury-goods empire, became Samsonite's largest shareholder,
acquiring 30 percent through a holding company.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett introduced his first travel wear for the company early
last year. It has brought Samsonite $10 million in sales, said
Beppi Fremder, president of Samsonite in Italy, the division of the
company responsible for fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes _ for men, women and children _ are meant to perform
sleight of hand. One jacket adjusts to the wearer's body
temperature, so that the wearer would theoretically be as
comfortable in it in Cleveland as in Phoenix. Other jackets have
travel pillows or reading lamps that pop out of the collars.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, a hiking coat comes with a walking stick
incongruously attached (in case the hiker falls down and is
injured), along with a flask inside a pocket (in case he wants to
numb the pain with some Maker's Mark). Some pants have zip-off legs
to turn them into shorts.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes perform almost every subsidiary function short of
turning into cappuccino makers, and the style seems to be
influencing others. When Naoki Takizawa showed his Issey Miyake
menswear collection in Milan this month, he showed sweaters that
had hoods and capes stealthily tucked into them, and jackets with
all sorts of gadget holders.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's first collection, for fall 1999, was picked up by
Louis Boston, Saks Fifth Avenue and Jeffrey in New York. Jeffrey
Kalinsky, owner of Jeffrey, said that Samsonite clothes have sold
better than anything else in his store. ``We didn't have a piece to
mark down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers like Fred Segal in Los Angeles, Neiman Marcus and
Bergdorf Goodman are carrying the line for spring. ``It's kind of
gimmicky,'' James Aguiar, Bergdorf's fashion director,
acknowledged. ``But it's gimmicky without being stupid.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Barrett's pedigree as a designer is akin to that of a banker who
has hurdled Harvard, Stanford Business School and Goldman, Sachs.
He studied at Central St. Martin's College of Art and Design in
London and then earned a master's degree at the Royal College of
Art before landing jobs at Gucci and Prada.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s he wrote Prada's chief executive, Patrizio
Bertelli, suggesting the company start a menswear division and
offering his services. Months went by, but Barrett was eventually
granted a brief meeting with Bertelli (``he flips through your work
so quickly,'' Barrett said) and was unexpectedly offered the job of
overseeing menswear design, which he held until 1998.
</P>
<P>
   His training at Gucci and Prada gave him, he said, ``a vision of
reality.'' He designs his Samsonite line aboard planes and trains
between London, Milan and Florence. The idea for his jacket cum
reading lamp was born when he was in the passenger seat of a car,
trying to do some work. The interior light didn't switch on. ``In
the car is when you want to make your phone calls,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Samsonite line, Barrett is making a name for
himself with his own menswear, also functional. He started, he
said, because ``I particularly dislike feminine clothes for men,''
a style that has dominated on the runways.
</P>
<P>
   When he offered his first collection last year, 100 stores
worldwide chose to carry it. Last week in Florence, Italy, he
showed his first signature line on a runway, with unfussy looks for
women, too, including conservative leather skirts and jackets.
</P>
<P>
   There were 1,000 people in the audience. After a few days of
watching men parade down some Milan runways in skirts, they no
doubt were relieved to be there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
