<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8612 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-RAMS-BUCS-HNS &LR;      01-17 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAMS-BUCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
This past weekend, the NFC's No. 1 defense shut down the NFL's
second-best offense. Now, that defense will be facing the very
best.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay Buccaneers, whose defense was ranked third in the
league in 1999, edged Washington 14-13 on Saturday. The victory
earned them an NFC Championship Game trip to St. Louis, where
they'll take on the explosive Rams, who waxed Minnesota on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tampa Bay has a great defense, so I don't think it will be a
circus act like it was today,'' Vikings linebacker Dwayne Rudd said
after his team's 49-37 loss. ``St. Louis may have a hard time with
(Tampa's) front four. But the thing about St. Louis is they score
points. I don't know if Tampa Bay will be able to score with St.
Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buccaneers probably aren't going to score 37 points like the
Vikings did. More important, they're not going to score 50, which
is what it would have taken Sunday to beat St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not,'' Bucs coach Tony Dungy said, ``win an 80-point
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs, who have held eight opponents to 10 or fewer points,
figure the only way to contain St. Louis will be to force mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to create turnovers, get sacks and stop the running
game,'' Bucs defensive end Steve White said. ``That's the nature of
our team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams did not play mistake-free football Sunday; they simply
overcame their miscues. Quarterback Kurt Warner threw an
interception and lost a fumble in the first half, with the Vikings
eventually scoring off both gifts. Not that it mattered.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams scored in a variety of ways Sunday. There was a 77-yard
scoring strike from Warner to Isaac Bruce on St. Louis' first play.
There was a screen to Marshall Faulk, who cut inside and covered 41
yards to the goal line. There was a 95-yard kickoff return by Tony
Horne to open the second half, followed by four more touchdown
drives, three that ended with catches by different players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done that all year long, trying to make them (opponents)
cover everybody,'' Warner said. ``You can't do it all game.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams in the NFC title game will be led by first-year
starting quarterbacks. Warner proved he deserved his Most Valuable
Player trophy with his five-touchdown performance against
Minnesota. But Bucs rookie quarterback Shaun King, who took over in
the 11th week of the season, has been another good story.
</P>
<P>
   King led his team to a 5-1 mark down the stretch, engineering
four second-half comebacks en route to the playoffs. He did it
again Saturday after the Bucs found themselves trailing 13-0 in the
third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw an NFL quarterback,'' Redskins cornerback Darrell Green
said after the game. ``I didn't see a rookie.''
</P>
<P>
   Though some of these players were mere infants at the time, the
city of Tampa would like to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the
last Bucs-Rams NFC Championship Game by reversing the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Rams won that game, stealing it from the Bucs
9-0 in Tampa. Until now, neither team had made it this far since.
</P>
<P>
   ``People really tend to believe in the NFC that you've got to
score a lot of points to win,'' White said. ``We think if you've
got a great defense, a good running attack and make plays in the
passing game when you can, you'll win the majority of your games.
So far, we have. And we're going to keep the same game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   But the high-powered Rams, who averaged 400.8 yards per game in
the regular season, will certainly be the toughest test thus far
for the Bucs, who gave up an average of 267.5 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring on the best to play the best,'' Tampa Bay defensive
tackle Warren Sapp said. ``If you want to go to the Super Bowl _
the greatest show on earth _ then you've got to figure on going
through the biggest challenge. Washington was the second-best
offense, and the only touchdown they scored was on a kickoff
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that St. Louis' offense has been the big story all
year. Maybe it figures our defense meets them at center stage.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question now is whether that defense will remain
standing for an encore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Warner said. ``I haven't seen a defense
that has done it yet. People are going to have to prove it to me
for me to believe it.''
</P>
<P>
