<HEADER>
A8613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-910     01-17 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-910(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRYSTAL JEANS ADD REALISM TO COUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It is not by chance that high fashion causes mere
mortals to grin with fright. Here is John Galliano, the chief
designer of Dior, in his studio explaining how his spring haute
couture collection was inspired by the tramp balls that aristocrats
used to throw for themselves in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Galliano has on a drab knit cap, and he is pointing to some old
photographs of French tramps, saying how the swells of Paris were
so taken with this naive style that they'd even go to their
hairdressers to get those elaborate bum hairdos.
</P>
<P>
   All very true. Yet go into one of the English bookstores here
and try to find a reference to the subject, even from a writer as
well known as Janet Flanner, and the young saleswoman will give you
a fey-bored look and say, ``Is that with one `n' or two?''
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't have a clue about the practice of socialites'
wrapping themselves up like mackerels in newspaper and running
around in the din of Paris, and what is more, she doesn't care. For
high fashion to have meaning, it must have roots, yet they can't be
so twisted or obscure as to have absolutely no connection to the
present.
</P>
<P>
   That's been the trouble with the spring 2000 couture shows, now
in their third day. Designers have been too besotted with the past,
and worse still with their own past, as Valentino was on Sunday
when he trawled back over 40 years of jet-set glamour, right down
to the blue eye shadow and petrified-looking hairdos that recalled
Baby Jane Holzer, circa 1963.
</P>
<P>
   So there have been too many spooks and not enough ghost busters.
The one brilliant exception was Jean Paul Gaultier. His collection
on Sunday, in the grand house in the Passy section that once
belonged to Marie-Laure de Noailles, who knew Cocteau, Dali,
Picasso _ well, practically everyone who mattered in Paris before
and after World War II _ combined Parisian elegance with Indian
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   It's interesting that he chose a house with so many associations
to the life of Paris in the 20th century. Yet he laid down an
Indian orange carpet scattered with flowers, and he covered the
chandeliers with gauze because, as he said, ``It's important to
remember that while I love the past, I am not from that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaultier did some ingenious things, like mixing old fabrics with
current materials like python and choosing pale shades of lavender
and green that looked as if they had been faded in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   The show opened with his saucy version of the trench-coat dress,
now opened in the back, followed by sharply cut navy or
cream-colored jackets over soft skirts or pants. A cream
double-breasted jacket, its sleeves pushed up to reveal a smoky
brown chiffon blouse, closed tightly over a pleated green polka-dot
skirt, with sheer yellow leggings underneath.
</P>
<P>
   There were crisp white shirts with slim, nude skirts embroidered
in orange and gold, and a vest made of mother-of-pearl paillettes,
and worn with a long slinky gray skirt and a pale lilac chiffon
blouse.
</P>
<P>
   The models wore simple turbans, usually in bright colors, and
there was no music, only a female voice calling out the number and
name of each style: ``Baroda,'' ``Tea Time,'' ``Indian Gypsy.''
</P>
<P>
   The clothes were light and free of gimmicks, and here and there
were touches of Gaultier's familiar wit: a parade float of a ball
gown made from densely packed tulle in a jungle camouflage pattern
and a pair of jeans embroidered from the pockets down in clear
crystals to look destroyed. Every bit of fraying was encrusted with
beads, taking the idea of couture jeans _ indeed, couture itself _
to a different level.
</P>
<P>
   This was Gaultier's strongest collection since he took on haute
couture a couple of years ago, and it's no wonder he is attracting
the interest of more established couture clients like Mouna Ayoub
and Deeda Blair. ``For me, the only reason to do couture is to
dress women, not to make something abstract,'' he said. His
business has grown from six clients to more than 35, and he now
employs 40 people in his atelier.
</P>
<P>
   As for Galliano's down-and-out collection of oversize tramp
pants and urchin skirts artfully printed with the fashion pages of
The International Herald Tribune _ which made the newspaper's
fashion editor, Suzy Menkes, beam in the front row _ the English
designer continued with the deconstructed theme of his last couture
and ready-to-wear shows.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, the ideas came together more convincingly.
Or maybe Galliano's impudence is growing on his audience.
</P>
<P>
   With Madonna's new version of ``American Pie'' in the
background, he sent out frayed beauties with Charlie Chaplin eyes
and hobo trinkets (including airline-size bottles of Scotch)
dangling from their waists.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes _ those impeccably tailored Dior jackets in light
gray, those signature underpinnings _ were twisted back to front
and inside out, so the labels and linings were all exposed. It was
much as if some poor Doolittle of the streets had nosed through the
duke of Windsor's waste bin and decked himself out like a gent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's hard to imagine a couture client shelling out
$25,000 for a dress just so she can look like a bum. But as
Galliano admitted in his studio a few days before the show, ``I'm
not all that interested in the old Dior clients.'' What Galliano is
really attempting to do by showing clothes in such a seemingly
deranged manner is to deconstruct the myth of Dior. The question is
whether his approach has enough followers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Donatella Versace sent out a simple but solid
collection of ultra-sexy evening looks in those vibrant hues of
pink and turquoise that little girls seem to love the moment they
first set eyes on Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   It was a skin-on-skin collection, with snake and suede worked
close to the body. Organdy was pieced together in swirls of black
and pale green, while a black snake town coat looked demure enough
from the front, but in the back was cut out in flower petals on
tulle.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Ungaro's inspiration was Rimbaud, and while that
immediately suggests something tortured, the clothes were light and
beautiful _ loose-fitting jackets embroidered with discreet (for
Ungaro) touches of stones, and intensely colored skirts of chiffon
graduating toward the hem in smokier hues.
</P>
<P>
   Valentino's retrospective collection, as someone said, left
nothing but an old impression _ which was uncharacteristic of him,
given that his last two couture collections were right on the
money.
</P>
<P>
   In a season elevated by Gaultier's light hand and the
consideration he so obviously gives to making an old tradition say
something new, Alexander McQueen's collection for Givenchy seemed
like heavy weather.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there were great moments, like a glacier-white coat plucked
with tiny feathers and a precisely cut gray coat over a silvery
dress with a gently draped neckline. But many of the hard-edged
shapes looked too familiar, advancing little, and McQueen's thick
coating of white feathers on an otherwise simple suit looked
morbid, as if a vulture had taken roost.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of spooks, McQueen opened his show with a model
wearing only a pair of men's underpants _ presumably meant to have
belonged to her departed mate _ and being slowly dressed from a
steamer trunk by an elderly valet in tails who bore an uncanny
resemblance to Hubert de Givenchy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2250EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
