u a BC-LONDON-HEROINE-NYT     01-17 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-HEROINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISITOR FROM THE COLONIES IS LONDON'S BRAVE `MUM OF 3'
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Saturday afternoon, while vacationing in London, the Webster
family of 10 Downing Place in Livingston, N.J., posed by the prime
minister's residence for a snapshot: a memento of their visit to 10
Downing Street.
</P>
<P>
   But the afternoon turned out to be more memorable than they
could have imagined: London newspapers and television have been
calling Ursula Webster a ``Heroine Mum-of-Three'' after she pushed
one of her sons out of the way of a speeding car, which hit her and
severely fractured one of her legs.
</P>
<P>
   The family flew back to New Jersey on Sunday, but not before
Prime Minister Tony Blair invited them to drop by for tea the next
time they are in town.
</P>
<P>
   But first Mrs. Webster, 39, must recuperate from the injuries
that put her on Britain's front pages.
</P>
<P>
   After a bobby took their picture at 10 Downing, the Websters
were on their way through the high iron gate, when an
out-of-control car barreled straight at them and plowed into the
gate. Mrs. Webster shoved Andrew, 8, out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her main concern was the boys,'' said her husband, David, at
the St. Barnabas Medical Center in Livingston, where Mrs. Webster
was having surgery Monday on her broken femur and tibia.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was lying on the ground, in excruciating pain, and she
wanted to know where the kids were,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew was bruised a bit, Webster said, and so was his brother,
Alex, 6, when a side mirror struck his head. Webster and the
youngest son, Peter, 3, were not hurt.
</P>
<P>
   An ambulance took Mrs. Webster to a London hospital, where
doctors treated her. The rest of the family followed in a van.
</P>
<P>
   For her operation, Mrs. Webster chose to return to New Jersey,
where she could receive follow-up treatment, her husband said.
</P>
<P>
   The London police arrested the driver of the car, Stephen
Bonnett, 26, an engineer from Chelmsford, east of London, who was
charged with causing grievous bodily harm and dangerous driving,
the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous articles in London newspapers praised the
``mother-of-three who braved death to push her children to
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys were ``pretty brave, and also in shock,'' their father
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty scary, to realize you could lose your wife and
children in an instant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Had the iron gate been shut, Mrs. Webster and Andrew would
almost certainly have been unable to get out of the car's path, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Webster, a banker, said the family had visited London several
times.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Webster has recovered, he said, they might well accept
Blair's invitation to tour 10 Downing Street from the inside, out
of the range of runaway cars, not to mention news photographers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
