<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-JOKES-1STLD-WR     01-17 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-JOKES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H-E-R-E'-S JOHNNY: MCCAIN LEAVES 'EM LAUGHING ON THE CAMPAIGN
TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: CORRECTS dateline to Hopkinton, sted Hamilton.) 
(nk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOPKINTON, N.H. _ Heard the one about the trees chasing the
dogs? If you were at Sen. John McCain's recent town hall meeting in
Merrimack, you would have. Twice.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little weather joke McCain likes to tell. So little water
in Arizona, the trees chase the dogs. Ba-dum-bum.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty amusing the first time, and it typically gets a chuckle
when the Republican presidential candidate uses it in his opening
remarks on the campaign trail. But even his staff was silent when
McCain recently offered the line a second time to the same
audience. Oops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed that as soon as I said it,'' a sheepish McCain said
later. ``They didn't laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Most candidates have a stump speech. McCain, who favors endless
question-and-answer sessions with the public and the press, has
more of a stand-up routine. His mix of dry sarcasm, terrific timing
and a sweet rasp of a voice is reminiscent of Johnny Carson (they
also have similar hair). He can be funny off the cuff, but the
cuffs are a little worn during long days riding around New
Hampshire in a campaign bus. So he relies on some old standbys:
</P>
<P>
   On who will play him in the movie version of his book, ``Faith
of My Fathers,'' a memoir of three generations of McCain military
men: ``I want Tom Cruise; my kids want Danny DeVito.''
</P>
<P>
   On the book, which many voters bring for him to autograph: ``I'm
not here to hype my book. I would never do that. $24.95, Random
House. It's been four months on the best-seller list, available on
Amazon.com. But I wouldn't hype it.''
</P>
<P>
   On campaign-finance abuses in the 1996 campaign: ``They were
renting out the Lincoln bedroom as though it were a Motel 6. Bill
Clinton was the bellhop.''
</P>
<P>
   On politicians taking credit for things they did not do: ``The
vice president invented the Internet. I invented television.''
</P>
<P>
   On young voters' cynicism about government: ``There's a study
out that says more young people believe Elvis is alive than believe
they'll ever get a Social Security check.''
</P>
<P>
   On early polls in New Hampshire: ``We were at 3 percent. The
margin of error was 5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the story of 101-year-old Neil Tillotson of
Dixville Notch, who came up with the idea of having his northern
hamlet be the first to count its ballots in this ``first in the
nation'' primary, making the burg a must-stop on every presidential
candidate's tour.
</P>
<P>
   Seems McCain, in his self-described desperation for votes _
including all 29 in Dixville Notch _ has visited with Tillotson not
once but twice this campaign season. Asked who his favorite
Republican was, out of all the candidates he had met, the old man
replied, ``Theodore Roosevelt.'' Ba-dum-bum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think humor is really important,'' McCain said. ``I've
thought it was important all my life. I think it's important in
these kind of, what sometimes get to be high-pressure situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Like when he was a prisoner of war in North Vietnam, tapping out
jokes about Hanoi Hannah, a piece of radio propaganda, in code
through the cell walls. And now in the heat of the presidential
race, where he tells audiences _ over and over and over again _
that his only problem with a television advertisement that shows
Bill Clinton's face morphing into his own is ``that it's the
ugliest picture of me I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   There are self-deprecating lines about how, with white hair at
63, people think he is his school-age children's grandfather. He
makes jabs at the press (``they go from liberal to communist'') and
his staff (``most of them are on work-release programs''), and he
offers a riff on Harry Truman's quest for a one-armed economist
``because economists always say, `On the one hand, on the other
hand.'''
</P>
<P>
   His audience eats it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them just talk serious and serious, but he's with the
people,'' said Caroline Jowders, 78, who has heard the senator's
routine at four campaign events since summer. ``He always has a
sense of humor.''
</P>
<P>
   In Keene the other night, the crowd was cracking up as if it
were a comedy club.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very entertaining,'' Barbara Hecker said afterward.
``There aren't too many politicians that I think are funny.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also does a mean Bob Dole impression (though he refused
to offer a rendition of the Viagra commercial), and freely admits
that most of his humor is borrowed. (``The trees chase the dogs''
is a Barry Goldwater original, and many others are borrowed from
Morris K. Udall, the late Democratic congressman from Arizona.)
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to one of the candidate's favorite closing
lines. Something about how Goldwater, Udall, and Bruce Babbitt, all
Arizonans, all trod this path before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arizona may be the only state where mothers don't tell their
children they can grow up to be president,'' McCain cracks. ``I
want to change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ba-dum-bum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
