<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEBODY TELL LAKERS TO KEEP RICE AROUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
The Lakers were hugging the road like a souped-up sports car. They
were accelerating out of hairpin curves and picking up such speed
and momentum, every other Pacific Division team save Portland
appeared to be standing still.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Then came this long weekend. It was a drawn-out, trance-inducing
three days for the Lakers, who hit a couple of bumps in the road
and swerved slightly off course. They lost at Indiana on Friday and
came up short against Seattle 82-81 on Monday at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden that 16-game winning streak looks like a dot in
their rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Two losses in three games is the nearest thing the Lakers have
had all season to a losing skid. To those predisposed to kick Glen
Rice when the Lakers are down _ and you know who you are, Dr. Jerry
Buss _ we have but one thing to say: Where was your mind during the
moment of silence that preceded Monday's game?
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and SuperSonics bowed their heads for a few seconds
to remember Bobby Phills, the Charlotte swingman who was killed
last week when he lost control of his speeding Porsche and crashed.
Phills' death was a grim reminder of how flimsy the blueprints
built on tomorrows are.
</P>
<P>
   Even plans spared by tragedy are tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   Winning teams come with piddling warranties, as the Lakers
discovered last year when they fired coach Del Harris and traded
Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell and plunged a season of ample
promise into a tailspin from which it never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom does much good come from tinkering with something that
isn't broken. With nothing to show for all their fiddling last
year, the Lakers, one would think, would have moved quickly the
past few weeks to quell the persistent rumors that Rice is on the
trading block.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be the double-digit scorer off the bench or the bona
fide power forward the Lakers are missing or the backup center they
sure wish they had to spell Shaquille O'Neal so he doesn't have to
play 47 minutes, as he did Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But to focus on what the Lakers don't have is to overlook what
they have in Rice: A terrific scoring option down the stretch (just
ask the SuperSonics, whom he torched in the fourth quarter earlier
this month at Seattle).
</P>
<P>
   And for a pure shooter he is a diligent passer. He demonstrated
as much in the first quarter Monday. Rice took three shots and made
eight passes. He fed O'Neal for three of his five baskets and
Bryant for another. How he wound up with just one assist in that
span is as much a mystery as the whereabouts of the Mars Lander.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Rice passing the ball is akin to Luc Robitaille
passing the puck or asking Celine Dion to sing backup. ``I'm just
running the offense,'' he said without resignation or rancor.
</P>
<P>
   He's doing more than that, said Bryant: ``He's giving up part of
himself to be part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   In a departure from Rice's salad days in Miami and Charlotte,
the screens aren't always set for him. He is finding ways to get
open just the same. Sometimes when that happens, he even gets the
ball. That this doesn't happen often enough is something we learned
from Bryant. Rice is wise enough not to touch the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to get Glen in the flow of the game,''
Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Rice didn't get sucked into the current until the fourth
quarter. He took five shots in that time and made two. If either of
his last two attempts had fallen _ a hook shot to extend the
Lakers' lead to three and a 3-pointer on the next possession to
break a 79-79 deadlock _ his defensive lapses (and those of his
teammates) would have been quietly forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   The truth? Defending the Gary Paytons of the NBA is hard enough
without having to expend a lot of energy defending oneself. For the
record, Rice said, he wants to stay in L.A. for the rest of this
season and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely do,'' said Rice, an impending free agent, ``and
that's one of the things that's really pretty much gotten me
(ticked) off. No one (in the Lakers front office) has ever come and
asked me, `Do you want to be in L.A.?' I would have told them,
`Yes, I want to be here.' It doesn't get any better than this. It's
a joy to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   So assure him of at least a few more months of bliss, already.
</P>
<P>
   The best move Buss or Jerry West could make before the Feb. 24
trading deadline? That would be pulling Rice aside and telling him
he isn't going anywhere for the rest of this season and meaning it.
</P>
<P>
   Anything short of that and the front office is not merely
feeding the rumors, it's feeding the anxiety of a player who
already is experiencing discomfort trying to fit his square peg of
a game into the triangle offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at peace regardless of all the talk I hear that the Lakers
have to get rid of Glen Rice,'' Rice said. ``I don't allow myself
to be affected by it.''
</P>
<P>
   His tired tone made us wonder if it was us Rice was trying to
convince or himself. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
