<SLUG> BC-TV-MARYKAY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MARY KAY LETOURNEAU STORY': A TEACHER STRAYS FAR FROM THE
LESSON PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Pditors: production notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mary Kay Letourneau's childhood explains a lot.
</P>
<P>
   You remember Ms. Letourneau; she was the 35-year-old Washington
state schoolteacher who had an affair with a 13-year-old student,
gave birth to his child, went to prison and had another baby by
him.
</P>
<P>
   What you probably don't know about is her family background, and
that's what ``The Mary Kay Letourneau Story: All-American Girl,''
Tuesday night's film on USA, has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Ms. Letourneau (Penelope Ann Miller, giving an
intelligent, beautifully controlled performance) fascinating is her
seemingly sincere conviction that she did nothing wrong in
conducting a sexual relationship with a child. Even Humbert
Humbert, not your paragon of emotional responsibility, admitted to
himself that he shouldn't have been fooling around with Lolita. So
what kind of woman could see the world this way? What kind of
childhood and moral education would such a person have had?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Letourneau's father was John Schmitz, the former congressman
who ran for president in 1972 under the banner of the American
Independent Party. Schmitz (Chris Bondy), an ultra-conservative
California Republican who was accustomed to protesters outside his
home, was little Mary Kay's hero. And at one point there was a
minor scandal about his having slept with students of his own
(albeit college students). He is, however, so opposed to sex
education that he transfers Mary Kay to a new school so she won't
be exposed to it.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Mary Kay's father is the only one who isn't
appalled by her adult behavior (except Mary Kay's court-appointed
psychiatrist, played by Mercedes Ruehl, who believes her problem is
bipolar depression).
</P>
<P>
   The story begins in 1995, when Mary Kay, a wife and mother so
happy that she sings while making breakfast, gets a telephone call
and learns that her father has prostate cancer. She's horribly
upset, and she gets no emotional support; when she tells her
husband the news, he doesn't even bother to turn off the electric
shaver while she talks. Later, as she's taking a misbehaving
student to the school office, she begins to cry in the hallway and
tells the student about her father. Yes, that student is Vili
Fualaau (Omar Anguiano), the future father of her children.
</P>
<P>
   Anguiano does a fine job of conveying youthful knowingness, but
he does not for a second look 13 years old. This was always the
problem with putting ``Lolita'' on the screen, too: how to convey
the innocence and inexperience of childhood when no one would stand
for casting an actor or actress the actual age of the character.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately ``The Mary Kay Letourneau Story'' doesn't have much
to say. Laying out the details of the case, it doesn't find a way
to explore the moral issues fully. Vili bets his friends $20 he can
seduce the teacher. Clearly he was a willing sex partner, but he
was still a child, with only 13 years of experience in the world to
guide his actions. One of the responsibilities of adulthood is
remembering not to treat children as if they were equals in
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The film's accomplishment is making Ms. Letourneau's actions
believable. As the months pass, Mary Kay and Vili have occasion to
talk privately, once sitting by the campfire on a school field
trip. Julie Heberts' restrained script reminds us how common
student-teacher crushes are by having one of Mary Kay's fellow
teachers tease her, saying with a smile, ``That boy is so in love
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Kay answers, ``Don't be silly.'' But by spring 1996 she is
taking late-night telephone calls from Vili during which he
serenades her by guitar. One summer night, after Mary Kay and her
husband have fought, she and Vili have sex for the first time. She
is arrested early in 1997 after a relative of her husband's reports
the affair to the school.
</P>
<P>
   With impeccable timing, Mary Kay gives birth to her and Vili's
daughter in August 1997, six days after she has pleaded guilty to
rape. She is found guilty, but the judge goes easy on her, at
first. Today Ms. Letourneau is serving seven and a half years in
prison, where she gave birth to her second daughter with Vili in
1998. She expects to be released in 2005, when her young lover will
be 22.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE MARY KAY LETOURNEAU STORY: All-American Girl'
</P>
<P>
   USA, Tuesday night at 8 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Grosso and Larry Jacobson, executive producers; J. Miles
Dale, producer; Lisa Parasyn, associate producer; written by Julie
Hebert; directed by Lloyd Kramer. A USA Pictures Original produced
by Grosso-Jacobson Communications.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Penelope Ann Miller (Mary Kay Letourneau), Omar Anguiano
(Vili Fualaau), Mercedes Ruehl (Dr. Jane Newhall), Rena Owen (Soona
Fualaau), Chris Bondy (John Schmitz) and Greg Spottiswood (Steve
Letourneau). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
