<SLUG> BC-NORTON-ART-SAATCHI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLECTING ART PLUS GRUDGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NORTON-ART-DONATE) 
(lb) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The British collector Charles Saatchi, whose ``Sensation''
exhibition has just closed at the Brooklyn Museum of Art in New
York, had a run-in with Peter Norton over a work that is part of
Norton's current donation to 29 museums.
</P>
<P>
   Norton is giving to the Tate Gallery in London ``The Wizard'' by
John Currin, a young American painter who often paints parodies of
pornography featuring buxom women. ``The Wizard'' shows a woman
wearing black gloves fondling another woman's breasts.
</P>
<P>
   Some time ago Saatchi said that he had completed a deal to buy
``The Wizard'' from Clyde Beswick, a California businessman and
collector. Meanwhile Beswick was convicted of embezzling money from
Brody Smythe Direct, a Pasadena-based mail-order company that he
founded.
</P>
<P>
   He served 11 months in prison and was sued for divorce by his
wife, Karen. His art collection was seized by the courts, which
ordered that it be sold, with the money to go toward legal fees and
the divorce settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the courts approved Norton's acquisition of the entire
Beswick collection for $1.5 million. This included ``The Wizard.''
Saatchi then sued for the work. He lost. Now Norton has donated the
picture to the Tate, meaning that it will be in the major museum of
modern art in Saatchi's home city.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my point of view it was just two gentlemen disagreeing,''
Norton said. ``Both of us thought it was rightfully his. It
appeared that Saatchi took the situation more seriously, but maybe
that was just his lawyers. Irrespective of his manner of handling
it, he was quite reasonable to believe it might be his. It's just
one of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton still seems to be enjoying the twist of circumstances
that permits him to be a benefactor on Saatchi's turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent it to the Tate cognizant of Saatchi,'' he said. ``The
Tate was very interested, and Saatchi had wanted it in Britain, as
his property. So we at least fulfilled part of his desire by
sending it there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2329EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
