u a BC-NY-PONZI-SCHEME-NYT &LR;      01-17 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PONZI-SCHEME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS PRESS WIFE TO TESTIFY IN FRAUD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Invoking the legal principle of spousal privilege,
the wife of a Syracuse, N.Y., businessman who was convicted of
creating one of the largest financial frauds in American history is
refusing to answer questions under oath concerning conversations
she had with him about his assets.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen K. Bennett, whose husband, Patrick R. Bennett, is scheduled
to be sentenced next week in U.S. District Court in Manhattan,
refused in a Jan. 7 deposition in Syracuse to respond to questions
regarding her conversations with Bennett about certain assets that
are in her name or in trusts for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett was convicted over the course of two jury trials last
year on charges of bank fraud, money laundering, securities fraud
involving promissory notes and perjury. All those charges arose out
of a scheme that defrauded more than 10,000 investors, many of them
elderly, of more than $600 million, the prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the office of Mary Jo White, U.S. attorney for
the Southern District of New York, which had taken the deposition,
Judge John S. Martin Jr. of U.S. District Court has ordered Mrs.
Bennett to appear before him on Thursday to explain her refusal to
answer the questions about the assets, which include the family's
home and a 100-acre horse farm in Oneida, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   When Bennett was convicted, he was ordered to forfeit $109
million to the government. But last fall, the government said that
Bennett was ``hiding assets'' behind ``fraudulent transfers to his
wife.'' In a hearing last month, Martin, questioning whether Mrs.
Bennett was living ``in luxury'' on victims' money, asked for
further investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that every dollar of money he and his family
had taken from the investors in this case be repaid,'' Martin said
Dec. 3, suggesting that prosecutors question Mrs. Bennett under
oath. The government then took the deposition on Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, 47, faces a sentence of roughly 15 to 20 years under
federal guidelines, but Martin said the potential sentence ``is
almost without limit if I am persuaded that Bennett and his family
continued to maintain funds that rightfully belonged to people whom
they defrauded.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the lawyer-client privilege, the privilege over private
communications between husband and wife is almost absolute, legal
experts say, even when one spouse confesses a crime to another. But
the privilege ends if one spouse joins in the illegal activities of
the other, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for each of the Bennetts, who have been married about 11
years, said prosecutors were improperly trying to force Mrs.
Bennett to break confidences protected by the spousal privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``The privilege is absolute unless it's shown to be in
furtherance of a fraud,'' said Bennett's lawyer, Michael D.
Pinnisi. ``No one has shown that Mrs. Bennett participated in any
fraudulent conduct whatsoever. The government didn't allege it in
the indictment. There was no proof at trial. She has never been
indicted.''
</P>
<P>
   In the trials, prosecutors said that Bennett had used his
family's company, Bennett Funding Group of Syracuse, which claimed
to finance office-equipment leases, to carry out the fraud from
1990 to 1996. Prosecutors said Bennett had spent millions of
dollars he took from his company to buy a local horse racing track,
hotels and gambling enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's lawyers said he was merely an inept businessman who
had been overwhelmed by his fast-growing company, and had never
intended to commit any crimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
