<DOCNO> NYT20000117.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8758 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-SEATTLE-LA     01-17 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SEATTLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE, PAYTON BEAT LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
Exposed as mortals, or at least a bad warmup act, the Lakers fell
to basketball Earth on Monday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another day, another streak snapped, this their 14-game home
winning streak after the Seattle SuperSonics played them tight in
the fourth quarter and then won it 82-81 when Gary Payton capped an
outstanding game by drilling an open 3-pointer with 15.9 seconds
left.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the Pacers snapped the Lakers' 16-game winning
streak in Indiana, the Lakers stumbled at home for the first time
since the Grizzlies surprised them here back on Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's shaky effort was in an afternoon game and preceded the
later Clippers affair against the Spurs, the first Staples Center
basketball doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Lakers couldn't get into opening for the Clippers, but
that stifling defense and precision offense that had marked their
impressive run mostly took the day off.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers complained of fatigue _ what with their playing a
Monday afternoon game following a Saturday night game in Minnesota
_ but this one had the looks of a game the Lakers just sort of
expected to pull out when the time came.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to get 'em,'' said Lakers guard Kobe
Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no getting to the blazing Payton, who finished
with 36 points _ two off his career-high _ and added seven assists
and six rebounds. Payton was a whirlwind operating at a different
level from everyone else, or at least one determined to exorcise
any demons from the 19-point lead the Sonics blew to the Lakers at
home nine days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Another strong overall game from Shaquille O'Neal _ 30 points,
10 rebounds, six assists, four blocks _ was about all the Lakers
could answer with.
</P>
<P>
   But after O'Neal made one of two free throws with 30.2 seconds
remaining to give the Lakers an 81-79 lead, every single silent
soul in the sellout crowd of 18,997 knew Payton would try to hit a
3-pointer. Then he make it look easy.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Laker and would-be Kobe stopper Ruben Patterson set a routine
screen on Ron Harper near the 3-point line above the key. When
Harper tried to work under the screen, Payton simply popped back
out and confidently swished a 27-footer.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Harper, unhappy with the Lakers' overall defensive
effort, was quick to take responsibility for the lapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my fault,'' Harper said. ``I ran under the screen. Hey,
I'll take the blame. I don't have a problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers still had a last chance to win the game, but Bryant
missed an open jumper from the baseline. Robert Horry missed the
follow shot and the rebound went back to Bryant, who penetrated
toward the basket but went out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to draw a foul,'' Bryant said. ``I didn't draw it very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics inbounded the ball with 1.8 seconds left, and
amazingly the ball suddenly popped out to Rice three feet from the
basket. But Rice couldn't get a shot off in time, which fittingly,
on a night the Lakers shot 40 percent from the field, missed
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   This was a game that could easily have been lacking suspense by
the fourth quarter. The Lakers had somewhat methodically pulled
away from Seattle to start the second half, building a nine-point
lead with five minutes to play in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But with Payton and ex-Clipper Brent Barry (17 points) leading
the way, the Sonics charged back with a 15-2 run to close the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the kind of games if you've been watching them long
enough, you know someone is going to get hurt at the end,'' Lakers
coach Phil Jackson said. ``We just missed too many opportunities
and played so poorly from mid-third quarter on, that it was due to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there could be finger-pointing anywhere along the
line, a lot of the finger-pointing is back at yourself in this one.
Everyone had a piece of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are still a league-best 32-7, but feeling slightly
less bullet-proof after losing two of their past three.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to win as many as possible at home,'' O'Neal said.
``You can't let one slip away. We have to get back on track, and we
will.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2330EST &QL; 
