<HEADLINE>
HARPER RAISES DEFENSIVE QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
It's hard to be too critical and lash out when your team is riding
a 16-game winning streak, but after the Lakers unexpectedly lost
for the second time in three games Monday, guard Ron Harper acted
like a man who had been waiting to vent.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harper took responsibility for letting Seattle's Gary Payton pop
free for his game-winning 3-pointer, but let it be known the Lakers
acted like a team that had forgotten it had ridden an impressive
defense to its winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be a team, then everyone has to lay it on
the line,'' Harper said. ``It's easy to go down there and shoot the
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to learn how to defend, stop folks, or at least act
like you're trying. You have to help somebody out, don't you think?
It isn't that hard a game. It's simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton was running amok all afternoon in the Sonics' 82-81
victory, scoring 36 points. When he'd break free of Harper, often
on a screen, he would too often find himself open for a medium
jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Payton had a great game,'' Harper said. ``He's a great
ballplayer who comes out and goes hard every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a great defensive game by our team. We had some guys
play good, but as a whole we didn't have a good defensive game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Kobe Bryant was 1 of 8 from the field. After
three quarters, Glen Rice was 2 for 8. Bryant ended up 6 for 18,
and 0 for 5 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   THEY'RE SO TIRED: Lakers coach Phil Jackson said after playing
Saturday night in Minnesota and then Monday afternoon at the
Staples Center, fatigue appeared a factor in the Lakers'
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can't shoot the ball any better than that (40
percent), those are either leg fatigue or terrific defense,''
Jackson said. ``And I didn't think they closed out shots. A lot of
guys had open shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said it's not unusual to see teams struggle in a Monday
afternoon game on Martin Luther King Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of these Martin Luther King _ I don't even
want his name associated with the game _ but these morning games
are like this,'' he said. ``They're all pretty pathetic games and
this certainly followed up on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bryant: ``It was like practice. We had a bunch of old
bones. It took everybody awhile to warm up.''
</P>
<P>
   TIDBITS: Jackson wasn't thrilled the officiating, either,
claiming Bryant was fouled on his final drive: ``They did as
pathetic a job refereeing as we did playing it.''... The Lakers
were 3 of 21 from the 3-point line.... The Lakers held a moment of
silence before the game for Hornets guard Bobby Phills. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
