<SLUG> BC-GM-ALLIANCES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN POLICY SHIFT, GM WILL RELY ON ALLIANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   (Eds: Adds to end of graf that begins ``Those kinds of ...'' Adds 2
new grafs at end.) 
 (lb) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ In the first acknowledgment by the world's largest
corporation that it cannot go it alone, the chairman of General
Motors Corp. said Monday night that the company would rely more on
partnerships and would better be described as ``the General Motors
group.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our approach is to develop long-term relationships with other
companies that offer a unique advantage to the General Motors group
of brands and businesses,'' said John F. Smith Jr., chairman and
chief executive of GM, who was speaking at the Automotive News
World Congress here. ``This alliance strategy is our major thrust,
and it is clearly a different approach to growth than most people
have associated with General Motors _ or with the rest of the
industry, for that matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The change in philosophy is remarkable for a company so large
that its spending seems to dwarf Third World economies, one so big
that a factory closing can attract more attention than the closing
of a U.S. military base, and one that can be as difficult to turn
as a battleship.
</P>
<P>
   ``No automaker today has the resources to achieve leadership in
all regions and all product segments on its own,'' Smith said, not
even GM, with its global presence and scores of household names _
from the Chevrolet Camaro to the Cadillac DeVille.
</P>
<P>
   GM has longstanding alliances with Isuzu Motors, Suzuki Motor
and Toyota Motor. But it has recently expanded some partnerships,
forged new ones and even formed three-way alliances. It is also
employing the alliance strategy with gusto when it comes to
Internet business initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, GM and Toyota formed a manufacturing partnership to
include research and development on fuel-cell and gas-electric
hybrid vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   About a month ago it formed an alliance with Fuji Heavy
Industries and its Subaru brand. GM benefits from Fuji's strength
in small sport utility vehicles, continuously variable
transmissions and all-wheel-drive systems, while Fuji can look
forward to sharing GM's vehicle platforms and other technologies.
</P>
<P>
   GM has also cut a deal with Honda Motor Co. in which Honda will
contribute six-cylinder engines and transmissions for a future
vehicle, and GM's previous partner, Isuzu, will send Honda diesel
engines for European sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are also discussing collaboration with Honda on other
technology and other business opportunities,'' Smith said. ``We
expect the value of the experience of working together, getting to
know each other at the individual level as well as companies, to
far outweigh the limited scope of this initial agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Just last week GM said it would buy the half of Saab Automobile
of Sweden that it did not already own. And it is now in talks to
buy some assets of Daewoo Motor of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not rule out acquisitions and mergers as opportunities
arise,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Those kinds of alliances will play an important role in GM's
Internet strategies, Smith said. Last week alone, GM said it would
enter marketing partnerships with Sony, America Online and NetZero.
On Monday night Smith said GM was working on another alliance that
would give customers using GM's Onstar communications program a
single bill for that service and for wireless phone service _ most
likely a deal with a large telecommunications provider. That deal
could comes within days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While GM has already predicted that its Onstar service would
have a million customers by the end of this year, Smith also said
Monday night that Onstar would have 4 million customers by 2003.
Onstar customers can now call operators, who are able to call tow
trucks when needed or even make restaurant reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Before the end of the year, GM expects 400,000 Onstar customers
to have the capability to use voice-recognition systems and
cellular phone connections to talk to their cars, and to reach the
Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
