<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-17 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8762 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-MCHALE-COLUMN-LAD     01-17 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MCHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS ON THE RIGHT TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
The Stanley Cup was not built in a day. And five losing weeks are
not going to undo the Kings' dream of having one someday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If anything, the Kings' 2-10-1 record the past 13 games
illustrates just how many elements go into winning hockey's biggest
prize.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings are moving in the right direction even if they keep
dropping in the standings. They are learning lessons from losing
that will help them for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one goal this season when the Kings moved into
Staples Center. Make the playoffs. There needed to be tangible
proof that this building was not just a cash cow for the owners and
a playpen for the city's corporate elite.
</P>
<P>
   The team needed to create an excitement that extended far beyond
the brass and marble. Despite all that has happened with injuries
to most of the two front lines and both goaltenders, the Kings are
well within that goal.
</P>
<P>
   It would be nice to win the Pacific Division, but that isn't
going to happen even without all the injuries. The Kings brought a
lot of emotional baggage over from the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The best sign that they have left some behind is the attitude
the club has kept in the face of defeat. The games are not always
well-played, but the effort is there and the crowds are responding.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, morale was the Kings' biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where we would have been then if this happened to
us,'' goaltender Jamie Storr said. ``The whole thing can be very
fragile, but there is real confidence in the dressing room that
this will get turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   New coach Andy Murray said early this season that there is a
reason his players have so little Stanley Cup experience. They have
to learn how to win.
</P>
<P>
   It is no different than what Bill Parcells did with the New York
Jets or even Phil Jackson is doing with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Murray is quick to point out that the Lakers were one of the
league's better teams even before Jackson arrived. He must not have
watched the NBA playoffs the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, whose team has made the playoffs just once in the past
six seasons, is building from the bottom. But even the best have
learned from mistakes. The Dallas Stars and Detroit Red Wings, who
combined to win the past three Stanley Cups, each suffered on their
way to the top. Both had seasons in which they had the league's
best record only to lose early in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But if you look at the Kings players, their careers have little
postseason experience.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Ziggy Palffy and Bryan Smolinski, who came over last
summer from the New York Islanders. Palffy has never been in
playoff game. Smolinski hasn't in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski even went to Murray in training camp to say he wanted
to be worked extra hard because he feared he had forgotten how to
win.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy was the team's leading scorer until he was hit with back
spasms six weeks ago. It is not a coincidence that the team's slide
began around the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Smolinski is now the team's leading scorer with 38 points, but
he is still in the learning process. There are some nights when he
is brilliant, others when he disappears. Smolinski made tactical
mistakes Saturday night on both goals by San Jose's Owen Nolan.
That put the Kings down 2-0 in a game they tied, then lost, in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   With the success of the Smolinski/Palffy deal, it would see that
trades might be the way to go to build the team for the next level.
</P>
<P>
   They certainly need to improve their first line and evaluate the
future of Jozef Stumpel as the center on the top unit. He looked
like a steal from Boston two years ago when he had 58 assists and
79 points. But since then he has missed so much time to injuries,
linemates have generated little offense.
</P>
<P>
   The team looked at Carolina's holdout Keith Primeau earlier this
year. They'll look again next summer.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble with trades is the Kings do not have much to deal.
Rob Blake is untouchable, the captain and the backbone of the team.
After injuries last season, he has regained his spot among the
league's top one or two defenseman.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille still has the scoring touch, but at 34 he's in
the last year of his contract. He has far more value as the Kings'
most popular player than anywhere else. Expect him to get dropped,
however, to the second unit as the team takes some of their luxury
box money to find an elite player for the first line.
</P>
<P>
   Goaltender Stephane Fiset has struggled since his return from a
hand injury. He also will be entering the first season of a
three-year contract extension. If he isn't taken in next summer's
expansion draft, Fiset probably could not bring more than a draft
choice in trade.
</P>
<P>
   The most marketable King is defenseman Aki Berg, even though he
has spent the past two games on the bench because of poor play.
Berg, 23, has enormous skill, but also has struggled coming back
after sitting out a year in Finland in a contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have been bitten by trading defensemen before. In
1992-93, the year they went to the Stanley Cup Finals, the Kings
had three young defensemen:
</P>
<P>
   Blake, Alexei Zhitnik and Darryl Sydor.
</P>
<P>
   All three have become All-Stars, but only Blake is a King.
Zhitnik was sent to Buffalo in a deal that included aging
goaltender Grant Fuhr. Sydor was traded to Dallas in Feb. 1996 for
Shane Churla and Doug Smolek. Neither are still with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all they are still moving forward. Not too fast, but
moving. Right now, you shouldn't ask for more. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Deputy Sports Editor Matt McHale covers the Kings for the Daily
News. The NHL column appears every Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
