<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS WORRIED ABOUT PALFFY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
LOS ANGELES _ The Kings have been meeting with their medical staff
to determine to what extent Ziggy Palffy's lower-back strain has
hurt his effectiveness.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Palffy was the club's leading scorer when he developed back
spasms in early December. He has one goal since and missed several
practices, raising questions about his conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy's injury has frustrated coach Andy Murray, who often
doesn't know if his top winger can play until after pregame
warmups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear Ziggy and his girlfriend are going back to Slovakia
this summer to open a health club,'' Murray said. ``I hope he buys
a membership.''
</P>
<P>
   Kings trainer Pete Demers says Palffy's conditioning is fine,
but the overall strength of his torso area needs improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have put him on a trunk stabilization program,'' Demers
said. ``He's getting stronger, but it is difficult when you have to
do it during an NHL season. This is not the off-season where you
can go all out. I don't want to wear him out in the weight room
before a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Demers said there are several areas that can help relieve stress
on Palffy's back. The first is improving his abdominal strength.
The Kings staff also is working on increasing flexibility in
Palffy's hamstrings and building strength in his glutes (backside).
</P>
<P>
   Palffy missed just three games during his first four seasons
with the New York Islanders. He already has missed four because of
back problems and often has had trouble playing during the Kings'
2-10-1 slide the past five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got here, Ziggy had tremendous jump in his game,''
Murray said. ``That is what he's missing now. We know this is
something that will be around all year, but we desperately need him
back to where he was.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ABOUT FISET: With the return of Jamie Storr, who will start
tonight against Buffalo, Stephane Fiset has moved to a backup role.
Fiset struggled after coming back too quickly from a bruised right
hand and goaltender consultant Don Edwards said the slower pace
will help Fiset regain his timing and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took over for Jamie before he was ready and he developed
some bad habits,'' Edwards said. ``Now you have a chance to tinker
with a few things without having to take them into a game. A couple
practices and he should be ready again.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE MEND: Jozef Stumpel, sidelined the past two weeks with a
knee injury, will attempt to skate today for the first time, but
still is probably two weeks away. Donald Audette, sidelined the
past two weeks with a sprained ankle, won't begin skating until the
end of the week. Glen Murray, who went on injured reserve Friday
with a deep chest bruise, is expected to miss two to three weeks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-00 2347EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
